function seedJourneyKB() {
  var sheet = SpreadsheetApp.getActiveSpreadsheet().getSheetByName('KnowledgeBase');
  if (!sheet) return { success: false, error: 'KnowledgeBase sheet not found' };
  var data = sheet.getDataRange().getValues();
  for (var i = 1; i < data.length; i++) {
    if (data[i][0] && data[i][0].toString().indexOf('jrn-') === 0) return { success: true, message: 'Journey KB already seeded' };
  }
  var now = new Date().toISOString();
  var e = [];
  e.push(['jrn-autism-overview','journey-autism','overview','Autism Journey Map — Overview','AUTISM SPECTRUM DISORDER (ASD) — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n16 steps across 6 phases:\n* 1 Concern & Screening: Parent Notices Developmental Concerns, Well-Child Visit Screening (M-CHAT-R/F), Referral to Regional Center (Self-Refer — No Docto\n* 2 Evaluation & Diagnosis: RC Intake Assessment, Multidisciplinary Evaluation (RC-Arranged), Private Diagnostic Evaluation (Optional but Valuab, Eligibility Determination (RC Decision)\n* 3 Service Planning: IPP Development (Initial Service Plan), Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE (Full Benef\n* 4 School District IEP: Request School District Evaluation (Written Reques, School District Evaluation & IEP Development, IEP Dispute Resolution (If Needed)\n* 5 Insurance & Therapy: Insurance Authorization for ABA Therapy, Begin and Coordinate All Therapy Services\n* 6 Financial Protection & Lifelong Management: CalABLE, SNT & Age-18 Planning, Ongoing Authorization Renewals, Reviews & Lifetime\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s11','journey-autism','step-11','Autism Step 1.1: Parent Notices Developmental Concerns','Autism — Step 1.1: Parent Notices Developmental Concerns\n\nWHAT TO DO: START DOCUMENTING IMMEDIATELY: (1) Keep a dated journal of specific behaviors — \'Jan 15: Teddy did not respond to name called 5 times at park.\' (2) Video record concerning behaviors on your phone — these are INVALUABLE for evaluators. (3) Track milestones against CDC/AAP checklist: by 12 mo = responds to name, points, waves; by 18 mo = at least 6 words, points to show you things, copies others; by 24 mo = 2-word phrases, follows 2-step instructions, notices when others are hurt. (4) Note any REGRESSION — loss of previously acquired words or skills is an urgent red flag requiring immediate action. (5) Talk to your pediatrician at the NEXT scheduled visit — do not wait for a special appointment. (6) Trust your instincts — parents are right about developmental concerns more often than not.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Download CDC Milestone Tracker app (free, cdc.gov/milestones) and complete age-appropriate checklist TODAY.\nSTEP 2: Start a \'concerns notebook\' — write date + specific observation + context. Example: \'Feb 3: At playgroup, Teddy lined up all cars instead of rolling them. Did not look at me when I said his name 3x.\'\nSTEP 3: Record 2-3 short videos (30-60 sec each) showing concerning behaviors in natural settings.\nSTEP 4: At next pediatrician visit, say: \'I have specific developmental concerns I\'d like to discuss. I\'ve been tracking milestones and have notes and videos to share.\'\nSTEP 5: If pediatrician says \'wait and see,\' say: \'I understand, but I\'d like a referral to the Regional Center and a developmental screening today. Early intervention has the strongest evidence base, and I don\'t want to lose time.\'\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Your child\'s primary care doctor — bring your notes and videos to the next visit.\nREGIONAL CENTER (RC): Find yours at dds.ca.gov/rc (21 RCs in California). You can self-refer — NO doctor referral needed. Call the intake line directly.\nCDC MILESTONE TRACKER: cdc.gov/milestones (free app, iOS/Android)\nFIRST SIGNS: firstsigns.org — video library of autism red flags\n\nDOCUMENTS: No documents required at this stage. BEGIN CREATING:\n• Developmental concerns journal (dated entries)\n• Video recordings of behaviors (save to dedicated phone folder)\n• Printed CDC milestone checklist with notes\n• List of specific questions for pediatrician\n• Baby book/medical records with developmental history\n\nTIMELINE: Act NOW — do not wait. Every month of delay during ages 0-3 is critical lost intervention time. The AAP recommends universal autism screening at 18 and 24 months, but if you have concerns at ANY age, act immediately. Call your Regional Center TODAY if you have concerns.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) \'Wait and see\' — this is the #1 cause of delayed diagnosis. Every month of delay is lost intervention during the critical brain plasticity window (ages 0-3). (2) Compare to siblings or other children — autism presents differently in every child. (3) Let anyone dismiss your concerns with \'boys talk later\' or \'Einstein didn\'t talk until 4.\' (4) Rely solely on verbal milestones — social engagement, play skills, and sensory responses are equally important. (5) Assume bilingualism is causing delays — it does NOT cause autism-like symptoms. (6) Wait for school to notice — you know your child best.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL DELAYS: (1) Pediatrician says \'wait and see\' — delays intervention by 6-12 months on average. (2) Cultural stigma prevents families from seeking evaluation — Latino/Black children diagnosed 2+ years later than White children. (3) Family members (grandparents, spouse) dismiss concerns — \'My brother didn\'t talk until 3 and he\'s fine.\' (4) Girls with autism missed — they mask/camouflage social difficulties better. (5) Child meets SOME milestones so parent assumes all is fine — autism is about quality of social interaction, not just presence/absence of skills.\n\nRESOURCES: FREE PARENT TRAINING:\n• CHADD Parent-to-Parent: chadd.org (covers neurodevelopmental concerns broadly)\n• Autism Speaks 100 Day Kit: autismspeaks.org/tool-kit (free download at diagnosis)\n• First Signs: firstsigns.org (video library of early signs)\n• CDC \'Learn the Signs, Act Early\': cdc.gov/actearly\n• CA PTI Network: Your local Parent Training & Information center — find at parentcenterhub.org\n• TASK (Team of Advocates for Special Kids): taskca.org\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org (Bay Area)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None\n(Parent-initiated)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s12','journey-autism','step-12','Autism Step 1.2: Well-Child Visit Screening (M-CHAT-R/F)','Autism — Step 1.2: Well-Child Visit Screening (M-CHAT-R/F)\n\nWHAT TO DO: REQUEST M-CHAT-R/F SCREENING: (1) At the 18-month and 24-month well-child visits, ASK your pediatrician: \'Will you be administering the M-CHAT autism screening today?\' (2) If they don\'t offer it, request it explicitly — it\'s a simple 20-question parent questionnaire that takes 5 minutes. (3) Complete the M-CHAT honestly — do not \'help\' your child\'s score by assuming what they CAN do vs what they ACTUALLY DO. (4) If M-CHAT is positive (score 3+), insist on the Follow-Up Interview (M-CHAT-R/F) — this reduces false positives. (5) If screening is positive, immediately request referral to Regional Center AND a developmental pediatrician. (6) Even if M-CHAT is negative but you still have concerns, pursue evaluation anyway — M-CHAT misses ~20% of children who are later diagnosed.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before your child\'s 18-month visit, call the office and ask: \'Will the M-CHAT-R/F be administered at this visit? If not, I\'d like to request it.\'\nSTEP 2: Complete the M-CHAT-R/F questionnaire honestly in the waiting room. Score is 0-20 — scores of 3-7 = medium risk (follow-up needed), 8+ = high risk (refer immediately).\nSTEP 3: If score is 3+, the pediatrician should administer the Follow-Up Interview. If they don\'t, request it or score it yourself at mchatscreen.com.\nSTEP 4: If screening is positive, say to your pediatrician: \'Based on this screening, I\'d like two things today: (a) a referral to a developmental pediatrician, and (b) the phone number for our Regional Center so I can self-refer for evaluation.\'\nSTEP 5: Do NOT leave the appointment without a written plan for next steps. If the doctor says \'let\'s rescreen in 6 months,\' say: \'I\'d prefer to begin the evaluation process now and cancel if concerns resolve.\'\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Your child\'s doctor administers the M-CHAT at well-child visits.\nM-CHAT ONLINE: mchatscreen.com — free, you can complete and score it yourself at any time.\nIF PEDIATRICIAN WON\'T SCREEN: Complete M-CHAT yourself at mchatscreen.com and bring results to appointment. Say: \'I completed the M-CHAT and my child scored [X]. I\'d like to discuss this and get referrals.\'\nDEVELOPMENTAL PEDIATRICIAN REFERRAL: Ask pediatrician for referral to developmental pediatrician at nearest children\'s hospital (e.g., UCSF, Stanford, Children\'s California).\nREGIONAL CENTER: Self-refer directly — no doctor needed.\n\nDOCUMENTS: • M-CHAT-R/F completed questionnaire (keep a copy)\n• M-CHAT-R/F Follow-Up Interview results (if applicable)\n• Well-child visit summary/after-visit note\n• Referral to developmental pediatrician (written)\n• Your developmental concerns journal and videos\n• Any prior developmental screening results\n\nTIMELINE: 18-month well-child visit: First M-CHAT screening.\n24-month well-child visit: Second M-CHAT screening.\nAAP also recommends general developmental screening at 9, 18, and 30 months.\nIf positive screen: referral should happen SAME DAY. Do not wait for next appointment.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Skip the 18- and 24-month well-child visits — these are the recommended screening windows. (2) Accept \'we don\'t do that screening\' from your pediatrician — M-CHAT is AAP recommended and free. (3) Assume a negative M-CHAT means no autism — false negatives occur, especially for girls and milder presentations. (4) Let the pediatrician screen without completing the M-CHAT questionnaire (just asking \'does your child point?\' in passing is NOT a valid screen). (5) Wait for a positive screen to act — if you have concerns regardless of screening result, self-refer to RC immediately.\n\nRISKS: ★ SCREENING FAILURES: (1) M-CHAT not administered — many pediatricians skip it despite AAP recommendation. (2) Screening done casually (verbal questions only, not formal questionnaire). (3) False negatives — M-CHAT sensitivity is ~83%, meaning ~17% of autistic children screen negative. (4) Positive screen but no follow-up — pediatrician says \'let\'s wait.\' (5) Latino and Black children 40% less likely to be screened and referred. (6) Screening at 18 months too early for some children — repeat at 24 months critical.\n\nRESOURCES: M-CHAT ONLINE: mchatscreen.com (free, validated, score instantly)\nAAP SCREENING GUIDELINES: aap.org/autism\nCDC \'Learn the Signs, Act Early\': cdc.gov/actearly — free materials in multiple languages\nAutism Navigator: autismnavigator.com — video-based screening tool for providers\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / PCP\nOTHER AGENCIES: None at this stage\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s13','journey-autism','step-13','Autism Step 1.3: Referral to Regional Center (Self-Refer — No Doctor Needed)','Autism — Step 1.3: Referral to Regional Center (Self-Refer — No Doctor Needed)\n\nWHAT TO DO: SELF-REFER TO YOUR REGIONAL CENTER TODAY: (1) Call your local RC intake line — you do NOT need a doctor referral, teacher letter, or any documentation. A parent phone call is sufficient. (2) Say: \'I am a parent and I\'d like to refer my child for a developmental evaluation. My child is [age] and I have concerns about [speech/social interaction/behavior].\' (3) Ask for the name and direct number of the intake coordinator assigned to your case. (4) Confirm: \'What is my intake appointment date? I understand you have 15 working days to complete intake.\' (5) Request a Spanish/other language interpreter if needed — RC is required to provide this. (6) You can ALSO pursue a school district evaluation (for age 3+) simultaneously — these are separate processes and you should do both.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Find your RC at dds.ca.gov/rc/listing. Find your local RC from the 21 statewide centers.\nSTEP 2: Call the intake line during business hours (M-F 8am-5pm). If you get voicemail, leave: your name, child\'s name, DOB, phone number, brief concern, and request for intake appointment.\nSTEP 3: If no callback within 3 business days, call again. Document every call attempt (date, time, who you spoke with).\nSTEP 4: At intake, bring: child\'s birth certificate, proof of CA residency (utility bill), medical records if available (but NOT required), your concerns journal and videos.\nSTEP 5: After intake, ask: \'What is the next step? When will the evaluation be scheduled? Who is my service coordinator?\' Get name and direct phone number.\nSTEP 6: Mark your calendar: 120 days from referral = deadline for RC to complete evaluation and make eligibility determination.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR LOCAL REGIONAL CENTER: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — California has 21 Regional Centers serving every county. Call your local RC\'s intake line.\nCA DDS (oversees all RCs): dds.ca.gov\nRC INTAKE HELP: If your RC is unresponsive:\n• OCRA (Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy): (800) 390-7032\n• Disability Rights California: (800) 776-5746\nLANTERMAN ACT INFO: disabilityrightsca.org/publications — free guides, multiple languages.\nUNDIVIDED NAVIGATOR: undivided.io — free family navigator service.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — Family Resource Centers statewide, parent-to-parent support.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TO BRING TO INTAKE:\n• Child\'s birth certificate (copy)\n• Proof of CA residency (utility bill, lease)\n• Medi-Cal card or insurance card\n• Any existing medical/developmental records\n• Your concerns journal and videos\n• Immunization records (optional)\n\nDOCUMENTS RC WILL PROVIDE:\n• Referral acknowledgment\n• Intake assessment form\n• Rights booklet (Lanterman Act rights)\n• Consent for evaluation forms\n\nTIMELINE: Lanterman Act requires: intake within 15 WORKING DAYS of referral. Complete evaluation and eligibility determination within 120 CALENDAR DAYS. If RC misses these deadlines, document and escalate to DDS or OCRA.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Wait for your pediatrician to make the referral — self-refer TODAY. (2) Assume you need a diagnosis first — RC evaluates and diagnoses. (3) Be intimidated by the intake process — you have a RIGHT to services under the Lanterman Act. (4) Accept \'we\'ll put you on a waitlist\' without getting a specific intake date within 15 working days. (5) Skip the RC referral because you\'re already pursuing school evaluation — RC provides different services (ABA, respite, parent training) that school does not.\n\nRISKS: ★ RC ACCESS BARRIERS: (1) Phone lines busy/understaffed — may take multiple calls. (2) Language barriers if intake staff don\'t speak family\'s language. (3) Rural families may be far from RC office. (4) RC may try to defer to school district — insist on RC evaluation for Lanterman eligibility. (5) Families with undocumented status may fear contact with government agency — RC does NOT share immigration information. (6) Intake coordinator may minimize concerns or discourage evaluation.\n\nRESOURCES: LANTERMAN ACT RIGHTS GUIDE: disabilityrightsca.org/publications — free, in multiple languages\nOCRA (Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy): (800) 390-7032 — free advocacy if RC is unresponsive\nUNDIVIDED: undivided.io — free navigator service to help with RC process\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — Family Resource Center in your area for peer support\nSERR MANUAL: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — complete special education and RC rights reference\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician (optional referral)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s21','journey-autism','step-21','Autism Step 2.1: RC Intake Assessment','Autism — Step 2.1: RC Intake Assessment\n\nWHAT TO DO: PREPARE FOR INTAKE MEETING: (1) Organize your documentation in a folder: medical records, concerns journal, videos, milestone tracking. (2) Write a 1-page \'Parent Concerns Letter\' summarizing your specific concerns — this becomes part of the official record. (3) At intake, be specific and detailed: not \'he doesn\'t talk much\' but \'at 22 months he has 3 words (mama, dada, ball), does not point to request items, does not follow simple commands like bring me your shoes, and does not look when I call his name.\' (4) Ask the intake coordinator: \'Will my child be evaluated by a psychologist, speech-language pathologist, and occupational therapist? I want a comprehensive multidisciplinary evaluation.\' (5) Request that evaluation be conducted in your home language if applicable.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before intake, write your Parent Concerns Letter. Include: child\'s age, specific concerns by domain (communication, social, behavior, sensory, motor), when you first noticed, what others have observed (daycare, family), any regression.\nSTEP 2: Call RC 1 week before intake to confirm: date, time, location, what to bring, whether interpreter will be present.\nSTEP 3: At intake meeting, give the coordinator your written concerns and ask them to include it in the file. Ask: \'Can I get a copy of the intake report when it\'s completed?\'\nSTEP 4: Before leaving, confirm: \'When will evaluations be scheduled? How many evaluation sessions will there be? Will I receive a copy of all evaluation reports?\'\nSTEP 5: Write down the name and direct contact of your intake coordinator. Follow up in writing (email) confirming what was discussed.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER INTAKE COORDINATOR: You\'ll be assigned one at intake — get their name, direct phone, and email.\nIF RC IS UNRESPONSIVE: Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy (OCRA): (800) 390-7032\nDISABILITY RIGHTS CALIFORNIA: (800) 776-5746 — free legal advocacy\nFAMILY RESOURCE NAVIGATOR: undivided.io — can help prepare for intake\n\nDOCUMENTS: BRING TO INTAKE:\n• Parent Concerns Letter (written, dated, keep copy)\n• Medical records and birth records\n• Developmental history notes and videos\n• Prior evaluations (if any)\n• Proof of CA residency\n• Birth certificate\n• Medi-Cal/insurance card\n\nRC PROVIDES AT INTAKE:\n• Intake assessment report\n• Consent for evaluation\n• Lanterman Act rights booklet\n• Service Coordinator assignment (may come later)\n\nTIMELINE: 15 WORKING DAYS from referral to intake appointment (Lanterman Act mandate). If RC schedules intake beyond 15 days, call and say: \'Under the Lanterman Act, intake must occur within 15 working days of referral. My referral date was [date]. Please schedule within this timeline.\'\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Understate your concerns — this is not the time to be optimistic. Describe your child\'s DAILY challenges, not their best moments. (2) Fail to mention regression (loss of skills) if it occurred — this is an urgent indicator. (3) Sign consent forms without reading them. (4) Accept a screening-level evaluation when your child needs comprehensive assessment. (5) Forget to ask about the evaluation timeline — 120-day clock starts at referral.\n\nRISKS: RC delays intake beyond 15 days. Intake is superficial — doesn\'t capture full picture of concerns. Records requests slow process. Parent doesn\'t know what to bring. Coordinator minimizes concerns. Bilingual family not offered interpreter.\n\nRESOURCES: UNDIVIDED: undivided.io — free family navigator, intake preparation help\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, may have parent mentor who\'s been through RC process\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org/publications — RC eligibility guides in English/Spanish\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org — Bay Area parent training on navigating RC\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician (records)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s22','journey-autism','step-22','Autism Step 2.2: Multidisciplinary Evaluation (RC-Arranged)','Autism — Step 2.2: Multidisciplinary Evaluation (RC-Arranged)\n\nWHAT TO DO: ENSURE COMPREHENSIVE EVALUATION: (1) RC should arrange evaluation by a TEAM: psychologist (cognitive/autism diagnostic), speech-language pathologist (communication), occupational therapist (sensory/motor/adaptive). (2) Autism-specific tools should include: ADOS-2 (Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule — gold standard), ADI-R or DISCO (parent interview), cognitive testing (Bayley-4 for young children, WISC-V for older), adaptive behavior (Vineland-3 or ABAS-3). (3) You have the RIGHT to be present during evaluations. (4) Ask evaluators to document strengths as well as challenges. (5) If your child is bilingual, request bilingual evaluator or interpreter — evaluation in one language only may underestimate abilities. (6) Share your videos and concerns journal with evaluators.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: When RC schedules evaluations, ask: \'Which professionals will evaluate my child? What specific tests will be administered? How many sessions?\'\nSTEP 2: Before each evaluation session, provide evaluators with: your Parent Concerns Letter, videos, milestone tracking notes, any medical records.\nSTEP 3: During evaluations, take notes on what you observe. Note anything that seems unusual about the testing environment or your child\'s behavior that day.\nSTEP 4: After evaluations are complete, request copies of ALL reports. You have a legal right to these. Say: \'I\'d like copies of all evaluation reports as soon as they\'re available, before the eligibility meeting.\'\nSTEP 5: Review reports carefully. If anything seems inaccurate, write a response letter to be included in the file.\n\nCONTACT: RC-CONTRACTED EVALUATORS: RC arranges these — you don\'t choose the providers, but you CAN request specific qualifications (e.g., bilingual, autism specialist).\nIF YOU DISAGREE WITH RC EVALUATION: You can request an Independent Evaluation — contact OCRA at (800) 390-7032.\nPRIVATE EVALUATION (OPTIONAL): If you want a second opinion or faster diagnosis, ask your pediatrician for referral to developmental pediatrician. UC Davis MIND Institute: (916) 703-0280. UCSF Autism Clinic: (415) 353-2101. Stanford Autism Center.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EVALUATION REPORTS (request copies of ALL):\n• Psychological/Cognitive evaluation report\n• Speech-Language evaluation report\n• Occupational Therapy evaluation report\n• Autism diagnostic report (ADOS-2 results)\n• Adaptive behavior assessment (Vineland-3)\n• Developmental history summary\n\nPARENT SHOULD PROVIDE:\n• Parent Concerns Letter\n• Video recordings\n• Medical records\n• Prior evaluations\n• Daycare/preschool reports\n\nTIMELINE: 120 CALENDAR DAYS from initial referral to RC eligibility determination. Evaluations should be completed well before this deadline to allow time for the eligibility meeting. If evaluations are delayed, call your Service Coordinator and say: \'I\'m tracking the 120-day timeline. When will evaluations be completed?\'\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept a diagnosis based on a single brief office visit — comprehensive evaluation typically requires 4-8 hours across multiple sessions. (2) Let evaluators see your child only at their best — if mornings are hard, schedule morning sessions. (3) Fail to mention all your concerns to every evaluator — each specialist needs the full picture. (4) Accept an evaluation conducted entirely in English if your child\'s primary language is different. (5) Skip sharing your videos — evaluators can\'t observe everything in a clinic setting.\n\nRISKS: ★ EVALUATION RISKS: (1) Evaluator not autism-qualified — may miss diagnosis or apply incorrect criteria. (2) ADOS-2 may miss girls/high-masking children — they score better on social items due to learned social strategies. (3) Bilingual child evaluated only in English — scores artificially depressed. (4) Evaluation conducted in unfamiliar clinical setting — child may perform differently than at home. (5) Evaluator relies on standardized tests only — misses real-world functional challenges. (6) Parent interview not thorough enough — evaluator doesn\'t understand home context.\n\nRESOURCES: UNDERSTANDING YOUR CHILD\'S EVALUATION:\n• Autism Speaks 100 Day Kit: autismspeaks.org/tool-kit\n• Undivided evaluation guide: undivided.io\n• ASHA parent resources on evaluation: asha.org/public\n• DRC guide to RC evaluations: disabilityrightsca.org\nPARENT TRAINING ON ADVOCACY:\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org\n• TASK: taskca.org — free workshops on evaluation and IEP\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: RC-contracted evaluators\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s23','journey-autism','step-23','Autism Step 2.3: Private Diagnostic Evaluation (Optional but Valuable)','Autism — Step 2.3: Private Diagnostic Evaluation (Optional but Valuable)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PURSUE PRIVATE EVALUATION IF: (1) RC evaluation is delayed or incomplete. (2) You want a more detailed assessment (neuropsychological). (3) You want a second opinion. (4) You need a faster diagnosis to begin insurance-authorized ABA. HOW: Ask pediatrician for referral to developmental pediatrician or neuropsychologist. Insurance may cover — check your plan\'s behavioral health or neurodevelopmental evaluation benefits. Medi-Cal covers developmental evaluations. Wait times: 3-12 months for developmental pediatrician, 2-8 weeks for private neuropsychologist.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Call your insurance company: \'Does my plan cover a neurodevelopmental or autism evaluation? What is my copay/coinsurance? Do I need a referral? Which providers are in-network?\'\nSTEP 2: Ask pediatrician for referral letter to developmental pediatrician or neuropsychologist.\nSTEP 3: Call 3-5 providers to compare wait times. Ask to be on cancellation lists.\nSTEP 4: When you get the appointment, bring ALL RC evaluation reports plus your documentation.\nSTEP 5: After private eval, share results with RC to support eligibility determination AND with school district for IEP.\n\nCONTACT: UNIVERSITY AUTISM CENTERS (CA):\n• UCSF Autism Clinic: (415) 353-2101\n• Stanford Autism Center: (650) 736-1235\n• UC Davis MIND Institute: (916) 703-0280\n• UCLA Autism Research: (310) 825-9011\n• Children\'s Hospital LA: (323) 361-2178\n• Rady Children\'s San Diego: (858) 576-1700\nFINDING CA EVALUATORS:\n• CA Psychological Association: cpapsych.org — find a psychologist\n• Psychology Today directory: psychologytoday.com — filter by \'autism evaluation\'\n• Your insurance provider directory\nINSURANCE COVERAGE:\n• Call number on back of card — ask for \'neurodevelopmental assessment\' or \'autism evaluation\' benefits\n• CA SB 946 requires commercial insurance to cover autism-related services\n\nDOCUMENTS: PRIVATE EVALUATION REPORTS:\n• Neuropsychological/developmental evaluation report\n• Autism diagnostic report with DSM-5 criteria\n• Recommendations for treatment\n\nINSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Referral from pediatrician\n• Insurance pre-authorization (if required)\n• EOB (Explanation of Benefits) after evaluation\n• Appeal materials if denied\n\nTIMELINE: Private wait times: 3-12 months for developmental pediatrician. 2-8 weeks for private neuropsychologist. Insurance pre-auth: 5-15 business days. CANCEL LIST: Always ask to be on cancellation list — significantly reduces wait.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Assume private eval replaces RC eval — you need BOTH for different purposes (private = clinical diagnosis for insurance; RC = Lanterman eligibility for RC services). (2) Pay $3K-$6K out of pocket without checking insurance first. (3) Assume a long waitlist means no options — call multiple providers and ask to be put on cancellation lists. (4) Use an evaluator who is not autism-qualified (look for ADOS-2 certified).\n\nRISKS: Insurance denies authorization. Long waitlists. Cost $2K-$6K out of pocket if uninsured. Private eval may use different criteria than RC. Results may not match RC findings. Medi-Cal covers but reimbursement rates low (fewer providers accept).\n\nRESOURCES: INSURANCE NAVIGATION:\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org — free insurance help\n• Medi-Cal Ombudsman: (888) 452-8609\n• DMHC Help Center: (888) 466-2219 (HMO plans)\n• CDI Consumer Hotline: (800) 927-4357 (PPO plans)\nEVALUATION PREPARATION:\n• Autism Speaks First Concern to Action: autismspeaks.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Provider / Insurance\nOTHER AGENCIES: Medi-Cal\nPediatrician (referral)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s24','journey-autism','step-24','Autism Step 2.4: Eligibility Determination (RC Decision)','Autism — Step 2.4: Eligibility Determination (RC Decision)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PREPARE FOR ELIGIBILITY MEETING: (1) Request copies of ALL evaluation reports at least 5 days before the meeting. (2) Review reports carefully — look for: DSM-5 autism diagnosis (299.00), severity level (Level 1/2/3), adaptive behavior scores (Vineland-3 composite), cognitive scores, speech-language findings. (3) Write a summary of any disagreements or corrections to the reports. (4) You may bring a support person (advocate, family member, friend) to the meeting. (5) If child is found eligible: immediately ask about service coordinator assignment, IPP scheduling, and interim services. (6) If child is found NOT eligible: do NOT accept this without understanding why and knowing your appeal rights.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: 2 weeks before eligibility meeting, call your RC contact: \'I\'d like copies of all evaluation reports mailed/emailed to me at least 5 business days before the eligibility meeting.\'\nSTEP 2: Review all reports. Highlight anything you disagree with. Note your questions.\nSTEP 3: At the meeting, take notes (or bring someone to take notes). Ask: \'Based on these evaluations, is my child eligible for Regional Center services under the autism category?\'\nSTEP 4: IF ELIGIBLE: Ask: \'Who is my Service Coordinator? When will we schedule the IPP meeting? Can we begin receiving services immediately?\' (RC must develop IPP within 60 days.)\nSTEP 5: IF DENIED: Say: \'I disagree with this determination. Please provide me with a written notice of denial with the specific reasons, and information about my fair hearing rights.\' You have 30 days to request a fair hearing.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER: Your assigned intake coordinator or service coordinator.\nIF DENIED — APPEAL HELP:\n• OCRA (Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy): (800) 390-7032 — FREE legal help with RC appeals\n• Disability Rights California: (800) 776-5746\n• Fair Hearing request: File with DDS Office of Administrative Hearings\nFOR ADVOCACY SUPPORT:\n• Undivided: undivided.io (free navigator)\n• Your local Family Resource Center: frcnca.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: RC PROVIDES AT ELIGIBILITY MEETING:\n• Eligibility determination letter\n• All evaluation reports (you should already have these)\n• Rights notification\n• If eligible: Service Coordinator assignment\n• If denied: Written denial with reasons and fair hearing rights\n\nPARENT SHOULD HAVE:\n• Copies of all evaluation reports (reviewed)\n• Your questions/disagreements written down\n• Parent Concerns Letter (updated)\n• Support person if desired\n\nTIMELINE: 120 CALENDAR DAYS from initial referral to eligibility determination (Lanterman Act mandate). If RC misses this deadline: call OCRA at (800) 390-7032. RC must provide written determination. If eligible, IPP meeting within 60 days of eligibility.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Go to the eligibility meeting without having read the reports first. (2) Accept denial without requesting a written explanation (Prior Written Notice equivalent). (3) Assume denial is final — you have appeal rights including fair hearing. (4) Sign anything you don\'t understand — ask for time to review. (5) Agree to \'provisional eligibility\' without understanding what it means for services.\n\nRISKS: ★ ELIGIBILITY RISKS: (1) Denied eligibility despite clinical diagnosis — RC uses narrower criteria than DSM-5 in some cases. (2) \'Provisional eligibility\' for ages 3-4 — may be used to delay full services. (3) Service Coordinator assigned with 60-80 caseload — limited attention to your child. (4) POS spending disparities: White families receive ~2x more in services than Black/Latino families. (5) Family doesn\'t understand the difference between RC eligibility and school IEP eligibility — BOTH are needed.\n\nRESOURCES: RC RIGHTS AND APPEALS:\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032 — free attorney assistance\n• DRC Fair Hearing Guide: disabilityrightsca.org\n• SERR Manual Chapter on RC: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\n• Lanterman Act full text: leginfo.legislature.ca.gov\nPEER SUPPORT:\n• Parents of autistic children who\'ve been through RC: connect through FRCNCA, Undivided, or local autism parent groups\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: DDS (oversight)\nOCRA (if appeal needed)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s31','journey-autism','step-31','Autism Step 3.1: IPP Development (Initial Service Plan)','Autism — Step 3.1: IPP Development (Initial Service Plan)\n\nWHAT TO DO: MAXIMIZE YOUR IPP: (1) IPP (Individual Program Plan) is your child\'s service plan at RC — equivalent to an IEP at school but for community/home services. (2) Before the IPP meeting, make a written list of EVERYTHING your child needs: ABA therapy (hours per week), speech therapy, occupational therapy, respite care, parent training, social skills, adaptive behavior support, crisis services. (3) Research what services RC CAN provide (visit dds.ca.gov or ask other parents). (4) At the meeting, present your list and advocate for each item. (5) IPP goals should be SPECIFIC, MEASURABLE, and TIME-BOUND. (6) Know that RC POS (Purchase of Service) spending should be equitable — if you\'re a family of color, you may need to advocate harder due to documented spending disparities.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: 2 weeks before IPP, prepare a written \'Parent Service Request\' listing: requested services, hours/frequency, justification for each. Example: \'Requesting 20 hours/week ABA therapy — evaluation documents significant behavioral and adaptive skill deficits requiring intensive intervention.\'\nSTEP 2: At IPP meeting, present your list. For each item, ask: \'Will this service be included in the IPP? If not, please document the reason for denial in writing.\'\nSTEP 3: Review proposed IPP goals. For each goal, ask: \'How will we measure progress? What is the specific target? By when?\'\nSTEP 4: Before signing, ask: \'Can I take this home to review? I have 30 days to sign.\' Review with an advocate or other parents.\nSTEP 5: Once IPP is signed, ask: \'How quickly will services begin? Who are the approved providers? Can I choose my ABA company?\'\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER SERVICE COORDINATOR: Your assigned SC manages your IPP — get their direct number and email.\nABA PROVIDERS: RC provides a vendor list. Ask for multiple options and interview providers before choosing.\nRESPITE AGENCIES: RC provides vendor list for respite workers.\nIF SC IS UNRESPONSIVE: Contact RC supervisor. If still unresponsive, contact OCRA: (800) 390-7032.\nPOS SPENDING DATA: dds.ca.gov/rc/purchase-of-service-data — check how your RC spends relative to demographics.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IPP DOCUMENTS:\n• Written IPP (your copy — keep in file)\n• Service authorization letters for each service\n• Provider vendor list\n• POS codes for authorized services\n• Parent rights notification\n\nPARENT SHOULD PREPARE:\n• Written Service Request letter\n• List of requested services with justifications\n• Questions about each proposed goal\n• Research on available services\n\nTIMELINE: IPP meeting within 60 DAYS of eligibility determination. IPP reviewed at least ANNUALLY. Parent can request IPP meeting at ANY time if needs change. Services should begin within 30 days of signed IPP (though ABA waitlists may cause delays).\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept whatever the SC offers without advocating for what your child needs. (2) Agree to vague goals (\'improve communication\') — demand measurable goals (\'Child will use 50 functional words in 3 months\'). (3) Let RC say \'school will provide that\' for services RC should fund (e.g., ABA, respite, parent training). (4) Sign the IPP if you disagree — you can request changes and have 30 days to sign. (5) Assume the SC will proactively offer all available services — many families don\'t receive services they\'re entitled to because they don\'t know to ask.\n\nRISKS: ★ IPP SERVICE GAPS: (1) SC doesn\'t inform parent of all available services — parent gets only what SC offers, not what child needs. (2) POS spending disparities well-documented — White families receive ~$14K more in services per year than Latino families at many RCs. (3) ABA hours approved at lower level than recommended. (4) Respite denied or given minimal hours. (5) Parent training not offered. (6) IPP goals too vague to measure progress. (7) SC caseload 60-80 clients — limited time for advocacy.\n\nRESOURCES: IPP PREPARATION:\n• Undivided IPP guide: undivided.io\n• DRC IPP rights guide: disabilityrightsca.org\n• SERR Manual: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\n• POS spending equity data: dds.ca.gov\nPARENT TRAINING ON ADVOCACY:\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org\n• TASK: taskca.org\n• Autism Society of America: autism-society.org\n• Local ABA company parent training programs\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\n(Service Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Therapy providers\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s32','journey-autism','step-32','Autism Step 3.2: Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE (Full Benefits Package)','Autism — Step 3.2: Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE (Full Benefits Package)\n\nWHAT TO DO: APPLY FOR ALL FOUR BENEFITS SIMULTANEOUSLY: (1) MEDI-CAL: RC eligibility often opens HCBS-DD waiver pathway — only child\'s income counts (institutional deeming). Apply at coveredca.com or county social services office. (2) SSI: Apply at ssa.gov or local SSA office. For autism, the Function Report is CRITICAL — describe WORST day, not average day. High initial denial rate — plan to appeal. (3) IHSS: Apply at county IHSS office. Requires Medi-Cal. County worker does in-home assessment. Parent CAN be paid provider. Request protective supervision if applicable. (4) CalABLE: Open account at calable.ca.gov — no minimum age, $19K/year, doesn\'t affect SSI under $100K.\n\nHOW TO ACT: MEDI-CAL: Apply online at coveredca.com or call (800) 300-1506. Contact your county social services office.\nSSI: Apply at ssa.gov/benefits/disability or call (800) 772-1213. Bring: birth certificate, medical records, evaluation reports, school records.\nIHSS: Apply at your county Social Services: your county IHSS office — cdss.ca.gov. Bring: Medi-Cal card, medical certification form (SOC 873), physician statement.\nCalABLE: Open at calable.ca.gov (online, takes 15 minutes). Need: SSN, proof of disability.\nSTEP-BY-STEP: Start all 4 applications within the same week. Track each separately.\n\nCONTACT: MEDI-CAL:\n• Covered California: coveredca.com or (800) 300-1506\n• Your county social services office\nSSI:\n• SSA: ssa.gov or (800) 772-1213\n• Local SSA office (California): 150 Frank H Ogawa Plaza, California 94612\nIHSS:\n• your county IHSS: your county IHSS office — cdss.ca.gov\n• IHSS Helpline: ihssunion.org for provider resources\nCalABLE:\n• calable.ca.gov (online enrollment)\nHELP WITH APPLICATIONS:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: MEDI-CAL: Application, income documentation, residency proof\nSSI: Application, medical evidence, Function Report (SSA-3375), financial disclosure\nIHSS: Application (SOC 295), Medical Certification (SOC 873), physician statement, Medi-Cal enrollment proof\nCalABLE: Online application, SSN, disability documentation\n\nKEEP COPIES OF EVERYTHING. Create a \'Benefits\' folder with subfolders for each program.\n\nTIMELINE: Medi-Cal: 45 days for determination. SSI: 3-6 months (plan for appeal). IHSS: 30-60 days from application to assessment. CalABLE: Immediate enrollment online. START ALL FOUR THIS WEEK.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Understate your child\'s challenges on SSI Function Report — describe the WORST day, not the best. (2) Skip IHSS because you don\'t know about it — many autism families qualify. (3) Forget CalABLE — open it immediately regardless of child\'s age. (4) Assume SSI denial is final — appeal rates are high and many win on appeal. (5) Let one application delay another — apply for all four simultaneously.\n\nRISKS: ★ SSI denied initially (common — ~60% denial rate). Function Report is too positive. IHSS protective supervision denied. Medi-Cal redetermination causes gaps. CalABLE not opened early. Benefits interactions complex (SSI + IHSS + Medi-Cal). Parent doesn\'t know they can be paid IHSS provider.\n\nRESOURCES: BENEFITS HELP:\n• DRC SSI Guide: disabilityrightsca.org\n• SSI denied? DRC Appeal Help: (800) 776-5746\n• IHSS Advocacy: Personal Assistance Services Council\n• CalABLE Info: calable.ca.gov/faqs\n• Benefits calculator: db101.org (Disability Benefits 101)\nPARENT TRAINING:\n• Undivided benefits webinars: undivided.io\n• Matrix Parent Network benefits training\n• TASK benefits workshops: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SSA (SSI)\nDHCS (Medi-Cal)\nCounty IHSS\nCalABLE\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s41','journey-autism','step-41','Autism Step 4.1: Request School District Evaluation (Written Request)','Autism — Step 4.1: Request School District Evaluation (Written Request)\n\nWHAT TO DO: SEND WRITTEN EVALUATION REQUEST: (1) Write a letter to your school district\'s Special Education Department requesting a comprehensive evaluation. This triggers legal timelines. (2) Be SPECIFIC about areas of concern: social communication, restricted/repetitive behaviors, sensory processing, adaptive behavior, academic readiness, speech-language, fine/gross motor. (3) Hand-deliver the letter AND send by email — keep copies of both with date stamps. (4) District must respond with an assessment plan within 15 CALENDAR DAYS. (5) You do NOT need the district\'s permission, teacher\'s agreement, or to wait for RTI. (6) Share RC evaluation reports with the school — they\'re required to consider them.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Write your evaluation request letter. Include: child\'s name, DOB, school, your specific concerns, request for \'comprehensive psychoeducational evaluation in all areas of suspected disability including but not limited to: cognitive, academic, speech-language, occupational therapy, social-emotional, adaptive behavior, and autism-specific assessment.\'\nSTEP 2: Hand-deliver to school office AND email to Special Education Director. Get a date-stamped receipt.\nSTEP 3: Mark calendar: 15 days from delivery = deadline for assessment plan. If no plan received, send follow-up: \'I sent my evaluation request on [date]. Under California law, you have 15 calendar days to provide an assessment plan. Please respond immediately.\'\nSTEP 4: Review assessment plan. If it doesn\'t include all areas, write back: \'I request the following areas be added to the assessment plan: [list areas].\'\nSTEP 5: Sign the plan only after all requested areas are included. 60-day assessment clock starts when you sign.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION DEPARTMENT: Find contact at your district\'s website under \'Special Education\' or \'Student Services.\'\nYOUR LOCAL SCHOOL DISTRICT: Special Education, 1000 Broadway Suite 680, California, CA 94607. Phone: your district SpEd office. Email: specialeducation@your local school district.org\nSELPA (Special Education Local Plan Area): Your district\'s SELPA handles dispute resolution.\nFREE ADVOCACY:\n• Disability Rights California: (800) 776-5746\n• DRC SERR Manual: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\n• Community Alliance for Special Education (CASE): caseadvocacy.org (Bay Area)\n• DREDF: dredf.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter (dated, keep copy)\n• Date-stamped delivery confirmation\n• Email copy with read receipt\n\nDISTRICT PROVIDES:\n• Assessment plan (within 15 days)\n• Parent rights notification (procedural safeguards)\n• Prior Written Notice if refusing evaluation\n\nSHARE WITH DISTRICT:\n• RC evaluation reports\n• Private evaluation reports\n• Medical records\n• Parent Concerns Letter\n\nTIMELINE: 15 CALENDAR DAYS: District must provide assessment plan after receiving written request.\n60 CALENDAR DAYS: From signed consent to completed evaluation (excluding school breaks >5 days).\n30 CALENDAR DAYS: From completed evaluation to IEP meeting.\nNO DEADLINE TO REQUEST: Parent can request evaluation at any time during the school year.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Make a verbal request only — it MUST be in writing to trigger legal timelines. (2) Let district say \'wait until next year\' or \'let\'s try the classroom first.\' (3) Accept an assessment plan that doesn\'t cover ALL areas of suspected disability. (4) Sign the assessment plan without reviewing it — you can request additions. (5) Assume school IEP replaces RC services — these are SEPARATE systems.\n\nRISKS: ★ SCHOOL BARRIERS: (1) District delays response beyond 15 days. (2) Assessment plan too narrow — misses OT, adaptive behavior, or autism-specific testing. (3) District says \'we need RTI data first\' — ILLEGAL to delay parent-requested evaluation for RTI. (4) Parent makes verbal request only — no paper trail. (5) District doesn\'t share assessment plan or parent rights. (6) District doesn\'t accept RC evaluations. (7) Assessment not conducted in child\'s primary language.\n\nRESOURCES: EVALUATION REQUEST HELP:\n• CASE (Community Alliance for Special Education): caseadvocacy.org — free advocacy, Bay Area\n• DREDF: dredf.org — free advocacy\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal help\n• TASK: taskca.org — free parent training\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org — Bay Area IEP training\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com — comprehensive SpEd law resource\n• Understood: understood.org — parent-friendly IEP guides\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\n(transition if under 3)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s42','journey-autism','step-42','Autism Step 4.2: School District Evaluation & IEP Development','Autism — Step 4.2: School District Evaluation & IEP Development\n\nWHAT TO DO: PREPARE FOR AND PARTICIPATE IN EVALUATION AND IEP: (1) School psychologist conducts evaluation (cognitive, academic, social-emotional, adaptive). SLP evaluates communication. OT evaluates sensory/motor. (2) Provide school with RC reports, private evaluations, and your documentation. (3) After evaluation is complete, REQUEST REPORTS 5 days before IEP meeting. Review carefully. (4) At IEP meeting, advocate for: autism eligibility category, speech therapy, OT, behavioral support (BIP if needed), 1:1 aide if appropriate, specialized academic instruction, ESY (extended school year), and APPROPRIATE placement (LRE). (5) Bring a support person — advocate, spouse, friend who takes notes. (6) If you disagree with the IEP offer, you do NOT have to sign — request a continuation meeting.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: After evaluation, call school: \'When is the IEP meeting scheduled? I\'d like copies of all reports at least 5 business days before.\'\nSTEP 2: Read reports. Highlight areas of concern and disagreement.\nSTEP 3: Write an IEP preparation letter listing: your priorities, requested services, placement preference, specific goals you want addressed.\nSTEP 4: At IEP meeting: introduce your support person, present your priorities, review each goal, ask about placement options.\nSTEP 5: For each proposed goal, ask: \'How will this be measured? How often? What happens if my child doesn\'t make progress?\'\nSTEP 6: If satisfied, you may sign. If not: \'I\'d like to take this home to review. When can we schedule a follow-up meeting?\'\nSTEP 7: After IEP is signed, confirm: \'When do services begin? Who are the providers? How will I receive progress reports?\'\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT IEP TEAM: Teacher, school psychologist, special ed coordinator, SLP, OT, and parent.\nADVOCACY SUPPORT:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP meeting advocate (Bay Area)\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• TASK: taskca.org — IEP training and coaching\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com\nIF DISPUTE:\n• CDE Complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n• Mediation/Due Process: OAH at dgs.ca.gov/OAH\n• SELPA for your district\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP DOCUMENTS (district provides):\n• IEP document (full written plan)\n• Assessment reports (psych, SLP, OT, etc.)\n• Prior Written Notice of any decisions\n• Parent rights (Procedural Safeguards)\n• Behavioral Intervention Plan (BIP) if applicable\n• ESY eligibility determination\n• Placement offer letter\n\nPARENT SHOULD BRING:\n• RC IPP (for coordination)\n• Parent Concerns Letter\n• Requested services list\n• Prior evaluations\n• Work samples/videos\n\nTIMELINE: 30 CALENDAR DAYS from completed evaluation to IEP meeting. IEP reviewed ANNUALLY. Triennial re-evaluation every 3 years. Parent can request IEP meeting at ANY time.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Go to the IEP meeting without reading reports first. (2) Go alone — bring support. (3) Accept an IEP that doesn\'t match your child\'s evaluation results. (4) Accept vague goals. (5) Accept a placement without visiting the classroom first. (6) Sign the IEP if you disagree — you can request time to review. (7) Forget to coordinate IEP services with RC IPP services.\n\nRISKS: ★ IEP RISKS: (1) School offers minimal services. (2) Goals not measurable or ambitious enough. (3) Placement too restrictive (segregated) OR not enough support (dumped in gen ed without services). (4) No coordination between IEP and RC IPP. (5) Parent overwhelmed in meeting. (6) ESY denied despite regression evidence. (7) BIP based on compliance rather than understanding function of behavior.\n\nRESOURCES: IEP PREPARATION:\n• CASE IEP training: caseadvocacy.org\n• Wrightslaw IEP guide: wrightslaw.com/info/iep.index.htm\n• Understood IEP guide: understood.org\n• TASK IEP workshops: taskca.org\n• DRC IEP rights: disabilityrightsca.org\n• Matrix IEP training: matrixparents.org\nBOOKS:\n• \'From Emotions to Advocacy\' by Pam Wright\n• \'The Complete IEP Guide\' by Lawrence Siegel\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nParent advocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s43','journey-autism','step-43','Autism Step 4.3: IEP Dispute Resolution (If Needed)','Autism — Step 4.3: IEP Dispute Resolution (If Needed)\n\nWHAT TO DO: IF YOU DISAGREE WITH THE IEP: (1) First try informal resolution — request another IEP meeting. Put disagreements in writing. (2) If informal fails, you have 4 formal options: (a) CDE State Complaint: file at cde.ca.gov — CDE investigates within 60 days. Free, no attorney needed. (b) Mediation: voluntary, conducted by OAH mediator. Free. Often resolves disputes. (c) Due Process Hearing: formal legal proceeding through OAH. 45 days to hearing. Attorney strongly recommended. (d) ADR (Alternative Dispute Resolution): your district may offer this. (3) You may request IEE (Independent Educational Evaluation) at district expense if you disagree with their evaluation. (4) Consider contacting DRC for free legal assistance — especially for low-income families.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Put your disagreement in writing: \'I disagree with [specific aspect] of the IEP proposed on [date]. I request [specific remedy].\'\nSTEP 2: Request another IEP meeting to try to resolve informally.\nSTEP 3: If no resolution, choose your path:\n  • CDE Complaint: File at cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — free online form.\n  • Mediation: Request through OAH at dgs.ca.gov/OAH — free, often effective.\n  • Due Process: File at OAH — strongly recommend consulting DRC first: (800) 776-5746.\nSTEP 4: Throughout, DOCUMENT EVERYTHING — save emails, keep notes of conversations with dates.\n\nCONTACT: CDE COMPLIANCE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp (online filing)\nOAH (OFFICE OF ADMINISTRATIVE HEARINGS): dgs.ca.gov/OAH — for mediation and due process. Phone: (916) 263-0880.\nDISABILITY RIGHTS CALIFORNIA: (800) 776-5746 — free legal help, priority for low-income families.\nCASE: caseadvocacy.org — free advocacy support (Bay Area)\nDREDF: dredf.org — free legal advocacy\nSELPA: Contact your district\'s SELPA for local dispute resolution.\nSPECIAL ED ATTORNEYS (if needed): CASE, DRC, or Education Law referral through your local bar association.\n\nDOCUMENTS: DISPUTE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written disagreement letter (dated)\n• Prior Written Notice request\n• CDE complaint form (if filing)\n• OAH mediation/due process request\n• IEE request letter (if applicable)\n• Complete documentation binder (all IEP records, evaluations, correspondence)\n\nTIMELINES:\n• CDE complaint: 60 days to investigate\n• Due process: hearing within 45 days of filing\n• Statute of limitations: 2 years from known violation\n• IEE: District must respond (pay or file due process)\n\nTIMELINE: CDE complaint: 60 days to investigate. Mediation: scheduled within weeks. Due process: hearing within 45 days of filing. 2-YEAR statute of limitations on complaints. IEE: district must respond within reasonable time.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Give up because you\'re intimidated by the process. (2) File due process without trying other options first (it\'s adversarial and stressful). (3) Miss the 2-year statute of limitations for filing. (4) Accept retaliation — it\'s illegal for the district to retaliate against you for advocating. (5) Sign an IEP you disagree with — you lose leverage.\n\nRISKS: ★ Parent doesn\'t know appeal rights. District pressures parent to sign. Attorney fees $300-600/hr prohibitive. Emotional toll of adversarial process. 2-year statute of limitations passes. District retaliates (illegal but happens).\n\nRESOURCES: DISPUTE RESOLUTION TRAINING:\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com/info/disres.index.htm\n• DRC: disabilityrightsca.org\n• CASE advocacy training: caseadvocacy.org\n• CDE dispute resolution info: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/\n• CADRE (Consortium for Dispute Resolution): directionservice.org/cadre\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District /\nCDE / OAH\nOTHER AGENCIES: DRC\nSpecial Ed Attorney\nParent advocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s51','journey-autism','step-51','Autism Step 5.1: Insurance Authorization for ABA Therapy','Autism — Step 5.1: Insurance Authorization for ABA Therapy\n\nWHAT TO DO: GET ABA THERAPY AUTHORIZED: (1) California law (SB 946) mandates health insurance coverage for behavioral health treatment (ABA) for autism — this includes Medi-Cal managed care plans. (2) Get physician referral/prescription for ABA from your pediatrician: \'My child has an autism diagnosis and I\'m requesting a referral for ABA therapy.\' (3) Call your insurance company: \'I need to start the prior authorization process for ABA therapy for my child who has an autism diagnosis.\' (4) Choose an ABA provider — ask RC for their vendor list, also check insurance provider directory. Interview 2-3 providers before selecting. (5) ABA provider submits treatment plan to insurance. Typical request: 10-40 hours/week depending on severity. (6) If authorized, confirm: hours approved, duration, renewal process. (7) If denied, appeal immediately — CA parity law is strong.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Get ABA referral from pediatrician (1 phone call — \'I need an ABA referral for my autistic child\').\nSTEP 2: Call insurance (number on card): \'I need to begin prior authorization for ABA therapy. What is the process? What documentation is needed?\'\nSTEP 3: Search for ABA providers: (a) Insurance provider directory, (b) RC vendor list, (c) bacb.com (BACB registry of certified analysts).\nSTEP 4: Interview 2-3 ABA providers. Ask: \'What is your supervision model? What is the BCBA-to-client ratio? Do you use naturalistic teaching? How do you involve parents? What does a typical session look like?\'\nSTEP 5: Selected provider submits treatment plan to insurance. Insurance has 5-15 business days for prior authorization.\nSTEP 6: If APPROVED: confirm hours, start date, authorization period. If DENIED: appeal immediately — contact DRC or Health Consumer Alliance for free help.\n\nCONTACT: INSURANCE COMPANY: Call number on back of insurance card. Ask for \'behavioral health prior authorization.\'\nMEDI-CAL MANAGED CARE: Each plan has its own ABA authorization process. Alameda Alliance: (510) 747-4500.\nABA PROVIDER SEARCH:\n• BACB registry: bacb.com/find-a-certificant\n• Insurance provider directory (online)\n• RC vendor list (ask Service Coordinator)\nIF DENIED:\n• DMHC (HMO plans): (888) 466-2219 — Independent Medical Review\n• CDI (PPO plans): (800) 927-4357\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org — free help\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n\nDOCUMENTS: INSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Physician referral for ABA\n• Autism diagnosis report\n• ABA treatment plan (from provider)\n• Prior authorization request\n• Authorization approval letter\n• If denied: denial letter, appeal letter, medical necessity evidence\n\nKEEP TRACKING:\n• Authorization start/end dates\n• Hours approved vs hours used\n• Renewal deadlines\n• Progress reports from provider\n\nTIMELINE: Prior auth: 5-15 business days. If denied, internal appeal: 30 days. DMHC Independent Medical Review: 45 days. Urgent review: 72 hours. Authorization renewal: typically every 6-12 months.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept denial without appealing — CA law mandates ABA coverage for autism. (2) Wait for RC to provide ABA — insurance should be billed first (RC is payer of last resort). (3) Choose the first ABA provider without interviewing others. (4) Assume \'ABA\' means one thing — quality varies enormously. Ask about their approach, qualifications, supervision ratios. (5) Let ABA hours be less than what the evaluation recommends without documented justification.\n\nRISKS: ★ Authorization denied despite CA parity law. Insufficient hours approved. Provider not in-network. Medi-Cal managed care barriers. ABA waitlists 3-6 months. Quality varies enormously across providers. Authorization gaps between renewals.\n\nRESOURCES: INSURANCE HELP:\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org — free insurance advocacy\n• DMHC Help Center: (888) 466-2219\n• CDI Consumer Hotline: (800) 927-4357\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\nABA QUALITY GUIDE:\n• Autism Speaks ABA guide: autismspeaks.org\n• BACB: bacb.com\n• Association for Behavior Analysis International: abainternational.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Insurance /\nMedi-Cal\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nABA provider\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s52','journey-autism','step-52','Autism Step 5.2: Begin and Coordinate All Therapy Services','Autism — Step 5.2: Begin and Coordinate All Therapy Services\n\nWHAT TO DO: COORDINATE YOUR CHILD\'S FULL SERVICE PACKAGE: (1) Your child may receive services from 3-4 DIFFERENT payers simultaneously: insurance-billed ABA, RC-vendored services (respite, parent training), school district IEP services (speech, OT, SDI), and potentially private pay therapies. (2) Create a MASTER SCHEDULE that accounts for all services without conflicts. (3) Ensure all providers communicate — school SLP, private ABA team, RC service coordinator should all know what others are doing. (4) You are the HUB of coordination — no one else will do this for you. (5) Track authorization dates, progress reports, and renewal deadlines for each payer.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Create a spreadsheet or use a planner with: Service | Provider | Payer | Schedule | Auth dates | Renewal deadline | Progress report due dates.\nSTEP 2: Share your child\'s full service schedule with every provider. Ask each provider: \'Are you aware of my child\'s other services? How will you coordinate?\'\nSTEP 3: Set calendar reminders for ALL renewal deadlines (at 60, 30, and 15 days before expiration).\nSTEP 4: Request progress reports from every provider quarterly. Compare progress across settings.\nSTEP 5: Hold a quarterly \'coordination call\' or email update with all providers.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR SERVICE COORDINATOR HUB:\n• ABA Provider: BCBA supervisor (get direct number)\n• RC Service Coordinator: direct number and email\n• School IEP Case Manager: direct number and email\n• Private therapists (if applicable): direct contacts\nCOORDINATION TOOLS:\n• Google Calendar shared with providers\n• Binder or digital folder organized by provider\n\nDOCUMENTS: SERVICE TRACKING DOCUMENTS:\n• Master service schedule (all providers/payers)\n• Authorization letters (all payers)\n• Progress reports (quarterly from each provider)\n• Renewal deadline calendar\n• Insurance EOBs (Explanations of Benefits)\n• RC service authorization letters\n• IEP service page\n\nCREATE A \'SERVICE BINDER\' with sections for: Insurance, RC, School, Private, Medical\n\nTIMELINE: ABA waitlists: 2-6 months. Other services typically begin within 30 days of authorization. Insurance re-auth: every 3-12 months. IEP services: begin upon consent. RC services: begin upon IPP signing.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Let services overlap without coordination (e.g., school speech goals and private speech goals should align). (2) Miss authorization renewal deadlines — services stop if authorization expires. (3) Assume one provider knows what another is doing — they usually don\'t communicate unless you facilitate. (4) Over-schedule your child — leave time for play, family, and rest. (5) Forget to track which payer covers which service.\n\nRISKS: Provider waitlists. Scheduling conflicts. Authorization gaps. Billing disputes. Providers don\'t communicate. Parent burnout from coordination burden. One change cascades across agencies.\n\nRESOURCES: MANAGING MULTIPLE SERVICES:\n• Undivided: undivided.io — service coordination tools\n• Autism Speaks Resource Guide: autismspeaks.org/resource-guide\n• Your ABA company\'s parent coordinator\nSELF-CARE FOR PARENTS:\n• FRCNCA support groups: frcnca.org\n• Autism parent support: autismspeaks.org/family-services\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Multiple providers\nand payers\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nRC\nMedi-Cal\nSchool District\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s61','journey-autism','step-61','Autism Step 6.1: CalABLE, SNT & Age-18 Planning','Autism — Step 6.1: CalABLE, SNT & Age-18 Planning\n\nWHAT TO DO: LONG-TERM FINANCIAL AND LEGAL PLANNING: (1) CalABLE: Open account at calable.ca.gov immediately — no minimum age. Save up to $19K/year. Balances under $100K don\'t affect SSI. Tax-advantaged growth. (2) Special Needs Trust (SNT): If your child will receive inheritances or large gifts, SNT protects SSI/Medi-Cal eligibility. Consult an SNT attorney ($2K-$5K to establish). (3) AT AGE 18: (a) SSI re-evaluation (child → adult criteria — PREPARE), (b) Conservatorship vs Supported Decision-Making decision, (c) Transition to adult RC services. (4) Start planning for age 18 by age 16. (5) Consider: Letter of Intent (non-legal document describing your child\'s daily life, preferences, needs — for future caregivers).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: CalABLE — go to calable.ca.gov TODAY. Click \'Open an Account.\' Takes 15 minutes. Fund with even $25/month.\nSTEP 2: By age 14, consult an SNT attorney. Ask your RC Service Coordinator or DRC for referrals to disability-focused estate planning attorneys.\nSTEP 3: By age 16, begin age-18 planning: conservatorship vs SDM research. Read DRC\'s guide at disabilityrightsca.org.\nSTEP 4: By age 17, if pursuing conservatorship, retain attorney and file petition. If pursuing SDM, create SDM agreement with your child.\nSTEP 5: 6 months before 18th birthday: prepare for SSI adult redetermination. Update medical evidence, gather school records, prepare new Function Report.\n\nCONTACT: INSURANCE AUTHORIZATION:\n• CA SB 946: Commercial insurance MUST cover behavioral health treatment (ABA) for autism. No age cap, no visit limit, no dollar cap.\n• DMHC (HMO complaints): (888) 466-2219 — file complaint if HMO denies ABA.\n• CDI (PPO complaints): (800) 927-4357 — file complaint if PPO denies.\n• Medi-Cal: Covers ABA through managed care plans and regional center.\nFINDING ABA PROVIDERS:\n• BACB registry: bacb.com — find certified behavior analysts by ZIP.\n• Your insurance provider directory.\n• Regional Center service coordinator — can help find vendored providers.\nAPPEAL DENIALS:\n• Always appeal in writing within 30 days.\n• DMHC/CDI Independent Medical Review: free, binding on insurer.\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — insurance advocacy help.\n\nDOCUMENTS: FINANCIAL/LEGAL DOCUMENTS:\n• CalABLE account confirmation\n• SNT trust document (if applicable)\n• Letter of Intent (informal but critical)\n• Conservatorship petition OR SDM agreement\n• SSI adult redetermination materials\n• Updated medical evidence for age-18 SSI\n• Power of Attorney (if applicable)\n• ABLE account contribution records\n\nTIMELINE: CalABLE: Open NOW (no minimum age). SNT: Consult attorney by age 14. Conservatorship: Begin process 12-18 months before 18th birthday. SSI age-18 redetermination: Prepare 6 months before. Start ITP (transition plan) in IEP by age 14-16.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Skip CalABLE — every year of delay is lost tax-advantaged saving. (2) Put money in your child\'s name without SNT — it can disqualify them from SSI/Medi-Cal. (3) Wait until 17 to plan for age 18 — conservatorship takes 6-12 months to process. (4) Default to full conservatorship without considering SDM (Supported Decision-Making). (5) Forget the Letter of Intent — it\'s not legally binding but invaluable.\n\nRISKS: ★ CalABLE not opened early. SNT not established — inheritance disqualifies benefits. Conservatorship pursued as default without considering SDM. SSI re-evaluation at 18 catches family off guard. Full conservatorship when limited would suffice. Costs of conservatorship ($3K-5K).\n\nRESOURCES: FINANCIAL PLANNING:\n• CalABLE webinars: calable.ca.gov\n• SNT training: NAELA (naela.org) — find disability estate planning attorneys\n• DRC publications: disabilityrightsca.org\n• The Arc future planning: thearc.org/our-initiatives\n• Disability Benefits 101: db101.org\n• Undivided financial planning: undivided.io\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: CalABLE / SSA /\nSNT Attorney /\nSuperior Court\nOTHER AGENCIES: RC (adult transition)\nDRC\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-autism-s62','journey-autism','step-62','Autism Step 6.2: Ongoing Authorization Renewals, Reviews & Lifetime Management','Autism — Step 6.2: Ongoing Authorization Renewals, Reviews & Lifetime Management\n\nWHAT TO DO: MANAGE THE ONGOING SYSTEM PERMANENTLY: (1) Create a MASTER DEADLINE CALENDAR for: insurance re-auth (every 3-12 months), IHSS annual reassessment, SSI CDR (every 1-7 years), Medi-Cal annual redetermination, IEP annual review (every 12 months), IPP annual review (every 12 months), triennial re-evaluation (every 3 years). (2) Set reminders at 60, 30, and 15 days before each deadline. (3) Attend every annual IEP and IPP meeting prepared with updated concerns and goals. (4) Request progress reports quarterly from all providers. (5) Track any SERVICE CHANGES across agencies — one change often affects others. (6) Keep your \'Service Binder\' updated continuously.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Create a digital calendar (Google Calendar) with ALL deadlines. Share with spouse/co-parent.\nSTEP 2: Create a \'Renewal Prep\' checklist for each agency.\nSTEP 3: 60 days before each deadline, begin gathering updated documentation.\nSTEP 4: 30 days before, submit renewal paperwork.\nSTEP 5: 15 days before expiration, follow up to confirm renewal is processing.\nSTEP 6: If any renewal is denied or delayed, contact DRC: (800) 776-5746.\n\nCONTACT: ALL AGENCY CONTACTS (keep in one place):\n• Insurance: [your plan\'s number]\n• RC Service Coordinator: [name, phone, email]\n• School IEP Case Manager: [name, phone, email]\n• IHSS: Your county IHSS office — find at cdss.ca.gov/in-home-supportive-services\n• SSA: (800) 772-1213\n• Medi-Cal: (800) 300-1506\n• ABA Provider: [company, BCBA name, phone]\n• CalABLE: calable.ca.gov\nIF PROBLEMS:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032\n• DMHC: (888) 466-2219\n\nDOCUMENTS: MASTER DOCUMENT SYSTEM:\nCreate folders for:\n1. INSURANCE: auth letters, EOBs, appeals\n2. REGIONAL CENTER: IPP, POS authorizations, correspondence\n3. SCHOOL: IEP, evaluations, progress reports, correspondence\n4. SSI: applications, CDR responses, Function Reports\n5. IHSS: assessments, hour authorizations\n6. MEDI-CAL: enrollment, renewals\n7. CalABLE/SNT: account records\n8. MEDICAL: records, specialist reports\n9. CORRESPONDENCE: all letters sent/received (dated)\n\nTIMELINE: Insurance re-auth: every 3-12 months. IHSS: annual reassessment. SSI CDR: every 1-7 years. Medi-Cal: annual redetermination. IEP: annual review (every 12 months). IPP: annual review (every 12 months). Triennial re-evaluation: every 3 years. CalABLE: ongoing contributions.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Miss a renewal deadline — services stop immediately. (2) Assume renewals happen automatically — most require parent action. (3) Let one agency\'s change slip through without updating others (e.g., SSI income change affects Medi-Cal and IHSS). (4) Skip annual IEP/IPP meetings — these are your opportunity to update goals and services. (5) Throw away any documents — keep everything.\n\nRISKS: ★ Missed renewal = service gap. Authorization expires before renewal processed. Parent overwhelmed by overlapping deadlines. One change cascades across agencies. Document loss. Provider turnover disrupts continuity. Benefits overpayment due to unreported changes.\n\nRESOURCES: STAYING ORGANIZED:\n• Undivided: undivided.io — organizational tools\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com — IEP/SpEd resources\n• DRC publications: disabilityrightsca.org — rights guides\n• TASK: taskca.org — ongoing parent training\n• Local parent support groups: frcnca.org\nSELF-CARE:\n• Parent to Parent support: frcnca.org\n• Respite through RC\n• NAMI (mental health support for caregivers): nami.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: ALL agencies\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nRC\nIHSS\nSSA\nMedi-Cal\nSchool District\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-overview','journey-pda','overview','PDA Journey Map — Overview','PDA (PATHOLOGICAL DEMAND AVOIDANCE) — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n19 steps across 7 phases:\n* 1 Recognition & \'Lightbulb Moment\': Parent Recognizes Atypical Demand Avoidance Patter, Parent Discovers PDA Framework\n* 2 Seeking Diagnosis (Through ASD Pathway): Pursue Autism/ASD Evaluation (Primary Pathway), Comprehensive Evaluation — PDA-Informed, Navigate Diagnostic Language (No PDA Diagnosis Ava\n* 3 Service Planning (PDA-Informed): IPP/Service Plan — RC (If ASD Eligible), Low-Demand Parenting & Therapeutic Approach\n* 4 School Navigation (IEP/504): Request School District Assessment, School District Evaluation — PDA-Aware Approach, IEP Development — PDA-Specific Accommodations, 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied), IEP/504 Dispute Resolution (If Needed)\n* 5 Therapy & Intervention (PDA-Informed): Find PDA-Affirming Therapists & Providers, Insurance Authorization for PDA-Informed Therapy\n* 6 School Avoidance & Crisis Management: Address School Avoidance / School Refusal, Manage PDA Crisis Episodes (Meltdowns/Shutdowns)\n* 7 Long-Term Planning & Transition: Ongoing IEP/504 Review — PDA-Specific Monitoring, Transition Planning (Age 14+), Adult PDA — Ongoing Support & Self-Advocacy\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s11','journey-pda','step-11','PDA Step 1.1: Parent Recognizes Atypical Demand Avoidance Pattern','PDA — Step 1.1: Parent Recognizes Atypical Demand Avoidance Pattern\n\nWHAT TO DO: TRACK AND DOCUMENT THE PDA BEHAVIORAL PATTERN: (1) PDA is NOT ordinary defiance — it\'s an anxiety-driven, pervasive avoidance of everyday demands that includes ANY expectation, even fun activities. Keep a DEMAND DIARY: for 2 weeks, log every demand that triggers avoidance, the child\'s specific response, and what worked/didn\'t. (2) Note PDA-specific markers: avoidance of routine demands (getting dressed, eating meals, leaving the house), social manipulation strategies (distraction, excuses, physical incapacitation claims, negotiation), surface sociability with difficulty sustaining friendships, extreme mood variability, comfort in role-play/fantasy/controlling play, equal avoidance of preferred AND non-preferred activities. (3) Document the ANXIETY underneath: your child is not choosing defiance — their nervous system perceives demands as threats. (4) Video-record episodes when safe to do so — clinicians rarely see PDA presentations in office settings because the novelty of the visit masks patterns. (5) Track what REDUCES avoidance: indirect language (\'I wonder if...\'), autonomy, novelty, humor, collaborative problem-solving. (6) Rate the demand avoidance on a 0-10 scale daily. (7) Prevalence: PDA affects an estimated 2-5% of all autistic individuals — it\'s uncommon but well-documented in research, particularly from the UK (Elizabeth Newson, Phil Christie).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Learn to recognize PDA patterns. Key signs: (a) Resists and avoids ordinary demands of daily life (getting dressed, eating, leaving the house), (b) Uses \'social strategies\' to avoid — distraction, negotiation, excuses, withdrawal, (c) Appears comfortable with peers but driven by need for control, (d) Can be charming and socially aware when not in demand situations, (e) May mask all day at school then meltdown upon returning home, (f) Severe distress when faced with direct demands — even positive ones like \'Let\'s go to the park!\'\nSTEP 2: Start a PDA-specific behavior journal. Record: date, demand or trigger, child\'s avoidance strategy (distraction, negotiation, refusal, meltdown), outcome, what helped reduce distress. Track patterns — what triggers are worst? What approaches reduce distress?\nSTEP 3: Take the PDA screening tool: Extreme Demand Avoidance Questionnaire (EDA-Q) — available free at pdanorthamerica.org. Note: this is a screening tool, not a diagnosis.\nSTEP 4: Join PDA parent communities immediately for peer support: PDA North America (pdanorthamerica.org), PDA Parents Facebook group, PDA Society UK (pdasociety.org.uk).\nSTEP 5: Begin reading about PDA: \'The Declarative Language Handbook\' (Linda Murphy), \'Low Demand Parenting\' (Amanda Diekman), PDA Society practice guides.\n\nCONTACT: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — screening tools, provider directory, parent community, webinars\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — comprehensive practice guidance (most established PDA resource worldwide)\nLOW DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources, coaching\nEDA-Q SCREENING: Available at pdanorthamerica.org\nFINDING PDA-INFORMED PROFESSIONALS IN CA:\n• PDANA provider directory: pdanorthamerica.org/find-help\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — search \'PDA\' or \'pathological demand avoidance\'\n• Ask PDA parent Facebook groups for CA-specific provider recommendations\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEGIN CREATING:\n• PDA behavior journal (triggers, strategies, outcomes)\n• EDA-Q screening results\n• Video recordings of demand avoidance episodes (CRITICAL evidence for future evaluations)\n• School communication records\n• Daily routine log showing where demands trigger distress\n• List of strategies tried and their outcomes\n\nDOCUMENTS TO COLLECT:\n• Any prior behavioral evaluations\n• School behavior reports\n• Pediatrician notes on behavior concerns\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — earlier recognition = earlier appropriate support. Many parents spend years on wrong interventions.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Assume your child is \'just being defiant\' or \'manipulative\' — PDA is driven by anxiety, not willful disobedience. Traditional behavioral approaches (reward charts, consequences, time-outs) typically INCREASE demand avoidance and distress. (2) Apply rigid behavioral frameworks — ABA, PBIS, or \'first-then\' boards often backfire with PDA profiles by increasing perceived demands. (3) Compare to typical autism presentations — PDA children are often highly social, use masking, and may not \'look autistic\' to untrained observers. (4) Blame yourself — PDA is a neurological profile, not a parenting failure. (5) Seek advice from professionals unfamiliar with PDA — they will likely recommend strategies that make things worse. (6) Wait for school to notice — PDA children often \'hold it toge\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL PDA TRAP: Child is misdiagnosed as ODD (Oppositional Defiant Disorder) or as having \'behavioral problems.\' Traditional behavioral interventions (reward/consequence) escalate conflict. Parents blamed for \'poor parenting.\' Child may mask at school and collapse at home (\'after-school restraint collapse\'). PDA not in DSM-5 — most U.S. clinicians unfamiliar with it.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA PARENT EDUCATION:\n• PDA North America: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\n• PDA Society UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses ($), practice guidance (free)\n• Low Demand Parenting: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s courses and community\n• Reframing Autism: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\n• PDA Parents: pdaparents.com — community\nBOOKS:\n• \'Low Demand Parenting\' by Amanda Diekman\n• \'The Declarative Language Handbook\' by Linda Murphy\n• \'Understanding Pathological Demand Avoidance Syndrome in Children\' by Phil Christie et al.\n• \'The PDA Paradox\' by Harry Thompson (adult PDA perspective)\nCA PTI: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org — Bay Area parent training\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None (Parent-initiated)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s12','journey-pda','step-12','PDA Step 1.2: Parent Discovers PDA Framework','PDA — Step 1.2: Parent Discovers PDA Framework\n\nWHAT TO DO: EDUCATE YOURSELF ON PDA BEFORE SEEKING EVALUATION: (1) PDA (Pathological Demand Avoidance) is a behavioral profile within the autism spectrum first described by Elizabeth Newson (1983, University of Nottingham). It\'s widely recognized in UK and increasingly in US clinical practice, but NOT a standalone DSM-5 diagnosis. (2) Read the foundational resources: PDA Society (pdasociety.org.uk) — the authoritative source; \'Understanding Pathological Demand Avoidance Syndrome in Children\' by Phil Christie et al.; \'The PDA Paradox\' by Harry Thompson (adult PDA). (3) Take the EDA-Q (Extreme Demand Avoidance Questionnaire) — a research-validated screening tool available at PDA Society website. Score 50+ suggests PDA profile. (4) Join PDA parent communities: PDA Society forum, PDA North America Facebook group (largest US group, 15K+ members), PDA Parents & Carers Facebook group. (5) CRITICAL: Learn LOW-DEMAND strategies NOW — don\'t wait for diagnosis. Traditional behavioral approaches (reward charts, consequences, ABA compliance training) typically WORSEN PDA. (6) Document your child\'s profile against the PDA criteria: demand avoidance, social strategies, lability of mood, role play/fantasy, surface sociability. (7) Prepare a \'1-page PDA profile\' summarizing your child\'s presentation — you\'ll use this with every provider.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Deep dive into PDA education. Priority resources: (a) PDA Society practice guidance: pdasociety.org.uk/what-is-pda/practice-guidance — the gold standard, (b) PDA North America: pdanorthamerica.org — U.S.-adapted information, (c) Laura Kerbey\'s PDA webinars (PDANA website).\nSTEP 2: Learn the LOW-DEMAND parenting approach — this is the cornerstone of PDA-informed parenting: reduce demands, use indirect language, offer choices, collaborate rather than direct, pick your battles ruthlessly.\nSTEP 3: Learn declarative language — replace commands (\'Put on your shoes\') with observations (\'I notice it\'s time to go\') and wonderings (\'I wonder if we need shoes?\'). Read \'The Declarative Language Handbook.\'\nSTEP 4: Map the U.S. service pathway: PDA → Autism evaluation → ASD diagnosis (if meets criteria) → Regional Center IPP + School IEP. PDA characteristics documented in the evaluation support accommodation requests.\nSTEP 5: Begin preparing for evaluation by documenting PDA-specific characteristics (see Step 2.1).\n\nCONTACT: PDA EDUCATION:\n• PDA North America: pdanorthamerica.org — U.S.-focused resources, provider directory\n• PDA Society UK: pdasociety.org.uk — practice guidance, professional courses\n• Low Demand Parenting: lowdemandparenting.com\nCA SERVICE PATHWAY:\n• Regional Center: dds.ca.gov/rc — find your local RC for autism evaluation\n• School District: your district\'s Special Education office\n• DISABILITY RIGHTS CA: (800) 776-5746 — legal rights guidance\nONLINE COMMUNITIES:\n• PDA Parents Facebook group (largest global PDA parent community)\n• PDANA private community\n• Reddit: r/PDA\n\nDOCUMENTS: PDA EDUCATION PORTFOLIO:\n• PDA Society practice guidance (downloaded/printed)\n• EDA-Q results and interpretation\n• Your PDA behavior journal (ongoing)\n• List of PDA-specific characteristics your child shows\n• Videos of demand avoidance episodes\n• Notes on strategies tried (traditional vs low-demand) and outcomes\n\nFOR FUTURE EVALUATORS:\n• Prepare a 1-page \'PDA Profile Summary\' for your child:\n  - Demand avoidance patterns\n  - Social strategies used to avoid\n  - Anxiety presentations\n  - Masking behaviors\n  - What makes things worse\n  - What reduces distress\n\nTIMELINE: N/A — self-education phase\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Present PDA as a \'diagnosis\' to schools or providers — PDA is NOT recognized in the DSM-5. In the U.S., there is no PDA diagnosis code. Instead, the pathway is through autism/ASD evaluation with PDA characteristics described. (2) Dismiss professionals who haven\'t heard of PDA — educate them gently. Most U.S. clinicians were not trained on PDA. (3) Use PDA as an excuse to avoid all intervention — PDA children still benefit from support, just through low-demand approaches. (4) Rely solely on UK-based guidance without adapting to U.S./CA systems — the service pathways are very different. (5) Overwhelm yourself trying to learn everything at once — PDA parenting is a marathon, not a sprint.\n\nRISKS: Most U.S. clinicians don\'t know about PDA. Parents may encounter skepticism from professionals. UK research is more advanced than U.S. Parents blamed as \'internet paediatricians\' for raising PDA. No standardized PDA assessment tool in widespread clinical use (EDA-Q under development). PDA not in DSM-5 or ICD-11.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None (Self-education)\nOTHER AGENCIES: PDA North America\nPDA Society UK\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s21','journey-pda','step-21','PDA Step 2.1: Pursue Autism/ASD Evaluation (Primary Pathway)','PDA — Step 2.1: Pursue Autism/ASD Evaluation (Primary Pathway)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PURSUE ASD EVALUATION AS PRIMARY DIAGNOSTIC PATHWAY: (1) PDA is NOT a standalone DSM-5 diagnosis — your child\'s diagnostic pathway is through ASD (Autism Spectrum Disorder). (2) Your child may present atypically for autism: they may be socially motivated, make eye contact, use advanced language, and engage in imaginative play — all of which can MASK autism in traditional screening. (3) Request evaluation through TWO parallel pathways: (a) Regional Center — self-refer for developmental evaluation, no doctor referral needed, call your local RC intake line; (b) School district — written request for assessment in all areas of suspected disability. (4) When requesting evaluation, say: \'I\'m concerned about autism spectrum features including pervasive demand avoidance, anxiety, social difficulties, and emotional dysregulation. My child may present atypically — they have surface sociability but struggle with genuine reciprocal friendship and demand tolerance.\' (5) Ask specifically for evaluators experienced with: masking/camouflaging autism, atypical autism presentations, PDA profile, girls/women on the spectrum (PDA is often missed in girls). (6) Bring your Demand Diary, video recordings, EDA-Q results, and 1-page PDA profile to every evaluation. (7) CA Regional Centers: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — find your local RC by county.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Contact your local Regional Center and request an autism evaluation. Say: \'I\'d like to refer my child for a comprehensive developmental evaluation. I have concerns about autism with a demand avoidance profile.\' RC evaluations are FREE regardless of income or insurance.\nSTEP 2: Simultaneously, pursue private evaluation if possible. Find a PDA-informed evaluator: check PDANA directory (pdanorthamerica.org/find-help), ask PDA parent groups for CA recommendations.\nSTEP 3: CRITICAL PREPARATION — write a detailed Parent Concerns Letter that specifically describes PDA characteristics: (a) pervasive demand avoidance across settings, (b) social strategies to avoid (negotiation, distraction, charm), (c) anxiety-driven behavior NOT willful defiance, (d) comfort with peers but need for control, (e) masking at school / meltdowns at home, (f) traditional behavioral approaches failed or worsened behavior.\nSTEP 4: Provide your PDA behavior journal and videos to the evaluator BEFORE the evaluation appointment.\nSTEP 5: Ask the evaluator: \'Are you familiar with the PDA profile? Will you use assessments that capture anxiety-driven demand avoidance rather than just social communication deficits?\'\nSTEP 6: If RC evaluation doesn\'t capture PDA: request a second opinion through a private neuropsychologist. If you disagree with RC\'s findings, you have the right to appeal.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER: Find yours at dds.ca.gov/rc — all 21 CA Regional Centers. Self-refer by phone. FREE evaluation regardless of income.\nPDA-INFORMED EVALUATORS:\n• PDANA directory: pdanorthamerica.org/find-help\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — search autism, PDA, demand avoidance\n• UC Davis MIND Institute: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — (916) 703-0280\n• Ask PDA parent Facebook groups for CA-specific provider names\nIF RC DENIES AUTISM:\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032 — clients\' rights advocacy\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — appeal guidance\n• Request a fair hearing through RC\nPRIVATE EVALUATION:\n• Neuropsychologists ($3K-$8K) — check insurance for \'neurodevelopmental testing\' benefit\n\nDOCUMENTS: PREPARE FOR EVALUATOR:\n• Parent Concerns Letter — PDA-specific (see template in Step 6)\n• PDA behavior journal with dates and examples\n• Video recordings of demand avoidance episodes and meltdowns\n• EDA-Q screening results\n• Prior evaluations (behavioral, school, medical)\n• School records (report cards, behavior reports, teacher comments)\n• List of interventions tried and outcomes (esp. traditional vs low-demand)\n• Daily routine challenges document\n\nEVALUATOR WILL PRODUCE:\n• Comprehensive evaluation report\n• Autism/ASD diagnosis (if criteria met) — diagnostic code to use\n• Recommendations for services and accommodations\n• Assessment instruments used and scores\n\nTIMELINE: RC: 120 days from referral to eligibility. Private dev ped: 6-12 month wait. Private neuropsych: 2-8 weeks.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Ask for a \'PDA evaluation\' — ask for a \'comprehensive autism/ASD evaluation with specific attention to anxiety-driven demand avoidance.\' (2) Accept a brief screener (M-CHAT, CARS) as sufficient — PDA children often PASS standard autism screens because they are socially engaged. ADOS-2 may also miss PDA children who mask effectively. (3) Accept evaluation from a provider unfamiliar with female autism presentations or PDA — masking is extremely common and can lead to false negatives. (4) Assume one evaluation attempt is final — if your child was not diagnosed but you believe PDA/autism is present, pursue a second opinion. (5) Let school-based evaluation replace a clinical autism evaluation — school evaluates for educational impact, not clinical diagnosis.\n\nRISKS: ★ MAJOR RISK: Standard autism assessments (ADOS-2) may MISS PDA children. Children with PDA are often \'socially oriented\' — they make eye contact, use social language, engage socially — which can mask autism on standardized tests. Evaluator unfamiliar with PDA may conclude \'not autistic.\' Masking during evaluation means child appears more capable than they are. Female/AFAB children especially under-identified.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center OR\nPrivate Provider\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician (referral)\nInsurance (authorization)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s22','journey-pda','step-22','PDA Step 2.2: Comprehensive Evaluation — PDA-Informed','PDA — Step 2.2: Comprehensive Evaluation — PDA-Informed\n\nWHAT TO DO: ENSURE THE EVALUATION IS PDA-INFORMED: (1) Standard autism evaluations (ADOS-2) may MISS PDA — children with PDA often perform well in structured, novel clinical settings because the novelty reduces demand avoidance temporarily. (2) Request evaluators who understand: camouflaging/masking, PDA behavioral profile, atypical autism presentations, the role of anxiety in avoidance. (3) CRITICAL: Provide your Demand Diary, video recordings of home behavior, and parent-completed EDA-Q BEFORE the evaluation — these capture what the clinician won\'t see in their office. (4) For private evaluation: seek a neuropsychologist or developmental psychologist who specifically lists PDA, atypical autism, or demand avoidance in their expertise. Check: PDA North America provider recommendations, Psychology Today filtered by \'autism spectrum.\' (5) If ADOS-2 results are borderline/negative but you believe PDA-autism is present: request the evaluator review your home documentation, administer the Diagnostic Interview for Social and Communication Disorders (DISCO — designed to capture PDA), or consider referral to a PDA-knowledgeable specialist. (6) Evaluation should include: cognitive testing, adaptive behavior (Vineland — PDA children often show significant adaptive skill deficits), social-emotional assessment, anxiety measures, sensory profile, and functional behavior analysis focused on demand avoidance. (7) In California, some Regional Centers will accept a \'provisional\' ASD diagnosis for childre\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before evaluation, submit your complete PDA documentation package to the evaluator (letter, journal, videos, EDA-Q).\nSTEP 2: Request multi-session evaluation if possible. PDA children often mask in initial sessions but reveal their profile over time.\nSTEP 3: Ask evaluator to use assessments beyond ADOS-2 that capture anxiety and demand avoidance: Extreme Demand Avoidance Questionnaire (EDA-Q), Anxiety measures (SCARED, Spence), Sensory Profile, MIGDAS-2 (better for masking profiles), parent and teacher rating scales.\nSTEP 4: Provide context before testing: \'My child tends to mask in new settings. The demand avoidance and distress you\'re more likely to see in familiar, routine settings.\'\nSTEP 5: If the evaluator concludes \'does not meet autism criteria,\' ask: (a) \'What alternative diagnosis captures my child\'s demand avoidance and anxiety?\' (b) \'Will you document the PDA characteristics observed?\' (c) \'Can you provide recommendations for low-demand approaches regardless of diagnostic label?\'\nSTEP 6: Obtain a copy of the full evaluation report. Review for accuracy — does it reflect the PDA profile you see at home?\n\nCONTACT: YOUR EVALUATOR: Get their direct contact information (phone, email) before the evaluation.\nRC EVALUATION TEAM: Your service coordinator can tell you who will evaluate.\nPRIVATE EVALUATORS (if needed):\n• PDANA provider directory: pdanorthamerica.org/find-help\n• UC Davis MIND Institute: (916) 703-0280\n• Stanford Autism Center: (650) 736-1235\n• UCSF Autism & Neurodevelopment: (415) 353-2101\nIF EVALUATION MISSES PDA:\n• Request second opinion through private neuropsych\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032 — dispute RC evaluation\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n\nDOCUMENTS: SUBMIT TO EVALUATOR (BEFORE appointment):\n• Parent Concerns Letter — PDA-specific\n• PDA behavior journal\n• Video recordings (CRITICAL for PDA)\n• EDA-Q results\n• Prior evaluations\n• School records\n\nEVALUATION SHOULD INCLUDE:\n• Autism-specific: ADOS-2 and/or MIGDAS-2\n• Demand avoidance: EDA-Q\n• Anxiety: SCARED or Spence Child Anxiety Scale\n• Adaptive: Vineland-3\n• Cognitive: if indicated\n• Sensory: Sensory Profile-2\n• Multiple informant: parent + teacher rating scales\n• Clinical observation (ideally multiple sessions)\n\nYOU RECEIVE:\n• Full evaluation report\n• Diagnostic determination\n• Recommendations\n\nTIMELINE: 60 days from consent (school district). 120 days from referral (RC). Private: varies.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Rely solely on ADOS-2 — it was designed for \'classic\' autism presentations and frequently MISSES PDA profiles, especially in females and children who mask. (2) Accept evaluation in an unfamiliar clinical setting as representative — PDA children may perform well in novel situations (novelty reduces demand anxiety). Request observation in natural settings. (3) Assume \'not meeting autism criteria\' means no support — PDA children may qualify under anxiety disorder, or may meet autism criteria with a PDA-informed evaluation approach. (4) Accept a single assessment session — PDA children\'s presentation varies dramatically by context, demand level, and familiarity. (5) Withhold your PDA documentation from the evaluator — your detailed observations are more diagnostically valuable than\n\nRISKS: Evaluator doesn\'t screen for PDA traits. EDA-Q not administered. ADOS-2 shows borderline/subclinical because PDA child is socially oriented. Evaluator attributes demand avoidance to ODD, anxiety, or \'behavioral issues.\' Significant IQ-adaptive skill gap not explored as PDA indicator. Female/AFAB presentation missed. After-school restraint collapse dismissed because \'child is fine at school.\'\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Evaluator\n(Psychologist/Neuropsych/\nDev Ped)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nInsurance\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s23','journey-pda','step-23','PDA Step 2.3: Navigate Diagnostic Language (No PDA Diagnosis Available)','PDA — Step 2.3: Navigate Diagnostic Language (No PDA Diagnosis Available)\n\nWHAT TO DO: NAVIGATE THE DIAGNOSTIC COMPLEXITY STRATEGICALLY: (1) Since PDA is not a DSM-5 diagnosis, your child\'s formal diagnosis will likely be: ASD (Autism Spectrum Disorder) — primary pathway that unlocks the most services; possibly with added specifiers like \'with associated anxiety\' or clinician notes describing the PDA behavioral profile. (2) If ASD diagnosis is given: request the clinician DOCUMENT the PDA profile in their report — \'meets criteria for ASD with a behavioral profile consistent with Pathological Demand Avoidance (PDA), characterized by pervasive demand avoidance driven by anxiety, social manipulation strategies, mood lability, and surface sociability.\' (3) If ASD is NOT given: push back with your documentation, request second opinion, or pursue private neuropsychological evaluation. Alternative diagnostic pathways: Anxiety Disorder (GAD, Social Anxiety), ODD (though PDA is NOT ODD — key distinction), or unspecified neurodevelopmental disorder. (4) CRITICAL: Do NOT accept ODD (Oppositional Defiant Disorder) as the sole diagnosis — ODD implies willful defiance and leads to punitive interventions that are harmful for PDA. If ODD is suggested, advocate: \'The avoidance is anxiety-driven, not defiance-driven. I\'d like anxiety-based approaches rather than compliance-based ones.\' (5) Whatever diagnosis is given, ensure the evaluation report includes detailed behavioral descriptions that will support service access: demand avoidance across settings, anxiety severity, adapti\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Understand the diagnostic landscape: In the U.S./CA, PDA is NOT a separate diagnosis. Options are: (a) ASD (Autism Spectrum Disorder) with notation of demand avoidance/anxiety profile, (b) Generalized Anxiety Disorder or Social Anxiety Disorder, (c) Unspecified Neurodevelopmental Disorder with PDA characteristics described. Each has different service implications.\nSTEP 2: FOR MAXIMUM SERVICE ACCESS in CA: ASD diagnosis unlocks the most services — Regional Center IPP (ABA, respite, parent training), insurance-funded behavioral therapy (SB 946), and school IEP under Autism eligibility category.\nSTEP 3: Ask evaluator to document PDA characteristics IN the report regardless of primary diagnosis: \'Please describe the demand avoidance profile, anxiety-driven behavior, masking, and need for low-demand approaches in your report.\'\nSTEP 4: If diagnosed with ASD: proceed to RC and school pathways. If diagnosed with anxiety/other: still pursue school IEP (under OHI or Emotional Disturbance) and insurance-covered therapy.\nSTEP 5: Keep seeking PDA-informed providers even without ASD diagnosis — the PDA framework guides effective intervention regardless of diagnostic code.\n\nCONTACT: DIAGNOSTIC GUIDANCE:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — which diagnosis accesses which CA services\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032 — RC eligibility questions\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org — navigating U.S. diagnostic landscape\nSERVICE ACCESS BY DIAGNOSIS:\n• ASD diagnosis → RC IPP + SB 946 insurance + IEP (Autism)\n• Anxiety diagnosis → Insurance therapy + IEP (OHI or ED)\n• No diagnosis → 504 Plan (if functional limitation) + private services\nSECOND OPINION:\n• UC Davis MIND: (916) 703-0280\n• Private neuropsychologist through PDANA directory\n\nDOCUMENTS: DIAGNOSTIC DOCUMENTS TO ORGANIZE:\n• Complete evaluation report\n• Diagnostic code(s) assigned (ICD-10/DSM-5)\n• Evaluator\'s description of PDA characteristics (CRITICAL — highlight these sections)\n• Service recommendations from evaluator\n• Your PDA Profile Summary (1-page parent document)\n\nCREATE A \'SERVICE ACCESS\' DOCUMENT:\n• Diagnosis received → services it unlocks\n• Regional Center eligibility (Y/N and basis)\n• School eligibility category\n• Insurance coverage basis\n• List of providers to contact next\n\nTIMELINE: Varies by evaluator — some do this readily, others resistant.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Get stuck on the label — the goal is accessing services, not getting a PDA diagnosis code (which doesn\'t exist in the U.S.). (2) Fight with evaluators who say \'PDA isn\'t a diagnosis\' — they are technically correct in the U.S. system. Instead, ensure PDA CHARACTERISTICS are documented within whatever diagnosis IS given. (3) Accept a diagnosis without PDA characteristics documented — the diagnosis alone won\'t get PDA-appropriate accommodations. (4) Assume an anxiety diagnosis means you can\'t also pursue autism — they can co-occur. (5) Give up if the first evaluation doesn\'t result in a diagnosis — seek a second opinion.\n\nRISKS: ★ DIAGNOSTIC GAP: Evaluator refuses to use PDA language. Child gets ASD diagnosis without PDA documentation, leading to inappropriate intervention recommendations (e.g., traditional ABA). OR child doesn\'t meet ASD criteria on standard tools and gets NO diagnosis, leaving family with no services. Some evaluators may diagnose ODD instead — leading to punitive interventions that worsen PDA. Insurance and school use diagnosis codes, not profile descriptions.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Evaluator\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s31','journey-pda','step-31','PDA Step 3.1: IPP/Service Plan — RC (If ASD Eligible)','PDA — Step 3.1: IPP/Service Plan — RC (If ASD Eligible)\n\nWHAT TO DO: DEVELOP A PDA-APPROPRIATE IPP WITH YOUR REGIONAL CENTER: (1) If your child has an ASD diagnosis, they qualify for Regional Center services under the Lanterman Act — ASD is an automatic qualifying condition. (2) At the IPP (Individual Program Plan) meeting, request services that work FOR PDA, not against it: (a) PDA-informed behavioral consultation (NOT traditional ABA focused on compliance — request Collaborative & Proactive Solutions, low-demand approaches, or Declarative Language strategies), (b) Occupational therapy with sensory integration focus, (c) Parent training in low-demand strategies and PDA-specific approaches, (d) Respite care (PDA parenting is exhausting — respite is critical for family sustainability), (e) Social skills support that respects autonomy (not forced social compliance). (3) AVOID requesting traditional ABA that uses: discrete trial training, token economies, forced compliance, planned ignoring of demand avoidance, or extinction of avoidance behaviors — these increase anxiety and worsen PDA. (4) Request your IPP specifically state: \'PDA profile — services must use low-demand, autonomy-respecting, anxiety-reduction approaches.\' (5) Know your POS (Purchase of Service) rights — RC must fund services; if they deny, request Prior Written Notice. (6) SSI, Medi-Cal, IHSS, and CalABLE may all apply — see benefits checklist.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: After ASD diagnosis, contact your Regional Center and request an IPP meeting. Say: \'My child has been diagnosed with ASD with a demand avoidance/PDA profile. I\'d like to develop an IPP that includes PDA-informed services.\'\nSTEP 2: Before the IPP meeting, write a \'Service Request Letter\' listing: (a) PDA-informed behavioral support (NOT traditional ABA), (b) Parent training in low-demand strategies, (c) Respite care (specify hours/week), (d) Occupational therapy for sensory needs, (e) Social skills group (with PDA-aware facilitator), (f) Mental health services for anxiety.\nSTEP 3: At the IPP meeting, present your request letter. For each service, explain why PDA-specific approach is needed: \'Traditional ABA increases my child\'s anxiety and demand avoidance. I\'m requesting a provider who uses naturalistic, play-based approaches.\'\nSTEP 4: Request specific language in IPP: \'Services will use low-demand, PDA-informed approaches. Provider must be willing to adapt to child\'s anxiety-driven demand avoidance profile.\'\nSTEP 5: Get names and contact info for all assigned providers. Interview them about PDA familiarity before starting.\nSTEP 6: If RC denies services, appeal: OCRA (800) 390-7032.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR REGIONAL CENTER: Find at dds.ca.gov/rc — contact your service coordinator directly.\nSERVICE COORDINATOR: Your main RC contact — get name, phone, email.\nOCRA: (800) 390-7032 — if services denied or inadequate\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — RC rights guidance, fair hearing help\nPDA-INFORMED PROVIDERS:\n• PDANA directory: pdanorthamerica.org/find-help\n• Ask RC for providers experienced with demand avoidance\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — filter by PDA/autism/anxiety\nPARENT TRAINING:\n• Low Demand Parenting: lowdemandparenting.com — courses\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org — training resources\n• Your RC should fund parent training as IPP service\n\nDOCUMENTS: FOR IPP MEETING:\n• ASD evaluation report (with PDA characteristics highlighted)\n• Service Request Letter (detailed, specific)\n• PDA Profile Summary (1-page)\n• Your PDA behavior journal\n• Research on PDA-informed approaches vs traditional ABA\n• List of specific provider requests\n\nIPP DOCUMENT SHOULD INCLUDE:\n• PDA profile description in Present Level\n• Specific services with PDA-informed approach noted\n• Provider qualifications (familiarity with demand avoidance)\n• Parent training services\n• Respite hours\n• Review schedule (every 6 months recommended for PDA)\n• Emergency/crisis plan for severe demand avoidance episodes\n\nTIMELINE: 60 days from eligibility to initial IPP.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept generic autism services that use high-demand approaches — standard ABA with discrete trial training is often counterproductive for PDA. Request PDA-informed or naturalistic ABA (PRT, ESDM, or play-based models). (2) Accept a \'one-size-fits-all\' IPP — PDA children need individualized, low-demand approaches documented in the plan. (3) Let the service coordinator assign providers without your input — YOU choose providers. Ask: \'Is this provider familiar with demand avoidance profiles? Do they use low-demand approaches?\' (4) Accept denial of parent training services — parent training in low-demand strategies is arguably the MOST important service for PDA families. (5) Forget to request respite care — PDA parenting is exhausting and burnout is common.\n\nRISKS: ★ PDA SERVICE TRAP: RC recommends traditional ABA (40 hrs/week structured compliance training) — this approach typically escalates PDA behaviors, increases anxiety, and can cause trauma. Service coordinator unfamiliar with PDA. Available providers don\'t understand PDA profile. POS spending disparities affect PDA families too. Rural areas: virtually no PDA-informed providers.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\n(Service Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Therapy providers\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s32','journey-pda','step-32','PDA Step 3.2: Low-Demand Parenting & Therapeutic Approach','PDA — Step 3.2: Low-Demand Parenting & Therapeutic Approach\n\nWHAT TO DO: IMPLEMENT LOW-DEMAND STRATEGIES IMMEDIATELY — DON\'T WAIT FOR SERVICES: (1) Low-demand parenting is the EVIDENCE-BASED approach for PDA. Core principles: reduce demands to the minimum necessary, use indirect language (\'I wonder if the shoes might want to go for a walk\'), offer autonomy and choice (\'Would you like to do X or Y, or something else entirely?\'), use humor, novelty, and role-play to bypass the anxiety response, collaborate rather than direct. (2) Read NOW: \'Low Demand Parenting\' by Amanda Diekman (the definitive parent guide), \'Declarative Language Handbook\' by Linda Murphy, \'The Explosive Child\' by Ross Greene (Collaborative & Proactive Solutions). (3) Strip demands to SURVIVAL LEVEL first (safety, food, basic hygiene) — let everything else go temporarily. You can add demands back gradually as your child\'s nervous system stabilizes. (4) Reframe ALL behavior through an anxiety lens: \'My child CAN\'T, not WON\'T.\' (5) Create a DEMAND AUDIT: list every demand in your child\'s day (waking up, getting dressed, eating breakfast, school arrival, each class transition...) and rate each 0-10 for your child\'s tolerance. Eliminate or modify demands rated 7+. (6) Find parent support: PDA North America community, At Peace Parents (atpeaceparents.com), Declarative Language community. (7) Track what works and share with school and providers — your daily data is the treatment plan.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: IMPLEMENT LOW-DEMAND PARENTING: (a) Audit ALL demands in your child\'s day — written list. (b) Categorize: Essential (safety), Important (hygiene, nutrition), Nice-to-have (homework, chores). (c) Temporarily DROP all \'nice-to-have\' demands and reduce \'important\' demands. (d) Rebuild slowly as your child\'s nervous system regulation improves.\nSTEP 2: SWITCH TO DECLARATIVE LANGUAGE: Replace \'Do X\' with observations and wonderings. Practice daily: \'I notice the toothbrush is on the counter\' instead of \'Brush your teeth.\' \'I wonder if it\'s a shoes day or a no-shoes day.\'\nSTEP 3: BUILD COLLABORATION: Instead of \'You need to do X,\' try \'We have a problem to solve — how should we handle [thing]?\' Give genuine choices (not \'my way or highway\').\nSTEP 4: REQUEST PARENT TRAINING through RC IPP (or privately): Low Demand Parenting coaching, Declarative Language training, SPACE treatment for accommodation-based approaches.\nSTEP 5: JOIN PDA PARENT SUPPORT GROUP — peer support is essential. PDANA, PDA Parents communities. Weekly/monthly.\nSTEP 6: Prioritize caregiver self-care: respite (through RC), therapy for yourself, regular breaks.\n\nCONTACT: LOW-DEMAND PARENTING:\n• Low Demand Parenting: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman, courses + coaching\n• PDA Society practice guidance: pdasociety.org.uk/what-is-pda/practice-guidance\nDECLARATIVE LANGUAGE:\n• \'The Declarative Language Handbook\' by Linda Murphy\nSPACE TREATMENT:\n• Yale Child Study Center: spactreatment.net — evidence-based approach for anxiety/avoidance\n• Find SPACE therapists through directory\nPARENT SUPPORT:\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org — peer groups\n• PDA Parents Facebook group\n• Your Regional Center — request parent training + respite\nCARGIVER SUPPORT:\n• NAMI CA: namica.org — family support groups\n• Your insurance: therapy for caregiver stress\n\nDOCUMENTS: LOW-DEMAND PARENTING TOOLKIT:\n• Demand audit worksheet (list all daily demands, categorize, reduce)\n• Declarative language cheat sheet (command → declarative alternatives)\n• Daily routine visual schedule (flexible, not rigid)\n• Calm-down/regulation strategy list (co-created with child)\n• Crisis plan for severe episodes\n• Communication scripts for family/friends who don\'t understand PDA\n\nTRACKING DOCUMENTS:\n• Weekly demand reduction log\n• Strategy effectiveness tracker\n• Caregiver stress/burnout check-in\n• Provider communication log\n• RC respite hours used vs approved\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — long-term approach, not quick fix.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Use traditional behavioral approaches: reward charts, sticker systems, token economies, \'first-then\' boards, time-outs, consequences, removal of privileges. These INCREASE demand anxiety in PDA children. (2) Use direct commands: \'Put on your shoes,\' \'Do your homework,\' \'Sit down.\' Instead use declarative language: \'I notice it\'s almost time to go,\' \'I wonder if the shoes are ready.\' (3) Engage in power struggles — PDA children cannot \'just comply\' any more than an anxious person can \'just relax.\' (4) Interpret masking at school as evidence that \'they can do it when they want to\' — masking is exhausting and unsustainable. (5) Ignore your own burnout — PDA parenting requires ongoing support for caregivers.\n\nRISKS: Traditional therapists unfamiliar with PDA use standard behavioral approaches that escalate. Parent exhaustion and burnout from constant negotiation. Other family members (grandparents, co-parent) don\'t understand low-demand approach — see it as \'giving in.\' School uses opposite approach from home, creating inconsistency. Cost of PDA-informed private therapy.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nTherapists\nOTHER AGENCIES: OT\nSpeech\nPsychologist\nPDA North America\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s41','journey-pda','step-41','PDA Step 4.1: Request School District Assessment','PDA — Step 4.1: Request School District Assessment\n\nWHAT TO DO: REQUEST SCHOOL EVALUATION WITH PDA-SPECIFIC FRAMING: (1) Submit written request for comprehensive evaluation \'in all areas of suspected disability including autism spectrum, anxiety, emotional disturbance, social-emotional functioning, adaptive behavior, and functional behavior.\' (2) CRITICAL FRAMING: Do NOT describe your child as \'defiant\' or \'oppositional\' — use: \'pervasive anxiety-driven demand avoidance,\' \'difficulty transitioning between activities,\' \'significant anxiety in response to everyday expectations,\' \'need for autonomy and control as anxiety management.\' (3) If your child has school avoidance/refusal, document every missed day and the anxiety-driven reasons. (4) Request: psychoeducational evaluation, Functional Behavior Assessment (FBA) focused on DEMAND AVOIDANCE as the behavior (not \'non-compliance\'), speech-language pragmatics evaluation, OT with sensory profile, social-emotional assessment. (5) CA law: 15 calendar days for assessment plan after written request. (6) Bring your Demand Diary, PDA profile, any RC evaluation, private evaluation, and video documentation. (7) If school refuses evaluation: file CDE compliance complaint or contact Disability Rights California (DRC).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Write your evaluation request letter: \'I am writing to request a comprehensive special education evaluation for my child. My child has been diagnosed with [ASD/anxiety/other] with a demand avoidance (PDA) profile. I request evaluation in: academic achievement, cognitive ability, social-emotional functioning, behavioral assessment, functional behavior, adaptive behavior, and any other areas of suspected disability.\'\nSTEP 2: ATTACH your PDA documentation: evaluation report, PDA Profile Summary, behavior journal excerpts, and a cover letter explaining PDA for the school team.\nSTEP 3: Hand-deliver AND email the letter. Get a date-stamped copy. This triggers the 15-day assessment plan deadline per CA Education Code §56321.\nSTEP 4: Include a 1-page PDA education brief for the school: \'What is PDA? Key points for educators.\' Available at pdasociety.org.uk/education.\nSTEP 5: Follow up in 10 days if no response. If 15 days pass with no assessment plan, send: \'My evaluation request submitted [date] triggered a 15-day assessment plan deadline that has now passed. Please respond immediately or I will file a compliance complaint with CDE.\'\n\nCONTACT: YOUR SCHOOL DISTRICT SpEd DEPARTMENT: Find contact at your district website under \'Special Education\' or call the main district office.\nCA DEPT OF EDUCATION: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/ — SpEd guidance and complaint process\nCDE COMPLIANCE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal advocacy if district refuses evaluation\nCASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP advocacy\nTASK: taskca.org — parent training on school rights\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org — parent support\nPDA SCHOOL GUIDANCE:\n• PDA Society education guidance: pdasociety.org.uk/education\n• PDANA school resources: pdanorthamerica.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT SUBMITS:\n• Written evaluation request letter (dated, keep copy with receipt stamp)\n• PDA documentation packet (diagnosis report, PDA Profile Summary, behavior journal)\n• PDA education brief for school team\n• Prior evaluations\n• School records showing impact (attendance, behavior reports, grades)\n\nDISTRICT MUST PROVIDE (within 15 days):\n• Assessment plan listing all areas to be evaluated\n• Parent rights notification (Procedural Safeguards)\n• OR: Prior Written Notice if refusing evaluation\n\nPARENT REVIEWS assessment plan for:\n• All requested areas included?\n• Social-emotional and behavioral areas included?\n• FBA (Functional Behavior Assessment) included?\n\nTIMELINE: District: 15 days to respond with assessment plan. 60 days from consent to completed assessment.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Assume school will understand PDA — most teachers and school psychologists have never heard of it. YOU must educate them. (2) Request a \'PDA evaluation\' from the school — request a comprehensive special education evaluation covering academic, behavioral, social-emotional, and functional areas. (3) Rely on verbal request only — PUT IT IN WRITING. (4) Accept \'your child is doing fine academically\' as reason not to evaluate — PDA affects functional performance, behavior, attendance, and emotional wellbeing, not just grades. A child masking all day is NOT \'doing fine.\' (5) Let RTI/MTSS delay your evaluation request. (6) Accept school\'s behavioral assessments as complete — they rarely capture the demand avoidance profile.\n\nRISKS: ★ SCHOOL PDA TRAP: Child masks at school — appears \'fine\' to teachers. School sees no disability because behavior only shows at home (\'after-school restraint collapse\'). School frames behaviors as willful noncompliance or ODD. District psychologist unfamiliar with PDA. Standard FBA (Functional Behavior Assessment) may miss anxiety-driven avoidance because it focuses on visible behaviors, not internal states. Child labeled as \'oppositional\' rather than anxious.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center (if involved)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s42','journey-pda','step-42','PDA Step 4.2: School District Evaluation — PDA-Aware Approach','PDA — Step 4.2: School District Evaluation — PDA-Aware Approach\n\nWHAT TO DO: ENSURE THE SCHOOL EVALUATION CAPTURES PDA ACCURATELY: (1) School psychologists typically do NOT know about PDA — you will need to educate them. Bring: PDA Society overview (pdasociety.org.uk), your 1-page PDA profile, EDA-Q results, and demand diary. (2) Request that the school psychologist review PDA research before evaluating: \'I\'d like to share some research on Pathological Demand Avoidance, a profile within autism, so the evaluation can capture my child\'s presentation accurately.\' (3) The FBA (Functional Behavior Assessment) is CRITICAL — ensure it identifies DEMAND AVOIDANCE as the function of behavior, driven by ANXIETY, not attention-seeking or escape from non-preferred tasks (the typical school interpretation). (4) Push back if the FBA labels behavior as \'non-compliance\' or \'defiance\' — reframe: \'The behavior is anxiety-driven avoidance of perceived demands, including demands the child wants to meet but cannot due to their neurological profile.\' (5) If the school psychologist isn\'t familiar with PDA, request a specialist consultant or request the district fund an outside PDA-knowledgeable evaluator. (6) Ensure adaptive behavior assessment (Vineland) is included — PDA children often have significant gaps between cognitive ability and adaptive functioning. (7) Request observation across multiple settings including unstructured time (recess, lunch, transitions) — PDA often presents differently than in structured classroom time.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Provide the school psychologist with your complete PDA documentation BEFORE testing begins. Include: clinical evaluation, PDA Profile Summary, behavior journal, and PDA education brief.\nSTEP 2: Request a FUNCTIONAL BEHAVIOR ASSESSMENT (FBA) as part of the evaluation: \'I request an FBA that specifically examines the function of my child\'s avoidance behavior. The function is anxiety reduction, not attention-seeking or escape from non-preferred tasks.\'\nSTEP 3: Complete Parent Input forms THOROUGHLY — describe the PDA profile in detail. Describe the HOME vs SCHOOL contrast: \'At school, my child masks and appears compliant. At home, after a day of masking, they experience severe meltdowns, demand avoidance, and emotional dysregulation.\'\nSTEP 4: Request observation during STRUCTURED/DEMANDING activities, not just free play or preferred activities.\nSTEP 5: After evaluation, request reports 5+ days before the eligibility meeting. Review for: (a) Does it accurately describe PDA? (b) Is demand avoidance framed as anxiety-driven? (c) Are recommendations PDA-appropriate?\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL PSYCHOLOGIST: Get name, email, phone from SpEd coordinator — request a pre-evaluation conversation.\nSPECIAL EDUCATION COORDINATOR: Your district contact for scheduling and process.\nFBA SPECIALIST: If school\'s FBA doesn\'t capture PDA function, request an Independent Educational Evaluation (IEE) at district expense.\nIEE RIGHTS: 34 CFR §300.502 — if you disagree with school evaluation\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — IEE guidance\nCASE: caseadvocacy.org — advocate for evaluation\nPDA SCHOOL RESOURCES:\n• PDA Society education: pdasociety.org.uk/education\n• Share with school psychologist: pdanorthamerica.org professional resources\n\nDOCUMENTS: SUBMIT TO SCHOOL (before evaluation):\n• Clinical evaluation report (with PDA characteristics highlighted)\n• PDA Profile Summary (1-page)\n• PDA education brief for school team\n• Behavior journal excerpts (home vs school contrast)\n• Video recordings (if available and appropriate)\n• Parent Input Form (detailed, PDA-specific)\n\nSCHOOL PRODUCES:\n• Psychoeducational evaluation report\n• FBA report (request separately if not included)\n• Classroom observation data\n• Teacher Input results\n• Social-emotional assessment results\n\nREVIEW CHECKLIST:\n• PDA accurately described? Or mischaracterized as ODD?\n• Demand avoidance framed as anxiety-driven?\n• Recommendations include low-demand approaches?\n\nTIMELINE: 60 calendar days from consent to completed assessment.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Let the school interpret demand avoidance as \'oppositional defiant disorder\' (ODD) — PDA is anxiety-driven, not defiance-driven. If the school is heading toward ODD, provide PDA literature and your clinical evaluation. (2) Accept evaluation only during \'good\' periods — request observation during demanding activities. (3) Let the school evaluate only academics — PDA impacts behavior, social-emotional functioning, attendance, and self-regulation. (4) Withhold your home data — the contrast between home and school behavior IS the evidence of masking. (5) Accept a brief behavioral checklist as a complete behavioral assessment — request FBA (Functional Behavior Assessment) that examines function of demand avoidance behavior.\n\nRISKS: Assessment only captures school behavior (where child masks). No home data collected. Evaluator uses standard autism tools that miss PDA social presentation. Demand avoidance attributed to ODD/defiance. Executive function deficits missed. Sensory needs underestimated. Child performs well on standardized tests (high IQ masks difficulties).\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School Psychologist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPrivate evaluator (if IEE)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s43','journey-pda','step-43','PDA Step 4.3: IEP Development — PDA-Specific Accommodations','PDA — Step 4.3: IEP Development — PDA-Specific Accommodations\n\nWHAT TO DO: If eligible, IEP team develops plan. CRITICAL PDA ACCOMMODATIONS to request: (1) Low-demand task entry — offer choice and novelty. (2) Predictable routines with opt-in breaks and sensory regulation spaces. (3) Assessment flexibility — oral, visual, chunked work options. (4) Collaborative language scripts (\'How could we make this easier?\'). (5) Reduced direct demands — use declarative language. (6) Safe space/regulation room access. (7) 1:1 aide trained in PDA-informed strategies (if needed). (8) Modified behavior plan — NO traditional reward/consequence charts. (9) Transition warnings and preparation. (10) Flexible attendance for high-anxiety days. IEP GOALS should be neurodiversity-affirming, using declarative language, supporting executive functioning, sensory needs, and emotional regulation.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before IEP meeting, prepare a written \'IEP Request\' document with PDA-specific accommodations. ESSENTIAL PDA ACCOMMODATIONS: (a) Reduced direct demands — use declarative language, indirect prompts, choices, (b) Flexible schedule — permission to leave/take breaks without asking, (c) Designated safe space for regulation, (d) Modified work demands (reduced volume, not reduced expectations), (e) No public call-outs, (f) Advance notice of transitions and changes, (g) Adult uses collaborative/negotiation approach rather than directives.\nSTEP 2: Propose PDA-appropriate IEP GOALS: \'Student will use self-regulation strategies to manage anxiety in demanding situations, demonstrating [specific behavior] in [X] of [Y] opportunities.\' NOT: \'Student will comply with teacher directives.\'\nSTEP 3: Bring an advocate if possible (CASE, DRC).\nSTEP 4: Request BIP uses Collaborative & Proactive Solutions (CPS/Ross Greene) approach, NOT traditional ABA/behaviorist approach.\nSTEP 5: Request staff training on PDA — the school team must understand WHY they\'re using these approaches.\nSTEP 6: Request 6-month IEP review (not 12-month) to monitor PDA accommodation effectiveness.\n\nCONTACT: IEP MEETING TEAM: You, SpEd teacher, gen ed teacher, school psychologist, administrator. Bring advocate.\nADVOCACY:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP advocates in CA\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• TASK: taskca.org — parent training\n• Matrix: matrixparents.org\nPDA IEP RESOURCES:\n• PDA Society education guidance: pdasociety.org.uk/education — accommodation lists\n• PDANA school toolkit: pdanorthamerica.org\n• \'The Explosive Child\' by Ross Greene — CPS approach for BIP\n• Lives in the Balance: livesinthebalance.org — free CPS resources\nIF IEP DENIED:\n• Request 504 Plan (see Step 4.4)\n• CDE complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT BRINGS TO IEP MEETING:\n• Written IEP Request document (PDA-specific accommodations, goals, BIP approach)\n• PDA Profile Summary (1-page)\n• Evaluation reports (clinical + school)\n• PDA education brief for team members who are new\n• Research on PDA-informed school approaches (PDA Society, PDANA)\n• Ross Greene\'s CPS overview for BIP discussion\n\nIEP DOCUMENT SHOULD INCLUDE:\n• Present Levels: PDA profile description, demand avoidance pattern, masking, anxiety\n• Goals: regulation, flexibility, self-advocacy (NOT compliance)\n• BIP: CPS-based, NOT behaviorist\n• Accommodations: comprehensive PDA accommodation list\n• Staff training: PDA awareness for all staff who interact with child\n• Review schedule: 6 months (not 12)\n• Crisis plan: for severe demand avoidance/meltdown episodes\n\nTIMELINE: 30 days from completed assessment to IEP meeting.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept a Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP) based on traditional behaviorist methods — no reward/consequence systems, no token economies, no \'earning\' breaks. PDA children need low-demand, collaborative approaches. (2) Accept rigid schedules without flexibility built in — PDA children need escape valves and choice. (3) Accept goals requiring direct compliance (\'Student will follow 3-step directions 80% of time\') — reframe as regulation goals. (4) Let the school remove your child from preferred activities as \'consequence\' for avoidance — this increases anxiety. (5) Accept \'they need to learn to comply\' as educational philosophy — compliance-based approaches cause harm in PDA children. (6) Let placement default to behavioral/ED classroom — PDA children often do best in general educ\n\nRISKS: ★ PDA IEP PITFALLS: School uses traditional behavior plan (sticker charts, earned privileges) that triggers PDA escalation. IEP goals focus on \'compliance\' rather than regulation and self-advocacy. 1:1 aide uses directive approach that increases demand avoidance. School removes child from preferred activities as consequence — increases trauma. Staff see accommodations as \'giving in\' to behavior. IEP doesn\'t address masking/after-school collapse.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPrivate therapist\nPDA advocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s44','journey-pda','step-44','PDA Step 4.4: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied)','PDA — Step 4.4: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PURSUE 504 PLAN IF IEP IS DENIED OR AS SUPPLEMENT: (1) 504 Plan has BROADER eligibility than IEP — any disability (including anxiety, ASD-related) that \'substantially limits a major life activity\' (learning, concentrating, social interaction). (2) For PDA, a 504 Plan can provide: reduced demand accommodations, flexible scheduling, movement breaks, alternative assignments, sensory accommodations, testing modifications, reduced homework, communication modifications (indirect language), safe space access. (3) 504 does NOT provide specialized instruction or related services — only accommodations. If your child needs a modified curriculum or therapeutic services, push for IEP. (4) CRITICAL: 504 can include a demand reduction plan: explicit list of demands that are modified or eliminated, alternative ways to demonstrate learning, flexible attendance for school avoidance, adult check-ins for anxiety management. (5) If 504 is denied: file OCR complaint with Office for Civil Rights — ed.gov/ocr, (800) 421-3481. (6) 504 is enforced under Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act and ADA — stronger anti-discrimination protection than IDEA in some areas. (7) Document accommodation implementation — 504 has no progress monitoring like IEP, so YOU must track.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: If IEP denied, immediately request 504 evaluation: \'My child has [diagnosis] with a demand avoidance profile that substantially limits major life activities including learning, concentrating, and self-care. I request a 504 evaluation.\'\nSTEP 2: Provide documentation: clinical evaluation, school evaluation, PDA Profile Summary.\nSTEP 3: At 504 meeting, present PDA-specific accommodation list (same as IEP accommodations from Step 4.3).\nSTEP 4: Get the 504 plan IN WRITING with specific PDA accommodations.\nSTEP 5: Monitor implementation — email teachers monthly: \'Is [child] receiving all 504 accommodations? Any challenges?\'\nSTEP 6: If accommodations not implemented: file OCR complaint (ed.gov/ocr) — (800) 421-3481.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL 504 COORDINATOR: Usually principal or school counselor — ask front office.\nDISTRICT 504 CONTACT: Through your district\'s special education or student services office.\nIF 504 DENIED:\n• OCR (Office for Civil Rights): ed.gov/ocr — (800) 421-3481\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• DREDF: dredf.org (disability rights)\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your school district Special Education department\n• CA Dept of Education: cde.ca.gov/sp/se\n• Parent Training & Information Centers: parentcenterhub.org — find your CA PTI by county\n\nDOCUMENTS: 504 DOCUMENTS:\n• Written request for 504 evaluation\n• Medical documentation (ASD/anxiety diagnosis, evaluation reports)\n• Private evaluation with PDA profile documentation\n• 504 Plan document (accommodations listed)\n• Teacher acknowledgment form\n• Annual review notes\n• Implementation tracking records (parent-maintained)\n\nFOR FUTURE TRANSITIONS:\n• Complete 504 accommodation history\n• All supporting evaluations\n• Documentation of accommodation effectiveness\n• SAT/ACT/college accommodation applications will need this history\n\nTIMELINE: No specific federal timeline — \'reasonable\' time.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept 504 if your child needs specialized instruction or a BIP — 504 only provides accommodations, not specially designed instruction. (2) Accept generic accommodations (just \'extra time\') — PDA needs very specific accommodations around demand reduction, flexibility, and safe space access. (3) Let 504 go unmonitored — there\'s no progress monitoring like IEP, so YOU must track implementation. (4) Forget that 504 accommodations are legally enforceable under Section 504 — file OCR complaint if school ignores them.\n\nRISKS: District doesn\'t mention 504 when denying IEP. 504 plan is generic (extra time only). PDA-specific accommodations not included. No enforcement mechanism as strong as IEP. Staff don\'t implement 504 accommodations consistently.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(504 Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPhysician (documentation)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s45','journey-pda','step-45','PDA Step 4.5: IEP/504 Dispute Resolution (If Needed)','PDA — Step 4.5: IEP/504 Dispute Resolution (If Needed)\n\nWHAT TO DO: KNOW YOUR DISPUTE RESOLUTION OPTIONS AND USE THEM: (1) If the school denies evaluation, denies eligibility, offers inadequate IEP/504, or fails to implement accommodations: you have legal rights. (2) California dispute resolution options in escalating order: (a) Informal resolution — meet with principal/SpEd director, bring advocate; (b) Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) — facilitated IEP or mediation through CDE; (c) CDE Compliance Complaint — file within 1 year at cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — CDE investigates and can order corrective action; (d) Mediation — free, through OAH (Office of Administrative Hearings), voluntary; (e) Due Process Hearing — formal legal proceeding through OAH, 2-year statute of limitations. (3) For PDA families, common disputes include: school uses punitive behavioral approach (restraint, seclusion, suspension) instead of anxiety-based, school attributes avoidance to \'choice\' rather than disability, IEP goals focused on compliance rather than anxiety reduction, school refuses to implement low-demand accommodations, school attendance policies penalize disability-related absences. (4) RESTRAINT AND SECLUSION: California law limits use — if your child is restrained or secluded, demand incident reports and file complaint. CA Ed Code §49005-49006.4. (5) FREE advocacy support available — use it.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Document the dispute clearly in writing. Email to SpEd director: \'I disagree with [specific decision]. My child requires [specific accommodation/service] because [PDA-specific reason].\'\nSTEP 2: Request another IEP meeting to resolve informally.\nSTEP 3: If informal resolution fails, choose escalation path:\n  (a) CDE Compliance Complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — for procedural violations. Free, CDE investigates. Decision within 60 days.\n  (b) Mediation through OAH: dgs.ca.gov/OAH — free, voluntary, confidential.\n  (c) Due Process Hearing: OAH — (916) 263-0880 — formal hearing, decision binding.\nSTEP 4: Contact DRC BEFORE filing anything: (800) 776-5746 — free consultation on best strategy.\nSTEP 5: Consider hiring a SpEd attorney for due process. Many work on contingency for strong cases.\nSTEP 6: 2-YEAR statute of limitations from the date you knew or should have known about the violation.\n\nCONTACT: DRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal consultation and representation for some cases\nCDE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file online or by mail\nOAH (mediation/due process): dgs.ca.gov/OAH — (916) 263-0880\nCASE: caseadvocacy.org — free advocacy support\nSPECIAL EDUCATION ATTORNEYS (CA):\n• Disability Rights Education & Defense Fund (DREDF): dredf.org\n• Ask DRC for attorney referrals\n• CA State Bar lawyer referral: calbar.ca.gov\nOCR (for 504 complaints): ed.gov/ocr — (800) 421-3481\n\nDOCUMENTS: DISPUTE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written description of dispute (dated)\n• All relevant IEP/504 documents\n• Evaluation reports\n• Communication log (all emails with school)\n• Evidence of PDA profile and needed supports\n• Prior Written Notice from district\n• Timeline of events\n\nFILING DOCUMENTS:\n• CDE Complaint: complaint form + supporting docs\n• OAH Mediation: request form\n• OAH Due Process: complaint filing\n• OCR Complaint (504): complaint form + evidence of discrimination\n\nTIMELINE: CDE complaint: 60 days. Due process: 45 days from filing.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept verbal promises — get everything in writing. (2) Skip the informal resolution step — many disputes resolve through a well-written letter or advocate call. (3) File due process without legal guidance — consult DRC first (free). (4) Let the 2-year statute of limitations pass. (5) Accept mediation if the school has already shown bad faith — go to due process. (6) Represent yourself at due process hearing without at least consulting an attorney.\n\nRISKS: Parent doesn\'t know appeal rights. District claims \'PDA isn\'t a real diagnosis.\' Attorney unfamiliar with PDA. Hearing officer unfamiliar with PDA research. Cost of private advocate/attorney.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District / CDE / OAH\nOTHER AGENCIES: DRC\nSpecial Ed Attorney\nPDA-informed advocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s51','journey-pda','step-51','PDA Step 5.1: Find PDA-Affirming Therapists & Providers','PDA — Step 5.1: Find PDA-Affirming Therapists & Providers\n\nWHAT TO DO: FIND PROVIDERS WHO UNDERSTAND PDA — THIS IS CRITICAL: (1) Traditional therapeutic approaches often FAIL or HARM PDA children: standard ABA (compliance-based), traditional CBT (demand-heavy worksheets/homework), behavioral reward/punishment systems, social skills groups focused on compliance. (2) PDA-AFFIRMING approaches: Collaborative & Proactive Solutions (Ross Greene model — cpsconnection.com), Declarative Language strategies (Linda Murphy), low-demand ABA or naturalistic ABA (if using ABA at all — play-based, child-led), DIR/Floortime (child-led, relationship-based), occupational therapy with sensory integration, drama therapy/art therapy (leverages PDA strength in role-play). (3) When interviewing providers, ask: \'Are you familiar with PDA/Pathological Demand Avoidance? How do you modify your approach for children who experience anxiety-driven demand avoidance? Do you use compliance-based or autonomy-based approaches?\' (4) RED FLAGS: provider says \'they just need firmer boundaries,\' uses token economies/sticker charts as primary strategy, insists on ABA compliance training, dismisses PDA as \'just ODD.\' (5) CA-specific: Regional Center can fund PDA-informed behavioral consultation — request \'behavioral services using collaborative, low-demand methodology.\' (6) Many PDA-knowledgeable providers offer telehealth — don\'t limit search to your city. (7) PDA North America maintains a growing provider directory.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Search for PDA-informed therapists: PDANA directory (pdanorthamerica.org/find-help), Psychology Today (filter: autism, anxiety, demand avoidance), ask PDA parent groups for CA recommendations.\nSTEP 2: Interview every potential therapist: \'Are you familiar with PDA/pathological demand avoidance? What approaches do you use with children who have anxiety-driven demand avoidance? Do you use reward/consequence systems? How do you handle a child who refuses to participate in a session?\'\nSTEP 3: RED FLAGS in therapist responses: mentions token economy, mentions \'earning\' privileges, describes compliance goals, says \'they just need consistent boundaries,\' unfamiliar with PDA.\nSTEP 4: GREEN FLAGS: mentions collaborative approaches, talks about reducing demands, discusses anxiety management, flexible about session structure, willing to follow child\'s lead.\nSTEP 5: Therapy types most compatible with PDA: Acceptance and Commitment Therapy (ACT), Play therapy (child-led), SPACE treatment (parent-focused), Modified/adapted CBT (low-demand), Art/music therapy.\nSTEP 6: Request RC fund PDA-informed therapy through IPP. Request insurance authorization citing autism diagnosis (SB 946).\n\nCONTACT: FIND PDA-INFORMED THERAPISTS:\n• PDANA directory: pdanorthamerica.org/find-help\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — search PDA, demand avoidance, autism anxiety\n• SPACE therapist directory: spacetreatment.net\n• Ask PDA parent Facebook groups for CA provider names\nINSURANCE AUTHORIZATION:\n• SB 946 (CA): requires insurance to cover behavioral therapy for autism\n• DMHC: (888) 466-2219 — HMO complaints\n• CDI: (800) 927-4357 — PPO complaints\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org\nREGIONAL CENTER:\n• Request PDA-informed therapy through IPP\n• If RC assigns non-PDA-informed provider, request change\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032\n\nDOCUMENTS: THERAPY DOCUMENTS:\n• Insurance pre-authorization (if required)\n• Therapist credentials and approach description\n• Treatment plan from therapist (should reflect PDA-informed approach)\n• Session notes and progress reports\n• Your tracking log: is therapy helping or increasing demand avoidance?\n\nINSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Referral from pediatrician/diagnosing clinician\n• Pre-authorization approval\n• EOB after sessions\n• Appeal materials if denied (DRC can help)\n\nTIMELINE: Waitlists vary. PDA-informed providers are scarce — may need telehealth.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Send your child to a therapist who uses compliance-based approaches — this includes traditional CBT that requires homework compliance, exposure therapy without child-led pacing, or any therapy that uses reward/consequence systems. (2) Assume all autism therapists understand PDA — most don\'t. (3) Continue with a therapist who makes your child worse — if demand avoidance increases after therapy starts, the approach may be wrong. (4) Pursue ABA without ensuring it\'s PDA-informed and naturalistic — discrete trial ABA is harmful for PDA profiles. (5) Skip therapy for parents — parent coaching in low-demand strategies is often MORE impactful than direct child therapy.\n\nRISKS: ★ PROVIDER DESERT: Very few U.S. therapists understand PDA. Traditional ABA providers dominate autism therapy landscape. Insurance may only cover \'ABA\' for autism, not PDA-informed alternatives. RC vendor list may not include PDA-affirming providers. Rural areas: virtually no options. Telehealth may be only option for PDA-informed care.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Providers\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nRegional Center\nMedi-Cal\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s52','journey-pda','step-52','PDA Step 5.2: Insurance Authorization for PDA-Informed Therapy','PDA — Step 5.2: Insurance Authorization for PDA-Informed Therapy\n\nWHAT TO DO: NAVIGATE INSURANCE FOR PDA-INFORMED THERAPY: (1) CA SB 946 (Autism insurance mandate) requires insurance to cover behavioral health treatment (BHT) for ASD — including ABA. For PDA, request \'modified ABA using naturalistic, play-based methodology\' or \'behavioral consultation using low-demand approaches.\' (2) Insurance will NOT cover \'PDA therapy\' — you must use covered diagnostic codes: ASD (F84.0), Generalized Anxiety (F41.1), Social Anxiety (F40.10), Adjustment Disorder. (3) Mental health parity laws require coverage for anxiety treatment: individual therapy (CBT modified for PDA), family therapy, psychiatric evaluation for medication (anxiety medication can help PDA). (4) If insurance denies ABA or therapy: CA DMHC complaint (HMO): (888) 466-2219; CA CDI complaint (PPO): (800) 927-4357. (5) Regional Center fills gaps insurance won\'t cover — respite, parent training, behavioral consultation. (6) Medi-Cal covers behavioral health through managed care plans. (7) School-based services (IEP/504) are FREE regardless of insurance. (8) For PDA medication evaluation: SSRIs (anxiety) may help reduce baseline anxiety, making demands more tolerable — discuss with child psychiatrist, not just pediatrician.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Call insurance: \'My child has an ASD diagnosis. I\'m requesting authorization for behavioral health treatment under CA SB 946. The treatment plan calls for [therapy type] with a PDA-informed provider.\'\nSTEP 2: If insurance denies: file internal appeal first, then external appeal through DMHC (HMO) or CDI (PPO).\nSTEP 3: If using Medi-Cal: your managed care plan covers behavioral therapy. Call the plan directly.\nSTEP 4: If insurance won\'t cover a PDA-informed provider: request a \'network inadequacy\' exception — if no in-network provider has PDA expertise, insurance may be required to cover an out-of-network provider.\nSTEP 5: Track all authorization dates, session limits, and renewal deadlines.\nSTEP 6: For services not covered by insurance, request through RC IPP.\n\nCONTACT: INSURANCE HELP:\n• DMHC (HMO complaints/appeals): (888) 466-2219\n• CDI (PPO complaints/appeals): (800) 927-4357\n• Health Consumer Alliance: healthconsumer.org — free insurance navigation help\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — insurance rights\nMEDI-CAL:\n• Managed care plan: call number on Medi-Cal card\n• Medi-Cal Ombudsman: (888) 452-8609\nSB 946 INFORMATION:\n• CA Health & Safety Code §1374.73 — autism behavioral therapy mandate\n• Autism Speaks insurance guide: autismspeaks.org/insurance\n\nDOCUMENTS: INSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Pre-authorization request and approval\n• Treatment plan from provider\n• Authorization dates and session limits\n• Denial letter (if denied)\n• Appeal documentation\n• EOBs (Explanation of Benefits)\n• Provider credentials\n\nTRACK:\n• Authorization start/end dates\n• Sessions used vs approved\n• Renewal deadlines\n• Co-pay/deductible status\n\nTIMELINE: Prior auth: 5-15 business days. Denial appeal: 30 days internal, 45 days DMHC IMR.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept insurance denial without appealing — CA SB 946 requires insurance to cover behavioral health treatment for autism. (2) Let insurance dictate the therapy type — you have the right to request specific PDA-informed approaches. (3) Accept a provider from insurance\'s list without verifying PDA familiarity. (4) Forget Medi-Cal as an option — Medi-Cal covers behavioral therapy for autism with no co-pay. (5) Let prior authorization expire without renewal — track authorization end dates.\n\nRISKS: Insurance denies non-ABA autism therapy. Authorization limited to traditional ABA hours. PDA-informed therapy coded differently — doesn\'t match ABA billing codes. Medi-Cal managed care plan unfamiliar with PDA. Prior auth requires \'medical necessity\' documentation that specifically addresses PDA approach.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Insurance / Medi-Cal\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician (referral)\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s61','journey-pda','step-61','PDA Step 6.1: Address School Avoidance / School Refusal','PDA — Step 6.1: Address School Avoidance / School Refusal\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADDRESS SCHOOL AVOIDANCE AS A DISABILITY SYMPTOM, NOT A BEHAVIOR PROBLEM: (1) School avoidance/refusal is one of the most common and devastating PDA impacts — up to 70% of PDA children experience significant school avoidance. (2) CRITICAL REFRAME: Your child is not \'truant\' or \'school-refusing\' — they are experiencing a disability-related inability to tolerate the demand-saturated school environment. Every aspect of school is a demand: arrival time, sitting still, following instructions, social navigation, academic work, transitions. (3) DOCUMENT EVERYTHING: every absence, every morning struggle (video if possible), anxiety symptoms (nausea, headaches, meltdowns, shutdowns), and what you\'ve tried. (4) Demand a TEAM MEETING immediately — bring your documentation and advocate. (5) Explore alternatives within the IEP/504: part-time schedule (gradual increase), homebound instruction (CA Ed Code §48206.3), independent study program, online/virtual school within your district, alternative school placement, hybrid schedule. (6) California chronic absence threshold: 10% of school days. Schools must provide intervention, NOT punishment. (7) If district threatens truancy: respond with disability documentation. Truancy proceedings against a child whose absences are disability-related violate Section 504 and ADA. Contact DRC immediately. (8) SARB (School Attendance Review Board) cannot override IEP accommodations for attendance.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: IMMEDIATELY notify the school IN WRITING: \'My child\'s attendance difficulties are directly related to their disability ([diagnosis]). I am requesting an IEP meeting to address school avoidance as a manifestation of their disability. I am also requesting that any attendance-related interventions be trauma-informed and PDA-appropriate.\'\nSTEP 2: Request IEP amendment for school avoidance accommodations: (a) Modified schedule (gradual re-entry, part-time, late start), (b) Designated safe person and safe space, (c) Alternative arrival/departure (avoid crowded times), (d) Home-hospital instruction if needed (CA Ed Code §48206.3), (e) Independent study option (CA Ed Code §51745).\nSTEP 3: Document all absences as disability-related — this protects against truancy consequences.\nSTEP 4: Consider whether current placement is appropriate — may need transfer, reduced setting, or alternative program.\nSTEP 5: Address underlying anxiety: increase therapy, consider SPACE treatment (parent-focused anxiety intervention), reduce non-school demands at home.\nSTEP 6: If SARB threatened: contact DRC immediately (800) 776-5746. PDA school avoidance is disability-related, not truancy.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT: Principal + SpEd coordinator — request emergency IEP meeting.\nHOME-HOSPITAL INSTRUCTION: Request through school district. CA Ed Code §48206.3.\nINDEPENDENT STUDY: CA Ed Code §51745 — request through district.\nLEGAL PROTECTION:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — school avoidance and disability rights\n• CA Ed Code §48900.5 — cannot suspend for attendance without considering disability\n• AB 2040 — attendance reforms protecting disabled students\nPDA SCHOOL REFUSAL RESOURCES:\n• PDA Society: pdasociety.org.uk/education — school avoidance guidance\n• Not Fine in School: notfineinschool.co.uk — parent support for school avoidance\n• SPACE treatment: spacetreatment.net\n\nDOCUMENTS: SCHOOL AVOIDANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written notification to school (disability-related absences)\n• IEP amendment request\n• Attendance records showing pattern\n• Clinical documentation linking avoidance to disability\n• Home-hospital instruction request (if needed)\n• Independent study request (if applicable)\n• Communication log with school re: attendance\n\nIF SARB THREATENED:\n• Written response: \'Absences are disability-related under [diagnosis]. SARB proceedings would constitute disability discrimination.\'\n• DRC contact information\n• All IEP/504 documentation showing disability\n• Medical/clinical letters supporting disability-related avoidance\n\nTIMELINE: Home/hospital: 5 school days for temporary certification. Modified schedule: IEP team decision.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Force school attendance through punishment — this increases trauma and may trigger school refusal crisis. (2) Assume school refusal is \'truancy\' — PDA-related school avoidance is anxiety-driven and disability-related. CA Education Code §48900.5 and AB 2040 protect against punitive attendance responses for disability-related absences. (3) Accept the school\'s \'tough love\' approach or threats of SARB (School Attendance Review Board). (4) Blame your child — they are not choosing to avoid school; their nervous system is in survival mode. (5) Wait for it to \'resolve on its own\' — school avoidance typically escalates without intervention. (6) Remove all support because \'they need to learn to cope\' — this is not a coping skills issue.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRISIS RISK: School threatens truancy/SARB (Student Attendance Review Board) proceedings against PDA family. Parent blamed for not \'making\' child attend. Child forced back to school prematurely — retraumatized. Home/hospital instruction limited to 60-day certification. Independent study requires specific agreement. District resists modified schedule.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District\nParent\nOTHER AGENCIES: County Office of Ed\nMental health provider\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s62','journey-pda','step-62','PDA Step 6.2: Manage PDA Crisis Episodes (Meltdowns/Shutdowns)','PDA — Step 6.2: Manage PDA Crisis Episodes (Meltdowns/Shutdowns)\n\nWHAT TO DO: DEVELOP A PDA CRISIS SAFETY PLAN FOR HOME AND SCHOOL: (1) PDA meltdowns are NOT tantrums — they are neurological overwhelm (fight/flight/freeze response) triggered by demand overload. The child has LOST voluntary control. (2) DURING CRISIS: ensure physical safety (yours and theirs), REMOVE ALL DEMANDS (stop talking, stop directing, step back), reduce sensory input (lights, noise), offer SPACE not solutions, wait. Say nothing or use only soothing sounds. Do NOT: restrain (unless imminent danger), lecture, give consequences, ask questions, or make demands during the crisis. (3) RECOVERY PERIOD: PDA meltdown recovery can take hours to DAYS. Demand tolerance is dramatically reduced after crisis. Drop demands to absolute minimum for 24-48 hours. (4) PREVENTION: maintain demand audit, monitor early warning signs (increased rigidity, refusal of previously tolerated activities, withdrawal, physical complaints), proactively reduce demands before threshold is reached. (5) SCHOOL CRISIS PLAN: Write it into the IEP/504/BIP. Include: designated safe space, named trusted adult, no demand/no consequence during crisis, recovery time protocol, parent notification, NO restraint or seclusion (CA Ed Code §49005). (6) IF SCHOOL USES RESTRAINT/SECLUSION: document, demand incident report within 24 hours, file CDE complaint, contact DRC. (7) Emergency: if child is in danger, call 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline or mobile crisis team.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: DURING MELTDOWN: (a) Reduce all demands to zero — say nothing or use minimal, calm reassurance, (b) Ensure safety — remove dangerous objects, keep distance if child is physical, (c) Reduce sensory input — dim lights, reduce noise, remove other people, (d) Offer regulation tools without demand: place weighted blanket nearby (don\'t put it on them), open the door to their safe space, (e) Wait — meltdowns have a physiological arc that must complete.\nSTEP 2: AFTER MELTDOWN (when child is regulated — may be hours later): (a) Reconnect with warmth, no judgment, (b) If child wants to discuss, use \'I noticed\' language: \'I noticed that was really hard.\' (c) Do NOT require apology or processing.\nSTEP 3: CREATE A CRISIS PLAN with your child (when calm): safe space, regulation tools, signal words, what helps, what doesn\'t.\nSTEP 4: Include crisis plan in IEP/504 — school staff must know the plan.\nSTEP 5: Debrief with partner/support system — caregiver emotional processing is essential.\nSTEP 6: If meltdowns are escalating in frequency or severity: increase therapy, request RC crisis services, reassess demand load.\n\nCONTACT: CRISIS SUPPORT:\n• Your child\'s therapist (if available for urgent consultation)\n• Regional Center: request crisis services through service coordinator\n• 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline: call/text 988 (if safety concern)\n• Crisis Text Line: text HOME to 741741\n• CA Behavioral Health Crisis Line: your county\'s crisis line\nPDA CRISIS RESOURCES:\n• PDA Society crisis guidance: pdasociety.org.uk\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org\nSCHOOL CRISIS:\n• Ensure IEP/504 includes crisis plan\n• School should NOT call police for disability-related meltdowns\n• If school uses restraint/seclusion: document and report to DRC (800) 776-5746\n\nDOCUMENTS: CRISIS PLAN DOCUMENTS:\n• Written crisis plan (co-created with child when calm)\n• Safe space identification (home and school)\n• Regulation tools list\n• Signal words/phrases\n• De-escalation steps for caregivers and staff\n• Emergency contacts\n• Medical information\n\nIEP/504 CRISIS ADDENDUM:\n• Crisis plan incorporated into BIP\n• Staff trained on plan\n• Documentation of any restraint/seclusion incidents (school must report to parent)\n• Incident reports from school (request copies)\n\nTIMELINE: Immediate response needed during crisis. Prevention is ongoing.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Restrain your child during a meltdown unless there is immediate danger — restraint escalates PDA crisis. (2) Use verbal demands during a meltdown: \'Stop crying,\' \'Calm down,\' \'Go to your room.\' (3) Punish after a meltdown — PDA meltdowns are involuntary nervous system responses, not behavioral choices. (4) Call police during a meltdown unless there is genuine safety risk — police involvement can be traumatic and dangerous for neurodivergent individuals. (5) Discuss the incident immediately after — wait until your child is fully regulated (may be hours). (6) Use physical interventions taught in schools (CPI, restraint) at home.\n\nRISKS: School staff physically restrain child during meltdown (common, traumatic for PDA children). School calls police for \'violent behavior.\' Seclusion room used. Child suspended or expelled for crisis behavior. Parent called to pick up child repeatedly — job loss risk. Crisis misidentified as manipulative behavior rather than dysregulation.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nSchool staff\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s71','journey-pda','step-71','PDA Step 7.1: Ongoing IEP/504 Review — PDA-Specific Monitoring','PDA — Step 7.1: Ongoing IEP/504 Review — PDA-Specific Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: MONITOR AND ADAPT THE IEP/504 FOR PDA\'S CHANGING PRESENTATION: (1) PDA demands change as your child grows — what worked at age 6 may fail at age 10. Puberty often dramatically increases demand sensitivity. (2) Review IEP/504 PROACTIVELY every 6 months (you can request a meeting anytime). Focus on: Are accommodations actually being implemented? Is the behavioral approach still anxiety-based (not compliance-based)? Has demand tolerance changed? Are new demands emerging (academic complexity, social pressure, puberty)? (3) Track quarterly: absences, grades, behavioral incidents, your child\'s self-reported anxiety level, demand avoidance severity. (4) Watch for MASKING COLLAPSE: PDA children often hold it together at school and collapse at home. If your child is \'fine at school\' but melting down every evening, they are NOT fine — they are masking at unsustainable cost. Document the home impact and present to the IEP team. (5) Triennial re-evaluation every 3 years — do NOT waive. Request updated FBA focused on demand avoidance. (6) If approaches aren\'t working, request: change in behavioral methodology, updated FBA, IEE at district expense, change in placement (more flexible environment). (7) Connect with other PDA parents for strategy sharing — PDA Society forum, PDA North America.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Create a PDA IEP monitoring calendar: annual IEP date, triennial date, quarterly progress checks.\nSTEP 2: 30 days before annual IEP: write updated Parent Concerns Letter describing current PDA presentation, what\'s working, what\'s not, new concerns.\nSTEP 3: At each review, assess: (a) Are accommodations being implemented? (b) Is the BIP approach still PDA-appropriate? (c) Has school avoidance improved or worsened? (d) Is masking being addressed? (e) Are staff trained on PDA? (f) Is the crisis plan current?\nSTEP 4: Request data: attendance records, behavioral incident reports, staff implementation logs.\nSTEP 5: If not progressing: request IEP meeting to revise approach, consider FBA update, consider change of placement.\nSTEP 6: Every 3 years (triennial): participate in re-evaluation. Request updated assessment of PDA profile, anxiety, and functional impact.\n\nCONTACT: IEP CASE MANAGER: Your child\'s SpEd teacher — primary contact.\nADVOCACY:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP advocacy\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• TASK: taskca.org\n• Matrix: matrixparents.org\nIF ACCOMMODATIONS NOT IMPLEMENTED:\n• Document in writing to SpEd coordinator\n• Request IEP meeting\n• If unresolved: CDE complaint (cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp)\nPDA MONITORING:\n• PDA Society education: pdasociety.org.uk/education\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: ONGOING DOCUMENTS:\n• Annual IEP documents (keep every version)\n• Parent Concerns Letters (annual)\n• Quarterly progress reports\n• Attendance records\n• Behavioral incident reports\n• Staff training documentation\n• Crisis plan (updated annually)\n• Communication log with school\n• Triennial evaluation reports (every 3 years)\n\nPARENT MONITORING BINDER:\n• Section 1: Current IEP + BIP\n• Section 2: Evaluations\n• Section 3: Progress reports\n• Section 4: Correspondence\n• Section 5: PDA resources shared with school\n• Section 6: Crisis plan\n\nTIMELINE: Annual IEP review. Triennial reassessment every 3 years. Parent can request review anytime.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Skip annual IEP reviews or go unprepared. (2) Accept the same accommodations year after year without checking effectiveness. (3) Waive triennial re-evaluation — PDA presentation changes as children develop, updated data is critical. (4) Let services decrease without evidence that PDA accommodation needs have decreased. (5) Assume PDA \'goes away\' — it\'s a lifelong neurological profile that requires ongoing support. (6) Stop monitoring implementation — PDA accommodations are often the first dropped by new teachers who \'don\'t believe in special treatment.\'\n\nRISKS: Goals changed to compliance-based without parent agreement. PDA-trained staff leave — replacements use traditional approaches. Success at school (masking) used to justify reducing supports. After-school collapse worsens but school claims child is \'doing great.\'\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPrivate therapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s72','journey-pda','step-72','PDA Step 7.2: Transition Planning (Age 14+)','PDA — Step 7.2: Transition Planning (Age 14+)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PLAN TRANSITION WITH PDA-SPECIFIC CONSIDERATIONS: (1) Transition for PDA is uniquely complex because traditional transition goals (employment, independent living, post-secondary education) involve HIGH-DEMAND environments. (2) ITP (Individual Transition Plan) by age 16 — include: flexible post-secondary pathway (gap year, part-time college, online learning, vocational with accommodations), career exploration focused on autonomy and interest-driven work (many PDA adults thrive in self-employment, creative fields, or roles with high autonomy and low external demand). (3) Self-advocacy is CRITICAL: teach your child to understand their PDA profile, recognize demand overload, communicate needs (\'I need a break,\' \'I can do this differently\'), and request accommodations. (4) College disability services: student must self-identify. IEP doesn\'t transfer but documentation does. Request accommodations: flexible attendance, extended deadlines, alternative assignments, reduced course load, testing modifications. (5) DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation) may provide vocational support: dor.ca.gov. (6) If ASD diagnosis: IHSS, SSI may continue into adulthood. Regional Center services continue through adult life. (7) CalABLE account: calable.ca.gov — available for disability-related savings. (8) Housing: independent living may require supported living services through RC. Explore gradual independence with support.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 14: request ITP (Individual Transition Plan) development within IEP. Include self-advocacy, career exploration, and independence goals.\nSTEP 2: Career exploration: help your child identify interests and strengths. PDA-friendly career characteristics: autonomy, flexibility, interest-driven, limited rigid hierarchy. Many PDA adults succeed in creative, entrepreneurial, and self-employed roles.\nSTEP 3: Self-advocacy: teach your child to understand and explain their PDA profile. Role-play: \'I work best when I can manage my own schedule. I need flexibility and autonomy. I have anxiety around rigid demands.\'\nSTEP 4: By age 15-16: prepare for SAT/ACT accommodations (if college-bound). Current evaluation + accommodation history needed. College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities.\nSTEP 5: College prep: identify colleges with strong disability services. Visit offices during tours. Community college as low-demand entry point.\nSTEP 6: DOR referral at age 16: dor.ca.gov — vocational support, job coaching, workplace accommodations.\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM: Transition planning at IEP meetings starting age 14.\nDOR: dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation (referral at age 16)\nSAT/ACT:\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities — (844) 255-7728\n• ACT: act.org/the-act/accommodations — (319) 337-1332\nCOLLEGE DISABILITY SERVICES:\n• AHEAD: ahead.org — college disability resource\n• Each college\'s disability office\nPDA ADULT RESOURCES:\n• PDA Society adult resources: pdasociety.org.uk/life-with-pda/adults\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org\n• Harry Thompson\'s \'The PDA Paradox\' (adult perspective)\nCalABLE: calable.ca.gov — if applicable\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ITP in IEP (starting age 14+)\n• Transition assessments (interests, strengths, needs)\n• Self-advocacy plan\n• Career exploration results\n• SAT/ACT accommodation application (6+ months before test)\n• College disability documentation packet\n• DOR referral and IPE (Individual Plan for Employment)\n• Summary of Performance (from school at graduation)\n\nCOLLEGE PREP PACKET:\n• Most recent evaluation (within 3 years)\n• IEP/504 history (accommodation documentation)\n• PDA Profile Summary (adapted for college disability office)\n• Clinician letter describing PDA and needed accommodations\n\nTIMELINE: Transition plan required by age 16 (14 recommended).\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Wait until senior year — start transition planning at age 14+. (2) Assume PDA means your child can\'t work or attend college — many PDA adults are highly successful in self-directed, flexible environments. (3) Push your child toward a career path that involves high demand compliance (rigid schedules, strict hierarchies) — PDA adults thrive in autonomous roles. (4) Skip self-advocacy skill development — understanding their own PDA profile is the most important transition skill. (5) Forget to build accommodation documentation history for college SAT/ACT requests. (6) Ignore DOR (Department of Rehabilitation) services — available at age 16.\n\nRISKS: \'Failure to launch\' — PDA youth may struggle with post-secondary demands (college, employment, independent living). Traditional transition programs are demand-heavy. Self-advocacy training uses directive approach that triggers PDA. College disability office unfamiliar with PDA. Employment environments are inherently demand-heavy.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: DOR\nCollege disability office\nRC (if eligible)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-pda-s73','journey-pda','step-73','PDA Step 7.3: Adult PDA — Ongoing Support & Self-Advocacy','PDA — Step 7.3: Adult PDA — Ongoing Support & Self-Advocacy\n\nWHAT TO DO: SUPPORT ADULT PDA — LIFELONG MANAGEMENT AND SELF-ADVOCACY: (1) PDA does not resolve in adulthood — it evolves. Many PDA adults develop sophisticated coping strategies but remain fundamentally demand-avoidant. (2) Key adult PDA resources: \'The PDA Paradox\' by Harry Thompson (adult PDA lived experience), PDA Society adult resources, PDA North America adult community. (3) Adult PDA challenges: employment (traditional 9-5 with boss demands is extremely difficult), relationships (partner demands trigger avoidance), healthcare (appointment demands, medication compliance demands), self-care (basic demands of daily living). (4) Successful PDA adults often: work for themselves or in high-autonomy roles, structure their environment to minimize external demands, use technology to manage demands (reminders, automation), have partners/supports who understand PDA. (5) Mental health: anxiety, depression, burnout, and autistic burnout are very common in PDA adults. Ensure ongoing mental health support with a PDA-aware therapist. (6) Benefits continuation: if receiving SSI/IHSS/RC services, navigate adult re-determination (SSI redetermination at 18, ongoing IHSS annual reviews). (7) Self-advocacy resources: ASAN (Autistic Self Advocacy Network), PDA Society, local self-advocacy organizations. (8) Legal planning: SDM (Supported Decision-Making) preferred over conservatorship — PDA adults can make their own decisions with appropriate support.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 18: ensure continuity of services. If RC-eligible: continue IPP with adult services. If employed: request workplace accommodations under ADA.\nSTEP 2: RC Self-Determination Program: perfect for PDA — YOU direct your own services and budget. Apply through your service coordinator.\nSTEP 3: Workplace accommodations (ADA): flexible schedule, remote work options, reduced meetings, written instructions instead of verbal, autonomy in task management. File ADA accommodation request with employer.\nSTEP 4: Ongoing mental health: continue PDA-informed therapy. Monitor for burnout, anxiety, depression.\nSTEP 5: Build PDA-affirming social network: PDANA community, autistic adult groups, online PDA communities.\nSTEP 6: Financial planning: CalABLE account (calable.ca.gov), SSI (if applicable), Special Needs Trust for assets above SSI limits.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER: Lifelong services if ASD-eligible. Self-Determination Program.\nWORKPLACE ACCOMMODATIONS:\n• ADA: ada.gov — accommodation information\n• JAN (Job Accommodation Network): askjan.org — (800) 526-7234 — free workplace accommodation consultation\n• DOR: dor.ca.gov — ongoing vocational support\nMENTAL HEALTH:\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — find PDA-informed therapist\n• NAMI CA: namica.org — support groups\nFINANCIAL:\n• CalABLE: calable.ca.gov\n• SSI: ssa.gov — (800) 772-1213\n• SNT attorneys: CA Special Needs Trust attorneys through DRC referral\nPDA ADULT COMMUNITY:\n• PDA Society (adults): pdasociety.org.uk/life-with-pda/adults\n• PDANA: pdanorthamerica.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: ADULT DOCUMENTS:\n• RC IPP (ongoing, with Self-Determination if applicable)\n• ADA accommodation request (employer)\n• DOR IPE (if using vocational services)\n• SSI application/records (if applicable)\n• CalABLE account setup\n• Special Needs Trust (if applicable)\n• Mental health treatment records\n• PDA Profile Summary (adult version — for employers, providers, colleges)\n\nTIMELINE: SSI re-evaluation at age 18. RC transition to adult services.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Assume adult services will be as structured as school-based services — adults must self-advocate. (2) Drop all professional support at age 18/22 — PDA is lifelong. (3) Ignore mental health — PDA adults have high rates of anxiety, depression, and burnout. (4) Force traditional employment model — PDA adults may need accommodations, flexible schedules, or self-employment pathways. (5) Forget about Regional Center — if ASD-eligible, RC provides lifelong services (Self-Determination Program is particularly PDA-compatible).\n\nRISKS: Adult PDA under-recognized. Workplace demands cause burnout and job loss. SSI evaluators unfamiliar with PDA. Mental health providers treat anxiety/depression without understanding PDA root. Relationship difficulties from demand sensitivity. Burnout from years of masking.\n\nRESOURCES: PDA NORTH AMERICA: pdanorthamerica.org — free PDA guide, webinars, peer support groups\nPDA SOCIETY UK: pdasociety.org.uk — online courses, practice guidance\nREFRAMING AUTISM: reframingautism.org.au — neurodiversity-affirming resources\nPDA PARENTS: pdaparents.com — parent community and strategies\nLOW-DEMAND PARENTING: lowdemandparenting.com — Amanda Diekman\'s resources\nUNSTUCK AND ON TARGET: flexibility-building program\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training center\nMATRIX PARENT NETWORK: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Multiple agencies\nOTHER AGENCIES: RC (if eligible)\nSSA\nDOR\nMental health\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-overview','journey-adhd','overview','ADHD Journey Map — Overview','ADHD — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n24 steps across 8 phases:\n* 1 Recognition & Concern: Parent/Teacher Notices Attention, Behavior, or Lea, Well-Child Visit / Pediatrician Discussion\n* 2 Evaluation & Diagnosis: Comprehensive ADHD Evaluation, Receive ADHD Diagnosis & Understand Presentation\n* 3 Treatment Planning: Develop Multimodal Treatment Plan, Navigate ADHD Medication (If Applicable), Behavioral Parent Training & Family Strategies\n* 4 School Supports (IEP/504): Request School District Evaluation, School District Evaluation — ADHD-Focused, IEP Development — ADHD-Specific Accommodations & G, 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied or Preferred), IEP/504 Dispute Resolution\n* 5 Insurance & Therapy: Insurance Authorization for ADHD Treatment, Access Behavioral & Organizational Therapy\n* 6 Home & Daily Life Management: Build ADHD-Friendly Home Environment, Executive Function Skill Building\n* 7 Co-occurring Conditions & Complex ADHD: Screen & Address Anxiety (Co-occurs ~40%), Screen & Address Learning Disabilities (Co-occurs , Screen & Address Behavioral/Conduct Problems (Co-o, Address Emotional Dysregulation\n* 8 Long-Term Planning & Transition: Ongoing Medication Management & Monitoring, Annual IEP/504 Review — ADHD-Specific Monitoring, Transition Planning (Age 14+), Adult ADHD — Ongoing Support\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s11','journey-adhd','step-11','ADHD Step 1.1: Parent/Teacher Notices Attention, Behavior, or Learning Concerns','ADHD — Step 1.1: Parent/Teacher Notices Attention, Behavior, or Learning Concerns\n\nWHAT TO DO: TRACK AND DOCUMENT ADHD-RELATED CONCERNS SYSTEMATICALLY: (1) ADHD affects ~9.8% of children ages 3-17 in the US — it is the most commonly diagnosed neurodevelopmental disorder. (2) Three presentations: INATTENTIVE (difficulty focusing, disorganized, forgetful, loses things, doesn\'t follow through — often missed, especially in girls), HYPERACTIVE-IMPULSIVE (fidgety, can\'t sit still, talks excessively, interrupts, acts without thinking), COMBINED (most common, both features). (3) Start a BEHAVIOR LOG: for 2 weeks, document daily observations across settings — school behavior (from teacher), homework battles, social interactions, emotional reactions, sleep quality, appetite. (4) Request TEACHER INPUT: email the teacher: \'I have concerns about [child\'s] attention/focus/behavior. Can you share your observations about how they\'re performing compared to peers? I\'m particularly interested in: staying on task, following multi-step directions, organization, completing work, social interactions, and impulsivity.\' (5) Note: ADHD symptoms must be present in 2+ settings and cause functional impairment. Track both home AND school. (6) Video-record examples if possible — homework sessions, morning routines, emotional outbursts. (7) Girls with ADHD are significantly under-diagnosed — they more often present inattentive (daydreamy, quiet, disorganized) rather than hyperactive.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Create a dated Behavior Log with columns: Date, Setting (home/school), What Happened, Duration, Your Response, What Helped/Didn\'t. Track for minimum 2 weeks.\nSTEP 2: Email your child\'s teacher: \'I\'ve been observing some attention/focus challenges with [child] at home. Can we schedule a brief meeting to compare notes? I\'d like to understand how [child] is doing with: sustained attention, task completion, following directions, staying organized, peer interactions, and self-regulation compared to same-age peers.\'\nSTEP 3: At the teacher meeting, ask: \'Would you be willing to complete a behavioral rating scale if I provide one? My pediatrician may request a Vanderbilt or Conners teacher form.\'\nSTEP 4: Check developmental milestones: Is your child significantly behind peers in executive function tasks (organization, planning, time management, emotional regulation)? ADHD is essentially a developmental delay in executive function.\nSTEP 5: Complete the Vanderbilt Parent Assessment Scale yourself (available free at nichq.org/adhd-toolkit). This is the #1 tool pediatricians use.\nSTEP 6: Schedule a well-child visit or dedicated ADHD concern appointment with your pediatrician. Bring: your behavior log, completed Vanderbilt parent form, teacher observations, report cards, and any prior standardized test scores.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR CHILD\'S TEACHER: First point of contact — request meeting and ask for behavioral observations.\nPEDIATRICIAN: Will likely conduct initial screening using Vanderbilt Assessment Scales.\nSCHOOL COUNSELOR: Can provide observations across settings.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your school district — request SST (Student Study Team) meeting if school concerns exist\n• CHADD (Children and Adults with ADHD): chadd.org — parent education, local chapters throughout CA\n• ADDitude Magazine: additudemag.com — free resources, expert webinars\n• NICHQ ADHD Toolkit: nichq.org/adhd-toolkit — free Vanderbilt forms\n• Understood.org: understood.org — screeners, explanations, tech tools\n• CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org — find your local Parent Training & Information center by county\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEGIN COLLECTING:\n• Behavior log (dated daily observations, 2+ weeks)\n• Report cards (last 2-3 years — look for comments about focus/behavior)\n• Standardized test scores (SBAC/STAR)\n• Teacher comments and progress notes\n• Teacher observation notes (from meeting)\n• Completed Vanderbilt Parent Assessment Scale\n• Your child\'s work samples showing pattern (incomplete work, careless errors, disorganization)\n• Homework time log (expected vs actual time)\n• Sleep log (ADHD often disrupts sleep)\n• Video recordings of concerning behavior (if available)\n• Any prior evaluations or school intervention records\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — earlier identification = better outcomes. Average age of diagnosis is 7, but inattentive type often not identified until middle school.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Parent or teacher observes patterns: difficulty sustaining attention, excessive fidgeting/movement, impulsive behavior (blurting out, not waiting turns), trouble organizing tasks, frequently losing things, difficulty following multi-step instructions, emotional dysregulation (big reactions, low frustration tolerance) | May also notice: daydreaming (inattentive presentation), hyperfocus on preferred activities but inability to engage with non-preferred tasks, social difficulties, homework battles lasting hours\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Girls/AFAB children with inattentive-type ADHD overlooked because they\'re quiet and \'well-behaved.\' Behaviors attributed to laziness, lack of motivation, or poor parenting. Gifted children with ADHD (\'twice exceptional\'/2e) mask through high IQ. C\n\nRISKS: Girls/AFAB children with inattentive-type ADHD overlooked because they\'re quiet and \'well-behaved.\' Behaviors attributed to laziness, lack of motivation, or poor parenting. Gifted children with ADHD (\'twice exceptional\'/2e) mask through high IQ. Cultural differences in how attention and behavior are perceived. Teachers may resist raising ADHD possibility due to fear of \'labeling.\'\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None (Parent/Teacher-initiated)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nSchool\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s12','journey-adhd','step-12','ADHD Step 1.2: Well-Child Visit / Pediatrician Discussion','ADHD — Step 1.2: Well-Child Visit / Pediatrician Discussion\n\nWHAT TO DO: DISCUSS ADHD CONCERNS WITH YOUR PEDIATRICIAN: (1) AAP (American Academy of Pediatrics) guidelines recommend ADHD evaluation for any child age 4-18 with academic or behavioral problems and symptoms of inattention, hyperactivity, or impulsivity. (2) Bring ALL your documentation: behavior log, completed Vanderbilt parent form, teacher observations, report cards. (3) Ask the pediatrician: \'I\'d like to discuss an ADHD evaluation for [child]. I have concerns about [specific symptoms]. Can you initiate the Vanderbilt Assessment process?\' (4) The pediatrician should: provide Vanderbilt forms for parent AND teacher (BOTH required), review your concerns, conduct a physical exam to rule out other causes (thyroid, sleep disorders, vision/hearing), and potentially refer for comprehensive evaluation. (5) CRITICAL: Pediatrician screening alone is often insufficient for complex cases — if there are concerns about co-occurring conditions (anxiety, LD, ASD), request referral to a developmental-behavioral pediatrician, child psychologist, or neuropsychologist. (6) Ask about AAP ADHD guidelines: for ages 4-5, behavioral therapy is first-line (before medication); for ages 6+, FDA-approved medication AND behavioral therapy together is recommended. (7) Request vision AND hearing screening — these can mimic ADHD symptoms.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Schedule a dedicated appointment (not a quick add-on to a sick visit). Tell scheduling: \'I need a 30-minute appointment to discuss behavioral/attention concerns.\'\nSTEP 2: Bring to appointment: your behavior log, completed Vanderbilt Parent form, teacher observations, report cards, standardized test scores, any videos.\nSTEP 3: Say to pediatrician: \'I have concerns about ADHD. I\'ve been tracking [child\'s] behavior for [X weeks] and have completed the Vanderbilt Parent Assessment. I\'ve also gathered teacher input. Can we initiate a formal ADHD evaluation?\'\nSTEP 4: Pediatrician provides Vanderbilt Teacher Assessment Scale — give to teacher (ideally 2+ teachers for accuracy). Ask teacher to return within 2 weeks.\nSTEP 5: Ask pediatrician: \'Based on the severity of symptoms, should we also pursue (a) a comprehensive neuropsychological evaluation, (b) school district evaluation, or (c) both?\'\nSTEP 6: If co-occurring concerns exist (anxiety, learning difficulties, ASD features): request referral to developmental-behavioral pediatrician or neuropsychologist for comprehensive assessment. In CA, wait times for dev-behavioral pediatricians can be 3-6 months — get on the list NOW.\nSTEP 7: Return for follow-up once Vanderbilt teacher forms are completed (typically 2-4 weeks).\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Your child\'s primary care provider — initiates Vanderbilt screening process.\nDEVELOPMENTAL-BEHAVIORAL PEDIATRICIAN: For complex cases. Ask pediatrician for referral. In CA:\n• UCSF Developmental-Behavioral Pediatrics: (415) 353-2101\n• Stanford ADHD Clinic: (650) 723-5511\n• UC Davis MIND Institute: (916) 703-0280\n• UCLA Semel Institute: (310) 825-9989\n• Children\'s Hospital Los Angeles: (323) 361-2471\n• Children\'s Hospital of Orange County: (714) 509-3939\nCHILD PSYCHOLOGIST: For comprehensive testing — ask pediatrician for referral or search Psychology Today (psychologytoday.com) filtered by \'ADHD\' and your city.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD local chapters: chadd.org/affiliate-locator\n• NICHQ ADHD Toolkit (free Vanderbilt forms): nichq.org\n• CA Academy of Pediatrics: calaap.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: BRING TO PEDIATRICIAN:\n• Behavior log (2+ weeks)\n• Completed Vanderbilt Parent Assessment Scale\n• Report cards (last 2-3 years)\n• Standardized test scores\n• Teacher observation notes\n• Work samples\n• Sleep log\n• Family history of ADHD (genetic component is strong — 75% heritability)\n\nPEDIATRICIAN PROVIDES:\n• Vanderbilt Teacher Assessment Scale forms (provide to teacher)\n• Physical exam results\n• Vision/hearing screening referral\n• Referral to specialist (if needed)\n• AAP ADHD guidelines discussion\n\nAFTER VISIT:\n• Track teacher form completion (2-week turnaround)\n\nTIMELINE: Can be initiated at any well-child visit. Evaluation may take 1-3 visits depending on complexity.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Pediatrician dismisses concerns (\'just a boy thing,\' \'they\'ll grow out of it\'). Only parent rating collected, no teacher input. Brief office visit insufficient for thorough evaluation. Pediatrician jumps to medication without full evaluation. Co-occurring conditions (anxiety, learning disabilities) not screened. Parent pressured to medicate or pressured NOT to medicate by conflicting family opinions.\n\nRISKS: Pediatrician dismisses concerns (\'just a boy thing,\' \'they\'ll grow out of it\'). Only parent rating collected, no teacher input. Brief office visit insufficient for thorough evaluation. Pediatrician jumps to medication without full evaluation. Co-occurring conditions (anxiety, learning disabilities) not screened. Parent pressured to medicate or pressured NOT to medicate by conflicting family opinions.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / PCP\nOTHER AGENCIES: School (teacher rating scales)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s21','journey-adhd','step-21','ADHD Step 2.1: Comprehensive ADHD Evaluation','ADHD — Step 2.1: Comprehensive ADHD Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: Full evaluation per AAP guidelines should include: (1) DSM-5 criteria assessment — 6+ symptoms of inattention and/or 6+ hyperactivity-impulsivity symptoms, present before age 12, in 2+ settings, for 6+ months. (2) Validated rating scales from multiple informants (parent, teacher, child if older). (3) Developmental and medical history. (4) Assessment of functional impairment. (5) Screening for co-occurring conditions (78% of children with ADHD have at least one: anxiety ~40%, behavior/conduct problems ~50%, learning disabilities ~30-50%, depression, autism, Tourette syndrome). (6) Rule out other causes. Can be conducted by: pediatrician, child psychiatrist, psychologist, neuropsychologist, developmental pediatrician.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: If pursuing comprehensive evaluation (recommended for complex presentations): call insurance for referral requirements: \'Does my plan cover neuropsychological or psychological testing? Do I need a referral?\'\nSTEP 2: If using Vanderbilt-only pathway (appropriate for straightforward ADHD): ensure BOTH parent AND teacher Vanderbilt forms are completed and scored. Child must meet criteria in both settings.\nSTEP 3: For comprehensive evaluation, provide evaluator with ALL documentation: behavior log, Vanderbilt scores, report cards, teacher input, work samples, any school intervention data.\nSTEP 4: Comprehensive evaluation should include: clinical interview (parent and child), behavioral observation, rating scales from multiple informants (parent, 2+ teachers), cognitive testing (WISC-V — important to identify co-occurring LD), achievement testing (to rule out LD as primary cause), executive function assessment (BRIEF-2), continuous performance test (CPT — measures sustained attention), social-emotional assessment, adaptive behavior.\nSTEP 5: Ask evaluator: \'Will you screen for co-occurring conditions? Up to 60% of ADHD children have at least one co-occurring condition (anxiety, LD, ODD, ASD).\'\nSTEP 6: Request full written report with DSM-5 diagnosis, specific recommendations for school and home, and medication recommendation (if applicable).\n\nCONTACT: EVALUATORS:\n• Neuropsychologist: Most comprehensive ($3K-$6K, insurance may cover)\n• Child psychologist: Thorough ($1.5K-$3K)\n• Developmental-behavioral pediatrician: Medical-focused\n• Pediatrician: Vanderbilt screening (quickest, least comprehensive)\nFIND CA EVALUATORS:\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — filter by ADHD, Testing/Evaluation, your CA city\n• CHADD professional directory: chadd.org\n• Ask pediatrician for referral network\n• UC system clinics: often shorter waits than private (UCSF, UCLA, Stanford, UC Davis)\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Insurance: call number on back of card — ask for \'psychological testing\' benefits\n• Medi-Cal: covers through managed care — request referral from PCP\n• Regional Center: generally does NOT serve ADHD-only (ADHD is not a Lanterman Act qualifying condi\n\nDOCUMENTS: FOR THE EVALUATION:\n• All documentation collected in Steps 1.1-1.2\n• Completed Vanderbilt Parent AND Teacher forms\n• Insurance pre-authorization (if required)\n• Referral from pediatrician (if required)\n\nEVALUATOR PRODUCES:\n• Comprehensive evaluation report including:\n  - Clinical interview summary\n  - Behavioral observation\n  - Cognitive testing results (IQ, processing speed, working memory)\n  - Achievement testing results\n  - Executive function assessment (BRIEF-2)\n  - Rating scale results (Vanderbilt, Conners, BASC-3)\n  - DSM-5 diagnosis with presentation type\n  - Co-occurring condition screening results\n  - Specific recommendations for school, home, therapy, medication\n• Summary letter for school (if requested)\n\nTIMELINE: Pediatrician: 1-3 visits. Specialist wait: 3-12 months for dev ped, 1-4 months for psychologist. Private neuropsych: 2-6 weeks but $$.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: EVALUATION GAPS: Diagnosis based solely on brief office visit without teacher input. 3 DSM-5 presentations (Predominantly Inattentive, Predominantly Hyperactive-Impulsive, Combined) not differentiated — affects treatment. Co-occurring conditions missed (especially anxiety, which mimics and co-occurs with ADHD in ~40% of cases). Learning disabilities not screened — child gets ADHD diagnosis but underlying LD unaddressed. IQ testing not done — 2e children missed. Evaluation focuses on deficits rather than also documenting strengths.\n\nRISKS: ★ EVALUATION GAPS: Diagnosis based solely on brief office visit without teacher input. 3 DSM-5 presentations (Predominantly Inattentive, Predominantly Hyperactive-Impulsive, Combined) not differentiated — affects treatment. Co-occurring conditions missed (especially anxiety, which mimics and co-occurs with ADHD in ~40% of cases). Learning disabilities not screened — child gets ADHD diagnosis but underlying LD unaddressed. IQ testing not done — 2e children missed. Evaluation focuses on deficits rather than also documenting strengths.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician OR\nSpecialist\nOTHER AGENCIES: School (teacher data)\nPsychologist (if comprehensive eval)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s22','journey-adhd','step-22','ADHD Step 2.2: Receive ADHD Diagnosis & Understand Presentation','ADHD — Step 2.2: Receive ADHD Diagnosis & Understand Presentation\n\nWHAT TO DO: DSM-5 recognizes three ADHD presentations: (1) Predominantly Inattentive (formerly ADD) — difficulty sustaining attention, organizing, following through, often overlooked in girls. (2) Predominantly Hyperactive-Impulsive — fidgeting, excessive talking, difficulty waiting, acting without thinking. (3) Combined Presentation — meets criteria for both. ADHD severity: Mild, Moderate, Severe. 2022 NSCH data: among 6.5M children with current ADHD, 36% mild, 52% moderate, 12% severe. Key: ADHD is a RECOGNIZED DSM-5 diagnosis (314.00/314.01) with established diagnostic codes — unlike PDA, this is widely accepted by clinicians, insurance, and schools.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Review the evaluation report carefully. Note: ADHD presentation type (Inattentive, Hyperactive-Impulsive, Combined), severity level (Mild, Moderate, Severe), co-occurring conditions identified, specific recommendations.\nSTEP 2: Ask the evaluator: \'What does this mean for my child\'s daily life? What interventions have the strongest evidence? Do you recommend medication, behavioral therapy, or both?\'\nSTEP 3: AAP RECOMMENDS by age group: Ages 4-5: Behavioral parent training FIRST (evidence-based programs: Triple P, Incredible Years, Parent-Child Interaction Therapy). Ages 6-11: FDA-approved ADHD medication AND behavioral therapy (combined is most effective). Ages 12+: Medication with adolescent\'s input, plus skills training.\nSTEP 4: Prepare to share the diagnosis with: (a) your child (age-appropriate explanation: \'Your brain works differently — it\'s very creative and energetic, AND it needs some extra help with focus and organization\'), (b) school (evaluation report supports IEP/504 request), (c) family members (education reduces stigma).\nSTEP 5: Join CHADD (chadd.org) for ongoing parent education. Attend a local Parent-to-Parent support group.\nSTEP 6: Request a copy of the evaluation report for your records — you\'ll need it for school, insurance, and future providers.\n\nCONTACT: EVALUATOR/DIAGNOSING CLINICIAN: Review results and ask questions.\nPEDIATRICIAN: Share results — they\'ll coordinate medication if recommended.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD Local Chapters: chadd.org/affiliate-locator — find your nearest chapter for parent education and support groups (chapters throughout CA: SF Bay Area, LA, San Diego, Sacramento, Orange County)\n• ADDitude Magazine: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, downloadable guides\n• Understood.org: understood.org — ADHD-specific resources\n• LDA of CA: ldaca.org — if co-occurring LD identified\n• NAMI CA: namica.org — mental health support if co-occurring anxiety/depression\nFOR YOUR CHILD:\n• CHADD\'s \'What is ADHD?\' youth resources\n• Understood.org child-friendly explanations\n• Books: \'The Survival Guide for Kids with ADHD\' by John Taylo\n\nDOCUMENTS: DIAGNOSIS DOCUMENTS:\n• Complete evaluation report (keep original + copies)\n• DSM-5 diagnostic summary (presentation type, severity)\n• Recommendations section (extract for school and providers)\n• Summary letter (request if not included)\n\nSHARE WITH:\n• Pediatrician (original or copy of full report)\n• School (copy for IEP/504 request)\n• Insurance (may need for pre-authorization of services)\n• Future providers (therapists, tutors)\n\nPARENT CREATES:\n• 1-page \'ADHD Profile\' summary (diagnosis, presentation type, key recommendations, what helps/hinders)\n• Service coordination binder (start organizing all ADHD-related documents)\n\nTIMELINE: Diagnosis typically within 1-3 visits after initial evaluation.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Diagnosis documentation insufficient for school/insurance needs. Presentation type not specified. Co-occurring conditions not documented. Parent receives diagnosis without adequate explanation of what ADHD is and isn\'t. Grief, guilt, relief — complex emotional response not addressed. Misinformation from social media about ADHD.\n\nRISKS: Diagnosis documentation insufficient for school/insurance needs. Presentation type not specified. Co-occurring conditions not documented. Parent receives diagnosis without adequate explanation of what ADHD is and isn\'t. Grief, guilt, relief — complex emotional response not addressed. Misinformation from social media about ADHD.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Diagnosing Provider\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s31','journey-adhd','step-31','ADHD Step 3.1: Develop Multimodal Treatment Plan','ADHD — Step 3.1: Develop Multimodal Treatment Plan\n\nWHAT TO DO: AAP recommends multimodal approach: (1) For ages 4-5: behavioral therapy FIRST, medication only if therapy insufficient. (2) For ages 6-11: BOTH medication AND behavioral therapy (gold standard). (3) For ages 12+: medication with consent of adolescent, behavioral therapy recommended. Treatment components: ADHD medication, behavioral parent training, school accommodations/interventions, organizational skills training, social skills support, executive function coaching. Evidence base: MTA study (largest ADHD treatment study) showed combination of medication + behavioral therapy produces best outcomes.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: With your pediatrician or evaluator, create a written treatment plan that includes: behavioral interventions (parent training, school accommodations, organizational strategies), medication (if recommended and consented), therapy (CBT, social skills, organizational coaching), school supports (IEP or 504). This is MULTIMODAL — no single intervention is sufficient for most children.\nSTEP 2: Prioritize based on age and severity: (a) Ages 4-5: Behavioral parent training first — enroll in evidence-based program (Triple P, Incredible Years, PCIT). (b) Ages 6+: Behavioral + medication consultation simultaneously. (c) All ages: School accommodations immediately.\nSTEP 3: Create a treatment timeline: Week 1-2: school evaluation request + medication consultation. Month 1: behavioral parent training enrollment + 504/IEP development. Month 2-3: therapist/coach identified. Month 4+: monitor, adjust, maintain.\nSTEP 4: For each provider, ensure they have the full evaluation report and your 1-page ADHD Profile.\nSTEP 5: Designate yourself as the CARE COORDINATOR — you connect the pediatrician, school, therapist, and any other providers. Create a shared communication plan.\nSTEP 6: Set review milestones: 30 days (initial medication adjustment), 90 days (comprehensive check-in), 6 months (full review of all interventions).\n\nCONTACT: TREATMENT TEAM:\n• Pediatrician: medication management, overall coordination\n• Child psychiatrist: complex medication needs (stimulants + additional medications)\n• Behavioral therapist/psychologist: CBT, parent training, skills coaching\n• School IEP/504 team: academic accommodations\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD: chadd.org — parent education courses (virtual and in-person)\n• Triple P (Positive Parenting Program): triplep.net — evidence-based parent training, CA locations\n• Incredible Years: incredibleyears.com — evidence-based parent training\n• PCIT (Parent-Child Interaction Therapy): pcit.org — for ages 2-7, CA providers listed\n• ADHD Coaches Organization: adhdcoaches.org — find ADHD coach for teens+\n• Medi-Cal Behavioral Health: through your managed care plan\n• Regional Center: only if ADHD co\n\nDOCUMENTS: TREATMENT PLAN DOCUMENTS:\n• Written multimodal treatment plan (create with pediatrician)\n• Medication consent form (if applicable)\n• Behavioral parent training enrollment\n• Insurance pre-authorizations for therapy\n• School evaluation request letter (copy)\n• Provider contact sheet (all providers, phone, email)\n• Treatment timeline with milestones\n• Communication plan for providers\n\nONGOING TRACKING:\n• Medication log (dose, time, effects, side effects)\n• Behavior tracking (weekly rating 1-10: focus, impulsivity, emotional regulation, homework, sleep)\n• School performance (grades, teacher feedback)\n• Therapy progress notes\n\nTIMELINE: Treatment plan should be developed within weeks of diagnosis.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: TREATMENT TRAPS: Medication prescribed without behavioral component. Behavioral therapy recommended without medication for moderate-severe ADHD in school-age children (undertreated). Only medication OR only therapy when both are needed. Family opposed to medication based on stigma/misinformation — child undertreated. Medication prescribed without monitoring plan. No school accommodations discussed alongside clinical treatment.\n\nRISKS: ★ TREATMENT TRAPS: Medication prescribed without behavioral component. Behavioral therapy recommended without medication for moderate-severe ADHD in school-age children (undertreated). Only medication OR only therapy when both are needed. Family opposed to medication based on stigma/misinformation — child undertreated. Medication prescribed without monitoring plan. No school accommodations discussed alongside clinical treatment.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / Psychiatrist\nOTHER AGENCIES: Therapist\nSchool\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s32','journey-adhd','step-32','ADHD Step 3.2: Navigate ADHD Medication (If Applicable)','ADHD — Step 3.2: Navigate ADHD Medication (If Applicable)\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADHD medications: STIMULANTS (first-line, 70-80% response rate): methylphenidate (Ritalin, Concerta, Focalin) and amphetamine (Adderall, Vyvanse, Dexedrine). Short-acting (4 hrs), intermediate (6-8 hrs), long-acting (10-14 hrs). NON-STIMULANTS (second-line): atomoxetine (Strattera), guanfacine (Intuniv), clonidine (Kapvay), viloxazine (Qelbree). Process: start low, titrate slowly, monitor for efficacy and side effects. Common side effects: appetite suppression, sleep difficulties, mood changes. Medication shortage has been ongoing issue (FDA Adderall shortage 2022-2024).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: ADHD medications: STIMULANTS (first-line, 70-80% response rate): methylphenidate (Ritalin, Concerta, Focalin) and amphetamine (Adderall, Vyvanse, Dexedrine).\nSTEP 2: Short-acting (4 hrs), intermediate (6-8 hrs), long-acting (10-14 hrs).\nSTEP 3: NON-STIMULANTS (second-line): atomoxetine (Strattera), guanfacine (Intuniv), clonidine (Kapvay), viloxazine (Qelbree).\nSTEP 4: Process: start low, titrate slowly, monitor for efficacy and side effects.\nSTEP 5: Common side effects: appetite suppression, sleep difficulties, mood changes.\n\nCONTACT: CHADD PROFESSIONAL DIRECTORY: chadd.org — find ADHD specialists\nCBT THERAPISTS: psychologytoday.com — filter by ADHD, CBT, children\nPARENT TRAINING PROGRAMS: CHADD Parent-to-Parent (free), Triple P, PCIT (ages 2-7)\nINSURANCE: Call number on card. ADHD medication + behavioral therapy covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA).\nMEDI-CAL: Covers ADHD evaluation, medication, and behavioral therapy.\nDMHC: (888) 466-2219 | CDI: (800) 927-4357\n\nDOCUMENTS: MEDICATION DOCUMENTS:\n• Medication consent form (signed)\n• Medication log: date, medication name, dose, time taken, effects observed, side effects\n• Height/weight tracking (stimulants can affect growth)\n• Blood pressure/heart rate (if monitored)\n• Teacher feedback forms (before and after medication starts)\n• Side effect checklist (appetite, sleep, mood, irritability, tics)\n• Insurance formulary information\n• Prior authorization documentation (if needed)\n\nKEEP FOR RECORDS:\n• All medication changes with dates and reasons\n• Any adverse reaction documentation\n• Annual medication review notes from prescriber\n\nTIMELINE: Titration: 4-8 weeks to find optimal dose. Follow-up: monthly initially, then every 3-6 months.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: MEDICATION CHALLENGES: Medication shortage — 71.5% of adults on stimulants had difficulty filling prescriptions (2024 CDC data). Prior authorization delays for specific medications. Generic vs brand-name differences. Side effects cause parents to discontinue without physician guidance. Medication doesn\'t cover full school day (wearing off). Diversion/misuse concerns at school. Medication stigma. Growth suppression concerns require monitoring.\n\nRISKS: ★ MEDICATION CHALLENGES: Medication shortage — 71.5% of adults on stimulants had difficulty filling prescriptions (2024 CDC data). Prior authorization delays for specific medications. Generic vs brand-name differences. Side effects cause parents to discontinue without physician guidance. Medication doesn\'t cover full school day (wearing off). Diversion/misuse concerns at school. Medication stigma. Growth suppression concerns require monitoring.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Prescribing Provider\n(Pediatrician/Psychiatrist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pharmacy\nInsurance\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s33','journey-adhd','step-33','ADHD Step 3.3: Behavioral Parent Training & Family Strategies','ADHD — Step 3.3: Behavioral Parent Training & Family Strategies\n\nWHAT TO DO: Evidence-based parent training programs: CHADD Parent-to-Parent (free, peer-led), Triple P (Positive Parenting Program), Parent-Child Interaction Therapy (PCIT, ages 2-7), Incredible Years. Key strategies: (1) Positive reinforcement systems (specific praise, token economies). (2) Clear, consistent expectations with visual supports. (3) Environmental modifications (reduce distractions, organize spaces). (4) Routine/structure with flexibility. (5) Break tasks into smaller steps. (6) Movement breaks. (7) Emotional coaching for dysregulation. (8) Collaborative problem-solving (Ross Greene\'s \'The Explosive Child\' approach). Russell Barkley\'s \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' widely recommended.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Find an evidence-based parent training program. AAP recommends for ADHD: Triple P (Positive Parenting Program), Incredible Years, PCIT (Parent-Child Interaction Therapy, ages 2-7), Barkley\'s Defiant Children program.\nSTEP 2: Check coverage: Insurance covers parent training when billed as \'family therapy\' or \'behavioral therapy.\' Medi-Cal covers through managed behavioral health. Some school districts offer free parent workshops.\nSTEP 3: Enroll in a program — most are 8-12 weekly sessions. Can be group or individual format.\nSTEP 4: Key strategies you\'ll learn: clear/specific commands (not \'behave\' but \'please put your backpack on the hook by the door\'), immediate positive reinforcement, structured routines with visual supports, planned ignoring of minor misbehavior, time-out procedures, daily report cards between school and home.\nSTEP 5: Practice consistency — ADHD children need MORE consistent structure, not less. Create visual schedules, use timers, establish predictable routines.\nSTEP 6: Involve all caregivers (both parents, grandparents, babysitters) — inconsistency across caregivers undermines progress.\nSTEP 7: If your child is age 8+, also consider organizational coaching or ADHD-specific CBT for the child directly.\n\nCONTACT: EVIDENCE-BASED PARENT TRAINING IN CA:\n• Triple P: triplep.net — multiple CA locations, also online\n• Incredible Years: incredibleyears.com — group format, check local listings\n• PCIT International: pcit.org — find CA providers (ages 2-7)\n• CHADD Parent-to-Parent: chadd.org — free peer support and education\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Medi-Cal covers parent training through managed behavioral health plans\n• County mental health departments often offer free parenting classes\n• Family Resource Centers: frcnca.org — peer support and parent workshops\n• SELPA (Special Education Local Plan Area): may offer parent workshops on behavioral strategies\n• 211 (dial 2-1-1): United Way resource line — connects to local parenting programs\nBOOKS:\n• \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' by Russell Barkley (gold standard parent gu\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT TRAINING DOCUMENTS:\n• Program enrollment confirmation\n• Session notes/handouts (keep from each session)\n• Practice worksheets (daily behavior charts, reward systems)\n• Home behavior tracking sheets (from program)\n• Insurance/Medi-Cal billing documentation\n\nIMPLEMENTATION TRACKING:\n• Daily behavior chart (from parent training program)\n• School-home daily report card\n• Visual schedule (posted in home)\n• Routine checklists (morning, homework, bedtime)\n• Reward system tracker\n• Weekly parent self-assessment (am I implementing consistently?)\n\nTIMELINE: Parent training: typically 8-16 sessions. Ongoing at home.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Insurance doesn\'t cover parent training programs. CHADD chapters not available in all areas. Waitlists for behavioral therapists. Parent burnout from implementing strategies consistently. Co-parent/family disagreement on approach. Strategies that work for typical ADHD may not work for ADHD + co-occurring conditions.\n\nRISKS: Insurance doesn\'t cover parent training programs. CHADD chapters not available in all areas. Waitlists for behavioral therapists. Parent burnout from implementing strategies consistently. Co-parent/family disagreement on approach. Strategies that work for typical ADHD may not work for ADHD + co-occurring conditions.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Therapist / CHADD\nParent Training\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nSchool\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s41','journey-adhd','step-41','ADHD Step 4.1: Request School District Evaluation','ADHD — Step 4.1: Request School District Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: Parent sends written request for special education evaluation. ADHD qualifies under IEP category \'Other Health Impairment\' (OHI) — specifically, ADHD causes \'limited alertness with respect to the educational environment\' or \'heightened alertness to environmental stimuli\' that results in limited alertness to educational tasks. IMPORTANT: ADHD diagnosis alone does NOT guarantee IEP eligibility — must demonstrate that ADHD adversely affects educational performance. Educational performance includes academics AND non-academic domains (social, behavioral, emotional regulation, organizational). OSEP has clarified \'educational performance\' is NOT limited to grades.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Parent sends written request for special education evaluation.\nSTEP 2: ADHD qualifies under IEP category \'Other Health Impairment\' (OHI) — specifically, ADHD causes \'limited alertness with respect to the educational environment\' or \'heightened alertness to environmental stimuli\' that results in limited alertness to educational tasks.\nSTEP 3: IMPORTANT: ADHD diagnosis alone does NOT guarantee IEP eligibility — must demonstrate that ADHD adversely affects educational performance.\nSTEP 4: Educational performance includes academics AND non-academic domains (social, behavioral, emotional regulation, organizational).\nSTEP 5: OSEP has clarified \'educational performance\' is NOT limited to grades.\n\nCONTACT: DELIVER YOUR LETTER TO:\n• School office (hand-deliver, get date stamp)\n• Email to: Principal AND Special Education Director\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your school district Special Education department\n• CA Dept of Education: cde.ca.gov/sp/se — SpEd information\n• CDE Complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\nIF SCHOOL WON\'T ACCEPT OR RESPOND:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal advocacy\n• CDE compliance complaint: cde.ca.gov\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• DREDF: dredf.org\n• Your local SELPA (Special Education Local Plan Area)\n• CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org — find your local center\nKEY LAW:\n• CA Ed Code §56321: 15 calendar days to provide assessment plan after written request\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter (CRITICAL — dated, keep copy with receipt stamp)\n• Email copy with read receipt\n• List of all areas to be evaluated (attention, executive function, academic achievement, social-emotional, behavioral)\n\nDISTRICT MUST PROVIDE (within 15 days):\n• Assessment plan listing all areas to be evaluated\n• Parent rights notification (Procedural Safeguards)\n• OR: Prior Written Notice if refusing (with reasons)\n\nALSO PREPARE:\n• Copy of ADHD evaluation/diagnosis report\n• Behavior log and teacher observations\n• Report cards and test scores\n• Any prior private evaluations\n\nTIMELINE: District: 15 days to respond with assessment plan. 60 days from consent to completed assessment.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: IMPORTANT: ADHD diagnosis alone does NOT guarantee IEP eligibility — must demonstrate that ADHD adversely affects educational performance | OSEP has clarified \'educational performance\' is NOT limited to grades\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: SCHOOL TRAP: District says child\'s grades are too good for IEP (\'A/B student doesn\'t need services\'). OSEP has clarified that grades alone don\'t determine eligibility — but many districts still use this gatekeeping. District claims ADHD is \'medical, not educational.\' District refuses OHI eligibility because child doesn\'t have physical health impairment (wrong — ADHD is specifically listed under OHI). Assessment only tests academics, misses behavioral/social/organizational impact. School psychologist doesn\'t assess executive functioning.\n\nRISKS: ★ SCHOOL TRAP: District says child\'s grades are too good for IEP (\'A/B student doesn\'t need services\'). OSEP has clarified that grades alone don\'t determine eligibility — but many districts still use this gatekeeping. District claims ADHD is \'medical, not educational.\' District refuses OHI eligibility because child doesn\'t have physical health impairment (wrong — ADHD is specifically listed under OHI). Assessment only tests academics, misses behavioral/social/organizational impact. School psychologist doesn\'t assess executive functioning.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPediatrician (documentation)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s42','journey-adhd','step-42','ADHD Step 4.2: School District Evaluation — ADHD-Focused','ADHD — Step 4.2: School District Evaluation — ADHD-Focused\n\nWHAT TO DO: Assessment plan should include: psychoeducational testing (to identify co-occurring LD), behavioral/social-emotional assessment (BASC-3, Conners teacher rating), executive function evaluation (BRIEF-2), classroom observation during structured AND unstructured activities, parent/teacher interviews, review of existing ADHD diagnosis and medical records. REQUEST SPECIFICALLY: (1) Executive function assessment — critical for ADHD. (2) Behavioral observation during HIGH-DEMAND tasks. (3) Academic fluency testing (not just accuracy — ADHD impacts speed/efficiency). (4) Social-emotional assessment across settings.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Assessment plan should include: psychoeducational testing (to identify co-occurring LD), behavioral/social-emotional assessment (BASC-3, Conners teacher rating), executive function evaluation (BRIEF-2), classroom observation during structured AND unstructured activities, parent/teacher interviews, review of existing ADHD diagnosis and medical records.\nSTEP 2: REQUEST SPECIFICALLY: (1) Executive function assessment — critical for ADHD.\nSTEP 3: (2) Behavioral observation during HIGH-DEMAND tasks.\nSTEP 4: (3) Academic fluency testing (not just accuracy — ADHD impacts speed/efficiency).\nSTEP 5: (4) Social-emotional assessment across settings.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL PSYCHOLOGIST: Primary evaluator — get their name and direct contact from SpEd coordinator.\nSPECIAL EDUCATION COORDINATOR: Manages evaluation timeline.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your school district Special Education department\n• CDE: cde.ca.gov/sp/se — SpEd resources\nIF EVALUATION IS DELAYED OR INADEQUATE:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CDE complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp (if 60-day deadline missed)\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com/info/adhd.index.htm — ADHD-specific school rights\n• Your local CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org\nIEE (Independent Educational Evaluation):\n• If you disagree with school evaluation, request IEE at district expense\n• 34 CFR §300.502 — district must agree or file due process to defend their evaluation\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT COMPLETES:\n• Parent Input Form (detailed, with specific ADHD examples)\n• Attached: private ADHD evaluation report, behavior log, work samples\n\nSCHOOL PRODUCES:\n• Psychoeducational evaluation report\n• Classroom observation report\n• Teacher Input Form results\n• ADHD-specific rating scales (school versions)\n• Executive function assessment results\n• Academic achievement testing\n• Social-emotional assessment\n• Behavioral assessment (FBA if behavioral concerns)\n\nREQUEST ALL REPORTS 5+ DAYS BEFORE IEP MEETING\n\nCOMPARE: school evaluation findings vs private evaluation — note any discrepancies\n\nTIMELINE: 60 calendar days from consent.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (3) Academic fluency testing (not just accuracy — ADHD impacts speed/efficiency)\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Executive function not assessed (BRIEF-2 not administered). Only academic testing done — behavioral and organizational impact missed. Observation done during preferred activity (looks fine) not during high-demand task. Teacher report minimizes issues (\'manageable with redirection\'). Child with inattentive type appears compliant in structured observation. Assessment doesn\'t connect ADHD symptoms to functional impairment.\n\nRISKS: Executive function not assessed (BRIEF-2 not administered). Only academic testing done — behavioral and organizational impact missed. Observation done during preferred activity (looks fine) not during high-demand task. Teacher report minimizes issues (\'manageable with redirection\'). Child with inattentive type appears compliant in structured observation. Assessment doesn\'t connect ADHD symptoms to functional impairment.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School Psychologist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nTeacher\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s43','journey-adhd','step-43','ADHD Step 4.3: IEP Development — ADHD-Specific Accommodations & Goals','ADHD — Step 4.3: IEP Development — ADHD-Specific Accommodations & Goals\n\nWHAT TO DO: If eligible under OHI, IEP team develops plan. KEY ADHD ACCOMMODATIONS: (1) Preferential seating (reduced distractions). (2) Extended time on tests/assignments. (3) Breaks for movement/sensory regulation. (4) Chunked assignments with check-ins. (5) Written/visual instructions (not just verbal). (6) Organizational system support (binder checks, assignment tracking). (7) Reduced homework load. (8) Testing in separate quiet setting. (9) Daily report card/home-school communication. (10) Executive function coaching. (11) Medication administration plan. (12) Teacher training on ADHD. (13) Transition support between activities. IEP GOALS should target: executive functioning, self-regulation, organizational skills, self-advocacy, social skills — NOT just \'paying attention\' or \'staying in seat.\'\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before IEP meeting, prepare a written \'IEP Request\' document: (a) Specific goals for executive function, organization, task completion, behavioral regulation. (b) Accommodations: extended time, preferential seating, movement breaks, chunked assignments, visual schedules, check-ins, modified homework, fidget tools, testing accommodations. (c) Services: behavioral support, counseling, social skills (if applicable). (d) Assistive technology: timers, graphic organizers, text-to-speech, organizational apps.\nSTEP 2: ADHD eligibility category: \'Other Health Impairment\' (OHI) under IDEA — 34 CFR §300.8(c)(9). OHI covers conditions that result in \'limited alertness\' affecting educational performance. ADHD directly qualifies.\nSTEP 3: At IEP meeting: \'My child qualifies under OHI for ADHD. I\'m requesting goals in executive function and self-regulation, accommodations for attention and impulsivity, and [specific services].\'\nSTEP 4: Push for SPECIFIC, MEASURABLE goals: not \'improve attention\' but \'Given a visual checklist, [child] will independently complete 4 of 5 steps of a classroom routine with no more than 1 verbal prompt, in 4 of 5 trials, as measured by teacher data collection.\'\nSTEP 5: Request a Behavior Intervention Plan (BIP) if behavioral issues exist — the BIP should use POSITIVE behavioral supports, not punitive consequences.\nSTEP 6: Consider Extended School Year (ESY) if regression is documented.\nSTEP 7: If you disagree with the offer, do NOT sign: \'I\'d like to revie\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM: You, SpEd teacher, gen ed teacher, school psychologist, administrator. Bring advocate if possible.\nADVOCACY SUPPORT:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP advocates\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• TASK: taskca.org — parent training on IEP advocacy\n• Matrix Parent Network: matrixparents.org\n• CHADD IEP/504 Guide: chadd.org — specific to ADHD\n• Wrightslaw ADHD: wrightslaw.com/info/adhd.index.htm\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your local SELPA: provides parent resources\n• CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org — find your local center\n• Community Alliance for Special Education (CASE): caseadvocacy.org\n• DRC SERR Manual: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — comprehensive rights reference\n• Undivided: undivided.io — free family navigator\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP DOCUMENT INCLUDES:\n• PLAAFP (Present Levels — describe ADHD impact on education)\n• Annual goals (executive function, self-regulation, organization, task completion)\n• SDI page (specially designed instruction)\n• Accommodations page (extended time, movement breaks, visual supports, testing, homework)\n• BIP (Behavior Intervention Plan, if applicable)\n• AT consideration\n• ESY determination\n• Placement (LRE)\n• Related services (counseling, social skills)\n• Progress reporting schedule\n\nPARENT BRINGS:\n• Your written IEP request document\n• ADHD evaluation reports (private + school)\n• 1-page ADHD Profile\n• Research on ADHD accommodations\n• Work samples showing impact\n\nTIMELINE: 30 days from completed assessment to IEP meeting.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (5) Written/visual instructions (not just verbal) | IEP GOALS should target: executive functioning, self-regulation, organizational skills, self-advocacy, social skills — NOT just \'paying attention\' or \'staying in seat\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: IEP PITFALLS: Generic accommodations that don\'t address specific child\'s ADHD presentation. \'Extra time\' and \'preferential seating\' offered as only accommodations (insufficient). Behavior plan focuses on compliance rather than teaching self-regulation. Goals about \'staying on task\' without addressing WHY (executive function deficit). Medication expected to be sole intervention — school reduces support. After-medication \'rebound\' period not addressed. Substitute teachers don\'t implement accommodations. IEP goals not updated to address exe\n\nRISKS: ★ IEP PITFALLS: Generic accommodations that don\'t address specific child\'s ADHD presentation. \'Extra time\' and \'preferential seating\' offered as only accommodations (insufficient). Behavior plan focuses on compliance rather than teaching self-regulation. Goals about \'staying on task\' without addressing WHY (executive function deficit). Medication expected to be sole intervention — school reduces support. After-medication \'rebound\' period not addressed. Substitute teachers don\'t implement accommodations. IEP goals not updated to address executive function as child ages.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPediatrician\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s44','journey-adhd','step-44','ADHD Step 4.4: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied or Preferred)','ADHD — Step 4.4: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Denied or Preferred)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Many children with ADHD receive 504 Plans rather than IEPs. 504 Plan may be appropriate when: ADHD impacts functioning but child doesn\'t need specialized instruction (just accommodations). Section 504 broader eligibility: disability that \'substantially limits one or more major life activities\' (learning, concentrating, thinking, reading, communicating). 504 accommodations can include: extended time, preferential seating, movement breaks, reduced homework, organizational support, testing modifications, behavioral expectations adjustments. NOTE: 504 Plans do NOT include specialized instruction or related services — if child needs those, IEP is more appropriate.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Many children with ADHD receive 504 Plans rather than IEPs.\nSTEP 2: 504 Plan may be appropriate when: ADHD impacts functioning but child doesn\'t need specialized instruction (just accommodations).\nSTEP 3: Section 504 broader eligibility: disability that \'substantially limits one or more major life activities\' (learning, concentrating, thinking, reading, communicating).\nSTEP 4: 504 accommodations can include: extended time, preferential seating, movement breaks, reduced homework, organizational support, testing modifications, behavioral expectations adjustments.\nSTEP 5: NOTE: 504 Plans do NOT include specialized instruction or related services — if child needs those, IEP is more appropriate.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL 504 COORDINATOR: Usually principal or school counselor.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• Your school district student services office\n• CA Dept of Education: cde.ca.gov/sp/se\nIF 504 DENIED:\n• OCR (Office for Civil Rights): ed.gov/ocr — (800) 421-3481\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\nFOR SAT/ACT ACCOMMODATIONS (start planning early):\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities — (844) 255-7728\n• ACT accommodations: act.org/the-act/accommodations\nNOTE: ADHD 504 accommodation HISTORY is critical documentation for SAT/ACT and college accommodations. Start documenting now.\n\nDOCUMENTS: 504 DOCUMENTS:\n• Written request for 504 evaluation\n• Medical documentation (ADHD diagnosis, evaluation reports)\n• Physician letter confirming ADHD diagnosis\n• 504 Plan document (all accommodations listed)\n• Teacher acknowledgment form\n• Annual review notes\n• Implementation tracking (parent-maintained)\n\nFOR FUTURE USE:\n• Complete 504 accommodation history (needed for SAT/ACT/college)\n• All supporting evaluations\n• Documentation of accommodation effectiveness\n• College Board/ACT accommodation applications\n\nTRACK: Whether accommodations are actually implemented — 504 has no progress monitoring like IEP\n\nTIMELINE: No specific federal timeline — \'reasonable\' time.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: NOTE: 504 Plans do NOT include specialized instruction or related services — if child needs those, IEP is more appropriate\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: 504 Plan offered as lesser alternative when IEP is warranted. 504 Plan is generic (only extra time, preferential seating). No enforcement mechanism as strong as IEP. 504 Plan not updated annually unless parent requests. Staff inconsistently implement 504. Substitute teachers unaware of 504 accommodations.\n\nRISKS: 504 Plan offered as lesser alternative when IEP is warranted. 504 Plan is generic (only extra time, preferential seating). No enforcement mechanism as strong as IEP. 504 Plan not updated annually unless parent requests. Staff inconsistently implement 504. Substitute teachers unaware of 504 accommodations.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(504 Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s45','journey-adhd','step-45','ADHD Step 4.5: IEP/504 Dispute Resolution','ADHD — Step 4.5: IEP/504 Dispute Resolution\n\nWHAT TO DO: KNOW YOUR DISPUTE RESOLUTION OPTIONS FOR ADHD: (1) If school denies evaluation, denies eligibility, offers inadequate IEP/504, or fails to implement: you have legal rights. (2) CA dispute resolution in escalating order: (a) Informal — meet with principal/SpEd director, bring advocate; (b) ADR — facilitated IEP or mediation through CDE; (c) CDE Compliance Complaint — cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — within 1 year; (d) OAH Mediation — free, voluntary; (e) Due Process Hearing — formal proceeding, 2-year statute. (3) Common ADHD disputes: school denies OHI eligibility (\'grades are too high\' — ADHD impact is functional, not just academic), school provides 504 when IEP is warranted, accommodations not implemented consistently (substitute teachers don\'t follow 504), behavioral consequences instead of BIP (suspension for ADHD-related behavior violates IDEA), medication-related conflicts. (4) CRITICAL: ADHD-related suspensions — if your child is suspended 10+ days, IDEA requires a Manifestation Determination Review (MDR). If behavior is related to ADHD, discipline must be modified. (5) RESTRAINT AND SECLUSION protections: CA Ed Code §49005.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Document the problem in writing: \'On [date], [specific accommodation] was not provided. This is the [Nth] occurrence.\'\nSTEP 2: Request an IEP/504 meeting in writing: \'I\'m requesting a meeting to address implementation concerns with my child\'s [IEP/504] plan.\'\nSTEP 3: Bring an advocate to the meeting. Free advocacy: CASE (caseadvocacy.org), DRC ((800) 776-5746), your local CA PTI.\nSTEP 4: If informal resolution fails, escalate: File CDE compliance complaint at cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp. CDE investigates and can order corrective action within 60 days.\nSTEP 5: For more complex disputes: request OAH mediation (free) through OAH at (916) 263-0880 or oah.ca.gov.\nSTEP 6: Last resort: Due Process hearing — consider retaining a special education attorney. DRC may provide free representation for significant violations.\nSTEP 7: If SUSPENSION is the issue: demand Manifestation Determination Review (MDR) if 10+ days total suspension. Is the behavior a manifestation of ADHD? If yes → school must modify discipline approach and conduct FBA/BIP.\n\nCONTACT: ADVOCACY SUPPORT:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP/504 advocacy\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal services for disability rights violations\n• DREDF: dredf.org — disability rights education and defense\n• OCRA: (800) 390-7032 — if RC services involved\n• CDE Complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n• OAH (Office of Administrative Hearings): (916) 263-0880 — mediation and due process\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• DRC SERR Manual: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com/info/discipl.index.htm — discipline and ADHD\n• Your local CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org\n• COPAA (Council of Parent Attorneys and Advocates): copaa.org — find SpEd attorney\n• Legal Aid: check your county\'s legal aid society\n\nDOCUMENTS: DISPUTE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written log of all violations/concerns with dates\n• Copies of IEP/504 showing what should be implemented\n• Evidence of non-implementation (emails, teacher communications)\n• Written requests for meetings and responses\n• CDE complaint form (if filing)\n• Suspension records and MDR documentation\n• Behavior incident reports\n\nKEEP ALL CORRESPONDENCE:\n• Emails (print copies)\n• Letters sent and received\n• Meeting notes (request audio recording of IEP meetings — CA law allows with notice)\n• Advocate\'s notes\n\nTIMELINE: CDE complaint: 60 days. Due process: 45 days from filing.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: If district denies eligibility or provides inadequate supports: (1) Request another IEP/504 meeting\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Parent doesn\'t know they can appeal. District claims \'good grades = no disability.\' IEE denied or district offers inadequate IEE provider. Attorney fees prohibitive. Parent burned out from adversarial process.\n\nRISKS: Parent doesn\'t know they can appeal. District claims \'good grades = no disability.\' IEE denied or district offers inadequate IEE provider. Attorney fees prohibitive. Parent burned out from adversarial process.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District / CDE / OAH\nOTHER AGENCIES: DRC\nSpecial Ed Attorney\nAdvocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s51','journey-adhd','step-51','ADHD Step 5.1: Insurance Authorization for ADHD Treatment','ADHD — Step 5.1: Insurance Authorization for ADHD Treatment\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADHD treatment coverage: Medication — generally covered under prescription benefit (stimulants may require prior auth, step therapy). Behavioral therapy — covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA). Psychological testing/evaluation — coverage varies widely. Parent training — often NOT covered. Key: Mental Health Parity Act requires equivalent coverage for mental health conditions including ADHD. Medi-Cal covers ADHD evaluation, medication, and behavioral therapy. Private insurance: check formulary for preferred medications, prior auth requirements.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: ADHD treatment coverage: Medication — generally covered under prescription benefit (stimulants may require prior auth, step therapy).\nSTEP 2: Behavioral therapy — covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA).\nSTEP 3: Psychological testing/evaluation — coverage varies widely.\nSTEP 4: Parent training — often NOT covered.\nSTEP 5: Key: Mental Health Parity Act requires equivalent coverage for mental health conditions including ADHD.\n\nCONTACT: CHADD PROFESSIONAL DIRECTORY: chadd.org — find ADHD specialists\nCBT THERAPISTS: psychologytoday.com — filter by ADHD, CBT, children\nPARENT TRAINING PROGRAMS: CHADD Parent-to-Parent (free), Triple P, PCIT (ages 2-7)\nINSURANCE: Call number on card. ADHD medication + behavioral therapy covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA).\nMEDI-CAL: Covers ADHD evaluation, medication, and behavioral therapy.\nDMHC: (888) 466-2219 | CDI: (800) 927-4357\n\nDOCUMENTS: INSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Insurance card and plan details\n• Referral documentation (if required)\n• Pre-authorization approvals\n• EOBs (Explanation of Benefits) for each claim\n• Denial letters (for appeal)\n• Appeal letters with supporting documentation\n• Prescription records\n• Provider invoices\n\nMEDICATION INSURANCE:\n• Formulary tier information\n• Prior authorization for non-formulary medications\n• Step therapy documentation\n• Cost comparison across pharmacies\n\nTRACK:\n• Annual deductible status\n• Out-of-pocket spending for tax deduction (IRS medical expense >7.5% AGI)\n\nTIMELINE: Prior auth: 5-15 business days. Formulary check: immediate.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Parent training — often NOT covered\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Preferred medication not on formulary — step therapy required (try cheaper option first). Prior auth delays for stimulant medications. Behavioral therapy sessions limited. Neuropsychological testing not covered or limited. Medication shortage compounds insurance issues. Out-of-network provider costs for specialists. Telehealth restrictions for controlled substance prescriptions.\n\nRISKS: Preferred medication not on formulary — step therapy required (try cheaper option first). Prior auth delays for stimulant medications. Behavioral therapy sessions limited. Neuropsychological testing not covered or limited. Medication shortage compounds insurance issues. Out-of-network provider costs for specialists. Telehealth restrictions for controlled substance prescriptions.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Insurance / Medi-Cal\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nTherapist\nPharmacy\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s52','journey-adhd','step-52','ADHD Step 5.2: Access Behavioral & Organizational Therapy','ADHD — Step 5.2: Access Behavioral & Organizational Therapy\n\nWHAT TO DO: Evidence-based therapies for ADHD: (1) Behavioral Parent Training (ages 4-12): most supported by evidence. (2) CBT for ADHD (ages 12+): addresses organizational skills, time management, emotional regulation. (3) Organizational Skills Training (OST): evidence-based for academic organization. (4) Social Skills Groups: address peer relationship difficulties common in ADHD. (5) Executive Function Coaching: not therapy per se, but growing field for building skills. (6) Occupational Therapy: for sensory, motor, and organizational needs. CHADD offers free/low-cost parent education programs including online courses.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Evidence-based therapies for ADHD: (1) Behavioral Parent Training (ages 4-12): most supported by evidence.\nSTEP 2: (2) CBT for ADHD (ages 12+): addresses organizational skills, time management, emotional regulation.\nSTEP 3: (3) Organizational Skills Training (OST): evidence-based for academic organization.\nSTEP 4: (4) Social Skills Groups: address peer relationship difficulties common in ADHD.\nSTEP 5: (5) Executive Function Coaching: not therapy per se, but growing field for building skills.\n\nCONTACT: CHADD PROFESSIONAL DIRECTORY: chadd.org — find ADHD specialists\nCBT THERAPISTS: psychologytoday.com — filter by ADHD, CBT, children\nPARENT TRAINING PROGRAMS: CHADD Parent-to-Parent (free), Triple P, PCIT (ages 2-7)\nINSURANCE: Call number on card. ADHD medication + behavioral therapy covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA).\nMEDI-CAL: Covers ADHD evaluation, medication, and behavioral therapy.\nDMHC: (888) 466-2219 | CDI: (800) 927-4357\n\nDOCUMENTS: THERAPY DOCUMENTS:\n• Therapist credentials and specialty\n• Treatment plan (goals, frequency, methodology)\n• Progress notes (request copies quarterly)\n• Insurance billing documentation\n• Session tracking (date, focus, homework)\n\nORGANIZATIONAL COACHING:\n• Coach credentials (ADHD-certified)\n• Coaching agreement\n• Goal tracking sheets\n• Executive function skill assessments (before/after)\n\nSOCIAL SKILLS:\n• Group curriculum description\n• Progress reports\n• Home generalization activities\n\nTIMELINE: Therapy: weekly for 8-20 sessions typically. Parent training: 8-16 sessions. Ongoing as needed.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (5) Executive Function Coaching: not therapy per se, but growing field for building skills\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Long waitlists for ADHD-specialized therapists. Insurance limits sessions. Generic therapy not ADHD-specific. OT often denied for ADHD by insurance. Parent training programs not locally available. Executive function coaching not insurance-covered.\n\nRISKS: Long waitlists for ADHD-specialized therapists. Insurance limits sessions. Generic therapy not ADHD-specific. OT often denied for ADHD by insurance. Parent training programs not locally available. Executive function coaching not insurance-covered.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Behavioral Therapist\nCHADD\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nSchool\nOT\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s61','journey-adhd','step-61','ADHD Step 6.1: Build ADHD-Friendly Home Environment','ADHD — Step 6.1: Build ADHD-Friendly Home Environment\n\nWHAT TO DO: Environmental modifications: (1) Dedicated homework station — minimal distractions, organized supplies. (2) Visual schedules and routines (morning, after-school, bedtime). (3) Timer-based task systems (Pomodoro for older kids). (4) Movement opportunities built into day. (5) Consistent routines with advance warnings for transitions. (6) Organization systems (labeled bins, color-coded folders, landing pad for belongings). (7) Technology management (content filters, app timers, phone-free homework zones). (8) Sleep hygiene — ADHD children often have sleep difficulties (medication timing, racing thoughts). (9) Nutrition support — regular meals/snacks (especially important with stimulant appetite suppression). (10) \'Body doubling\' for focus support.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: MORNING ROUTINE — Create a visual checklist (pictures for younger kids, words for older) posted at child\'s eye level: wake up → bathroom → get dressed → eat breakfast → brush teeth → pack backpack → shoes on → out the door. Use a timer for each step.\nSTEP 2: HOMEWORK STATION — Designate a specific, distraction-free homework spot: cleared desk, good lighting, all supplies within reach, no screens visible. Use a \'homework caddy\' with pencils, erasers, paper. Timer for work intervals (Pomodoro: 15 min work → 5 min break for young kids, 25/5 for older).\nSTEP 3: ORGANIZATION SYSTEMS — Color-coded folders by subject. Launch pad by front door (backpack hook, shoe tray, permission slip basket). Weekly backpack clean-out ritual.\nSTEP 4: EVENING ROUTINE — Posted visual schedule: homework → free time → dinner → bath → reading → bed. Consistent bedtime is CRITICAL for ADHD (sleep deprivation dramatically worsens symptoms).\nSTEP 5: POSITIVE REINFORCEMENT — Daily behavior chart with specific, achievable goals (not \'be good\' but \'complete homework checklist before 5pm\'). Immediate rewards (not end-of-week — ADHD requires immediate feedback).\nSTEP 6: REDUCE DEMAND OVERLOAD — Give ONE instruction at a time. Ask child to repeat back. Break multi-step tasks into single steps.\nSTEP 7: EXERCISE — 30+ min daily physical activity SIGNIFICANTLY reduces ADHD symptoms. Schedule active time before homework.\n\nCONTACT: HOME STRATEGY RESOURCES:\n• CHADD: chadd.org — home management strategies, webinars\n• ADDitude: additudemag.com — hundreds of free articles on home strategies\n• Understood.org: understood.org — practical home tips by age\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD local chapters: chadd.org/affiliate-locator — parent workshops\n• County behavioral health: free parenting workshops (check your county website)\n• 211 (dial 2-1-1): local resources for family support\nBOOKS:\n• \'Smart but Scattered\' by Peg Dawson — executive function strategies\n• \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' by Russell Barkley — comprehensive home strategies\n• \'The ADHD Effect on Marriage\' by Melissa Orlov — for parents/couples\n• \'Organizing Solutions for People with ADHD\' by Susan Pinsky\nAPPS:\n• Visual Schedule Planner (visual routines)\n• Choiceworks (visu\n\nDOCUMENTS: HOME ENVIRONMENT DOCUMENTS:\n• Visual routine checklists (morning, homework, evening, bedtime)\n• Daily behavior chart\n• Homework log (assignment, time started, time finished, breaks)\n• Reward system tracker\n• Exercise/activity log\n• Sleep log (bedtime, wake time, quality)\n• Meal/snack schedule (regular meals help ADHD — blood sugar drops worsen symptoms)\n• Screen time rules (posted)\n• Weekly organization checklist (backpack clean-out, desk clean-up)\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — implement gradually, not all at once.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Overwhelm from trying to change everything at once. System works initially then compliance fades. Technology battles. Sleep difficulties persist despite hygiene changes. Stimulant appetite suppression causes nutritional concerns. Sibling resentment about \'different rules.\' Parent burnout from constant structure-building.\n\nRISKS: Overwhelm from trying to change everything at once. System works initially then compliance fades. Technology battles. Sleep difficulties persist despite hygiene changes. Stimulant appetite suppression causes nutritional concerns. Sibling resentment about \'different rules.\' Parent burnout from constant structure-building.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nOTHER AGENCIES: Therapist\nOT\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s62','journey-adhd','step-62','ADHD Step 6.2: Executive Function Skill Building','ADHD — Step 6.2: Executive Function Skill Building\n\nWHAT TO DO: Executive function deficits are the CORE challenge of ADHD. Key EF skills to build: (1) Working memory — external memory aids (written lists, phone reminders, visual cues). (2) Time management — timers, visual time tools, \'time estimation\' practice. (3) Organization — systems that are simple enough to maintain (the \'2-minute rule\'). (4) Planning/prioritizing — break projects into steps, use planners/apps. (5) Task initiation — \'just do the first step,\' body doubling, accountability partners. (6) Emotional regulation — identify triggers, use coping strategies, self-advocacy for breaks. (7) Flexible thinking — practice plan B thinking. (8) Self-monitoring — learn to recognize when attention has drifted. Programs: Unstuck and on Target, Understood.org EF guides, CHADD EF resources.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Understand executive function (EF) as ADHD\'s core challenge. EF skills develop 3-5 years behind peers. Key EF skills: working memory, flexible thinking, self-monitoring, planning/prioritization, task initiation, organization, time management, emotional regulation.\nSTEP 2: Teach EXPLICIT EF strategies by age:\n• Ages 5-8: Visual checklists, \'first/then\' boards, timer use, single-step instructions, color-coded supplies\n• Ages 9-12: Planner use (teach HOW to use it, not just give one), assignment tracking system, test preparation checklists, self-monitoring cards (\'Am I on track?\'), break tasks into sub-tasks\n• Ages 13-18: Digital planner (Google Calendar), time estimation practice, project planning templates, self-advocacy skills, study strategies (spaced retrieval, active recall)\nSTEP 3: Practice EF skills EXTERNALLY first (visual supports, adult scaffolding), then gradually internalize.\nSTEP 4: Consider an ADHD coach for teens — they specialize in EF skill building. ADHD Coaches Organization: adhdcoaches.org.\nSTEP 5: Request EF goals in IEP/504 — these are legitimate, measurable goals.\nSTEP 6: Build in MOVEMENT — physical activity directly improves EF. Exercise before homework, movement breaks during study.\n\nCONTACT: EXECUTIVE FUNCTION RESOURCES:\n• Smart but Scattered (book/website): smartbutscatteredkids.com\n• ADHD Coaches Organization: adhdcoaches.org — find ADHD coach\n• Understood.org: understood.org — EF strategies by age\n• ADDitude: additudemag.com — EF articles and webinars\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD chapters: chadd.org/affiliate-locator — workshops on EF\n• School OT: request OT evaluation if fine motor/organizational issues\n• School counselor: may provide EF groups\n• Local tutoring centers with EF focus (many Kumon/Sylvan locations offer organizational support)\nPROGRAMS:\n• Cogmed Working Memory Training (computer-based)\n• Brain Balance (locations throughout CA)\n• Neurofeedback (some evidence, not first-line — discuss with clinician)\n\nDOCUMENTS: EF SKILL BUILDING DOCUMENTS:\n• Executive function assessment (BRIEF-2 results from evaluation)\n• EF goal tracking sheet (by skill area)\n• Visual supports created (checklists, schedules, planners)\n• Teacher EF feedback forms\n• ADHD coach notes (if applicable)\n• IEP/504 EF goals and progress\n\nTRACK PROGRESS:\n• Task initiation (how long to start homework?)\n• Organization (backpack/desk rating weekly)\n• Time management (assignment time estimates vs actual)\n• Planning (multi-step project completion)\n• Emotional regulation (meltdown frequency/intensity)\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — EF skills develop through mid-20s in ADHD (delayed maturation).\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: EF skills taught in isolated context — don\'t generalize to daily life. School and home not coordinating EF approach. Child resistant to \'more strategies.\' Parent doing EF work FOR child instead of coaching. Developmental expectations don\'t account for ADHD EF delay (30% maturity gap).\n\nRISKS: EF skills taught in isolated context — don\'t generalize to daily life. School and home not coordinating EF approach. Child resistant to \'more strategies.\' Parent doing EF work FOR child instead of coaching. Developmental expectations don\'t account for ADHD EF delay (30% maturity gap).\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nTherapist\nSchool\nOTHER AGENCIES: OT\nExecutive function coach\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s71','journey-adhd','step-71','ADHD Step 7.1: Screen & Address Anxiety (Co-occurs ~40%)','ADHD — Step 7.1: Screen & Address Anxiety (Co-occurs ~40%)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Anxiety co-occurs with ADHD in approximately 40% of children. Can be: (1) Primary anxiety + ADHD (both independent conditions). (2) Anxiety CAUSED by ADHD experiences (academic failure, social rejection, constant criticism). (3) ADHD symptoms that LOOK like anxiety (restlessness, difficulty concentrating, avoidance). Treatment: anxiety may need to be treated first or alongside ADHD. SSRIs for anxiety can be combined with stimulants for ADHD. CBT for anxiety is first-line behavioral treatment. School accommodations should address BOTH conditions.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Anxiety co-occurs with ADHD in approximately 40% of children.\nSTEP 2: Can be: (1) Primary anxiety + ADHD (both independent conditions).\nSTEP 3: (2) Anxiety CAUSED by ADHD experiences (academic failure, social rejection, constant criticism).\nSTEP 4: (3) ADHD symptoms that LOOK like anxiety (restlessness, difficulty concentrating, avoidance).\nSTEP 5: Treatment: anxiety may need to be treated first or alongside ADHD.\n\nCONTACT: ANXIETY SCREENING:\n• Pediatrician: request anxiety screening (Screen for Child Anxiety Related Disorders — SCARED)\n• Child psychologist/psychiatrist: comprehensive anxiety evaluation\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• NAMI CA: namica.org — mental health support, local affiliates\n• CHADD: chadd.org — co-occurring conditions resources\n• ADDitude: additudemag.com — ADHD + anxiety articles\n• Medi-Cal behavioral health: through managed care plan\n• County mental health: check your county website for children\'s services\n• School ERMHS: request through IEP (Educationally Related Mental Health Services)\n• Crisis support: 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline (call or text 988)\n\nDOCUMENTS: ANXIETY DOCUMENTS:\n• Anxiety screening results (SCARED, GAD-7)\n• Anxiety evaluation report (if comprehensive eval done)\n• Medication management notes (if SSRI prescribed)\n• Therapy progress notes\n• School-based ERMHS assessment (if requested)\n• IEP/504 updated to include anxiety accommodations\n• Crisis safety plan (if anxiety is severe)\n\nTIMELINE: Screening at initial ADHD evaluation and ongoing. Treatment concurrent.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Anxiety masked by ADHD diagnosis — provider treats only ADHD. Stimulant medication worsens anxiety in some children. Anxiety causes school avoidance that is attributed to ADHD avoidance. CBT for anxiety conflicts with ADHD behavioral strategies. Child on multiple medications — complex interactions.\n\nRISKS: ★ Anxiety masked by ADHD diagnosis — provider treats only ADHD. Stimulant medication worsens anxiety in some children. Anxiety causes school avoidance that is attributed to ADHD avoidance. CBT for anxiety conflicts with ADHD behavioral strategies. Child on multiple medications — complex interactions.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / Psychiatrist /\nPsychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: Therapist\nSchool\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s72','journey-adhd','step-72','ADHD Step 7.2: Screen & Address Learning Disabilities (Co-occurs ~30-50%)','ADHD — Step 7.2: Screen & Address Learning Disabilities (Co-occurs ~30-50%)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Learning disabilities co-occur with ADHD in 30-50% of children. Most common: dyslexia, dyscalculia, dysgraphia, processing disorders. CRITICAL: ADHD medication improves attention but does NOT remediate LD — both must be addressed separately. Child may have IEP for LD and accommodate for ADHD, or IEP covering both. Evaluation should test academic skills AT CURRENT GRADE LEVEL. Watch for: child whose reading/math/writing doesn\'t improve with ADHD treatment alone, significant discrepancy between ability and achievement, specific academic areas of persistent difficulty.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Learning disabilities co-occur with ADHD in 30-50% of children.\nSTEP 2: Most common: dyslexia, dyscalculia, dysgraphia, processing disorders.\nSTEP 3: CRITICAL: ADHD medication improves attention but does NOT remediate LD — both must be addressed separately.\nSTEP 4: Child may have IEP for LD and accommodate for ADHD, or IEP covering both.\nSTEP 5: Evaluation should test academic skills AT CURRENT GRADE LEVEL.\n\nCONTACT: LD SCREENING:\n• School psychologist: request academic achievement testing if not already done\n• Private neuropsychologist: most comprehensive LD evaluation\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• LDA of CA: ldaca.org — learning disability resources\n• IDA (International Dyslexia Association): dyslexiaida.org — dyslexia screening\n• Understood.org: understood.org — LD screening tools\n• REFER TO SLD JOURNEY MAP IN THIS WORKBOOK for complete navigation guidance\nKEY STAT: Up to 50% of children with ADHD also have a co-occurring learning disability. If academic struggles persist despite ADHD treatment, screen for LD.\n\nDOCUMENTS: LD SCREENING DOCUMENTS:\n• Academic achievement testing results\n• Reading fluency/comprehension assessments\n• Math calculation/reasoning assessments\n• Written expression samples\n• IEP updated with dual eligibility (OHI + SLD) if applicable\n• Private LD evaluation (if obtained)\n• See SLD Journey Map for complete document guidance\n\nTIMELINE: School: within IEP timeline. Private: 2-8 weeks.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: CRITICAL: ADHD medication improves attention but does NOT remediate LD — both must be addressed separately\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: LD MISSED: ADHD medication helps attention — everyone assumes academics will improve. They don\'t. Underlying LD never identified. Child labeled \'not trying hard enough\' despite medication. LD evaluation not requested because \'we already know it\'s ADHD.\' School attributes academic difficulties to ADHD alone. Gifted + ADHD + LD (triple exceptional) — all three mask each other.\n\nRISKS: ★ LD MISSED: ADHD medication helps attention — everyone assumes academics will improve. They don\'t. Underlying LD never identified. Child labeled \'not trying hard enough\' despite medication. LD evaluation not requested because \'we already know it\'s ADHD.\' School attributes academic difficulties to ADHD alone. Gifted + ADHD + LD (triple exceptional) — all three mask each other.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School Psychologist /\nNeuropsychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: School\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s73','journey-adhd','step-73','ADHD Step 7.3: Screen & Address Behavioral/Conduct Problems (Co-occurs ~50%)','ADHD — Step 7.3: Screen & Address Behavioral/Conduct Problems (Co-occurs ~50%)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Behavioral or conduct problems co-occur with ADHD in approximately 50% of children. Includes: ODD (Oppositional Defiant Disorder) — approximately 40% of ADHD children. Conduct Disorder — approximately 15-20% of ADHD children (more common in adolescence). ADHD + ODD/CD significantly increases risk for: school discipline, substance use, justice system involvement. Key: distinguish ADHD impulsivity from intentional defiance. ADHD impulsivity = acting without thinking. ODD defiance = deliberate opposition. Treatment: behavioral parent training effective for both. Some medications help both ADHD and aggression (guanfacine, risperidone for severe cases).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Behavioral or conduct problems co-occur with ADHD in approximately 50% of children.\nSTEP 2: Includes: ODD (Oppositional Defiant Disorder) — approximately 40% of ADHD children.\nSTEP 3: Conduct Disorder — approximately 15-20% of ADHD children (more common in adolescence).\nSTEP 4: ADHD + ODD/CD significantly increases risk for: school discipline, substance use, justice system involvement.\nSTEP 5: Key: distinguish ADHD impulsivity from intentional defiance.\n\nCONTACT: BEHAVIORAL SUPPORT:\n• Pediatrician/psychiatrist: behavioral assessment\n• Child psychologist: behavioral therapy, parent training\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CHADD: chadd.org — behavioral strategies\n• Medi-Cal behavioral health: through managed care plan\n• County mental health children\'s services\n• School counselor: school-based behavioral support\n• BIP (Behavior Intervention Plan): request through IEP if behavioral issues at school\nCRITICAL: Distinguish ADHD impulsivity from conduct disorder. ADHD behavior is not intentionally malicious — it\'s impulsive. Punitive approaches worsen ADHD behavior.\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEHAVIORAL DOCUMENTS:\n• FBA (Functional Behavior Assessment) results\n• BIP (Behavior Intervention Plan)\n• Behavioral incident reports from school\n• Suspension records (track all — MDR required at 10+ days)\n• Manifestation Determination Review documentation\n• Behavioral therapy progress notes\n• Daily behavior charts (home and school)\n\nTIMELINE: Screening at ADHD evaluation and ongoing.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: ADHD impulsivity mislabeled as ODD/defiance. Child disciplined/suspended for ADHD-driven behaviors. Zero tolerance policies disproportionately affect ADHD children. School-to-prison pipeline risk for ADHD + conduct issues. Medication alone insufficient for combined ADHD + ODD.\n\nRISKS: ADHD impulsivity mislabeled as ODD/defiance. Child disciplined/suspended for ADHD-driven behaviors. Zero tolerance policies disproportionately affect ADHD children. School-to-prison pipeline risk for ADHD + conduct issues. Medication alone insufficient for combined ADHD + ODD.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Psychiatrist /\nPsychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: School\nBehavioral therapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s74','journey-adhd','step-74','ADHD Step 7.4: Address Emotional Dysregulation','ADHD — Step 7.4: Address Emotional Dysregulation\n\nWHAT TO DO: Emotional dysregulation is increasingly recognized as a CORE feature of ADHD, not just a co-occurring condition. Includes: intense emotional reactions disproportionate to situation, difficulty calming down once upset, low frustration tolerance, rejection sensitivity (\'Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria\' — not a formal diagnosis but widely discussed), rapid mood shifts, emotional impulsivity (saying hurtful things in the moment). Treatment: emotional regulation skills training, CBT, medication (some children respond to guanfacine or atomoxetine for emotional regulation), dialectical behavior therapy (DBT) skills for adolescents.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Emotional dysregulation is increasingly recognized as a CORE feature of ADHD, not just a co-occurring condition.\nSTEP 2: Includes: intense emotional reactions disproportionate to situation, difficulty calming down once upset, low frustration tolerance, rejection sensitivity (\'Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria\' — not a formal diagnosis but widely discussed), rapid mood shifts, emotional impulsivity (saying hurtful things in the moment).\nSTEP 3: Treatment: emotional regulation skills training, CBT, medication (some children respond to guanfacine or atomoxetine for emotional regulation), dialectical behavior therapy (DBT) skills for adolescents.\n\nCONTACT: EMOTIONAL DYSREGULATION SUPPORT:\n• Child psychologist: CBT for emotional regulation\n• Occupational therapist: sensory regulation strategies\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• NAMI CA: namica.org\n• DBT for adolescents: dialecticalbehaviortherapy.com — skills training\n• Medi-Cal behavioral health\n• School ERMHS: request through IEP\n• Crisis: 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline\nKEY: Emotional dysregulation is a CORE feature of ADHD, not a separate condition. It should be addressed in the treatment plan.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EMOTIONAL REGULATION DOCUMENTS:\n• Emotional dysregulation assessment\n• Therapy progress notes\n• Coping strategy list (written, visual)\n• School de-escalation plan\n• BIP with emotional regulation strategies\n• Crisis safety plan (if needed)\n• Medication adjustment notes (if dysregulation is medication side effect)\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — skill building is long-term.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Emotional dysregulation is increasingly recognized as a CORE feature of ADHD, not just a co-occurring condition | Includes: intense emotional reactions disproportionate to situation, difficulty calming down once upset, low frustration tolerance, rejection sensitivity (\'Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria\' — not a formal diagnosis but widely discussed), rapid mood shifts, emotional impulsivity (saying hurtful things in the moment)\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Emotional dysregulation misdiagnosed as bipolar disorder or mood disorder. Medication changes made for \'mood instability\' when issue is ADHD emotional dysregulation. RSD causes social withdrawal and avoidance. Emotional outbursts at school lead to suspension/restraint. Parent doesn\'t recognize emotional component as part of ADHD.\n\nRISKS: Emotional dysregulation misdiagnosed as bipolar disorder or mood disorder. Medication changes made for \'mood instability\' when issue is ADHD emotional dysregulation. RSD causes social withdrawal and avoidance. Emotional outbursts at school lead to suspension/restraint. Parent doesn\'t recognize emotional component as part of ADHD.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Therapist\nPsychiatrist\nOTHER AGENCIES: School\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s81','journey-adhd','step-81','ADHD Step 8.1: Ongoing Medication Management & Monitoring','ADHD — Step 8.1: Ongoing Medication Management & Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADHD medication requires ongoing management: (1) Growth monitoring every 3-6 months (height, weight, BMI). (2) Medication efficacy review — is current dose/medication still working? (3) Dosage adjustments as child grows. (4) Annual medication \'holiday\' consideration (controversial — AAP does not recommend routine drug holidays). (5) Transition from pediatric to adult prescriber. (6) Medication diversion prevention for stimulants. (7) Manage ongoing shortage issues. (8) Re-evaluation of medication need as child matures. 30.1% of children with current ADHD receive neither medication nor behavioral treatment — significant treatment gap.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: ADHD medication requires ongoing management: (1) Growth monitoring every 3-6 months (height, weight, BMI).\nSTEP 2: (2) Medication efficacy review — is current dose/medication still working? (3) Dosage adjustments as child grows.\nSTEP 3: (4) Annual medication \'holiday\' consideration (controversial — AAP does not recommend routine drug holidays).\nSTEP 4: (5) Transition from pediatric to adult prescriber.\nSTEP 5: (6) Medication diversion prevention for stimulants.\n\nCONTACT: CHADD PROFESSIONAL DIRECTORY: chadd.org — find ADHD specialists\nCBT THERAPISTS: psychologytoday.com — filter by ADHD, CBT, children\nPARENT TRAINING PROGRAMS: CHADD Parent-to-Parent (free), Triple P, PCIT (ages 2-7)\nINSURANCE: Call number on card. ADHD medication + behavioral therapy covered under mental health parity (MHPAEA).\nMEDI-CAL: Covers ADHD evaluation, medication, and behavioral therapy.\nDMHC: (888) 466-2219 | CDI: (800) 927-4357\n\nDOCUMENTS: MEDICATION MANAGEMENT DOCUMENTS:\n• Medication log (ongoing): dose, time, effects, side effects\n• Prescriber visit notes (every 1-3 months)\n• Height/weight growth chart (annual)\n• Teacher feedback forms (each school year start + quarterly)\n• Annual medication review summary\n• Pharmacy records\n• Insurance formulary updates\n• Any genetic testing results (pharmacogenomics)\n\nTIMELINE: Every 3-6 months for medication review. Annually for comprehensive re-assessment.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (4) Annual medication \'holiday\' consideration (controversial — AAP does not recommend routine drug holidays)\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Medication complacency — \'set it and forget it.\' Growth suppression not monitored. Medication stops working (tolerance or dose needs adjustment) — parent assumes ADHD is untreatable. Adolescent medication non-compliance. Provider shortage for stimulant prescribers. Pharmacy switches generic manufacturers — different response.\n\nRISKS: Medication complacency — \'set it and forget it.\' Growth suppression not monitored. Medication stops working (tolerance or dose needs adjustment) — parent assumes ADHD is untreatable. Adolescent medication non-compliance. Provider shortage for stimulant prescribers. Pharmacy switches generic manufacturers — different response.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Prescribing Provider\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pharmacy\nInsurance\nSchool nurse\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s82','journey-adhd','step-82','ADHD Step 8.2: Annual IEP/504 Review — ADHD-Specific Monitoring','ADHD — Step 8.2: Annual IEP/504 Review — ADHD-Specific Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: Annual IEP/504 review should assess: (1) Are accommodations still appropriate for current ADHD presentation? (2) Are IEP goals addressing executive function development? (3) Has medication change affected school needs? (4) Are co-occurring conditions (anxiety, LD) adequately addressed? (5) Is organizational support scaling appropriately with increasing academic demands? (6) Does child need more/fewer supports based on current functioning? Key: academic demands INCREASE each year while ADHD supports should EVOLVE, not just continue unchanged.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: 30 days before annual IEP/504 meeting: write updated Parent Concerns Letter with current ADHD impact, medication status, what\'s working/not working.\nSTEP 2: Review quarterly progress reports: Is your child on track for annual goals? If not, email: \'My child is not on track for [goal]. I\'d like to discuss revising the approach.\'\nSTEP 3: At annual review, update: (a) Accommodations — are they still needed? Are new ones needed as demands increase? (b) Goals — advancing or repeating? (c) BIP — current behaviors and effective strategies? (d) Medication impact on school performance. (e) Executive function progress.\nSTEP 4: Triennial re-evaluation every 3 years — do NOT waive. Updated testing protects eligibility and captures changes.\nSTEP 5: Monitor for co-occurring conditions emerging: anxiety and depression often emerge in middle school for ADHD students. LD may become apparent as academic demands increase.\nSTEP 6: If approaches aren\'t working: request IEP meeting (anytime), request FBA/BIP revision, request IEE at district expense, request change in services or placement.\nSTEP 7: If SUSPENSION occurs: demand MDR if 10+ total days. Track all disciplinary incidents.\n\nCONTACT: IEP CASE MANAGER: Your child\'s SpEd teacher or 504 coordinator.\nSCHOOL ADMINISTRATION: Systemic issues.\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — annual IEP preparation support\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com — IEP monitoring strategies\n• CHADD: chadd.org — school advocacy resources\n• Your local CA PTI: parentcenterhub.org\nIF SERVICES NOT PROVIDED:\n• Document missing services with dates\n• Request compensatory education for services not delivered\n• File CDE complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n\nDOCUMENTS: ONGOING IEP/504 DOCUMENTS:\n• Quarterly progress reports (file chronologically)\n• Annual IEP/504 (keep every version)\n• Report cards and standardized test scores\n• Updated Parent Concerns Letters (annual)\n• Behavioral incident reports\n• Suspension records (track all)\n• Communication log (all emails/letters with school)\n• Triennial evaluation reports\n• Service delivery log (are services being provided?)\n\nMASTER BINDER:\n• Section 1: Current IEP/504\n• Section 2: Evaluations\n• Section 3: Progress reports\n• Section 4: Correspondence\n• Section 5: Behavioral/discipline records\n• Section 6: Medical/medication records\n\nTIMELINE: Annual IEP review. Triennial reassessment every 3 years. Parent can request review anytime.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Annual IEP/504 review should assess: (1) Are accommodations still appropriate for current ADHD presentation? (2) Are IEP goals addressing executive function development? (3) Has medication change affected school needs? (4) Are co-occurring conditions (anxiety, LD) adequately addressed? (5) Is organizational support scaling appropriately with increasing academic demands? (6) Does child need more/fewer supports based on current functioning? Key: academic demands INCREASE each year while ADHD supports should EVOLVE, not just continue unchanged\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Same accommodations carried over without update. Executive function supports reduced as child ages (opposite needed — EF demands increase). Medication changes at home not communicated to school. Success with support\n\nRISKS: Same accommodations carried over without update. Executive function supports reduced as child ages (opposite needed — EF demands increase). Medication changes at home not communicated to school. Success with supports used to justify removing them. Transition to middle school/high school with inadequate accommodation transfer.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nPediatrician\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s83','journey-adhd','step-83','ADHD Step 8.3: Transition Planning (Age 14+)','ADHD — Step 8.3: Transition Planning (Age 14+)\n\nWHAT TO DO: By age 14-16, IEP must include transition goals. For ADHD: (1) Self-advocacy — understanding ADHD and communicating needs. (2) Self-management — medication management, using organizational tools independently. (3) College preparation — SAT/ACT accommodations (apply 6+ months early), college disability services registration, 504/IEP documentation transfer. (4) Career exploration — careers matching ADHD strengths (entrepreneurship, creative fields, emergency services, sales). (5) Driving — ADHD increases accident risk 2-4x; medication timing for driving important. (6) DOR services if vocational support needed. (7) Financial literacy — ADHD impulsivity affects spending.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 14-15: begin transition discussions at IEP meetings. Include: self-advocacy goals (understanding ADHD, requesting accommodations), executive function independence goals, medication self-management goals.\nSTEP 2: By age 15-16: begin SAT/ACT accommodation application. Gather: current evaluation (within 3 years), 504/IEP history, documentation of accommodation use. Apply through College Board SSD (collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities) or ACT (act.org) — submit 6+ months before test.\nSTEP 3: College preparation: (a) Visit college disability offices during tours — ask about ADHD-specific support. (b) Many colleges have ADHD support programs (coaching, study skills, extended testing). (c) Student must self-identify and register with disability office BEFORE classes begin. IEP does NOT transfer.\nSTEP 4: Teach medication self-management: by age 16-17, teen should understand their medication, set their own reminders, and communicate with prescriber.\nSTEP 5: DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation): dor.ca.gov — may provide vocational support for significant ADHD. Refer through IEP by age 16.\nSTEP 6: Driver\'s license: ADHD increases accident risk — consider graduated driving, extra practice hours, medication timing for driving.\nSTEP 7: CalABLE: calable.ca.gov — if ADHD significantly limits functioning.\n\nCONTACT: SAT/ACT ACCOMMODATIONS:\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities — (844) 255-7728\n• ACT accommodations: act.org/the-act/accommodations — (319) 337-1332\nCOLLEGE SUPPORT:\n• AHEAD: ahead.org — college disability resources\n• CHADD college guide: chadd.org — ADHD and college\n• SALT Center (U of Arizona): salt.arizona.edu — model ADHD college program\n• Landmark College (VT): landmark.edu — designed for ADHD/LD\nFOR CA FAMILIES:\n• DOR: dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation\n• CalABLE: calable.ca.gov\n• UC and CSU disability offices: each campus has one\n• Community college DSPS (Disabled Student Programs and Services): available at all CA community colleges\nSELF-ADVOCACY:\n• CHADD youth resources\n• ADDitude teen articles: additudemag.com\n• Eye to Eye: eyetoeyenational.org — me\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ITP (in IEP) with post-secondary goals\n• Transition assessments\n• SAT/ACT accommodation application + supporting docs\n• College disability documentation packet\n• Self-advocacy plan\n• Medication self-management plan\n• DOR referral documentation\n• Summary of Performance (SOP) from school at graduation\n\nCOLLEGE PREP PACKET:\n• Most recent evaluation (within 3 years)\n• All IEP/504 plans showing accommodation history\n• Documentation of accommodation USE\n• Physician letter confirming ADHD diagnosis\n• Medication history\n\nTIMELINE: Begin by age 14 (recommended), required by 16.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: TRANSITION GAPS: Self-advocacy skills never taught — child always had adults advocating. College disability services require STUDENT to self-identify and request accommodations (different from K-12). IEP accommodations don\'t automatically transfer to college. Medication management transitions from parent to teen — gap in adherence. ADHD impulsivity + new freedom = higher risk period (substance use, risky driving, academic failure). Financial impulsivity without parental oversight.\n\nRISKS: ★ TRANSITION GAPS: Self-advocacy skills never taught — child always had adults advocating. College disability services require STUDENT to self-identify and request accommodations (different from K-12). IEP accommodations don\'t automatically transfer to college. Medication management transitions from parent to teen — gap in adherence. ADHD impulsivity + new freedom = higher risk period (substance use, risky driving, academic failure). Financial impulsivity without parental oversight.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: DOR\nCollege disability office\nDMV (driving)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-adhd-s84','journey-adhd','step-84','ADHD Step 8.4: Adult ADHD — Ongoing Support','ADHD — Step 8.4: Adult ADHD — Ongoing Support\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADHD persists into adulthood in 60-75% of cases. Adult needs: (1) Transition to adult prescriber — many pediatric patients lose continuity. (2) Workplace accommodations under ADA. (3) Ongoing medication management. (4) Relationship skills — ADHD affects partnerships. (5) Financial management strategies. (6) Executive function support systems. (7) Mental health monitoring — ADHD adults at higher risk for depression, anxiety, substance use. (8) If co-occurring LD: workplace and continuing education accommodations. 15.5 million U.S. adults had ADHD diagnosis by late 2023 — growing recognition of lifelong nature.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Adult ADHD: diagnosis continues — ~60% of children with ADHD continue to meet criteria as adults. Updated adult evaluation may be needed (use DSM-5 adult criteria).\nSTEP 2: Medication: continue or adjust as needed. Find an adult psychiatrist or primary care provider experienced with adult ADHD. In CA, psychiatrists are accessed through insurance (private) or county mental health (Medi-Cal).\nSTEP 3: Workplace accommodations: ADA (Americans with Disabilities Act) requires reasonable accommodations — flexible scheduling, written instructions, noise reduction, organizational support. JAN (Job Accommodation Network): askjan.org.\nSTEP 4: Adult ADHD coaching: ADHD Coaches Organization (adhdcoaches.org) — find a certified coach for career, relationship, and life management.\nSTEP 5: Relationships: ADHD significantly impacts relationships. Resources: \'The ADHD Effect on Marriage\' by Melissa Orlov, couples therapy with ADHD-aware therapist.\nSTEP 6: Benefits: SSI (if ADHD significantly limits functioning), Medi-Cal, CalABLE. Most adults with ADHD do not qualify for SSI, but severe cases may.\nSTEP 7: Self-advocacy organizations: CHADD (chadd.org), ADDA (Attention Deficit Disorder Association: add.org).\n\nCONTACT: ADULT ADHD SUPPORT:\n• CHADD: chadd.org — adult ADHD resources, local chapters throughout CA\n• ADDA (Attention Deficit Disorder Association): add.org — adult-focused\n• ADDitude: additudemag.com — adult ADHD articles and webinars\n• ADHD Coaches Organization: adhdcoaches.org — find certified ADHD coach\nFOR CA ADULTS:\n• Medi-Cal behavioral health: through managed care plan\n• County mental health: adult services division\n• JAN (Job Accommodation Network): askjan.org — workplace accommodation guidance\n• DOR: dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation for adults\n• CalABLE: calable.ca.gov\n• NAMI CA: namica.org — mental health support\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com — find adult ADHD specialist by CA city\n\nDOCUMENTS: ADULT ADHD DOCUMENTS:\n• Updated adult ADHD evaluation (if transitioning from childhood diagnosis)\n• Medication management records\n• Workplace accommodation request (ADA)\n• JAN consultation documentation\n• ADHD coaching agreement and progress\n• Insurance/Medi-Cal documentation\n• DOR vocational plan (if applicable)\n• CalABLE account documentation\n• SSI application (if pursuing)\n\nLIFELONG FILE:\n• Complete diagnostic history (childhood through adult)\n• All evaluations\n• Medication history\n• Educational accommodation history\n• Employment accommodation records\n\nTIMELINE: Transition to adult care at 18-21. Ongoing.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Gap in care during transition from pediatric to adult provider. Adult prescribers less experienced with ADHD. Stimulant medication stigma increases for adults. Workplace disclosure concerns. ADHD burnout. Relationship difficulties. Financial impulsivity consequences. Substance use risk (self-medication). Many adults only diagnosed after child\'s diagnosis — parental ADHD affects family dynamics.\n\nRISKS: Gap in care during transition from pediatric to adult provider. Adult prescribers less experienced with ADHD. Stimulant medication stigma increases for adults. Workplace disclosure concerns. ADHD burnout. Relationship difficulties. Financial impulsivity consequences. Substance use risk (self-medication). Many adults only diagnosed after child\'s diagnosis — parental ADHD affects family dynamics.\n\nRESOURCES: CHADD: chadd.org — Parent-to-Parent training (FREE), local chapters, webinars, Attention Magazine\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — free expert webinars, articles, checklists\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — ADHD parent guides, tech tools, community\nCDC ADHD RESOURCES: cdc.gov/adhd — treatment information, data\nBOOKS: \'Taking Charge of ADHD\' (Barkley), \'The Explosive Child\' (Greene), \'Smart but Scattered\' (Dawson/Guare), \'What Your ADHD Child Wishes You Knew\' (Saline)\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nMATRIX: matrixparents.org\nTASK: taskca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Adult prescriber\n(Psychiatrist/PCP)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Employer (ADA accommodations)\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-overview','journey-sli','overview','SLI Journey Map — Overview','SPEECH OR LANGUAGE IMPAIRMENT (SLI) — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n20 steps across 7 phases:\n* 1 Early Recognition & Screening: Parent Notices Speech or Language Concerns, Pediatrician Screening & Referral\n* 2 Early Intervention (Birth-3): Early Start Referral & IFSP (Ages 0-3), Transition from Early Start to School District (Ag\n* 3 Evaluation & Diagnosis (Age 3+): School District Speech-Language Evaluation, Private SLP Evaluation (Optional/Supplemental), Understand Diagnosis: Speech Sound Disorder vs DLD\n* 4 School Services (IEP): IEP Development — SLI-Specific Services & Goals, Advocate for Appropriate Service Delivery Model, 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Not Warranted)\n* 5 Therapy & Home Support: Private Speech Therapy (Insurance/Medi-Cal), Parent-Implemented Language Strategies (Home Progr, AAC (Augmentative and Alternative Communication) —\n* 6 Co-occurring Conditions & Academic Impact: Screen for Reading/Literacy Impact (DLD → SLD Risk, Screen for Social-Emotional Impact, Address Co-occurring Conditions (Autism, ADHD, Hea\n* 7 Long-Term Planning & Transition: Ongoing IEP Review — SLI-Specific Monitoring, Transition Planning (Age 14+) — DLD-Specific, Stuttering-Specific Long-Term Management, CalABLE Account & Financial Planning\nCalABLE DETAI\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s11','journey-sli','step-11','SLI Step 1.1: Parent Notices Speech or Language Concerns','SLI — Step 1.1: Parent Notices Speech or Language Concerns\n\nWHAT TO DO: Parent observes developmental concerns: SPEECH concerns — child difficult to understand, substitutes sounds, omits sounds, stutters/repeats sounds or words, voice sounds hoarse/nasal. LANGUAGE concerns — late talker (no words by 18 months, no 2-word phrases by 24 months), difficulty following directions, limited vocabulary for age, short/simple sentences, trouble telling stories or answering questions, difficulty with reading/writing in school-age children. ASHA milestones: by 12 mo = 1-2 words; by 24 mo = 50+ words, 2-word combos; by 36 mo = 3-word sentences, understood by familiar adults. Red flags: not babbling by 9 months, no words by 15-18 months, regression in any speech/language skills.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Parent observes developmental concerns: SPEECH concerns — child difficult to understand, substitutes sounds, omits sounds, stutters/repeats sounds or words, voice sounds hoarse/nasal.\nSTEP 2: LANGUAGE concerns — late talker (no words by 18 months, no 2-word phrases by 24 months), difficulty following directions, limited vocabulary for age, short/simple sentences, trouble telling stories or answering questions, difficulty with reading/writing in school-age children.\nSTEP 3: ASHA milestones: by 12 mo = 1-2 words; by 24 mo = 50+ words, 2-word combos; by 36 mo = 3-word sentences, understood by familiar adults.\nSTEP 4: Red flags: not babbling by 9 months, no words by 15-18 months, regression in any speech/language skills.\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Request hearing test and SLP referral at well-child visit.\nREGIONAL CENTER (ages 0-3): Find yours at dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — 21 Regional Centers statewide. Self-referral accepted, no doctor referral needed.\nASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — \'How Does Your Child Hear and Talk?\' milestones, parent handouts in English/Spanish.\nFIRST 5 CALIFORNIA: ccfc.ca.gov — local First 5 county commissions fund early childhood development. Find your county at first5association.org.\nHELP ME GROW CA: helpmegrowca.org — statewide developmental screening and referral, call 211.\nCA FAMILY RESOURCE CENTERS (FRCNCA): frcnca.org — peer support and information/referral in your area.\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEGIN COLLECTING:\n• Dated observations journal: \'Oct 5: Child said \'wabbit\' for \'rabbit,\' drops final consonants, 3-word sentences at age 3 (expect 4-5 words)\'\n• Video recordings of child\'s speech in natural settings (play, mealtime, with peers)\n• ASHA milestone checklist: asha.org/public/speech/development — completed and dated\n• CDC Milestone Tracker app results\n• Well-child visit notes mentioning speech/language\n• Daycare/preschool teacher observations (request in writing)\n\nDO NOT NEED YET:\n• No medical referral needed for RC self-referral\n• No documentation needed to call RC intake\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — earlier is better. \'Wait and see\' advice delays intervention during critical period. Late talkers: some catch up, but persistent delay by age 3 = higher risk for DLD.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Red flags: not babbling by 9 months, no words by 15-18 months, regression in any speech/language skills\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: CRITICAL DELAY: Pediatrician says \'wait and see, they\'ll catch up\' — delays critical early intervention window. Boys are late talkers more often AND more likely to be referred, while girls\' language issues are overlooked. Bilingual children\'s normal language development misidentified as disorder, OR true disorder attributed to bilingualism. Family members normalize delay (\'dad didn\'t talk until 3\'). Hearing loss not ruled out as cause.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL DELAY: Pediatrician says \'wait and see, they\'ll catch up\' — delays critical early intervention window. Boys are late talkers more often AND more likely to be referred, while girls\' language issues are overlooked. Bilingual children\'s normal language development misidentified as disorder, OR true disorder attributed to bilingualism. Family members normalize delay (\'dad didn\'t talk until 3\'). Hearing loss not ruled out as cause.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None (Parent-initiated)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s12','journey-sli','step-12','SLI Step 1.2: Pediatrician Screening & Referral','SLI — Step 1.2: Pediatrician Screening & Referral\n\nWHAT TO DO: AAP recommends developmental screening at 9, 18, and 30 months (ASQ-3 or PEDS). Speech/language-specific concerns should trigger: (1) Hearing test — MUST rule out hearing loss as cause of speech/language delay. (2) Referral to SLP (Speech-Language Pathologist) for evaluation. (3) For children under 3: referral to Early Start (California Part C early intervention). (4) For children 3+: referral to school district for evaluation. Pediatrician should NOT wait — early intervention is evidence-based and more effective than \'watch and wait.\'\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: AAP recommends developmental screening at 9, 18, and 30 months (ASQ-3 or PEDS).\nSTEP 2: Speech/language-specific concerns should trigger: (1) Hearing test — MUST rule out hearing loss as cause of speech/language delay.\nSTEP 3: (2) Referral to SLP (Speech-Language Pathologist) for evaluation.\nSTEP 4: (3) For children under 3: referral to Early Start (California Part C early intervention).\nSTEP 5: (4) For children 3+: referral to school district for evaluation.\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: AAP recommends developmental screening at 9, 18, 30 months (ASQ-3 or PEDS). Request hearing test + SLP referral.\nAUDIOLOGIST: Hearing test is REQUIRED before speech evaluation. Ask pediatrician for referral or contact your county\'s Children\'s Audiology program.\nREGIONAL CENTER (ages 0-3): dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — intake line at your local RC. Self-referral accepted.\nCA NEWBORN HEARING SCREENING: If newborn screening was not done or showed concerns — contact CA DHCS Newborn Screening Program: (510) 412-1502.\nASHA PROFIND: asha.org/profind — find licensed SLPs by ZIP code, specialty, and language.\nHELP ME GROW CA: Call 211 for developmental screening and referral in your county.\n\nDOCUMENTS: FROM PEDIATRICIAN:\n• Developmental screening results (ASQ-3, PEDS, or M-CHAT if ASD concern)\n• Hearing test results — REQUIRED before speech eval (audiogram or OAE)\n• Referral letter to SLP or Early Start/school district\n• Well-child visit notes documenting concerns\n\nPARENT PROVIDES:\n• Your observations journal with dated examples\n• Video recordings\n• Completed milestone checklists\n• Any daycare/preschool teacher observations\n• Family history of speech/language delays (relevant genetic factor)\n\nTIMELINE: Hearing test: schedule ASAP. Early Start referral: services begin within 45 days. School district: 60 days from consent.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Pediatrician should NOT wait — early intervention is evidence-based and more effective than \'watch and wait\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Pediatrician uses \'wait and see\' instead of referring. Hearing test not done. Speech concerns addressed but language comprehension not assessed. Referral only to private SLP (family doesn\'t know about free school/Early Start services). Insurance doesn\'t cover evaluation or limits sessions.\n\nRISKS: Pediatrician uses \'wait and see\' instead of referring. Hearing test not done. Speech concerns addressed but language comprehension not assessed. Referral only to private SLP (family doesn\'t know about free school/Early Start services). Insurance doesn\'t cover evaluation or limits sessions.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / PCP\nOTHER AGENCIES: Audiologist (hearing test)\nEarly Start / School District\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s21','journey-sli','step-21','SLI Step 2.1: Early Start Referral & IFSP (Ages 0-3)','SLI — Step 2.1: Early Start Referral & IFSP (Ages 0-3)\n\nWHAT TO DO: California\'s Early Start program (IDEA Part C) provides early intervention for infants/toddlers with developmental delays. Self-referral accepted — no doctor referral required. Regional Center coordinates evaluation and services. IFSP (Individualized Family Service Plan) developed — family-centered, addresses child AND family needs. Speech-language services may include: direct SLP therapy, parent coaching (teaching parents strategies for daily routines), and assistive technology. Hanen Centre \'It Takes Two to Talk\' program widely used — teaches parents to be their child\'s primary language facilitator. Services delivered in \'natural environments\' (home, daycare).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: California\'s Early Start program (IDEA Part C) provides early intervention for infants/toddlers with developmental delays.\nSTEP 2: Self-referral accepted — no doctor referral required.\nSTEP 3: Regional Center coordinates evaluation and services.\nSTEP 4: IFSP (Individualized Family Service Plan) developed — family-centered, addresses child AND family needs.\nSTEP 5: Speech-language services may include: direct SLP therapy, parent coaching (teaching parents strategies for daily routines), and assistive technology.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR LOCAL REGIONAL CENTER: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — 21 RCs statewide. Call intake line, say: \'I\'d like to refer my child for Early Start services for speech/language concerns.\'\nEARLY START PROGRAM: CA DDS administers Early Start (IDEA Part C). Info: dds.ca.gov/services/early-start\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS (FEC): CA Education Code requires FECs in each SELPA — free advocacy and parent training. Find yours: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — Family Resource Centers provide peer support during Early Start process.\nDRC (Disability Rights California): (800) 776-5746 — if RC delays intake beyond 45 days or denies services.\nOCRA (Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy): (800) 390-7032 — free advocacy for RC disputes.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TO BRING TO RC INTAKE:\n• Child\'s birth certificate (copy)\n• Proof of CA residency (utility bill, lease)\n• Medi-Cal card or insurance card\n• Hearing test results\n• Pediatrician referral letter (if available, NOT required)\n• Your observations journal and videos\n\nRC WILL PROVIDE:\n• Referral acknowledgment\n• Rights booklet (Lanterman Act rights)\n• Consent for evaluation\n\nAFTER EVALUATION:\n• Multidisciplinary evaluation report\n• IFSP document (service plan)\n• Service authorization(s)\n• Service coordinator contact info\n• Annual IFSP review schedule\n\nTIMELINE: 45 days from referral to IFSP and start of services. Services continue until age 3.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: EARLY START GAPS: Regional Center evaluates but may use narrow eligibility criteria — child must show 33% delay in one area or 25% in two areas. \'Mild\' delay may not qualify despite parent concern. Service frequency may be insufficient (1x/month instead of weekly). Transition from Early Start to school district at age 3 is a critical vulnerability — services can stop abruptly. SLP shortage means waitlists even within Early Start.\n\nRISKS: ★ EARLY START GAPS: Regional Center evaluates but may use narrow eligibility criteria — child must show 33% delay in one area or 25% in two areas. \'Mild\' delay may not qualify despite parent concern. Service frequency may be insufficient (1x/month instead of weekly). Transition from Early Start to school district at age 3 is a critical vulnerability — services can stop abruptly. SLP shortage means waitlists even within Early Start.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\n(Early Start)\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nAudiologist\nPediatrician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s22','journey-sli','step-22','SLI Step 2.2: Transition from Early Start to School District (Age 3)','SLI — Step 2.2: Transition from Early Start to School District (Age 3)\n\nWHAT TO DO: At age 3, children transition from Early Start (Part C) to school district (Part B). This is one of the MOST CRITICAL transitions — services can change dramatically. School district must evaluate and develop IEP by child\'s 3rd birthday. Parent should: (1) Start transition planning at 2.5 years. (2) Attend transition meeting with RC and school district. (3) Request comprehensive speech-language evaluation. (4) Understand that service delivery model changes: from home-based/natural environment to school-based/pull-out or push-in. IFSP goals ≠ IEP goals — IEP must address \'educational performance.\'\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 3, children transition from Early Start (Part C) to school district (Part B).\nSTEP 2: This is one of the MOST CRITICAL transitions — services can change dramatically.\nSTEP 3: School district must evaluate and develop IEP by child\'s 3rd birthday.\nSTEP 4: Parent should: (1) Start transition planning at 2.\nSTEP 5: (2) Attend transition meeting with RC and school district.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR SCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: Contact the SpEd department 6 months before child turns 3. Find your district: cde.ca.gov/ds/si/ds/redist.asp\nYOUR REGIONAL CENTER SERVICE COORDINATOR: Must facilitate transition meeting with school district per Early Start requirements.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS (FEC): cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — free transition support and IEP advocacy.\nCA SELPA ADMINISTRATORS: your SELPA manages special education for your region. Find yours: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/as/caselpas.asp\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — if transition is delayed or services reduced at age 3.\nTASK (Team of Advocates for Special Kids): taskca.org — (714) 533-8275 — free parent training statewide.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• Transition meeting invitation (RC must initiate 6+ months before age 3)\n• Transition plan document\n• All Early Start/IFSP records (request complete copy from RC)\n• All evaluation reports from RC services\n• Progress reports from SLP and other Early Start providers\n\nSCHOOL DISTRICT WILL REQUIRE:\n• Written parental consent for evaluation\n• Assessment plan (district provides within 15 days of request)\n• Your signed consent on assessment plan (starts 60-day clock)\n\nPARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter to school district\n• Updated Parent Concerns Letter describing current abilities and needs\n• \'What Works\' document: strategies that help your child communicate\n\nTIMELINE: Transition conference: at least 90 days before 3rd birthday. IEP in place by 3rd birthday.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: TRANSITION CLIFF: Services stop at age 3 if school district doesn\'t complete evaluation on time. School district provides less therapy than Early Start (30 min/week vs weekly home visits). Service model change (home → school) disrupts child\'s progress. Child doesn\'t qualify for IEP because educational impact not yet documented (they haven\'t been in school yet). \'Speech-only\' IEP limits access to broader special education supports.\n\nRISKS: ★ TRANSITION CLIFF: Services stop at age 3 if school district doesn\'t complete evaluation on time. School district provides less therapy than Early Start (30 min/week vs weekly home visits). Service model change (home → school) disrupts child\'s progress. Child doesn\'t qualify for IEP because educational impact not yet documented (they haven\'t been in school yet). \'Speech-only\' IEP limits access to broader special education supports.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center →\nSchool District\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s31','journey-sli','step-31','SLI Step 3.1: School District Speech-Language Evaluation','SLI — Step 3.1: School District Speech-Language Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: Parent requests evaluation (written request). Under IDEA, SLI is defined as \'a communication disorder, such as stuttering, impaired articulation, a language impairment, or a voice impairment, that adversely affects a child\'s educational performance\' (34 CFR §300.8(c)(11)). Evaluation by school SLP should include: (1) Parent interview and history. (2) Hearing screening (REQUIRED). (3) Oral mechanism exam. (4) Standardized speech/language tests (articulation, receptive language, expressive language). (5) Language sample analysis. (6) Classroom observation. (7) Teacher input on educational impact. (8) Review of academic performance. SLI covers FOUR domains: articulation/speech sounds, language (receptive + expressive), fluency (stuttering), and voice.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Parent requests evaluation (written request).\nSTEP 2: Under IDEA, SLI is defined as \'a communication disorder, such as stuttering, impaired articulation, a language impairment, or a voice impairment, that adversely affects a child\'s educational performance\' (34 CFR §300.\nSTEP 3: Evaluation by school SLP should include: (1) Parent interview and history.\nSTEP 4: (2) Hearing screening (REQUIRED).\nSTEP 5: (3) Oral mechanism exam.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: Submit written evaluation request to SpEd Director. Find your district contact: cde.ca.gov/ds/si/ds/redist.asp\nSCHOOL SLP: Will conduct the speech-language evaluation. Ask for their name and direct contact after submitting request.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — help with evaluation request letters.\nCDE COMPLAINT (if school delays): cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file if 15-day assessment plan timeline missed.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — evaluation rights guidance.\nASHA: asha.org/public — parent guides on speech-language evaluations.\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter (CRITICAL — hand-deliver AND email, keep date-stamped copy)\n• Parent Input Form (detailed, with specific examples of communication at home)\n• Updated concerns journal with recent examples\n• Video recordings of communication in natural settings\n\nSCHOOL DISTRICT MUST PROVIDE:\n• Assessment plan within 15 calendar days of request\n• Signed assessment plan triggers 60-day evaluation clock\n• Evaluation report including: standardized speech-language testing, language sampling, classroom observation, teacher input\n• Eligibility determination document\n• Parent rights notification (Procedural Safeguards)\n\nKEEP ALL:\n• Your original request letter with date stamp\n• Email confirmations\n• All evaluation reports\n• Calendar with 15-day and 60-day deadline\n\nTIMELINE: 15 days: district presents assessment plan. 60 days from consent: evaluation completed.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: EVALUATION RISKS: Hearing not screened — hearing loss causes speech/language delays that are treatable but misidentified as SLI. Standardized tests biased against bilingual/bidialectal children — language DIFFERENCE misidentified as DISORDER. Cognitive referencing used (comparing IQ to language scores) — ASHA does NOT support this practice. Only expressive language tested — receptive language deficits missed. Language sample not collected — standardized tests alone miss real-world communication difficulties. Educational impact narrowly defined as academic grades only.\n\nRISKS: ★ EVALUATION RISKS: Hearing not screened — hearing loss causes speech/language delays that are treatable but misidentified as SLI. Standardized tests biased against bilingual/bidialectal children — language DIFFERENCE misidentified as DISORDER. Cognitive referencing used (comparing IQ to language scores) — ASHA does NOT support this practice. Only expressive language tested — receptive language deficits missed. Language sample not collected — standardized tests alone miss real-world communication difficulties. Educational impact narrowly defined as academic grades only.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School SLP)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nTeacher\nAudiologist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s32','journey-sli','step-32','SLI Step 3.2: Private SLP Evaluation (Optional/Supplemental)','SLI — Step 3.2: Private SLP Evaluation (Optional/Supplemental)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Private SLP evaluation may be pursued: (1) If school evaluation is delayed or incomplete. (2) For second opinion. (3) For more comprehensive assessment than school provides. (4) If parent suspects school will not qualify child. Private SLPs can diagnose speech/language disorders clinically — but clinical diagnosis ≠ school eligibility. IMPORTANT: a child can have a clinical speech/language diagnosis but NOT qualify for school services if educational impact isn\'t demonstrated. Conversely, school can identify SLI without clinical diagnosis. Insurance may cover private SLP evaluation and therapy (check plan). Medi-Cal covers speech therapy.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Private SLP evaluation may be pursued: (1) If school evaluation is delayed or incomplete.\nSTEP 2: (2) For second opinion.\nSTEP 3: (3) For more comprehensive assessment than school provides.\nSTEP 4: (4) If parent suspects school will not qualify child.\nSTEP 5: Private SLPs can diagnose speech/language disorders clinically — but clinical diagnosis ≠ school eligibility.\n\nCONTACT: ASHA PROFIND: asha.org/profind — find certified SLPs by ZIP code, specialty (articulation, language, stuttering, voice), and language spoken.\nINSURANCE: Call number on back of card. Ask: \'Does my plan cover speech-language evaluation for my child? Do I need a referral? What is my copay/coinsurance?\'\nUNIVERSITY SPEECH CLINICS (reduced cost):\n• UC Davis Speech-Language-Hearing Center: (530) 752-0583\n• San Jose State Univ Communicative Disorders: (408) 924-3688\n• SDSU Speech-Language Clinic: (619) 594-7746\n• CSU Sacramento: (916) 278-6601\n• Cal State LA: (323) 343-4690\nIEE RIGHTS: If you disagree with school eval, request IEE at district expense — DRC: (800) 776-5746.\n\nDOCUMENTS: INSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Physician referral letter (some plans require)\n• Insurance pre-authorization (if required)\n• EOB (Explanation of Benefits) after evaluation\n\nPRIVATE SLP PROVIDES:\n• Comprehensive evaluation report with standardized scores\n• Diagnosis with type and severity\n• Detailed recommendations for treatment and school accommodations\n• Prognosis statement\n\nIEE DOCUMENTS (if requesting at district expense):\n• Written IEE request letter citing 34 CFR §300.502\n• District response (agreement or due process filing)\n• IEE evaluation report\n\nSHARE with school: Private evaluation supports IEP — school MUST consider it.\n\nTIMELINE: Private evaluation: 1-4 weeks. Insurance auth: 5-15 business days.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (4) If parent suspects school will not qualify child | IMPORTANT: a child can have a clinical speech/language diagnosis but NOT qualify for school services if educational impact isn\'t demonstrated\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Private evaluation contradicts school evaluation — confusing for parents. Insurance limits evaluation to brief screening, not comprehensive assessment. Private SLP diagnoses disorder but school says \'no educational impact.\' Medi-Cal reimbursement rates low — fewer SLPs accept it. SLP shortage — waitlists for private evaluation, especially in rural areas.\n\nRISKS: Private evaluation contradicts school evaluation — confusing for parents. Insurance limits evaluation to brief screening, not comprehensive assessment. Private SLP diagnoses disorder but school says \'no educational impact.\' Medi-Cal reimbursement rates low — fewer SLPs accept it. SLP shortage — waitlists for private evaluation, especially in rural areas.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private SLP\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance / Medi-Cal\nPediatrician (referral)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s33','journey-sli','step-33','SLI Step 3.3: Understand Diagnosis: Speech Sound Disorder vs DLD vs Stuttering v','SLI — Step 3.3: Understand Diagnosis: Speech Sound Disorder vs DLD vs Stuttering vs Voice\n\nWHAT TO DO: SLI encompasses four distinct types, each with different prognosis and treatment: (1) SPEECH SOUND DISORDER (articulation/phonological) — difficulty producing sounds correctly. Most common type. ~8-9% of young children. Many resolve by school age with therapy. (2) DEVELOPMENTAL LANGUAGE DISORDER (DLD) — persistent difficulty understanding and/or using spoken language. 1 in 14 children (~7%). Does NOT resolve on its own. Impacts reading, writing, social skills, academic performance long-term. Previously called \'Specific Language Impairment.\' (3) STUTTERING (fluency disorder) — affects ~1% of children. 75% recover naturally, 25% persist. (4) VOICE DISORDER — hoarseness, breathiness, abnormal pitch. Less common in children. Rarest SLI type.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: SLI encompasses four distinct types, each with different prognosis and treatment: (1) SPEECH SOUND DISORDER (articulation/phonological) — difficulty producing sounds correctly.\nSTEP 2: ~8-9% of young children.\nSTEP 3: Many resolve by school age with therapy.\nSTEP 4: (2) DEVELOPMENTAL LANGUAGE DISORDER (DLD) — persistent difficulty understanding and/or using spoken language.\nSTEP 5: 1 in 14 children (~7%).\n\nCONTACT: YOUR CHILD\'S SLP: Primary resource for explaining diagnosis, prognosis, and treatment plan.\nASHA: asha.org/public — diagnosis-specific parent handouts:\n• Speech Sound Disorders: asha.org/public/speech/disorders/speech-sound-disorders\n• Language Disorders: asha.org/public/speech/disorders/language-disorders-in-children\n• Stuttering: asha.org/public/speech/disorders/stuttering\n• Voice Disorders: asha.org/public/speech/disorders/voice-disorders\nRAISING AWARENESS OF DLD: radld.org — Developmental Language Disorder resources, awareness campaign.\nNATIONAL STUTTERING ASSOCIATION: westutter.org — (800) 937-8888 — peer support for stuttering.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — emotional support and peer connections after diagnosis.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EVALUATION REPORTS SHOULD INCLUDE:\n• Specific diagnosis TYPE: Speech Sound Disorder (articulation vs phonological), Developmental Language Disorder (receptive and/or expressive), Childhood-Onset Fluency Disorder (stuttering), Voice Disorder\n• Severity rating (mild/moderate/severe/profound)\n• Standardized test scores with percentiles\n• Functional impact statement (how it affects daily communication and academics)\n• Prognosis (expected trajectory with/without treatment)\n• Treatment recommendations\n\nPARENT SHOULD HAVE:\n• Your copy of all evaluation reports\n• Written explanation of diagnosis from SLP\n• Questions list for follow-up: \'What is the prognosis? How long will therapy be needed? What type of therapy is evidence-based for this diagnosis?\'\n\nTIMELINE: At evaluation completion.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Does NOT resolve on its own\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: DIAGNOSIS CONFUSION: Parents told child has \'speech delay\' without distinguishing type — treatment differs dramatically for articulation vs DLD. DLD underdiagnosed — it\'s 7x more common than autism but gets far less research attention and public awareness. Stuttering assessed too early (normal disfluency in 2-5 year olds) or too late (early intervention most effective). Voice disorder not evaluated — hoarseness normalized. DLD misattributed to \'laziness,\' ADHD, or behavior problems.\n\nRISKS: ★ DIAGNOSIS CONFUSION: Parents told child has \'speech delay\' without distinguishing type — treatment differs dramatically for articulation vs DLD. DLD underdiagnosed — it\'s 7x more common than autism but gets far less research attention and public awareness. Stuttering assessed too early (normal disfluency in 2-5 year olds) or too late (early intervention most effective). Voice disorder not evaluated — hoarseness normalized. DLD misattributed to \'laziness,\' ADHD, or behavior problems.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SLP (School or Private)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nENT (for voice disorders)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s41','journey-sli','step-41','SLI Step 4.1: IEP Development — SLI-Specific Services & Goals','SLI — Step 4.1: IEP Development — SLI-Specific Services & Goals\n\nWHAT TO DO: SLI is UNIQUE under IDEA: speech-language services can be BOTH special education AND a related service. \'Speech-only\' IEP: child\'s sole disability is SLI, and speech-language is the primary service. IEP SERVICES may include: (1) Direct SLP therapy (individual or small group). (2) Classroom-based/push-in services. (3) Consultation model (SLP advises teacher). (4) AAC (Augmentative and Alternative Communication) devices/training if needed. IEP GOALS should be: specific, measurable, tied to educational impact (not just \'improve articulation\' but \'produce /r/ sound in 80% of opportunities in classroom reading\'). Common goal areas: articulation accuracy, sentence length/complexity, vocabulary, comprehension of directions, narrative skills, social communication, fluency management.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: SLI is UNIQUE under IDEA: speech-language services can be BOTH special education AND a related service.\nSTEP 2: \'Speech-only\' IEP: child\'s sole disability is SLI, and speech-language is the primary service.\nSTEP 3: IEP SERVICES may include: (1) Direct SLP therapy (individual or small group).\nSTEP 4: (2) Classroom-based/push-in services.\nSTEP 5: (3) Consultation model (SLP advises teacher).\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM: You, school SLP, gen ed teacher, SpEd teacher (if applicable), administrator.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — free IEP advocacy and meeting support.\nTASK: taskca.org — (714) 533-8275 — parent training on IEP development.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — IEP rights guidance.\nDRC SERR MANUAL: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — comprehensive special education rights reference.\nASHA SCHOOL-BASED SERVICES: asha.org/public/speech/development — understand what school SLP should provide.\nCA SELPA ADMINISTRATORS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/as/caselpas.asp — your local SELPA for policy questions.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP DOCUMENT INCLUDES:\n• PLAAFP (Present Levels) with current speech-language functioning\n• Annual goals: measurable, time-bound, specific to diagnosis type\n• Service page: SLP minutes/week, individual vs group, push-in vs pull-out, provider qualifications\n• Accommodations: preferential seating, visual supports, reduced verbal demands, extended response time\n• AT consideration (AAC if applicable)\n• ESY determination (if regression risk)\n• Progress reporting schedule (quarterly)\n\nPARENT BRINGS:\n• All evaluation reports (school and private)\n• Parent Concerns Letter (updated)\n• Your goal priorities document\n• Research on evidence-based SLI interventions\n• Private SLP input/report if applicable\n• Work samples showing academic impact of SLI\n\nTIMELINE: 30 days from completed assessment to IEP meeting.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: IEP GOALS should be: specific, measurable, tied to educational impact (not just \'improve articulation\' but \'produce /r/ sound in 80% of opportunities in classroom reading\')\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: IEP PITFALLS: Therapy frequency insufficient (20-30 min 1x/week for severe disorder). Group therapy used when individual is needed. \'Articulation only\' goals when child also has language disorder. Goals not connected to curriculum/classroom performance. Consultation-only model when direct service is needed. School SLP has excessive caseload (national average 48 students, many have 60+) — reduces service quality. \'Speech-only\' IEP limits access to other supports child may need.\n\nRISKS: ★ IEP PITFALLS: Therapy frequency insufficient (20-30 min 1x/week for severe disorder). Group therapy used when individual is needed. \'Articulation only\' goals when child also has language disorder. Goals not connected to curriculum/classroom performance. Consultation-only model when direct service is needed. School SLP has excessive caseload (national average 48 students, many have 60+) — reduces service quality. \'Speech-only\' IEP limits access to other supports child may need.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nParent\nTeacher\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s42','journey-sli','step-42','SLI Step 4.2: Advocate for Appropriate Service Delivery Model','SLI — Step 4.2: Advocate for Appropriate Service Delivery Model\n\nWHAT TO DO: Service delivery models for SLI: (1) PULL-OUT: child removed from classroom for individual/small group therapy. Most traditional. (2) PUSH-IN/CLASSROOM-BASED: SLP works with child within classroom context. Better for generalization. (3) CONSULTATION: SLP trains teacher, who implements strategies. Least direct. (4) COMBINED: mix of models based on goals. Best practice is often a combination. For DLD specifically: classroom-based services help language skills transfer to academic contexts. For articulation: pull-out may be efficient for drill-based practice. Research shows collaboration between SLP and teacher produces better outcomes than isolated pull-out therapy.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Service delivery models for SLI: (1) PULL-OUT: child removed from classroom for individual/small group therapy.\nSTEP 2: (2) PUSH-IN/CLASSROOM-BASED: SLP works with child within classroom context.\nSTEP 3: Better for generalization.\nSTEP 4: (3) CONSULTATION: SLP trains teacher, who implements strategies.\nSTEP 5: (4) COMBINED: mix of models based on goals.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL SLP: Discuss service model options — pull-out, push-in, consultation, collaborative.\nSCHOOL PRINCIPAL: If frequency/model is insufficient, escalate to administration.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — advocacy support.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — if services are inadequate.\nASHA SERVICE DELIVERY: asha.org/practice/service-delivery — evidence-based service models.\nCDE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file if IEP services not delivered as written.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP SERVICE PAGE MUST SPECIFY:\n• Service model: pull-out, push-in, consultation, or combination\n• Frequency: minutes per week (not \'as needed\')\n• Duration: session length\n• Group size: individual, small group (specify max), classroom-based\n• Location: speech room, classroom, other\n• Provider: school SLP (qualifications)\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Service delivery log — are sessions actually happening?\n• Cancellation tracking (if SLP is absent, are sessions made up?)\n• Progress toward goals by model type\n• Your child\'s preference and comfort with model\n\nTIMELINE: Established at IEP meeting. Reviewed annually.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: School defaults to pull-out only (easier to schedule). Consultation model used when direct service is warranted (saves district money). Frequency reduced due to SLP caseload, not child\'s needs. Group size too large for effective therapy. Service minutes not actually delivered as written.\n\nRISKS: School defaults to pull-out only (easier to schedule). Consultation model used when direct service is warranted (saves district money). Frequency reduced due to SLP caseload, not child\'s needs. Group size too large for effective therapy. Service minutes not actually delivered as written.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nTeacher\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s43','journey-sli','step-43','SLI Step 4.3: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Not Warranted)','SLI — Step 4.3: 504 Plan Alternative (If IEP Not Warranted)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Some children with speech/language concerns may not qualify for IEP but need accommodations. 504 Plan appropriate when: mild articulation errors that don\'t significantly impact academics, stuttering that primarily affects social participation, voice disorder that needs accommodations but not specialized instruction. 504 accommodations may include: extra time for verbal responses, alternative to oral presentations, preferential seating, reduced public speaking pressure for stuttering, classroom amplification system for voice conservation, note-taking support for children with language processing difficulties.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Some children with speech/language concerns may not qualify for IEP but need accommodations.\nSTEP 2: 504 Plan appropriate when: mild articulation errors that don\'t significantly impact academics, stuttering that primarily affects social participation, voice disorder that needs accommodations but not specialized instruction.\nSTEP 3: 504 accommodations may include: extra time for verbal responses, alternative to oral presentations, preferential seating, reduced public speaking pressure for stuttering, classroom amplification system for voice conservation, note-taking support for children with language processing difficulties.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL 504 COORDINATOR: Usually the principal or counselor — ask the front office.\nOCR (Office for Civil Rights): ed.gov/ocr — file complaint if 504 rights violated. Phone: (800) 421-3481. Regional Office serving CA: San Francisco OCR, (415) 486-5555.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — 504 rights guidance.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — advocacy for 504 plans.\nWRIGHTSLAW: wrightslaw.com/info/sec504.index.htm — 504 plan resources.\n\nDOCUMENTS: 504 DOCUMENTS:\n• Documentation of speech/language condition (evaluation report, medical diagnosis)\n• Functional impact evidence — how SLI affects classroom performance\n• Written 504 Plan with specific accommodations:\n  - Preferential seating near teacher\n  - Extended time for verbal responses\n  - Visual supports for verbal instructions\n  - Reduced verbal demands in assessment\n  - Permission to use AAC/AT in class\n  - Modified oral presentation requirements\n• Annual 504 review documentation\n• Teacher acknowledgment of accommodations\n\nKEEP FOR FUTURE:\n• Complete 504 accommodation history (needed for SAT/ACT/college)\n• All medical/evaluation documentation\n\nTIMELINE: No specific federal timeline.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Some children with speech/language concerns may not qualify for IEP but need accommodations | 504 Plan appropriate when: mild articulation errors that don\'t significantly impact academics, stuttering that primarily affects social participation, voice disorder that needs accommodations but not specialized instruction | 504 accommodations may include: extra time for verbal responses, alternative to oral presentations, preferential seating, reduced public speaking pressure for stuttering, classroom amplification system for voice conservation, note-taking support for children with language processing difficulties\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: 504 not offered when IEP denied. Stuttering accommodations not included. Teacher doesn\'t implement 504 consistently. 504 not reviewed regularly.\n\nRISKS: 504 not offered when IEP denied. Stuttering accommodations not included. Teacher doesn\'t implement 504 consistently. 504 not reviewed regularly.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(504 Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nSLP\nPhysician\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s51','journey-sli','step-51','SLI Step 5.1: Private Speech Therapy (Insurance/Medi-Cal)','SLI — Step 5.1: Private Speech Therapy (Insurance/Medi-Cal)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Private speech therapy may supplement or replace school services. Insurance coverage: most plans cover speech therapy as \'habilitative\' service (developing skills not previously had) or \'rehabilitative\' (restoring lost skills). Medi-Cal: covers speech-language services with physician referral. Common therapy approaches by type: ARTICULATION — drill-based practice, minimal pairs, phonological awareness. DLD — language stimulation, narrative intervention, vocabulary instruction, Hanen strategies. STUTTERING — Lidcombe Program (ages 3-6), fluency shaping, stuttering modification, avoidance reduction therapy. Frequency: typically 1-2x/week, 30-60 min sessions.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Private speech therapy may supplement or replace school services.\nSTEP 2: Insurance coverage: most plans cover speech therapy as \'habilitative\' service (developing skills not previously had) or \'rehabilitative\' (restoring lost skills).\nSTEP 3: Medi-Cal: covers speech-language services with physician referral.\nSTEP 4: Common therapy approaches by type: ARTICULATION — drill-based practice, minimal pairs, phonological awareness.\nSTEP 5: DLD — language stimulation, narrative intervention, vocabulary instruction, Hanen strategies.\n\nCONTACT: ASHA PROFIND: asha.org/profind — find SLPs by ZIP, specialty (articulation, language, fluency, voice, AAC), and language spoken.\nINSURANCE: Call member services. Ask: \'What are my speech therapy benefits? Visit limit? Copay? Do I need a referral?\'\nMEDI-CAL: Speech therapy covered under EPSDT (Early and Periodic Screening, Diagnostic and Treatment) for children under 21. No visit limits for medically necessary services. Managed care plan handles authorization.\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — \'It Takes Two to Talk\' and \'More Than Words\' parent programs. Find CA practitioners.\nNATIONAL STUTTERING ASSOCIATION: westutter.org — (800) 937-8888 — support groups, SLP referrals for stuttering.\nUNIVERSITY SPEECH CLINICS (reduced cost): See Private SLP Evaluation step for list.\nREGIONAL CENTER (ages 0-3 or \n\nDOCUMENTS: INSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Physician referral (if required by plan)\n• Insurance pre-authorization\n• Treatment plan from SLP\n• Progress reports from SLP (quarterly)\n• EOBs for each session\n• Appeal letter if visits are denied\n\nMEDI-CAL DOCUMENTS:\n• Medi-Cal card\n• Physician referral\n• EPSDT request for services (for children under 21, no visit limits for medically necessary services)\n• Managed care plan authorization\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Session attendance log\n• Insurance authorization dates and renewal deadlines\n• Visit count vs authorized visits\n• Coordination notes between private SLP and school SLP\n\nTIMELINE: Insurance auth: 5-15 business days. Therapy: ongoing, reviewed every 6-12 months.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Insurance coverage: most plans cover speech therapy as \'habilitative\' service (developing skills not previously had) or \'rehabilitative\' (restoring lost skills) | STUTTERING — Lidcombe Program (ages 3-6), fluency shaping, stuttering modification, avoidance reduction therapy\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Insurance caps sessions per year (often 20-30 visits). Prior authorization required for continued therapy. SLP shortage — waitlists common, especially for specialized areas (stuttering, AAC, bilingual SLPs). Medi-Cal reimbursement rates low. Telehealth may be effective but not offered. Private and school SLPs don\'t coordinate goals.\n\nRISKS: Insurance caps sessions per year (often 20-30 visits). Prior authorization required for continued therapy. SLP shortage — waitlists common, especially for specialized areas (stuttering, AAC, bilingual SLPs). Medi-Cal reimbursement rates low. Telehealth may be effective but not offered. Private and school SLPs don\'t coordinate goals.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private SLP\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance / Medi-Cal\nPediatrician (referral)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s52','journey-sli','step-52','SLI Step 5.2: Parent-Implemented Language Strategies (Home Program)','SLI — Step 5.2: Parent-Implemented Language Strategies (Home Program)\n\nWHAT TO DO: Parents are the MOST IMPORTANT intervention agent — more time with child than any therapist. Evidence-based parent strategies: (1) Follow child\'s lead in play — comment on what they\'re interested in. (2) Expand and extend child\'s utterances (\'Doggy!\' → \'Big brown doggy!\'). (3) Model correct production — don\'t correct, recast (\'I seed a cat\' → \'You SAW a cat!\'). (4) Read together daily — pause, point, ask open questions. (5) Reduce questions, increase comments and descriptions. (6) Create communication opportunities (put desired items in sight but out of reach). (7) Narrate daily routines. Programs: Hanen \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (language), Hanen \'More Than Words\' (autism/limited communication), Mommy Speech Therapy (free videos).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Parents are the MOST IMPORTANT intervention agent — more time with child than any therapist.\nSTEP 2: Evidence-based parent strategies: (1) Follow child\'s lead in play — comment on what they\'re interested in.\nSTEP 3: (2) Expand and extend child\'s utterances (\'Doggy!\' → \'Big brown doggy!\').\nSTEP 4: (3) Model correct production — don\'t correct, recast (\'I seed a cat\' → \'You SAW a cat!\').\nSTEP 5: (4) Read together daily — pause, point, ask open questions.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR CHILD\'S SLP: Ask for specific home practice activities at every session.\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs:\n• \'It Takes Two to Talk\' — for language delays\n• \'More Than Words\' — for ASD-related communication\n• \'Target Word\' — for late talkers\nASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — activities organized by age.\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — oral language activities that build literacy.\nPUBLIC LIBRARY: Free storytime programs build language. CA State Library: library.ca.gov — find your local library.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — parent support groups and information.\n\nDOCUMENTS: FROM YOUR SLP:\n• Written home practice activities (updated each session)\n• Practice schedule recommendations\n• Strategy cards or visual reminders for home\n• Progress monitoring you can do at home\n\nPARENT CREATES:\n• Home practice log (date, activity, duration, child\'s response)\n• Video recordings of practice sessions (share with SLP for feedback)\n• Language-rich routine plans (mealtime, bath, play — built-in language opportunities)\n\nHANEN PROGRAM MATERIALS (if enrolled):\n• \'It Takes Two to Talk\' guidebook\n• Session handouts and strategy sheets\n• Video coaching feedback\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — daily embedded in routines.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (3) Model correct production — don\'t correct, recast (\'I seed a cat\' → \'You SAW a cat!\')\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Parents correct child instead of modeling — increases anxiety and reduces communication attempts. Too much questioning (\'What\'s this? What color?\') becomes drill, not conversation. Parents compare to siblings or peers — increases stress. Home strategies not aligned with therapy goals. Parent burnout from \'always being the therapist.\' Cultural differences in parent-child communication styles not respected.\n\nRISKS: Parents correct child instead of modeling — increases anxiety and reduces communication attempts. Too much questioning (\'What\'s this? What color?\') becomes drill, not conversation. Parents compare to siblings or peers — increases stress. Home strategies not aligned with therapy goals. Parent burnout from \'always being the therapist.\' Cultural differences in parent-child communication styles not respected.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP (coaching)\nHanen Centre\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s53','journey-sli','step-53','SLI Step 5.3: AAC (Augmentative and Alternative Communication) — If Needed','SLI — Step 5.3: AAC (Augmentative and Alternative Communication) — If Needed\n\nWHAT TO DO: For children with severe expressive language impairments, AAC provides alternative ways to communicate. AAC ranges from LOW-TECH (picture boards, PECS — Picture Exchange Communication System) to HIGH-TECH (speech-generating devices, tablet apps like Proloquo2Go, TouchChat). KEY MYTH TO DISPEL: AAC does NOT prevent speech development — research consistently shows AAC SUPPORTS spoken language. AAC evaluation should be conducted by SLP with AAC expertise. Funding: school district responsible for AAC as assistive technology under IEP. Insurance/Medi-Cal may cover devices. Regional Center may fund AAC for children with autism/ID.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: For children with severe expressive language impairments, AAC provides alternative ways to communicate.\nSTEP 2: AAC ranges from LOW-TECH (picture boards, PECS — Picture Exchange Communication System) to HIGH-TECH (speech-generating devices, tablet apps like Proloquo2Go, TouchChat).\nSTEP 3: KEY MYTH TO DISPEL: AAC does NOT prevent speech development — research consistently shows AAC SUPPORTS spoken language.\nSTEP 4: AAC evaluation should be conducted by SLP with AAC expertise.\nSTEP 5: Funding: school district responsible for AAC as assistive technology under IEP.\n\nCONTACT: SLP WITH AAC SPECIALTY: ASHA ProFind filter by \'Augmentative and Alternative Communication.\' asha.org/profind\nCA ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY PROGRAM (ATAP): atnet.org — device demonstrations, loans, and funding assistance.\nPRAACTICALAAC.ORG: praacticalaac.org — free AAC implementation resources for families and therapists.\nINSURANCE/MEDI-CAL: AAC devices are covered as durable medical equipment (DME). Medi-Cal covers under EPSDT.\nSCHOOL DISTRICT AT TEAM: IEP must consider assistive technology including AAC. Request AT evaluation.\nREGIONAL CENTER: May fund AAC devices and training for eligible children.\nUSSAAC: ussaac.org — United States Society for AAC — resources and advocacy.\n\nDOCUMENTS: AAC DOCUMENTS:\n• AAC evaluation report by qualified SLP\n• AT assessment through school (IEP requirement)\n• Device trial documentation (what was tried, results)\n• Insurance/Medi-Cal pre-authorization for AAC device (covered as DME)\n• IEP AT page specifying AAC device, training, and implementation plan\n• AAC vocabulary/programming plan\n\nTRAINING DOCUMENTATION:\n• Staff training plan (all teachers/aides who work with child)\n• Parent training on device operation and modeling\n• AAC competency checklist for communication partners\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Device usage log\n• Communication growth with AAC\n• Device maintenance and updates needed\n• Insurance authorization renewals for device\n\nTIMELINE: AAC evaluation: within IEP timeline. Device acquisition: varies (insurance 4-8 weeks, school district varies).\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: KEY MYTH TO DISPEL: AAC does NOT prevent speech development — research consistently shows AAC SUPPORTS spoken language\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: AAC BARRIERS: School claims child must \'try to talk first\' before getting AAC — WRONG, no prerequisite skills required. Device funding denied by insurance. School provides low-tech when high-tech is needed. Staff not trained to implement AAC across settings. AAC device stays at school — child can\'t communicate at home. Only one communication app evaluated instead of trial of multiple options.\n\nRISKS: ★ AAC BARRIERS: School claims child must \'try to talk first\' before getting AAC — WRONG, no prerequisite skills required. Device funding denied by insurance. School provides low-tech when high-tech is needed. Staff not trained to implement AAC across settings. AAC device stays at school — child can\'t communicate at home. Only one communication app evaluated instead of trial of multiple options.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SLP (AAC specialist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: School District\nInsurance\nRegional Center\nATAP (CA Assistive Technology)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s61','journey-sli','step-61','SLI Step 6.1: Screen for Reading/Literacy Impact (DLD → SLD Risk)','SLI — Step 6.1: Screen for Reading/Literacy Impact (DLD → SLD Risk)\n\nWHAT TO DO: DLD is a MAJOR risk factor for reading and learning disabilities. The oral language → written language connection: children who struggle to understand and use spoken language are at significantly higher risk for dyslexia, reading comprehension difficulties, and written expression problems. By school age, children with DLD often qualify under BOTH \'Speech-Language Impairment\' AND \'Specific Learning Disability\' categories. Important: as children age, SLI identification may shift to SLD — child \'exits\' speech services but underlying language disorder continues to affect reading/writing. The language disorder doesn\'t go away — it shows up differently in academic demands.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: DLD is a MAJOR risk factor for reading and learning disabilities.\nSTEP 2: The oral language → written language connection: children who struggle to understand and use spoken language are at significantly higher risk for dyslexia, reading comprehension difficulties, and written expression problems.\nSTEP 3: By school age, children with DLD often qualify under BOTH \'Speech-Language Impairment\' AND \'Specific Learning Disability\' categories.\nSTEP 4: Important: as children age, SLI identification may shift to SLD — child \'exits\' speech services but underlying language disorder continues to affect reading/writing.\nSTEP 5: The language disorder doesn\'t go away — it shows up differently in academic demands.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL READING SPECIALIST: Request literacy assessment if DLD is diagnosed.\nSCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: Request evaluation for SLD if reading concerns emerge. See SLD Journey Map.\nCLASSROOM TEACHER: Ask about reading benchmark data (DIBELS, iReady, STAR).\nIDA (International Dyslexia Association): dyslexiaida.org — if dyslexia suspected.\nDECODING DYSLEXIA CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org — CA-specific dyslexia advocacy.\nUNDERSTOOD: understood.org — LD screening and resources.\nCROSS-REFERENCE: SLD Journey Map in this workbook for full reading disability pathway.\n\nDOCUMENTS: LITERACY SCREENING DOCUMENTS:\n• Reading benchmark data from school (DIBELS, iReady, STAR, SBAC)\n• Reading fluency rates vs grade-level expectations\n• Written language samples\n• Teacher input on academic performance\n\nIF SLD SUSPECTED:\n• Written evaluation request for SLD (separate from SLI evaluation)\n• Cross-reference: SLD Journey Map Step 1.3 for full evaluation request guidance\n• Research showing DLD → SLD connection: ~50% of children with DLD develop reading difficulties\n\nIEP UPDATES:\n• Dual-eligibility documentation (SLI + SLD) if both qualify\n• Updated goals addressing both oral and written language\n\nTIMELINE: Screen at kindergarten entry and ongoing. Formal LD evaluation if concerns persist.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: CRITICAL RISK: Child exits speech therapy because articulation improved, but underlying language disorder (DLD) continues to impact reading and writing — now UNFUNDED. School doesn\'t connect prior SLI to current reading difficulties. Child re-evaluated years later for LD when language was the issue all along. \'Speech-only\' IEP didn\'t address literacy connections. DLD goes \'underground\' as child ages — shows up as poor reading comprehension, weak writing, difficulty with abstract language.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL RISK: Child exits speech therapy because articulation improved, but underlying language disorder (DLD) continues to impact reading and writing — now UNFUNDED. School doesn\'t connect prior SLI to current reading difficulties. Child re-evaluated years later for LD when language was the issue all along. \'Speech-only\' IEP didn\'t address literacy connections. DLD goes \'underground\' as child ages — shows up as poor reading comprehension, weak writing, difficulty with abstract language.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School SLP / School Psychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: Reading specialist\nSpecial educator\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s62','journey-sli','step-62','SLI Step 6.2: Screen for Social-Emotional Impact','SLI — Step 6.2: Screen for Social-Emotional Impact\n\nWHAT TO DO: Children with SLI frequently experience social-emotional difficulties: (1) Social isolation — difficulty making friends due to communication barriers. (2) Behavioral issues — frustration from inability to express needs leads to acting out. (3) Bullying — children with speech differences are targets. (4) Anxiety — fear of speaking, avoidance of social situations. (5) Low self-esteem — awareness of communication difficulties. (6) Juvenile justice risk — 60-64% of youth in juvenile justice system have language disorders (often undiagnosed). CRITICAL: language difficulties are often misinterpreted as behavior problems, defiance, or low intelligence.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Children with SLI frequently experience social-emotional difficulties: (1) Social isolation — difficulty making friends due to communication barriers.\nSTEP 2: (2) Behavioral issues — frustration from inability to express needs leads to acting out.\nSTEP 3: (3) Bullying — children with speech differences are targets.\nSTEP 4: (4) Anxiety — fear of speaking, avoidance of social situations.\nSTEP 5: (5) Low self-esteem — awareness of communication difficulties.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL COUNSELOR: Request social-emotional screening and support.\nPEDIATRICIAN: Discuss social-emotional concerns at well-child visit.\nERMHS (Educationally Related Mental Health Services): Request through IEP for school-based counseling.\nCOUNTY BEHAVIORAL HEALTH: Each CA county has a children\'s behavioral health program. Access through Medi-Cal managed care plan or call county directly.\nNAMI CALIFORNIA: namica.org — family support groups, education programs.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support for families navigating emotional challenges.\n\nDOCUMENTS: SOCIAL-EMOTIONAL ASSESSMENT:\n• Behavioral rating scales (BASC-3, Conners if ADHD concern)\n• Social skills assessment\n• Parent/teacher input on social functioning\n• Counselor observations\n\nERMHS DOCUMENTS (if requested through IEP):\n• Written ERMHS request\n• ERMHS assessment report\n• Counseling goals added to IEP\n• Progress reports from school counselor/psychologist\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Social interaction observations\n• Peer relationship concerns\n• Self-esteem indicators\n• Behavioral changes at home\n\nTIMELINE: Screen at evaluation and ongoing.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Behavior problems treated without identifying underlying communication cause. Child punished for \'not listening\' when they don\'t understand. Social skills groups use language above child\'s level. Bullying not addressed. Anxiety about speaking not recognized. Zero-tolerance discipline applied without communication disorder consideration.\n\nRISKS: Behavior problems treated without identifying underlying communication cause. Child punished for \'not listening\' when they don\'t understand. Social skills groups use language above child\'s level. Bullying not addressed. Anxiety about speaking not recognized. Zero-tolerance discipline applied without communication disorder consideration.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School counselor / Psychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nParent\nTherapist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s63','journey-sli','step-63','SLI Step 6.3: Address Co-occurring Conditions (Autism, ADHD, Hearing Loss)','SLI — Step 6.3: Address Co-occurring Conditions (Autism, ADHD, Hearing Loss)\n\nWHAT TO DO: SLI frequently co-occurs with other conditions: (1) AUTISM — speech-language delay is often first sign; many children initially identified with SLI are later diagnosed with autism. If child has social communication deficits beyond language disorder, screen for autism. (2) ADHD — attention/executive function impacts language processing and therapy participation; 30-50% co-occurrence. (3) HEARING LOSS — even mild/fluctuating hearing loss (chronic ear infections) significantly impacts speech-language development. Hearing must be re-tested if progress is slow. (4) INTELLECTUAL DISABILITY — language disorder associated with ID has different trajectory than DLD. (5) APRAXIA OF SPEECH — motor planning disorder for speech, requires specialized treatment (not standard articulation therapy).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: SLI frequently co-occurs with other conditions: (1) AUTISM — speech-language delay is often first sign; many children initially identified with SLI are later diagnosed with autism.\nSTEP 2: If child has social communication deficits beyond language disorder, screen for autism.\nSTEP 3: (2) ADHD — attention/executive function impacts language processing and therapy participation; 30-50% co-occurrence.\nSTEP 4: (3) HEARING LOSS — even mild/fluctuating hearing loss (chronic ear infections) significantly impacts speech-language development.\nSTEP 5: Hearing must be re-tested if progress is slow.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER: If autism suspected — self-refer for evaluation. dds.ca.gov/rc/listing\nPEDIATRICIAN: ADHD screening (Vanderbilt/SNAP-IV). Hearing re-evaluation.\nAUDIOLOGIST: Annual hearing monitoring recommended for any child with speech concerns.\nCHADD: chadd.org — if ADHD is confirmed.\nCROSS-REFERENCE JOURNEY MAPS:\n• Autism Journey Map — if ASD suspected/diagnosed\n• ADHD Journey Map — if attention concerns\n• ID Journey Map — if cognitive delays co-occur\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — dual-eligibility IEP advocacy.\n\nDOCUMENTS: COMPREHENSIVE EVALUATION DOCUMENTS:\n• Autism screening results (M-CHAT, SCQ, ADOS-2 if pursued)\n• ADHD screening (Vanderbilt rating scales from teacher and parent)\n• Updated audiological evaluation (annual hearing monitoring recommended)\n• Developmental evaluation from Regional Center (if autism suspected)\n• Private developmental pediatrician or neuropsychologist evaluation\n\nDUAL-ELIGIBILITY DOCUMENTS:\n• IEP eligibility under multiple categories (SLI + Autism, SLI + OHI)\n• Updated IEP with goals addressing all diagnosed conditions\n• RC IPP (if autism/ID diagnosed — RC services supplement school)\n• Coordinated service plan between school, RC, and private providers\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — reassess as child develops and new concerns emerge.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (5) APRAXIA OF SPEECH — motor planning disorder for speech, requires specialized treatment (not standard articulation therapy)\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Autism identified late because SLI was the initial diagnosis. Hearing re-check not done when progress plateaus. Apraxia misdiagnosed as typical articulation disorder (treatment approach differs significantly). ADHD medication helps attention but doesn\'t resolve language disorder. Multiple providers not coordinating care.\n\nRISKS: Autism identified late because SLI was the initial diagnosis. Hearing re-check not done when progress plateaus. Apraxia misdiagnosed as typical articulation disorder (treatment approach differs significantly). ADHD medication helps attention but doesn\'t resolve language disorder. Multiple providers not coordinating care.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / Developmental Ped\nAudiologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nSchool\nRegional Center\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s71','journey-sli','step-71','SLI Step 7.1: Ongoing IEP Review — SLI-Specific Monitoring','SLI — Step 7.1: Ongoing IEP Review — SLI-Specific Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: Annual IEP review should assess: (1) Is therapy frequency/model still appropriate? (2) Are goals advancing (not repeating same goals yearly)? (3) Has diagnosis type changed or clarified? (4) Is literacy impact being monitored? (5) Should eligibility category shift from SLI to SLD as academic impacts emerge? (6) Is dismissal from speech services appropriate? ASHA dismissal guidelines: (1) Goals met — communication no longer adversely affects educational performance. (2) Plateau — child has reached maximum benefit from current approach. (3) Progress maintained without direct services. IMPORTANT: dismissal from speech DOESN\'T mean disorder is gone — child may need ongoing classroom supports.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Annual IEP review should assess: (1) Is therapy frequency/model still appropriate? (2) Are goals advancing (not repeating same goals yearly)? (3) Has diagnosis type changed or clarified? (4) Is literacy impact being monitored? (5) Should eligibility category shift from SLI to SLD as academic impacts emerge? (6) Is dismissal from speech services appropriate? ASHA dismissal guidelines: (1) Goals met — communication no longer adversely affects educational performance.\nSTEP 2: (2) Plateau — child has reached maximum benefit from current approach.\nSTEP 3: (3) Progress maintained without direct services.\nSTEP 4: IMPORTANT: dismissal from speech DOESN\'T mean disorder is gone — child may need ongoing classroom supports.\n\nCONTACT: IEP CASE MANAGER: Your child\'s school SLP or SpEd teacher.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — annual IEP review support.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — if services not delivered or goals stagnant.\nCDE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file if IEP not implemented.\nOAH (Office of Administrative Hearings): (916) 263-0880 — mediation or due process if needed.\nTASK: taskca.org — parent training on IEP monitoring and advocacy.\n\nDOCUMENTS: ANNUAL REVIEW DOCUMENTS:\n• Quarterly progress reports (file chronologically)\n• Annual IEP with updated goals\n• Current standardized assessment data\n• Language samples showing growth trajectory\n• Teacher/SLP input forms\n• Service delivery log (actual vs planned sessions)\n\nTRIENNIAL RE-EVALUATION (every 3 years):\n• Updated comprehensive speech-language evaluation\n• Continued eligibility determination\n• DO NOT waive triennial — updated data protects eligibility\n\nPARENT\'S MASTER BINDER:\n• Section 1: Current IEP\n• Section 2: All evaluations\n• Section 3: Progress reports\n• Section 4: Correspondence with school\n• Section 5: Private SLP reports\n• Section 6: Medical records\n\nTIMELINE: Annual IEP review. Triennial reassessment every 3 years.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Annual IEP review should assess: (1) Is therapy frequency/model still appropriate? (2) Are goals advancing (not repeating same goals yearly)? (3) Has diagnosis type changed or clarified? (4) Is literacy impact being monitored? (5) Should eligibility category shift from SLI to SLD as academic impacts emerge? (6) Is dismissal from speech services appropriate? ASHA dismissal guidelines: (1) Goals met — communication no longer adversely affects educational performance\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Same goals repeated for years without meaningful progress — approach needs changing. Child dismissed prematurely because articulation improved but language disorder persists. Triennial re-evaluation not comprehensive. SLP leaves and replacement doesn\'t understand child\'s history. Therapy minu\n\nRISKS: Same goals repeated for years without meaningful progress — approach needs changing. Child dismissed prematurely because articulation improved but language disorder persists. Triennial re-evaluation not comprehensive. SLP leaves and replacement doesn\'t understand child\'s history. Therapy minutes reduced due to caseload, not child\'s needs. Parent not informed about dismissal criteria.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nParent\nTeacher\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s72','journey-sli','step-72','SLI Step 7.2: Transition Planning (Age 14+) — DLD-Specific','SLI — Step 7.2: Transition Planning (Age 14+) — DLD-Specific\n\nWHAT TO DO: For children with persistent DLD (NOT resolved articulation): (1) Self-advocacy — understanding own communication needs and requesting accommodations. (2) SAT/ACT accommodations for language processing (extended time, reader for instructions). (3) College disability services — language disorder documentation for accommodations. (4) Career exploration — careers that match communication strengths. (5) Workplace communication strategies. (6) DOR referral for vocational support if needed. DLD impacts PERSIST into adulthood: difficulty with complex language, abstract reasoning, reading comprehension, written expression, social communication in professional settings.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: For children with persistent DLD (NOT resolved articulation): (1) Self-advocacy — understanding own communication needs and requesting accommodations.\nSTEP 2: (2) SAT/ACT accommodations for language processing (extended time, reader for instructions).\nSTEP 3: (3) College disability services — language disorder documentation for accommodations.\nSTEP 4: (4) Career exploration — careers that match communication strengths.\nSTEP 5: (5) Workplace communication strategies.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL TRANSITION COORDINATOR: Part of IEP team for transition planning.\nCA DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation): dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation if DLD impacts employment. Referral through IEP by age 16.\nCOLLEGE BOARD SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities — (844) 255-7728 — SAT accommodations for language disorders.\nACT ACCOMMODATIONS: act.org/the-act/accommodations — (319) 337-1332.\nCOLLEGE DISABILITY OFFICES: Register BEFORE first semester. IEP does not transfer to college.\nCALABLE: calable.ca.gov — if communication disability is significantly limiting.\nASHA: asha.org — adult communication resources.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ITP (Individual Transition Plan) in IEP — required by age 16\n• Transition assessments (vocational, independent living, communication)\n• Post-secondary goals (education, employment, independent living)\n• DOR referral documentation (by age 16)\n\nSAT/ACT ACCOMMODATION DOCUMENTS:\n• Current evaluation (within 3 years)\n• Complete accommodation history (IEP/504)\n• Documentation of accommodation USE\n• College Board SSD application or ACT application\n• Submit 6+ months before test date\n\nCOLLEGE PREP PACKET:\n• Most recent evaluation with diagnosis\n• All IEP/504 plans showing accommodation history\n• Summary of Performance (SOP) from school at graduation\n• Self-advocacy plan\n\nTIMELINE: Begin by age 14 (recommended), required by 16.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: For children with persistent DLD (NOT resolved articulation): (1) Self-advocacy — understanding own communication needs and requesting accommodations\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Child dismissed from speech services in elementary/middle school — transition plan doesn\'t address communication needs. College disability services unfamiliar with DLD. Workplace communication difficulties not recognized as disability-related. Self-advocacy not taught because child appeared to \'outgrow\' the disorder.\n\nRISKS: Child dismissed from speech services in elementary/middle school — transition plan doesn\'t address communication needs. College disability services unfamiliar with DLD. Workplace communication difficulties not recognized as disability-related. Self-advocacy not taught because child appeared to \'outgrow\' the disorder.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: DOR\nCollege disability office\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s73','journey-sli','step-73','SLI Step 7.3: Stuttering-Specific Long-Term Management','SLI — Step 7.3: Stuttering-Specific Long-Term Management\n\nWHAT TO DO: For children/teens who stutter: stuttering management is LONG-TERM, not a \'cure.\' Approaches evolve with age: (1) Preschool: Lidcombe Program (parent-delivered, most evidence). (2) School-age: fluency shaping + stuttering modification + avoidance reduction. Self-advocacy and disclosure skills. (3) Teen/adult: continued therapy as needed, support groups (NSA — National Stuttering Association), self-acceptance and desensitization. Key: goal is NOT fluent speech — it\'s effective communication with reduced impact on participation. IEP should address: classroom accommodations (extra time for verbal responses, alternative to oral reports), social-emotional support, self-advocacy.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: For children/teens who stutter: stuttering management is LONG-TERM, not a \'cure.\nSTEP 2: \' Approaches evolve with age: (1) Preschool: Lidcombe Program (parent-delivered, most evidence).\nSTEP 3: (2) School-age: fluency shaping + stuttering modification + avoidance reduction.\nSTEP 4: Self-advocacy and disclosure skills.\nSTEP 5: (3) Teen/adult: continued therapy as needed, support groups (NSA — National Stuttering Association), self-acceptance and desensitization.\n\nCONTACT: NATIONAL STUTTERING ASSOCIATION (NSA): westutter.org — (800) 937-8888 — support groups (adult and teen chapters throughout CA), annual conference, peer support.\nSTUTTERING FOUNDATION: stutteringhelp.org — (800) 992-9392 — free resources, SLP referrals, workshops.\nASHA PROFIND: asha.org/profind — find SLPs specializing in fluency disorders.\nFRIENDS (National Association of Young People Who Stutter): friendswhostutter.org — teen programs.\nSLP WITH FLUENCY SPECIALTY: Board-recognized specialty — ask for fluency-specialist SLP specifically.\nSCHOOL SLP: Ensure IEP addresses stuttering with appropriate goals (not \'fluent speech\' but communication confidence and management strategies).\n\nDOCUMENTS: STUTTERING-SPECIFIC DOCUMENTS:\n• Comprehensive fluency evaluation (stuttering frequency, types, severity)\n• IEP goals addressing: stuttering management strategies, communication confidence, self-advocacy, classroom participation\n• NOT goals for \'fluent speech\' — this is outdated and harmful\n• IEP accommodations: extended time for verbal responses, no penalty for stuttering, alternative to oral reports if desired, safe speaking environment\n\nNSA/FRIENDS RESOURCES:\n• Support group participation records\n• Conference attendance\n• Self-advocacy development documentation\n\nFOR OLDER TEENS/ADULTS:\n• ADA workplace accommodation documentation\n• Self-disclosure and advocacy plan\n• Insurance coverage for ongoing fluency therapy\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — long-term management, not cure.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: For children/teens who stutter: stuttering management is LONG-TERM, not a \'cure | (2) School-age: fluency shaping + stuttering modification + avoidance reduction | Key: goal is NOT fluent speech — it\'s effective communication with reduced impact on participation\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: SLP not specialized in stuttering — uses outdated approaches. School pressures child to speak in front of class. Peers/teachers interrupt or finish sentences. Child told to \'slow down\' or \'take a breath\' (increases anxiety, doesn\'t help). Stuttering dismissed as \'they\'ll grow out of it.\' Covert stuttering (hiding it) not recognized.\n\nRISKS: SLP not specialized in stuttering — uses outdated approaches. School pressures child to speak in front of class. Peers/teachers interrupt or finish sentences. Child told to \'slow down\' or \'take a breath\' (increases anxiety, doesn\'t help). Stuttering dismissed as \'they\'ll grow out of it.\' Covert stuttering (hiding it) not recognized.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SLP (stuttering specialist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: NSA (National Stuttering Association)\nSchool\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sli-s74','journey-sli','step-74','SLI Step 7.4: CalABLE Account & Financial Planning\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.g','SLI — Step 7.4: CalABLE Account & Financial Planning\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n\nWHAT TO DO: For children with persistent communication disabilities: CalABLE account available at any age (no minimum age). Allows saving up to $19K/year without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal eligibility ($100K SSI threshold). Tax-advantaged savings for disability-related expenses including therapy, assistive technology, AAC devices. SSI may be available if speech/language impairment is severe enough to significantly limit functioning. Most children with SLI alone do NOT qualify for SSI, but SLI + co-occurring conditions (autism, intellectual disability) may qualify.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: For children with persistent communication disabilities: CalABLE account available at any age (no minimum age).\nSTEP 2: Allows saving up to $19K/year without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal eligibility ($100K SSI threshold).\nSTEP 3: Tax-advantaged savings for disability-related expenses including therapy, assistive technology, AAC devices.\nSTEP 4: SSI may be available if speech/language impairment is severe enough to significantly limit functioning.\nSTEP 5: Most children with SLI alone do NOT qualify for SSI, but SLI + co-occurring conditions (autism, intellectual disability) may qualify.\n\nCONTACT: CALABLE: calable.ca.gov — CA\'s ABLE savings program. Enroll online.\nSSA (Social Security Administration): ssa.gov — (800) 772-1213 — SSI eligibility if communication disability is significantly limiting.\nIHSS (In-Home Supportive Services): Contact your county IHSS office. CA DSS IHSS info: cdss.ca.gov/in-home-supportive-services\nSPECIAL NEEDS TRUST ATTORNEYS: Find through Special Needs Alliance: specialneedsalliance.org or Academy of Special Needs Planners: specialneedsplanners.com\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — benefits counseling and advocacy.\nREGIONAL CENTER (if eligible): Self-Determination Program and community-based services.\n\nDOCUMENTS: CALABLE DOCUMENTS:\n• CalABLE enrollment: calable.ca.gov\n• Proof of disability onset before age 26 (evaluation report with diagnosis date)\n• OR: SSI/SSDI eligibility letter\n• OR: Disability certification from licensed professional\n\nSSI DOCUMENTS (if applicable):\n• SSI application (online at ssa.gov or in person)\n• Medical records documenting communication disability\n• Function Report (SSA-3375 for children)\n• School records (IEP, evaluations)\n\nFINANCIAL PLANNING:\n• CalABLE contribution records ($19K/year limit, $100K SSI-safe)\n• Special Needs Trust (if applicable) — attorney consultation documentation\n• Benefits coordination plan (CalABLE + SSI + Medi-Cal)\n• Annual review of financial plan\n\nTIMELINE: CalABLE: enroll anytime. SSI: 3-6 months for determination.\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Most children with SLI alone do NOT qualify for SSI, but SLI + co-occurring conditions (autism, intellectual disability) may qualify\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Parents don\'t know about CalABLE. SSI denied for SLI alone. AAC device costs not covered by school — family pays out of pocket. Private therapy costs accumulate.\n\nRISKS: Parents don\'t know about CalABLE. SSI denied for SLI alone. AAC device costs not covered by school — family pays out of pocket. Private therapy costs accumulate.\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n\nRESOURCES: ASHA PARENT RESOURCES: asha.org/public — milestones, FAQs, parent toolkits\nHANEN CENTRE: hanen.org — evidence-based parent programs for language development\nMOMMY SPEECH THERAPY: mommyspeechtherapy.com — free videos and parent strategies\n4GASLPS: 4gaslps.com — free parent handouts and play-based activities\nNIDCD: nidcd.nih.gov/health/developmental-language-disorder — DLD information\nREADING ROCKETS: readingrockets.org — SLI/DLD and literacy connection\nCPIR: parentcenterhub.org — Speech & Language Impairments parent guide\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'It Takes Two to Talk\' (Hanen), \'More Than Words\' (Hanen)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: CalABLE / SSA\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center (if eligible)\nFinancial planner\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-overview','journey-sld','overview','SLD Journey Map — Overview','SPECIFIC LEARNING DISABILITY (SLD) — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n14 steps across 6 phases:\n* 1 Concern & Early Indicators: Parent or Teacher Notices Academic Struggles, School Implements Classroom Interventions (Pre-Ref, Parent Requests Formal Special Education Evaluatio\n* 2 Evaluation & Eligibility: Review & Sign Assessment Plan, School Conducts Psychoeducational Evaluation, Private Psychoeducational Evaluation (Optional but, Eligibility Determination — SLD Criteria\n* 3 IEP Development & Services: IEP Development — SLD-Specific Goals & Services, Assistive Technology & Accommodations\n* 4 504 Plan Alternative: Section 504 Plan (If IEP Denied or Preferred)\n* 5 Private Services & Insurance: Private Tutoring & Educational Therapy, Medical Evaluation for Co-occurring Conditions\n* 6 Ongoing Management & Transition: Annual IEP Review & Progress Monitoring, Transition Planning & College Preparation (Age 14+\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s11','journey-sld','step-11','SLD Step 1.1: Parent or Teacher Notices Academic Struggles','SLD — Step 1.1: Parent or Teacher Notices Academic Struggles\n\nWHAT TO DO: START TRACKING ACADEMIC CONCERNS IMMEDIATELY: (1) Keep dated samples of your child\'s work — homework, tests, writing samples, report cards. These become evidence. (2) Note SPECIFIC struggles: reading (decoding, fluency, comprehension?), writing (spelling, handwriting, composition?), math (number sense, computation, word problems?). (3) Compare to grade-level expectations, not siblings. (4) Track HOW LONG homework takes vs. expected time — if 20-min assignment takes 90 min, that\'s significant. (5) Note if child avoids reading/writing, complains of headaches when reading, loses their place, reverses letters past age 7, or has strong verbal skills but poor written output (\'smart but can\'t show it on paper\'). (6) LD patterns: DYSLEXIA = reading (most common, ~80% of LD); DYSCALCULIA = math (~5-8%); DYSGRAPHIA = writing (~7-15%). (7) Talk to the teacher FIRST — ask for specifics: \'Where does my child fall compared to grade-level benchmarks in reading, writing, and math?\'\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Collect your child\'s last 3 report cards, last 5 graded assignments in areas of concern, and any standardized test scores (STAR/SBAC). Create a \'Concerns Folder.\'\nSTEP 2: Write dated observations: \'Oct 5: 2nd grade reading homework (15 min expected) took 55 min. Child cried twice. Reversed b/d in 4 of 10 words. Read 42 WPM (grade level is 90 WPM).\'\nSTEP 3: Email teacher: \'I\'ve noticed [child] struggling in [specific area]. Can we schedule a brief meeting to discuss where they fall compared to grade-level expectations? I\'d like to understand their benchmark assessment results.\'\nSTEP 4: At teacher meeting, ask: \'What is their reading level/Lexile? How do they compare to grade benchmarks? What interventions have you tried? Can you share progress monitoring data?\'\nSTEP 5: If teacher confirms struggles, say: \'I\'d like to request a formal special education evaluation. I\'ll put that in writing.\'\n\nCONTACT: CLASSROOM TEACHER: Your first contact — request meeting through school email or front office.\nSCHOOL PRINCIPAL: If teacher is unresponsive, escalate to principal.\nSCHOOL READING SPECIALIST: Many schools have one — ask teacher or principal for referral.\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your local school district\'s Special Education office. Find your district: cde.ca.gov/ds/si/ds/faq.asp. CA Parent Training Centers: parentcenterhub.org.\nPEDIATRICIAN: Request vision AND hearing screening to rule out as causes.\nUNDERSTOOD.ORG: Free parent resource — understood.org — take the \'Could my child have a learning disability?\' screener.\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEGIN COLLECTING:\n• Report cards (last 2-3 years)\n• Graded work samples (keep originals/photos)\n• Standardized test results (SBAC/STAR/iReady)\n• Teacher comments and progress notes\n• Benchmark assessment data (from teacher)\n• Your dated observations journal\n• Homework time log (assignment vs actual time)\n• Any medical records (vision, hearing tests)\n• Prior report cards from earlier grades\n\nTIMELINE: Act NOW — do not wait. Key timing: if reading concerns exist by mid-1st grade, request evaluation. By mid-2nd grade, the gap between LD readers and peers begins to widen dramatically (\'Matthew Effect\' — strong readers get stronger, struggling readers fall further behind). Math LD may not surface until grade 3-4. Writing LD may not surface until grade 4-5.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept \'they\'re just lazy\' or \'they\'ll catch up\' — persistent academic struggles despite effort are the hallmark of LD. (2) Assume good grades in some subjects rule out LD — a child can be gifted in math and have severe dyslexia. (3) Wait for the school to notice — teachers manage 25+ students and may not flag a quiet, compliant struggling reader. (4) Confuse LD with low intelligence — LD means a GAP between ability and achievement (your child may be very smart). (5) Blame yourself or your child — LD is neurobiological, not caused by insufficient help or practice. (6) Compare to other children — each child\'s profile is unique. (7) Wait beyond mid-2nd grade if reading concerns exist — the \'window\' for easiest intervention narrows significantly after age 8.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL DELAYS: (1) Teacher says \'they\'ll catch up\' — delays evaluation 1-2 years during critical window. (2) Gifted students mask LD through high IQ until middle school when demands exceed compensation strategies (\'twice-exceptional\'/2e). (3) Girls with LD less likely to be referred — they tend to be quiet and compliant rather than disruptive. (4) Minority students under-referred for LD evaluation. (5) Parents blame child\'s effort rather than recognizing neurobiological LD. (6) School attributes struggles to English learner status when LD is the actual cause. (7) ADHD co-occurs with LD in up to 50% of cases — if only ADHD is identified, LD goes untreated.\n\nRESOURCES: FREE PARENT RESOURCES:\n• Understood.org: understood.org — comprehensive LD parent resource, screeners, tech tools, expert Q&A\n• Learning Disabilities Association (LDA): ldaamerica.org — parent resources, local chapters\n• International Dyslexia Association (IDA): dyslexiaida.org — dyslexia fact sheets, provider directory\n• Decoding Dyslexia CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org — CA-specific parent advocacy\n• Reading Rockets: readingrockets.org — evidence-based reading strategies\n• National Center for LD: ncld.org\n• CA PTI: Your local Parent Training & Information center — parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS:\n• \'Overcoming Dyslexia\' by Sally Shaywitz (essential reading)\n• \'The Dyslexia Empowerment Plan\' by Ben Foss\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None\n(Parent/Teacher)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\n(rule out vision/hearing)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s12','journey-sld','step-12','SLD Step 1.2: School Implements Classroom Interventions (Pre-Referral / MTSS)','SLD — Step 1.2: School Implements Classroom Interventions (Pre-Referral / MTSS)\n\nWHAT TO DO: UNDERSTAND YOUR RIGHTS DURING MTSS/RTI: (1) Many schools use Multi-Tiered System of Supports (MTSS) or Response to Intervention (RTI) — Tier 1 (whole class), Tier 2 (small group targeted intervention), Tier 3 (intensive individual intervention). (2) This is GOOD — it provides data and early intervention. BUT: RTI/MTSS CANNOT be used to DELAY your right to request a special education evaluation. (3) Ask the school: \'What specific Tier 2 intervention are you using? Is it evidence-based? How often? For how long? How are you measuring progress?\' (4) Request to see progress monitoring data at least every 2 weeks. (5) If your child is in Tier 2 for 6+ weeks without progress, the school should move to Tier 3 or consider evaluation. (6) You can request a special education evaluation AT ANY TIME during RTI — you do not have to wait.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Ask teacher/principal: \'What intervention is my child receiving? What is the program name? How many minutes per day/week? In what group size? Who delivers it? How is progress measured?\'\nSTEP 2: Request progress monitoring data in writing: \'I\'d like to receive my child\'s progress monitoring data (CBM scores, reading fluency data, etc.) every 2 weeks.\'\nSTEP 3: After 6-8 weeks, if inadequate progress: \'My child has been in Tier 2 intervention for [X weeks] and the progress data shows [limited/no improvement]. I am now requesting a formal special education evaluation in writing.\'\nSTEP 4: PUT YOUR EVALUATION REQUEST IN WRITING — hand deliver AND email. This triggers the 15-day assessment plan timeline regardless of RTI status.\nSTEP 5: Continue RTI interventions during the evaluation process — they are not mutually exclusive.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL RTI/MTSS COORDINATOR: Ask front office who manages interventions at your school.\nSCHOOL PRINCIPAL: Escalate if RTI is being used to delay evaluation.\nDISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: If school won\'t accept evaluation request.\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your school\'s RTI/MTSS coordinator through the front office or district Special Education department.\nLEGAL HELP IF SCHOOL REFUSES EVALUATION:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• Wrightslaw RTI guidance: wrightslaw.com/info/rti.index.htm\n\nDOCUMENTS: REQUEST FROM SCHOOL:\n• Written description of Tier 2 intervention (program name, frequency, duration, group size, provider)\n• Progress monitoring data (graphs/charts showing your child\'s trajectory)\n• Benchmark comparison data (your child vs grade level)\n• Meeting notes from any Student Study Team (SST) or intervention team meetings\n\nPARENT CREATES:\n• Written log of all interventions tried\n• Copies of progress monitoring data received\n• Your own homework/academic tracking\n• Written evaluation request (when ready)\n\nTIMELINE: RTI/MTSS: Typically 6-12 weeks per tier. CRITICAL: RTI timeline does NOT extend the 15-day assessment plan deadline once you submit a written evaluation request. If school says \'we need 12 more weeks of RTI data,\' respond: \'I\'ve submitted my written request. The 15-day clock for the assessment plan has started.\'\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Let RTI/MTSS delay a special education evaluation — this is the #1 barrier to LD identification in California. If school says \'we need to try RTI first before we can evaluate,\' respond: \'Under IDEA, a parent\'s request for evaluation cannot be delayed by RTI. I\'m requesting an evaluation now.\' (2) Accept interventions that aren\'t evidence-based or implemented consistently. (3) Let the school use RTI for more than 8-12 weeks without meaningful progress before escalating. (4) Assume Tier 2 intervention = special education. It\'s not — it\'s general education. (5) Sign anything waiving your right to evaluation.\n\nRISKS: ★ RTI GATEKEEPING — THE #1 SLD BARRIER: (1) District uses RTI to delay evaluation by months or years — telling parents \'we need more data.\' This violates IDEA when parent has requested evaluation. (2) RTI interventions not evidence-based (e.g., using Reading Recovery for dyslexia when structured literacy is needed). (3) Interventions not implemented with fidelity (right program but wrong delivery). (4) Progress monitoring data not shared with parents. (5) Student Study Team (SST) used as additional delay before evaluation. (6) School tells parent \'they don\'t qualify for evaluation yet\' — FALSE if parent has submitted written request.\n\nRESOURCES: RTI/MTSS PARENT GUIDES:\n• Wrightslaw RTI: wrightslaw.com/info/rti.index.htm\n• Understood RTI guide: understood.org/en/articles/understanding-response-to-intervention\n• NCLD RTI guide: ncld.org\n• LDA RTI position: ldaamerica.org\n• DRC SERR Manual Chapter 3: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\nKEY LEGAL POINT:\n• OSEP has confirmed RTI cannot delay parent-requested evaluation. Cite: OSEP Letter to Zirkel (2011), OSEP Memo on RTI (Jan 2011)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(Gen Ed Teacher)\nOTHER AGENCIES: School counselor\nReading specialist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s13','journey-sld','step-13','SLD Step 1.3: Parent Requests Formal Special Education Evaluation','SLD — Step 1.3: Parent Requests Formal Special Education Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: SUBMIT YOUR WRITTEN EVALUATION REQUEST: (1) Write a letter requesting a \'comprehensive psychoeducational evaluation in all areas of suspected disability.\' (2) Be SPECIFIC about your concerns: \'My child struggles with reading decoding and fluency, written expression including spelling and handwriting, and reading comprehension. I suspect a specific learning disability.\' (3) List ALL areas you want tested: cognitive ability, academic achievement (reading, math, written expression), auditory processing, visual processing, processing speed, working memory, executive function, social-emotional (LD causes anxiety/depression). (4) Hand-deliver AND email the letter — keep dated copies. (5) This triggers a 15-day legal clock — the district MUST provide an assessment plan within 15 calendar days.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Write your letter. Template: \'Dear [Special Education Director], I am the parent of [child\'s name], a student in [grade/teacher] at [school]. I am writing to formally request a comprehensive psychoeducational evaluation under IDEA. I have concerns about [specific academic areas]. I request evaluation in the following areas: cognitive/IQ, academic achievement in all areas, processing skills (auditory, visual, processing speed, working memory), social-emotional impact, and any other areas of suspected disability. Please provide the assessment plan within 15 calendar days per California Education Code § 56321. Sincerely, [your name, date].\'\nSTEP 2: Print two copies. Hand-deliver one to the school office — ask them to date-stamp YOUR copy. Also email to principal AND Special Education Director.\nSTEP 3: Mark calendar: 15 days from delivery = deadline for assessment plan.\nSTEP 4: If no assessment plan in 15 days: send follow-up letter: \'My evaluation request was submitted on [date]. Under California law, you have 15 calendar days to provide an assessment plan. This deadline has passed. Please respond immediately or I will file a compliance complaint with CDE.\'\nSTEP 5: When you receive the assessment plan, do NOT sign immediately — review it, compare to your requested areas, and add any missing areas before signing.\n\nCONTACT: DELIVER YOUR LETTER TO:\n• School office (hand-deliver, get date stamp)\n• Email to: Principal AND Special Education Director/Coordinator\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your local school district\'s Special Education director. Find your district: cde.ca.gov. CDE complaint line: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp.\nIF SCHOOL WON\'T ACCEPT OR RESPOND:\n• Disability Rights California: (800) 776-5746\n• CDE Complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org (Bay Area free advocacy)\n• DREDF: dredf.org (Bay Area disability rights)\n• Wrightslaw letter templates: wrightslaw.com/info/test.index.htm\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter (CRITICAL — dated, keep copy with receipt stamp)\n• Email copy with read receipt\n• List of all areas to be evaluated\n\nDISTRICT MUST PROVIDE (within 15 days):\n• Assessment plan listing all areas to be evaluated\n• Parent rights notification (Procedural Safeguards)\n• OR: Prior Written Notice if refusing to evaluate (with reasons)\n\nALSO PREPARE:\n• All collected work samples and report cards\n• RTI/MTSS progress monitoring data\n• Your observations journal\n• Any prior private evaluations\n\nTIMELINE: 15 CALENDAR DAYS: District must provide assessment plan after receiving your written request. If they fail, they are in violation. File CDE complaint. 60 CALENDAR DAYS: From your signed consent on the assessment plan to completed evaluation.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Make a VERBAL request only — there is no paper trail and no legal clock starts. (2) Let the school talk you out of requesting: \'Let\'s wait another semester\' or \'They\'re not far enough behind.\' (3) Accept \'we don\'t have the resources right now.\' (4) Let the school limit the evaluation to just reading — if you suspect LD, request comprehensive evaluation covering ALL academic areas plus processing. (5) Wait for the school to suggest evaluation — YOU have the right to request at any time. (6) Assume you need teacher agreement — you don\'t.\n\nRISKS: ★ CRITICAL: (1) Parent makes verbal request — no paper trail, no legal timeline triggered. (2) District discourages evaluation: \'Let\'s wait\' / \'They\'re not behind enough\' — delay tactic. (3) District says \'RTI must be completed first\' — FALSE, violates IDEA. (4) District refuses evaluation — must provide Prior Written Notice with reasons (then parent can file complaint). (5) Assessment plan doesn\'t include all areas parent requested — parent should NOT sign until all areas are included. (6) Parent doesn\'t know they can request evaluation — waits for school to suggest it.\n\nRESOURCES: EVALUATION REQUEST HELP:\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com — sample letters, IEP strategies, law\n• Understood: understood.org/en/articles/how-to-request-a-free-school-evaluation\n• LDA: ldaamerica.org — parent guides\n• DRC SERR Manual: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — comprehensive rights guide\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free advocacy (Bay Area)\n• TASK: taskca.org — parent training on evaluation rights\n• Matrix: matrixparents.org — Bay Area parent training\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: None required\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s21','journey-sld','step-21','SLD Step 2.1: Review & Sign Assessment Plan','SLD — Step 2.1: Review & Sign Assessment Plan\n\nWHAT TO DO: REVIEW THE ASSESSMENT PLAN CAREFULLY BEFORE SIGNING: (1) Compare what you requested vs what the district proposes to test. (2) For SLD, the assessment plan should include AT MINIMUM: cognitive/IQ (WISC-V or similar), academic achievement in ALL areas (WJ-IV, WIAT, KTEA — reading decoding, reading fluency, reading comprehension, math calculation, math reasoning, written expression, oral expression, listening comprehension), processing skills (processing speed, working memory, auditory processing, visual processing), classroom observation, teacher input, parent input, review of records, social-emotional assessment. (3) If any area is MISSING, write back immediately: \'I request the following areas be added to the assessment plan before I sign: [list areas].\' (4) Once satisfied, sign and return — the 60-day evaluation clock starts when you sign.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: When you receive the assessment plan (within 15 days of your request), read every area listed. Highlight anything missing.\nSTEP 2: Compare to this SLD assessment checklist:\n  ✓ Cognitive/IQ (WISC-V, SB-5)\n  ✓ Reading (decoding, fluency, comprehension)\n  ✓ Math (calculation, reasoning)\n  ✓ Written expression (spelling, composition, handwriting)\n  ✓ Processing speed\n  ✓ Working memory\n  ✓ Auditory processing\n  ✓ Visual processing/motor\n  ✓ Executive function\n  ✓ Social-emotional/behavioral\n  ✓ Classroom observation\n  ✓ Teacher/parent input\nSTEP 3: If areas are missing, email the SpEd coordinator: \'Before signing the assessment plan, I request the following areas be added: [list]. Please send a revised plan.\'\nSTEP 4: Once all areas are included, sign and return. Mark calendar: 60 days from signing = evaluation completion deadline.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL PSYCHOLOGIST: Will conduct the evaluation — ask to speak with them before signing the plan. \'Can you walk me through what tests you\'ll administer and what areas they cover?\'\nSPECIAL EDUCATION COORDINATOR: Sends the assessment plan — your contact for adding areas.\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your district\'s Special Education office. Find your district: cde.ca.gov/ds/si/ds/faq.asp.\nIF DISTRICT WON\'T ADD REQUESTED AREAS:\n• Write: \'I disagree with the proposed assessment plan. Under IDEA, the evaluation must assess in all areas of suspected disability. I request [areas] be added.\'\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: DISTRICT PROVIDES:\n• Assessment plan document\n• Parent rights notification (Procedural Safeguards)\n• Consent form for you to sign\n\nPARENT SHOULD HAVE:\n• Your original evaluation request letter\n• Your assessment area checklist (compared to plan)\n• Written additions if areas are missing\n• All collected work samples, report cards, RTI data\n• Signed copy (keep your copy, return district\'s copy)\n\nTIMELINE: 15 calendar days: District provides assessment plan. Parent reviews and signs (take 1-5 days to review — no deadline on parent to sign, but don\'t delay unnecessarily). 60 CALENDAR DAYS: From signed consent to completed evaluation (excluding school breaks >5 days).\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Sign the assessment plan the same day you receive it — take it home and review carefully. (2) Sign without checking that ALL areas of concern are listed. (3) Let the district omit processing assessments (processing speed, working memory, auditory processing) — these are often the KEY to understanding WHY your child struggles. (4) Accept a plan that only tests reading if you also have math or writing concerns. (5) Forget that YOU have the right to ADD areas — the district\'s initial plan is a starting point, not final.\n\nRISKS: ★ ASSESSMENT PLAN GAPS: (1) Plan only tests reading but child also has math/writing concerns — incomplete. (2) Processing assessments omitted (processing speed, working memory) — these explain the WHY behind academic struggles. (3) Executive function not assessed — impacts organization, task completion. (4) No observation planned — critical for seeing real-world performance. (5) Social-emotional impact not assessed — LD causes significant anxiety and self-esteem impact. (6) Parent signs without reviewing — loses opportunity to add areas.\n\nRESOURCES: UNDERSTANDING EVALUATIONS:\n• Wrightslaw evaluation guide: wrightslaw.com/info/test.index.htm\n• Understood evaluation guide: understood.org/en/articles/the-evaluation-process\n• DRC evaluation rights: disabilityrightsca.org/publications/understanding-psycho-educational-evaluations\n• NCLD evaluation checklist: ncld.org\n• LDA evaluation fact sheet: ldaamerica.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School Psychologist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s22','journey-sld','step-22','SLD Step 2.2: School Conducts Psychoeducational Evaluation','SLD — Step 2.2: School Conducts Psychoeducational Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: PARTICIPATE ACTIVELY IN THE EVALUATION: (1) Complete the Parent Input Form thoroughly — this is your chance to describe your child\'s daily challenges, homework battles, emotional reactions, and history. Use specific examples with dates. (2) Share ALL your documentation with the school psychologist: work samples, RTI data, homework time logs, your observations journal, and any private evaluations. (3) Ask the school psychologist: \'When will you observe my child in the classroom? Can you observe during a reading/writing/math lesson when they typically struggle?\' (4) Know what tests will be administered: IQ (WISC-V typical), achievement (WJ-IV, WIAT, or KTEA), processing, and behavioral rating scales (BASC-3 or similar). (5) California uses EITHER the discrepancy model (significant gap between IQ and achievement) OR RTI model — ask which your district uses.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: When you receive the Parent Input Form, set aside 1 hour to complete it thoughtfully. For EVERY question, use specific examples: not \'struggles with reading\' but \'reads at 45 WPM in 3rd grade (benchmark is 100 WPM), frequently loses place, skips lines, guesses at words from first letter, avoids reading aloud, and takes 90 minutes for 20-minute homework assignments.\'\nSTEP 2: Attach your documentation to the Parent Input Form: work samples, homework time log, report cards, RTI data.\nSTEP 3: Email the school psychologist: \'I\'ve completed the Parent Input Form and attached additional documentation. I\'d like to discuss my child\'s evaluation before testing begins. When can we talk?\'\nSTEP 4: Track the 60-day timeline. At 30 days, email: \'Checking in on the evaluation timeline. When are testing sessions scheduled?\'\nSTEP 5: After testing is complete, request ALL reports at least 5 days BEFORE the IEP eligibility meeting.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL PSYCHOLOGIST: Primary evaluator — get their name, email, and direct phone from the SpEd coordinator.\nSCHOOL SLP: If speech-language is part of the assessment.\nSCHOOL OT: If handwriting/fine motor is a concern.\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your school psychologist through the district Special Education office.\nIF EVALUATION IS DELAYED:\n• Email SpEd coordinator: \'The 60-day evaluation deadline is [date]. Please confirm completion.\'\n• If deadline passes: File CDE compliance complaint at cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT COMPLETES:\n• Parent Input Form (detailed, with examples)\n• Attached documentation (work samples, RTI data, homework log, report cards)\n\nSCHOOL PRODUCES:\n• Psychoeducational evaluation report (cognitive, achievement, processing)\n• Classroom observation report\n• Teacher Input Form results\n• Speech-language report (if assessed)\n• OT report (if assessed)\n• Social-emotional assessment results\n• Summary of eligibility recommendation\n\nREQUEST ALL REPORTS 5+ DAYS BEFORE IEP MEETING\n\nTIMELINE: 60 CALENDAR DAYS from signed consent to completed evaluation (excluding school breaks >5 consecutive days). At 30 days: check in. At 50 days: confirm completion date. If deadline missed: document and file CDE complaint.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Skip or rush the Parent Input Form — it\'s often the most powerful evidence because it describes real-world functioning. (2) Fail to share your homework time data — this shows functional impact beyond test scores. (3) Assume the school psychologist knows everything about your child — they have limited time and dozens of evaluations. (4) Forget about the 60-day deadline — if approaching deadline, email: \'Evaluation was consented on [date]. The 60-day deadline is [date]. Please confirm completion schedule.\' (5) Allow testing only on a \'good day\' — if your child struggles in the morning, that\'s when testing should happen.\n\nRISKS: ★ EVALUATION FAILURES: (1) School psychologist has 80+ evaluations — limited time per student. (2) Only a narrow test battery used — misses processing deficits. (3) Discrepancy model misses LD in gifted students (\'scores are too high to show discrepancy\'). (4) RTI model delays identification while collecting more data. (5) Testing not done in primary language — bilingual students may be misidentified or missed. (6) No classroom observation during area of difficulty. (7) Teacher Input Form incomplete or minimizing. (8) Parent Input Form not provided or completed hastily.\n\nRESOURCES: EVALUATION PREPARATION:\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com/info/test.index.htm — parent guide to evaluations\n• Understood: understood.org — evaluation explainer with glossary\n• DRC Psychoeducational Evaluation Guide: disabilityrightsca.org\n• National Center for LD: ncld.org\n• \'From Emotions to Advocacy\' by Pam Wright — Chapter on evaluations\n• Parent Input Form guide: wrightlaw.com/advoc/articles/parent.input.htm\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School Psychologist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Classroom teacher\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s23','journey-sld','step-23','SLD Step 2.3: Private Psychoeducational Evaluation (Optional but Powerful)','SLD — Step 2.3: Private Psychoeducational Evaluation (Optional but Powerful)\n\nWHAT TO DO: CONSIDER A PRIVATE EVALUATION IF: (1) You want a more comprehensive assessment than school typically provides. (2) You suspect the school evaluation will be insufficient or biased toward denial. (3) You want specific dyslexia/LD identification that goes beyond school criteria. (4) You need documentation for both school AND private tutoring. PRIVATE EVALUATIONS: Neuropsychologist provides the most comprehensive assessment ($3K-$6K). Educational psychologist ($1.5K-$3K) may be sufficient. Some insurance covers under \'neurodevelopmental\' or \'psychological testing\' benefits. IEE (Independent Educational Evaluation): If you disagree with school\'s evaluation, you have the RIGHT to request an IEE at district expense. District must either pay for IEE or file due process to defend their evaluation.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Call insurance: \'Does my plan cover neuropsychological or psychoeducational testing for my child? What is my benefit? Do I need a referral?\'\nSTEP 2: If pursuing private eval: search for neuropsychologists or educational psychologists specializing in LD. Ask: \'Do you evaluate for specific learning disabilities? What tests do you use? What is your experience with dyslexia/dyscalculia?\'\nSTEP 3: If pursuing IEE (at district expense): write to the district: \'I disagree with the school evaluation completed on [date]. Under 34 CFR §300.502, I am requesting an Independent Educational Evaluation at public expense.\'\nSTEP 4: District must either (a) agree and pay for IEE, or (b) file due process to defend their evaluation. Most districts will agree.\nSTEP 5: Whether private pay or IEE, share results with school for IEP consideration.\n\nCONTACT: PRIVATE EVALUATORS (Bay Area):\n• Psychology Today directory: psychologytoday.com — filter by \'learning disabilities,\' \'neuropsychological testing,\' children\n• University psychology clinics — many CA universities offer sliding-scale assessments (search \'psychology clinic\' + your nearest UC or CSU)\n• Ask pediatrician for referral\nIEE RIGHTS:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746 — IEE rights guidance\n• Wrightslaw IEE guide: wrightslaw.com/info/test.iee.index.htm\nINSURANCE:\n• Call number on back of card — ask for \'psychological testing\' or \'neurodevelopmental assessment\' benefits\n\nDOCUMENTS: PRIVATE EVALUATION PRODUCES:\n• Comprehensive neuropsychological or psychoeducational report\n• Specific LD diagnosis (if applicable)\n• Detailed recommendations for school and home\n• Supporting documentation for IEP/504\n\nIEE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written IEE request letter (keep copy)\n• District response (agreement or due process filing)\n• IEE evaluation report\n\nINSURANCE DOCUMENTS:\n• Referral from pediatrician\n• Pre-authorization (if required)\n• EOB after evaluation\n\nTIMELINE: Private wait times: 2-8 weeks for neuropsychologist (faster than dev ped). Insurance pre-auth: 5-15 business days. IEE: district must respond within \'reasonable time\' — typically 2-4 weeks. CANCEL LIST: Ask to be put on provider\'s cancellation list.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Pay for private evaluation before checking insurance — many plans cover neuropsychological testing. (2) Assume private eval replaces school eval — you need BOTH (school eval determines eligibility, private eval can support and supplement). (3) Use an evaluator who is not experienced with learning disabilities (look for specialty in LD, dyslexia, educational assessment). (4) Skip the IEE option — if you disagree with school\'s evaluation, the district may be required to pay for a private one.\n\nRISKS: Cost $2K-$6K if insurance doesn\'t cover. Insurance denies \'educational\' testing. Private eval disagrees with school — district may disregard. District fights IEE request. Parent doesn\'t know about IEE right. Long waitlists for qualified evaluators.\n\nRESOURCES: IEE RIGHTS:\n• Wrightslaw IEE: wrightslaw.com/info/test.iee.index.htm\n• DRC: disabilityrightsca.org\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\nFINDING EVALUATORS:\n• Psychology Today: psychologytoday.com (filter by specialty)\n• IDA provider directory: dyslexiaida.org\n• LDA: ldaamerica.org\n• Your pediatrician\'s referral network\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Psychologist /\nNeuropsychologist\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nPediatrician (referral)\nSchool district (IEE)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s24','journey-sld','step-24','SLD Step 2.4: Eligibility Determination — SLD Criteria','SLD — Step 2.4: Eligibility Determination — SLD Criteria\n\nWHAT TO DO: UNDERSTAND AND PREPARE FOR THE ELIGIBILITY DECISION: (1) IEP team (including you) reviews all evaluation data. (2) For SLD eligibility, team must determine ALL THREE: (a) Child has SLD (using discrepancy model OR RTI model — California allows both), (b) It adversely affects educational performance, (c) Child needs specially designed instruction. (3) SLD covers 7 areas under IDEA: oral expression, listening comprehension, written expression, basic reading skill, reading fluency, reading comprehension, mathematics calculation, mathematics reasoning. (4) If using discrepancy model: typically 1.5 standard deviation gap between IQ and achievement in one or more areas. (5) CRITICAL: Request reports 5+ days before the meeting. Review scores yourself. Use Wrightslaw\'s chart to understand standard scores, percentiles, and discrepancies.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Request all evaluation reports 5+ days before IEP meeting. Read them carefully.\nSTEP 2: For each test, note the standard score, percentile, and whether it\'s significantly below average (below 85 = low average, below 70 = significantly below).\nSTEP 3: Calculate discrepancies yourself: if IQ composite is 105 and reading composite is 78, that\'s a 27-point gap (significant). Use Wrightslaw discrepancy chart.\nSTEP 4: Prepare a written summary of your analysis for the meeting. Include: \'Based on the evaluation data, my child meets SLD criteria because [specific data points].\'\nSTEP 5: At the meeting, ask: \'What specific eligibility criteria is the team using? Discrepancy model or RTI model?\'\nSTEP 6: IF ELIGIBLE: proceed to IEP development. IF DENIED: say: \'I disagree. I request Prior Written Notice with specific reasons for denial. I also request a Section 504 evaluation as an alternative. And I may pursue an IEE at district expense.\'\nSTEP 7: If denied, you have 2 years to file complaint or due process.\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM MEETING: You, school psychologist, SpEd teacher, general ed teacher, administrator.\nBRING AN ADVOCATE IF POSSIBLE:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org — free IEP advocates (Bay Area)\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• TASK: taskca.org — parent mentors\n• Matrix: matrixparents.org\nIF DENIED:\n• Request Prior Written Notice (legal document)\n• Request 504 evaluation\n• Consider IEE request\n• Contact DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• CDE complaint: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n\nDOCUMENTS: FOR THE MEETING:\n• All evaluation reports (reviewed, annotated)\n• Your score analysis summary\n• Parent Concerns Letter (updated)\n• Work samples showing impact\n• RTI/MTSS data\n• Private evaluation (if obtained)\n\nAFTER THE MEETING:\n• Eligibility determination document\n• Prior Written Notice (if denied)\n• IEP document (if eligible, may be same meeting or scheduled within 30 days)\n• Parent rights notification\n\nTIMELINE: Eligibility meeting: within 60 days of signed consent (same deadline as evaluation completion). If eligible, IEP development typically same meeting or within 30 days. 2-YEAR statute of limitations for filing complaint or due process if denied.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Go to the eligibility meeting without reviewing all reports first. (2) Accept \'they\'re not far enough behind\' without understanding the specific scores and criteria. (3) Accept denial without requesting Prior Written Notice (written explanation of why). (4) Forget that 504 Plan is a fallback if IEP is denied. (5) Assume a gifted child can\'t have SLD — \'twice-exceptional\' (2e) children can have high IQ AND significant LD. The discrepancy model may actually help identify these students. (6) Let the team dismiss processing deficits as \'not educationally relevant.\'\n\nRISKS: ★ ELIGIBILITY BARRIERS: (1) Discrepancy threshold too high — child struggling but \'not far enough behind.\' (2) Gifted student denied — scores \'too high\' despite significant gap. (3) RTI model delays identification while collecting more data. (4) English learner exclusion used inappropriately — team must rule out language difference vs LD but often over-excludes. (5) District says \'lack of instruction\' is the cause — must document adequate instruction was provided. (6) Team overrides school psychologist recommendation. (7) Parent outnumbered and pressured to accept denial.\n\nRESOURCES: ELIGIBILITY PREPARATION:\n• Wrightslaw eligibility guide: wrightslaw.com/info/sld.index.htm\n• Wrightslaw discrepancy chart: wrightslaw.com/advoc/articles/tests.htm\n• Understood: understood.org/en/articles/types-of-tests-for-learning-disabilities\n• DRC SERR Manual Chapter 3: serr.disabilityrightsca.org\n• \'Overcoming Dyslexia\' by Sally Shaywitz — Chapter on school identification\n• LDA position on eligibility: ldaamerica.org\n• Decoding Dyslexia CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(IEP Team)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nSchool psychologist\nTeachers\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s31','journey-sld','step-31','SLD Step 3.1: IEP Development — SLD-Specific Goals & Services','SLD — Step 3.1: IEP Development — SLD-Specific Goals & Services\n\nWHAT TO DO: ADVOCATE FOR A STRONG IEP: (1) IEP must include: Present Levels of Academic Achievement and Functional Performance (PLAAFP), measurable annual goals, specially designed instruction (SDI) with specific methodology, accommodations, modifications, and related services. (2) For DYSLEXIA: demand STRUCTURED LITERACY instruction (Orton-Gillingham, Wilson Reading System, Barton, RAVE-O, Lindamood-Bell). These are evidence-based and EXPLICITLY teach phonics, decoding, fluency, and comprehension. Generic \'reading support\' is NOT sufficient. (3) For DYSCALCULIA: math intervention using concrete-representational-abstract (CRA) approach, manipulatives, explicit instruction. (4) For DYSGRAPHIA: OT for handwriting, assistive technology (text-to-speech, speech-to-text, word prediction). (5) Goals must be SMART: Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound. (6) DEMAND specific program names — not \'reading intervention\' but \'Orton-Gillingham-based structured literacy, 5x/week, 45 min/session, delivered by trained specialist.\'\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before IEP meeting, prepare a written \'IEP Request\' document listing: (a) Specific goals you want in each area, (b) Specific programs/methodologies you want (e.g., \'structured literacy\'), (c) Service frequency/duration (e.g., \'45 min daily\'), (d) Accommodations (list all needed), (e) Assistive technology requests.\nSTEP 2: Research evidence-based programs: For dyslexia, see IDA Structured Literacy page. Confirm your school has trained staff.\nSTEP 3: At IEP meeting, present your request. For each goal, ask: \'How will this be measured? How often will progress be reported? What evidence-based program will be used?\'\nSTEP 4: Request AT consideration: \'Has AT been considered? My child would benefit from [text-to-speech/speech-to-text/audiobooks/graphic organizers].\'\nSTEP 5: Request ESY evaluation if applicable: \'I want ESY considered — my child shows regression after school breaks.\'\nSTEP 6: If you disagree with the offer, do NOT sign: \'I\'d like to take this home to review.\'\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM: You, SpEd teacher, gen ed teacher, school psychologist, administrator. Bring advocate if possible.\nSTRUCTURED LITERACY INFORMATION:\n• IDA: dyslexiaida.org/structured-literacy — explanation and program list\n• Orton-Gillingham Academy: ortonacademy.org\n• Wilson Reading System: wilsonlanguage.com\n• Lindamood-Bell: lindamoodbell.com\nADVOCACY SUPPORT:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• Wrightslaw IEP guide: wrightslaw.com/info/iep.index.htm\n• TASK: taskca.org\n• Matrix: matrixparents.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP DOCUMENT INCLUDES:\n• PLAAFP (Present Levels)\n• Annual goals (measurable, time-bound)\n• SDI page (program, frequency, duration, provider, setting)\n• Accommodations page\n• Modifications page\n• AT consideration\n• ESY determination\n• Placement (LRE)\n• Services page (speech, OT, if applicable)\n• Progress reporting schedule (quarterly)\n\nPARENT BRINGS:\n• Your written IEP request document\n• Evaluation reports (annotated)\n• Private eval (if applicable)\n• Research on evidence-based programs\n• Work samples\n\nTIMELINE: IEP meeting: within 30 days of completed evaluation. IEP reviewed annually (every 12 months). Parent can request IEP meeting at ANY time. Progress reports: quarterly (aligned with grading periods). Services begin upon parent consent.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept vague goals (\'improve reading\' → instead: \'Read grade-level passages at 100 WPM with 95% accuracy by [date]\'). (2) Accept vague SDI (\'modified work\' → instead: \'Structured literacy instruction using Wilson Reading System, 45 min daily, 1:1 or small group\'). (3) Accept only \'extra time\' and \'preferential seating\' as accommodations — these are table stakes, not sufficient. (4) Let the school use a non-evidence-based reading program for dyslexia (many popular programs are NOT structured literacy). (5) Accept no assistive technology consideration — IEP team MUST consider AT for every student. (6) Skip requesting ESY (Extended School Year) if your child regresses over summer.\n\nRISKS: ★ IEP PITFALLS FOR SLD: (1) Non-evidence-based reading program used — many schools use Fountas & Pinnell or balanced literacy rather than structured literacy for dyslexic students (research shows structured literacy is significantly more effective). (2) Goals are vague and unmeasurable. (3) SDI is \'pull-out\' 30 min 2x/week — insufficient for moderate-severe LD. (4) AT not considered (checkbox left unchecked). (5) ESY denied despite regression evidence. (6) No specific program named — \'reading support\' instead of \'Wilson Reading System.\' (7) SpEd teacher not trained in structured literacy. (8) Accommodation list is only \'extra time\' and \'preferential seating.\'\n\nRESOURCES: IEP FOR LD:\n• Wrightslaw IEP strategies: wrightslaw.com/info/iep.index.htm\n• Understood IEP guide: understood.org\n• IDA IEP accommodations: dyslexiaida.org\n• Decoding Dyslexia CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org\n• LDA: ldaamerica.org\n• NCLD: ncld.org\n• AT for LD: understood.org/en/articles/assistive-technology-for-learning-disabilities\nBOOKS:\n• \'From Emotions to Advocacy\' by Pam Wright\n• \'The Complete IEP Guide\' by Lawrence Siegel\n• \'Overcoming Dyslexia\' by Sally Shaywitz (school advocacy chapter)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nGeneral ed teacher\nSpecial ed teacher\nRelated services\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s32','journey-sld','step-32','SLD Step 3.2: Assistive Technology & Accommodations','SLD — Step 3.2: Assistive Technology & Accommodations\n\nWHAT TO DO: DEMAND ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY FOR YOUR CHILD: (1) IDEA requires IEP team to consider AT for EVERY student — it\'s not optional. (2) AT for dyslexia: text-to-speech (Learning Ally, NaturalReader, Bookshare — FREE for students with LD), audiobooks, read-aloud tools, colored overlays, large print. (3) AT for dysgraphia: speech-to-text (Google Voice Typing, Dragon), word prediction (Co:Writer), graphic organizers, laptop/tablet for writing, smart pen. (4) AT for dyscalculia: calculator (even on tests), graph paper, manipulatives apps, math notation tools. (5) ACCOMMODATIONS beyond basics: extended time (1.5x or 2x), separate testing environment, tests read aloud, reduced assignment length, no penalty for spelling in content areas, note-taking support, copy of teacher notes, preferential seating, movement breaks, chunked assignments.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Before IEP meeting, research AT options for your child\'s specific LD type. Create a list of requested AT tools.\nSTEP 2: At IEP meeting: \'I\'d like to discuss assistive technology. Has the AT consideration been completed? I\'m requesting [specific tools] for my child.\'\nSTEP 3: If the team says AT isn\'t needed, ask: \'What specific AT tools were considered and why were they rejected? Please document this in the IEP.\'\nSTEP 4: If AT evaluation needed: request one. Say: \'I request a formal AT evaluation to determine what tools would support my child\'s access to the curriculum.\'\nSTEP 5: Register for Bookshare (bookshare.org — FREE for qualified students) and Learning Ally (learningally.org).\nSTEP 6: For accommodations, provide a comprehensive list organized by setting (classroom, homework, testing).\n\nCONTACT: AT RESOURCES:\n• Bookshare: bookshare.org — FREE digital library for LD (apply through school or individually)\n• Learning Ally: learningally.org — human-narrated audiobooks (membership ~$99/yr but school can join)\n• Google Accessibility: Chromebook built-in tools (Select-to-speak, dictation)\n• ATAP (CA Assistive Technology Access Program): atnet.org\n• CAST UDL: cast.org — Universal Design for Learning resources\nAT EVALUATION:\n• Request through IEP team\n• School AT specialist (ask if your district has one)\n• ATAP: atnet.org — state AT program\n\nDOCUMENTS: AT DOCUMENTS:\n• AT consideration documented in IEP (IDEA requirement)\n• AT evaluation report (if formal eval conducted)\n• AT listed on IEP accommodations page\n• Bookshare membership documentation\n• Learning Ally membership\n• AT training plan for student and staff\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Which AT tools are in place\n• Whether AT is actually being used in classroom\n• Student\'s progress with AT\n• Any AT needs not yet met\n\nTIMELINE: AT must be considered at EVERY IEP meeting (IDEA requirement). AT evaluation: within 60 days if requested as part of assessment. Bookshare: apply online, approved within days. Learning Ally: immediate membership.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept an IEP that says \'AT considered — not needed\' without specific explanation. (2) Let AT be limited to special education settings only — AT must be available in general education too. (3) Forget about FREE AT resources: Bookshare (bookshare.org — free ebooks for LD students), Learning Ally (learningally.org — human-narrated audiobooks), Google Accessibility features. (4) Accept only \'extra time\' as accommodation — most LD students need much more. (5) Let the school say \'we don\'t have that technology\' — they must provide it if needed.\n\nRISKS: ★ AT FAILURES: (1) AT \'considered\' but not actually evaluated or provided. (2) AT only available in resource room, not general education. (3) Teacher not trained on student\'s AT tools. (4) Student embarrassed to use AT in class (needs desensitization and normalization). (5) AT device stays at school — student can\'t access at home for homework. (6) Free resources (Bookshare, Learning Ally) not activated. (7) School claims cost as barrier — AT is required regardless of cost.\n\nRESOURCES: AT FOR LD:\n• Understood AT guide: understood.org/en/articles/assistive-technology-for-learning-disabilities\n• Bookshare: bookshare.org\n• Learning Ally: learningally.org\n• CAST UDL: cast.org\n• ATAP: atnet.org\n• Wrightslaw AT: wrightslaw.com/info/atech.index.htm\n• IDA AT guide: dyslexiaida.org\n• LD Online: ldonline.org — AT resources\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: AT specialist\nOT (if handwriting AT)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s41','journey-sld','step-41','SLD Step 4.1: Section 504 Plan (If IEP Denied or Preferred)','SLD — Step 4.1: Section 504 Plan (If IEP Denied or Preferred)\n\nWHAT TO DO: 504 PLAN AS ALTERNATIVE OR SUPPLEMENT: (1) If IEP denied because child doesn\'t need \'specially designed instruction\' but HAS a disability affecting a major life activity (learning, reading, concentrating) — 504 Plan provides ACCOMMODATIONS. (2) 504 has BROADER eligibility than IEP — any disability that \'substantially limits\' a major life activity. (3) 504 accommodations can include everything on the IEP accommodation list EXCEPT specially designed instruction and related services. (4) Many students with LD get 504 Plans, especially: milder LD, students whose grades are adequate with accommodations, students transitioning off IEP. (5) 504 is ALSO the bridge to college/SAT/ACT accommodations — accommodation history is critical for testing accommodation approval.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: If IEP denied, immediately request 504 evaluation: \'Since my child was not found eligible for an IEP, I request a Section 504 evaluation. My child has [LD type] which substantially limits learning/reading/concentrating.\'\nSTEP 2: Provide documentation: evaluation reports, private eval, medical documentation, teacher input.\nSTEP 3: At 504 meeting, present comprehensive accommodation list (not just extra time). Include AT.\nSTEP 4: Get the 504 plan IN WRITING with specific accommodations, review schedule, and contact person.\nSTEP 5: Monitor implementation quarterly — email teachers: \'Is [child] receiving all 504 accommodations? Are there any challenges?\'\nSTEP 6: Keep detailed records of 504 history — you WILL need this for SAT/ACT College Board accommodation requests.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL 504 COORDINATOR: Every school has one — often the principal or counselor. Ask the front office.\nCA STATEWIDE: Contact your school\'s 504 coordinator (typically principal or counselor).\nIF 504 NOT OFFERED:\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• OCR (Office for Civil Rights): ed.gov/ocr — file complaint if 504 rights violated\n• OCR complaint hotline: (800) 421-3481\nFOR SAT/ACT ACCOMMODATIONS:\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities\n• ACT accommodations: act.org/the-act/accommodations\n\nDOCUMENTS: 504 DOCUMENTS:\n• 504 evaluation documentation\n• 504 Plan (written, with specific accommodations)\n• Annual 504 review documentation\n• Teacher acknowledgment of accommodations\n• Implementation tracking records\n\nFOR FUTURE USE:\n• Complete 504 accommodation history (needed for SAT/ACT/college)\n• All evaluation reports supporting LD diagnosis\n• Documentation of accommodation use and effectiveness\n• College Board/ACT accommodation applications\n\nTIMELINE: No specific federal timeline for 504 — push for completion within 30 days. 504 reviewed annually. OCR complaint: file within 180 days of violation. SAT/ACT accommodation requests: submit 6+ months before test date.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Accept 504 if your child needs SPECIALIZED INSTRUCTION — 504 only provides accommodations, not teaching methodology changes. (2) Forget that 504 has no federal timeline requirements — push for prompt development. (3) Accept a generic 504 with only \'extra time.\' (4) Let 504 substitute for IEP when IEP is warranted. (5) Forget to document the 504 accommodation history — you\'ll need it for SAT/ACT/college accommodations. (6) Let the school ignore the 504 — there\'s no progress monitoring like IEP, so YOU must track implementation.\n\nRISKS: ★ 504 RISKS: (1) Not offered when IEP denied — parent doesn\'t know to ask. (2) Generic plan (extra time only). (3) No enforcement mechanism — teachers may not implement. (4) No progress monitoring. (5) Annual review skipped. (6) SAT/ACT accommodation denied because accommodation history not documented. (7) College disability services harder to access without strong 504 history.\n\nRESOURCES: 504 PLAN RESOURCES:\n• Understood 504 guide: understood.org/en/articles/the-difference-between-ieps-and-504-plans\n• Wrightslaw 504: wrightslaw.com/info/sec504.index.htm\n• DRC 504 rights: disabilityrightsca.org\n• OCR: ed.gov/ocr — complaint process\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities\n• LDA 504 guide: ldaamerica.org\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(504 Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nTeacher\nSchool counselor\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s51','journey-sld','step-51','SLD Step 5.1: Private Tutoring & Educational Therapy','SLD — Step 5.1: Private Tutoring & Educational Therapy\n\nWHAT TO DO: SUPPLEMENT SCHOOL SERVICES WITH PRIVATE SUPPORT: (1) Many families use private structured literacy tutoring (Orton-Gillingham, Wilson, Barton) to supplement school services. (2) Educational therapists combine teaching with therapeutic support — particularly helpful for LD-related anxiety and self-esteem. (3) Costs: $75-$200/hour, typically 2-3x/week. (4) Insurance RARELY covers tutoring or educational therapy (it\'s \'educational\' not \'medical\'). (5) IEE AT DISTRICT EXPENSE: If you disagree with school evaluation, district may be required to pay for independent evaluation. (6) Tax deductions: Tutoring prescribed by a physician for a diagnosed LD may be tax-deductible as medical expense (get physician letter of medical necessity). (7) Ensure private tutoring goals ALIGN with IEP goals.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Search for structured literacy tutors: IDA provider directory (dyslexiaida.org), Orton-Gillingham Academy, Wilson-certified tutors, Barton System tutors.\nSTEP 2: Interview tutors: \'What methodology do you use? Are you certified in a structured literacy program? What is your experience with [dyslexia/dyscalculia/dysgraphia]?\'\nSTEP 3: If cost is a barrier, ask school: \'Can the district provide structured literacy instruction as part of the IEP?\' If they can\'t, document this.\nSTEP 4: For tax deduction: Get a letter from your pediatrician: \'Specialized tutoring is medically necessary for treatment of [child\'s] diagnosed learning disability.\'\nSTEP 5: Track all expenses for tax filing: tutor fees, evaluation costs, AT purchases, transportation to tutoring.\n\nCONTACT: FIND PRIVATE TUTORS:\n• IDA provider directory: dyslexiaida.org/provider-directories\n• Orton-Gillingham Academy: ortonacademy.org — find certified practitioners\n• Wilson Language: wilsonlanguage.com — find Wilson-certified tutors\n• Barton Reading & Spelling: bartonreading.com — train yourself or find tutor\n• Learning Ally: learningally.org\n• Academic Language Therapy Association: altaread.org\nLOW-COST OPTIONS:\n• University tutoring clinics (UC and CSU systems)\n• University education departments (supervised student tutors)\n• Barton System (parent-delivered at home, ~$400/level)\n\nDOCUMENTS: PRIVATE SERVICE DOCUMENTS:\n• Tutor credentials and methodology\n• Treatment plan from tutor\n• Progress reports from tutor (align with IEP goals)\n• Physician letter of medical necessity (for tax deduction)\n• Receipts for all LD-related expenses\n• IEE documentation (if requesting at district expense)\n\nTAX DOCUMENTS:\n• All receipts for evaluations, tutoring, AT, therapy\n• Physician letter\n• IEP/504 documentation (proof of disability)\n• IRS Form 1040 Schedule A (medical expenses >7.5% AGI)\n\nTIMELINE: Private tutoring: begin as soon as possible (no waiting period). IEE: request at any time after school evaluation. Tax deduction: file with annual return. Structured literacy programs: typically 1-2 years minimum for meaningful progress.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Use private tutoring as substitute for school\'s legal obligation to provide FAPE — the school must provide appropriate education regardless. (2) Hire a tutor who isn\'t trained in structured literacy for dyslexia (generic tutoring often doesn\'t help). (3) Forget to coordinate private and school goals. (4) Skip getting a physician letter for tax deduction. (5) Ignore IEE option — district may be required to pay.\n\nRISKS: Cost prohibitive ($150-400/month). No insurance coverage. Private tutor not trained in structured literacy. Private goals don\'t align with school IEP. IEE request rejected by district. Tax deduction missed. Quality varies enormously.\n\nRESOURCES: PRIVATE SERVICES:\n• IDA: dyslexiaida.org — provider directory, fact sheets\n• Decoding Dyslexia CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org\n• Barton System: bartonreading.com — parent-delivered option\n• Wrightslaw IEE: wrightslaw.com/info/test.iee.index.htm\n• LDA: ldaamerica.org\n• NCLD: ncld.org\nTAX INFO:\n• IRS Publication 502 (medical expense deductions)\n• Consult tax professional experienced with disability deductions\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Private Providers\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance (limited)\nSchool district (IEE)\nIRS (tax deduction)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s52','journey-sld','step-52','SLD Step 5.2: Medical Evaluation for Co-occurring Conditions','SLD — Step 5.2: Medical Evaluation for Co-occurring Conditions\n\nWHAT TO DO: SCREEN FOR CO-OCCURRING CONDITIONS — THEY\'RE THE RULE, NOT EXCEPTION: (1) ADHD co-occurs with LD in 30-50% of cases — if your child has LD AND attention difficulties, pursue ADHD evaluation. ADHD medication may help but does NOT remediate the LD. (2) ANXIETY co-occurs frequently — LD causes school-related anxiety, test anxiety, social anxiety from embarrassment. (3) DEPRESSION: repeated academic failure affects self-esteem. Watch for avoidance, withdrawal, \'I\'m stupid\' statements. (4) If ADHD is confirmed: child may qualify for IEP under BOTH SLD and OHI (Other Health Impairment) categories, or receive dual 504 accommodations. (5) Speech-language disorders: check for underlying language issues contributing to reading difficulties.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Ask pediatrician: \'My child has a learning disability. I\'d like to screen for ADHD, anxiety, and depression as well. Can you administer Vanderbilt/SNAP-IV rating scales?\'\nSTEP 2: If ADHD confirmed: pursue ADHD-specific accommodations in addition to LD accommodations. See ADHD Journey Map for full guidance.\nSTEP 3: If anxiety/depression: request school counseling or ERMHS (Educationally Related Mental Health Services) through IEP.\nSTEP 4: If speech-language concerns: request SLP evaluation through school.\nSTEP 5: Update IEP to address ALL conditions — not just the LD.\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Primary screener for ADHD, anxiety, depression.\nCHILD PSYCHIATRIST: For medication evaluation if ADHD confirmed. Ask pediatrician for referral.\nSCHOOL COUNSELOR: For school-based mental health support.\nERMHS: Request through IEP for educationally-related mental health services.\nCHADD: chadd.org — ADHD resources if ADHD confirmed.\nADDITUDE: additudemag.com — LD + ADHD resources.\n\nDOCUMENTS: CO-OCCURRING CONDITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ADHD evaluation results (if applicable)\n• Vanderbilt/SNAP-IV rating scales\n• Psychiatric evaluation (if applicable)\n• Anxiety/depression screening results\n• ERMHS assessment (if requested)\n• Updated IEP with dual eligibility (SLD + OHI)\n• Medication management plan (if applicable)\n• SLP evaluation (if language concerns)\n\nTIMELINE: ADHD evaluation: 1-3 months. Psychiatric eval: 2-6 months wait. ERMHS: request through IEP, assessment within 60 days. Medication titration: 2-4 weeks.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Treat only LD while missing ADHD — medication + LD intervention together is more effective than either alone. (2) Dismiss anxiety as \'just nerves\' — it may require treatment. (3) Attribute ALL struggles to LD when ADHD is also present — both need separate interventions. (4) Skip speech-language screening — some reading difficulties have underlying language disorder roots. (5) Assume medication will fix reading — ADHD meds improve attention but don\'t teach reading skills.\n\nRISKS: ★ Co-occurring ADHD missed — child treated for LD only. Anxiety from LD not addressed. ADHD medication prescribed but LD intervention not started. ERMHS not offered. Dual eligibility (SLD + OHI) not pursued. Speech-language link to reading not evaluated.\n\nRESOURCES: CO-OCCURRING CONDITIONS:\n• CHADD: chadd.org — ADHD resources\n• ADDitude: additudemag.com — LD + ADHD articles\n• NAMI: nami.org — mental health support\n• Anxiety and Depression Association: adaa.org\n• ADHD Journey Map in this workbook — cross-reference\n• SLI Journey Map — if speech-language concerns\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician /\nPsychiatrist\nOTHER AGENCIES: Insurance\nSchool district\nSchool counselor\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s61','journey-sld','step-61','SLD Step 6.1: Annual IEP Review & Progress Monitoring','SLD — Step 6.1: Annual IEP Review & Progress Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: ACTIVELY MANAGE YOUR CHILD\'S IEP YEAR-ROUND: (1) Request and review quarterly progress reports. If goals show insufficient progress, request an IEP meeting to revise approach. (2) At annual IEP review: (a) Are goals advancing or repeating? (b) Is the intervention program working? (c) Is service frequency sufficient? (d) Are accommodations being implemented consistently? (e) Does AT need updating? (3) TRACK GRADES AND STANDARDIZED TEST SCORES — if your child isn\'t making expected progress with services, the IEP needs revision. (4) Visit the classroom — you have the right to observe. (5) Monitor service delivery — are the minutes on the IEP actually being provided? (6) Triennial re-evaluation every 3 years — generally DO NOT waive this.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Create an \'IEP Monitoring Calendar\': quarterly progress report review dates, annual IEP date, triennial date.\nSTEP 2: At each quarterly progress report, check: is your child on track to meet annual goals? If not, email: \'My child is not on track for [goal]. I\'d like to discuss revising the approach at an IEP meeting.\'\nSTEP 3: 30 days before annual IEP: write updated Parent Concerns Letter with current priorities.\nSTEP 4: At annual IEP: review each goal\'s progress, propose updated goals, review accommodations and services.\nSTEP 5: Every 3 years (triennial): participate actively in re-evaluation. Request it covers all areas. DO NOT waive.\nSTEP 6: If child is progressing well, maintain vigilance — academic demands INCREASE each year and LD may re-emerge at higher levels (e.g., reading comprehension issues in middle school, essay writing in high school).\n\nCONTACT: IEP CASE MANAGER: Your child\'s SpEd teacher — primary contact for progress and concerns.\nSCHOOL ADMINISTRATION: For systemic issues (services not delivered, teacher turnover).\nADVOCACY:\n• CASE: caseadvocacy.org\n• DRC: (800) 776-5746\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com\n• Understood: understood.org\nIF SERVICES NOT PROVIDED:\n• Document missing services\n• Request compensatory education\n• File CDE complaint if needed\n\nDOCUMENTS: ONGOING DOCUMENTS:\n• Quarterly progress reports (file chronologically)\n• Annual IEP (keep every version)\n• Report cards and standardized test results\n• Work samples (periodic — save 1/month)\n• Service delivery log (are minutes being provided?)\n• Communication log (all emails with school)\n• Triennial evaluation reports (every 3 years)\n• Updated Parent Concerns Letters (annual)\n\nCREATE A MASTER BINDER:\n• Section 1: Current IEP\n• Section 2: Evaluations\n• Section 3: Progress reports\n• Section 4: Correspondence\n• Section 5: Work samples\n• Section 6: Medical records\n\nTIMELINE: Annual IEP review: every 12 months. Progress reports: quarterly. Triennial re-evaluation: every 3 years. Parent can request IEP meeting at ANY time.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Skip the annual IEP meeting or go unprepared. (2) Accept the same goals carried over year after year without progress — this means the program isn\'t working. (3) Waive the triennial re-evaluation — updated data protects eligibility. (4) Let service minutes be reduced without data justification. (5) Assume services are being delivered as written — verify. (6) Accept premature exit from special education — LD doesn\'t \'go away.\'\n\nRISKS: ★ Goals repeated without progress — program isn\'t working but nobody changes approach. Services reduced without data. Teacher turnover disrupts continuity. Triennial waived — updated data lost. Premature exit from SpEd. Services not actually delivered as written (especially with substitutes). Parent doesn\'t prepare for annual review.\n\nRESOURCES: ONGOING ADVOCACY:\n• Wrightslaw: wrightslaw.com — ongoing IEP monitoring\n• Understood: understood.org — progress tracking\n• DRC: disabilityrightsca.org — rights guides\n• LDA: ldaamerica.org — parent resources\n• Decoding Dyslexia CA: decodingdyslexiaca.org\n• Parent support groups: LDA local chapters, Decoding Dyslexia chapters\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nSpEd teacher\nGen ed teacher\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-sld-s62','journey-sld','step-62','SLD Step 6.2: Transition Planning & College Preparation (Age 14+)','SLD — Step 6.2: Transition Planning & College Preparation (Age 14+)\n\nWHAT TO DO: PLAN FOR LIFE AFTER HIGH SCHOOL: (1) ITP (Individual Transition Plan) required in IEP by age 16 (start at 14). (2) KEY FOR LD: SAT/ACT ACCOMMODATIONS — apply 6+ months before test date through College Board SSD (collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities). Requires: current evaluation (within 3 years), documented history of accommodations USE, and specific disability documentation. (3) College disability services: student must self-identify and register with disability office BEFORE classes begin. IEP does NOT transfer to college — but 504 plan documentation does support accommodation requests. (4) Self-advocacy skills: teach your child to understand their LD, explain it to others, and request accommodations independently. (5) Career exploration: many successful adults have LD — focus on strengths. (6) DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation): may provide vocational support for significant LD. (7) CalABLE: available if LD is severe enough to substantially limit functioning.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 14-15: begin discussing transition goals at IEP meetings. Include self-advocacy goals.\nSTEP 2: By age 15-16: begin SAT/ACT accommodation application. Gather: current evaluation (within 3 years), 504/IEP history, documentation of accommodation use.\nSTEP 3: Apply for SAT/ACT accommodations through College Board SSD (collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities) or ACT (act.org/the-act/accommodations). Submit 6+ months before test.\nSTEP 4: Visit college disability offices during campus visits. Ask: \'What documentation do you require? What accommodations are typically provided for [LD type]?\'\nSTEP 5: Create a \'College Prep Packet\': all evaluations, IEP/504 history, accommodation documentation, physician letter.\nSTEP 6: Practice self-advocacy: role-play with your child: \'I have dyslexia. I learn best when I have extended time and text-to-speech. Can we discuss accommodations?\'\n\nCONTACT: SAT ACCOMMODATIONS:\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org/students-with-disabilities — (844) 255-7728\n• ACT accommodations: act.org/the-act/accommodations — (319) 337-1332\nCOLLEGE DISABILITY SERVICES:\n• AHEAD (Association on Higher Ed & Disability): ahead.org\n• Each college\'s disability office (find on college website)\nDOR:\n• CA DOR: dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation\n• DOR referral: request through IEP by age 16\nCALABLE: calable.ca.gov (if LD is significantly limiting)\nSELF-ADVOCACY:\n• Eye to Eye: eyetoeyenational.org — LD mentoring program\n• LD Online: ldonline.org\n• Understood: understood.org\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ITP (in IEP) with post-secondary goals\n• Transition assessments\n• SAT/ACT accommodation application\n• College disability documentation packet\n• Self-advocacy plan\n• DOR referral (if applicable)\n• Complete evaluation and accommodation history\n\nCOLLEGE PREP PACKET:\n• Most recent evaluation (within 3 years)\n• All IEP/504 plans (history of accommodations)\n• Documentation of accommodation USE\n• Physician/psychologist letter\n• Summary of Performance (SOP) from school\n\nTIMELINE: Transition plan: by age 16 (start at 14). SAT/ACT accommodations: apply 6+ months before test. College disability registration: before first semester. DOR referral: by age 16. Self-advocacy: ongoing from age 12+.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (1) Wait until senior year to request SAT/ACT accommodations — start in sophomore year. (2) Assume IEP transfers to college — it does NOT. Student must self-identify and request accommodations. (3) Skip teaching self-advocacy — this is the most important transition skill. (4) Stop IEP too early — keep through high school graduation if LD persists. (5) Forget to keep ALL evaluation and accommodation records — college will need them. (6) Overlook trade/vocational schools as excellent options — LD doesn\'t limit career success.\n\nRISKS: ★ SAT/ACT accommodations denied (requires current evaluation AND accommodation history). College disability office requires documentation student doesn\'t have. Student doesn\'t self-identify at college. Self-advocacy skills never taught. DOR services not explored. Transition plan is boilerplate. Student exits SpEd too early.\n\nRESOURCES: TRANSITION RESOURCES:\n• Wrightslaw transition: wrightslaw.com/info/trans.index.htm\n• Understood college prep: understood.org/en/articles/transition-planning\n• Eye to Eye: eyetoeyenational.org — LD mentoring\n• LD Online: ldonline.org\n• AHEAD: ahead.org — college disability resources\n• College Board SSD: collegeboard.org\n• Decoding Dyslexia: decodingdyslexiaca.org\nBOOKS:\n• \'The Dyslexia Empowerment Plan\' by Ben Foss\n• \'Fish in a Tree\' by Lynda Mullaly Hunt (for your child to read)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: DOR\nCollege Board/ACT\nCollege disability office\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-overview','journey-id','overview','ID Journey Map — Overview','INTELLECTUAL DISABILITY (ID) — Complete Family Navigation Journey (California)\n\n19 steps across 8 phases:\n* 1 Early Recognition: Parent/Provider Notices Developmental Delays, Referral to Regional Center (Self-Referral, Any Ag\n* 2 Evaluation & Diagnosis: Regional Center Comprehensive Evaluation, Understand ID Severity Levels & What They Mean, Process Diagnosis — Emotional Support & Next Steps\n* 3 Early Intervention (Birth-3): Early Start IFSP — ID-Specific Services, Transition from Early Start to School District + O\n* 4 School District IEP (Age 3+): School District Evaluation for ID Eligibility, IEP Development — ID-Specific Placement & Services, IEP Dispute Resolution — ID-Specific Issues\n* 5 Regional Center IPP & Services (Lifelong): IPP Development — ID-Specific Services, Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE\nCalABLE DET\n* 6 Therapy, Health & Daily Life: Coordinate Medical & Therapeutic Care, Build Adaptive Skills & Community Inclusion\n* 7 Transition Planning (Age 14+): Begin Transition Planning — ITP Required, Conservatorship / Alternatives at Age 18, Adult Services Planning (RC IPP, Employment, Housi\n* 8 Lifelong Support & Advocacy: Ongoing Benefits Management & Monitoring, Long-Term Advocacy & Community Engagement\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s11','journey-id','step-11','ID Step 1.1: Parent/Provider Notices Developmental Delays','ID — Step 1.1: Parent/Provider Notices Developmental Delays\n\nWHAT TO DO: Parent or pediatrician observes significant delays across multiple developmental domains: motor milestones delayed (sitting, walking, reaching), speech/language delayed (late babbling, no words by 18 months), difficulty with problem-solving and learning for age, social engagement differences, self-care skills delayed (feeding, dressing). Associated conditions often identified first: Down syndrome (at birth via genetic testing), Fragile X, cerebral palsy, fetal alcohol spectrum disorder. For milder ID, delays may not be apparent until preschool or school age when academic demands increase. Males more commonly diagnosed than females. Prevalence: 1-3% of population (~4.6-7.7M in U.S.).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Parent or pediatrician observes significant delays across multiple developmental domains: motor milestones delayed (sitting, walking, reaching), speech/language delayed (late babbling, no words by 18 months), difficulty with problem-solving and learning for age, social engagement differences, self-care skills delayed (feeding, dressing).\nSTEP 2: Associated conditions often identified first: Down syndrome (at birth via genetic testing), Fragile X, cerebral palsy, fetal alcohol spectrum disorder.\nSTEP 3: For milder ID, delays may not be apparent until preschool or school age when academic demands increase.\nSTEP 4: Males more commonly diagnosed than females.\nSTEP 5: Prevalence: 1-3% of population (~4.\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN: Request developmental screening at 9, 18, 30 months (ASQ-3). Raise concerns about cognitive, motor, and adaptive delays.\nREGIONAL CENTER: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — 21 RCs statewide. Self-referral accepted, no doctor referral needed. ID is a Lanterman Act qualifying condition.\nHELP ME GROW CA: helpmegrowca.org — call 211 for developmental screening and referral.\nFIRST 5 CALIFORNIA: ccfc.ca.gov — local First 5 county commissions fund early childhood development.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — Family Resource Centers provide peer support and information/referral.\nCDC MILESTONE TRACKER: cdc.gov/milestones — free app to track developmental milestones.\n\nDOCUMENTS: BEGIN COLLECTING:\n• Dated observations journal: note specific delays across domains — \'Oct 5: At age 2, not walking independently (expected by 12-15 months), 5 single words (expected 50+ words), doesn\'t point to request\'\n• Video recordings of child in natural settings (play, mealtimes, with peers)\n• CDC Milestone Tracker app results\n• Well-child visit notes mentioning concerns\n• Daycare/preschool teacher observations (request in writing)\n• Growth charts and medical records\n• Family history of developmental delays or ID (genetic component)\n\nNO DOCUMENTS NEEDED TO SELF-REFER TO RC — just call.\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — more severe ID identified earlier (birth-2). Milder ID may not be identified until school age.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: For milder ID, delays may not be apparent until preschool or school age when academic demands increase\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Milder ID missed because child is \'just a little behind.\' Pediatrician uses \'wait and see\' during critical early intervention window. Associated conditions (Down syndrome, CP) diagnosed but ID not formally assessed as separate condition. Cultural factors affect when families seek evaluation. Grief and denial delay parent action after initial concerns.\n\nRISKS: ★ Milder ID missed because child is \'just a little behind.\' Pediatrician uses \'wait and see\' during critical early intervention window. Associated conditions (Down syndrome, CP) diagnosed but ID not formally assessed as separate condition. Cultural factors affect when families seek evaluation. Grief and denial delay parent action after initial concerns.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: None (Parent/Pediatrician)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician\nGenetic counselor\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s12','journey-id','step-12','ID Step 1.2: Referral to Regional Center (Self-Referral, Any Age)','ID — Step 1.2: Referral to Regional Center (Self-Referral, Any Age)\n\nWHAT TO DO: California Regional Centers are the PRIMARY service system for intellectual disability. ID is one of the 5 qualifying Lanterman Act conditions (ID, cerebral palsy, epilepsy, autism, 5th category). Self-referral accepted at any age — no doctor referral required. For children under 3: Regional Center provides Early Start (Part C) services. For children 3+: Regional Center provides ongoing service coordination AND school district provides IEP. KEY: ID qualifies for BOTH Regional Center services AND school district special education — DUAL SYSTEM. This is different from SLD/ADHD which are school-district only.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: California Regional Centers are the PRIMARY service system for intellectual disability.\nSTEP 2: ID is one of the 5 qualifying Lanterman Act conditions (ID, cerebral palsy, epilepsy, autism, 5th category).\nSTEP 3: Self-referral accepted at any age — no doctor referral required.\nSTEP 4: For children under 3: Regional Center provides Early Start (Part C) services.\nSTEP 5: For children 3+: Regional Center provides ongoing service coordination AND school district provides IEP.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR LOCAL REGIONAL CENTER: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — call intake line. Say: \'I\'d like to refer my child for a developmental evaluation. I have concerns about [cognitive development/adaptive skills/learning].\'\nCA DDS (Dept of Developmental Services): dds.ca.gov — oversees all 21 Regional Centers.\nDRC (Disability Rights California): (800) 776-5746 — if RC delays intake beyond 15 working days.\nOCRA (Office of Clients\' Rights Advocacy): (800) 390-7032 — free advocacy for RC intake issues.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support during the referral process.\nUNDIVIDED: undivided.io — free family navigator service to help with RC referral.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TO BRING TO RC INTAKE:\n• Child\'s birth certificate (copy)\n• Proof of CA residency (utility bill, lease)\n• Medi-Cal card or insurance card\n• Medical records (if available, NOT required)\n• Your observations journal and videos\n• Any prior evaluations or medical reports\n\nRC WILL PROVIDE:\n• Referral acknowledgment letter\n• Rights booklet (Lanterman Act rights — in your language)\n• Consent for evaluation forms\n• Service coordinator assignment\n• Intake assessment form\n\nPARENT TRACKS:\n• Date of referral (starts 15-working-day intake clock)\n• Service coordinator name and direct contact\n• 120-day evaluation completion deadline\n\nTIMELINE: RC must complete intake within 15 working days of referral.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Family doesn\'t know about Regional Center. Family referred only to school district — misses RC services. Language barriers prevent self-referral. RC intake delayed. Family told child is \'too young\' or \'not delayed enough\' for referral.\n\nRISKS: Family doesn\'t know about Regional Center. Family referred only to school district — misses RC services. Language barriers prevent self-referral. RC intake delayed. Family told child is \'too young\' or \'not delayed enough\' for referral.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Pediatrician (optional referral)\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s21','journey-id','step-21','ID Step 2.1: Regional Center Comprehensive Evaluation','ID — Step 2.1: Regional Center Comprehensive Evaluation\n\nWHAT TO DO: RC conducts multidisciplinary evaluation: (1) Cognitive/IQ testing — standardized tests (WISC-V, Stanford-Binet 5, Bayley for infants). IQ ≤70 generally indicates ID (with 5-point measurement error allowing 70-75 range). (2) Adaptive behavior assessment — Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales (VABS-3) or ABAS-3, measuring conceptual (language, reading, math), social (interpersonal, responsibility), and practical (self-care, daily living) skills. (3) Developmental history. (4) Medical evaluation. DSM-5 criteria: (A) Deficits in intellectual functions, (B) Deficits in adaptive functioning, (C) Onset during developmental period. DSM-5 severity levels based on ADAPTIVE functioning (not IQ): Mild, Moderate, Severe, Profound.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: RC conducts multidisciplinary evaluation: (1) Cognitive/IQ testing — standardized tests (WISC-V, Stanford-Binet 5, Bayley for infants).\nSTEP 2: IQ ≤70 generally indicates ID (with 5-point measurement error allowing 70-75 range).\nSTEP 3: (2) Adaptive behavior assessment — Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales (VABS-3) or ABAS-3, measuring conceptual (language, reading, math), social (interpersonal, responsibility), and practical (self-care, daily living) skills.\nSTEP 4: (3) Developmental history.\nSTEP 5: (4) Medical evaluation.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Assigned after intake — get name, direct phone, and email.\nRC PSYCHOLOGIST: Conducts cognitive and adaptive behavior assessment.\n★ LARRY P. COMPLIANCE: For African American/Black students — IQ tests CANNOT be used to identify or place in ID category in CA. RC must use alternative assessments. Contact DRC: (800) 776-5746 if IQ testing is proposed.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — evaluation rights, Larry P. compliance.\nOCRA: (800) 390-7032 — if evaluation exceeds 120-day timeline.\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: (916) 703-0280 — comprehensive neurodevelopmental evaluations, accepts Medi-Cal.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EVALUATION COMPONENTS FOR ID:\n• Cognitive/IQ assessment (WISC-V, SB-5, Bayley-4) — NOTE: Larry P. prohibits IQ tests for Black students\n• Adaptive behavior assessment (Vineland-3, ABAS-3) — THIS determines severity level, not IQ\n• Developmental history\n• Medical/genetic evaluation if indicated\n• Speech-language evaluation\n• Motor/OT evaluation\n• Behavioral assessment\n\nRC WILL PRODUCE:\n• Comprehensive evaluation report\n• Eligibility determination letter\n• If eligible: IPP development meeting scheduled\n• If denied: Prior Written Notice with appeal rights\n\nPARENT KEEPS:\n• ALL evaluation reports (request copies)\n• Eligibility determination letter\n• Calendar with 120-day deadline marked\n\nTIMELINE: 120 days from referral to eligibility determination.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: DSM-5 severity levels based on ADAPTIVE functioning (not IQ): Mild, Moderate, Severe, Profound\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: EVALUATION ISSUES: Larry P. v. Riles ruling — in California, standardized IQ tests CANNOT be used to identify or place Black students in ID category. School districts must use alternative assessments for Black students. Culturally/linguistically biased testing may overidentify minority children or underidentify those from non-dominant cultures. IQ score near cutoff (70-75) creates eligibility disputes. Adaptive behavior not assessed comprehensively — only parent report collected, not teacher/clinician observation. Child performs better on structured testing than in daily life (or vice versa).\n\nRISKS: ★ EVALUATION ISSUES: Larry P. v. Riles ruling — in California, standardized IQ tests CANNOT be used to identify or place Black students in ID category. School districts must use alternative assessments for Black students. Culturally/linguistically biased testing may overidentify minority children or underidentify those from non-dominant cultures. IQ score near cutoff (70-75) creates eligibility disputes. Adaptive behavior not assessed comprehensively — only parent report collected, not teacher/clinician observation. Child performs better on structured testing than in daily life (or vice versa).\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Psychologist\nPediatrician\nSLP\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s22','journey-id','step-22','ID Step 2.2: Understand ID Severity Levels & What They Mean','ID — Step 2.2: Understand ID Severity Levels & What They Mean\n\nWHAT TO DO: DSM-5 severity is based on ADAPTIVE FUNCTIONING (not IQ scores alone): MILD (IQ ~50-70, ~85% of ID population): can develop academic skills to ~6th grade level, live independently with support, competitive employment possible with accommodations. MODERATE (IQ ~35-49, ~10%): academic skills to ~2nd grade, semi-independent living with moderate support, supported employment. SEVERE (IQ ~20-34, ~3-4%): limited communication, significant daily support needed, may learn sight words and basic self-care. PROFOUND (IQ <20, ~1-2%): requires 24-hour support, very limited communication, may use AAC. KEY: ID is LIFELONG but with appropriate supports, functioning improves throughout life.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: DSM-5 severity is based on ADAPTIVE FUNCTIONING (not IQ scores alone): MILD (IQ ~50-70, ~85% of ID population): can develop academic skills to ~6th grade level, live independently with support, competitive employment possible with accommodations.\nSTEP 2: MODERATE (IQ ~35-49, ~10%): academic skills to ~2nd grade, semi-independent living with moderate support, supported employment.\nSTEP 3: SEVERE (IQ ~20-34, ~3-4%): limited communication, significant daily support needed, may learn sight words and basic self-care.\nSTEP 4: PROFOUND (IQ <20, ~1-2%): requires 24-hour support, very limited communication, may use AAC.\nSTEP 5: KEY: ID is LIFELONG but with appropriate supports, functioning improves throughout life.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Explain severity determination and what it means for services.\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE FAMILY NAVIGATOR: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer support, monthly virtual groups, parent coaching after ID diagnosis.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support from families with similar experiences.\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — largest national IDD advocacy org, 600+ local chapters. Find your local chapter.\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS (PHP): php.com — (408) 727-5775 — one-on-one consultations, support groups.\nNDSS (National Down Syndrome Society): ndss.org — (800) 221-4602 — if Down syndrome is the cause.\nAAIDD (American Association on Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities): aaidd.org — professional resources on ID.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EVALUATION REPORT SHOULD INCLUDE:\n• DSM-5 severity level: Mild (85%), Moderate (10%), Severe (3-4%), Profound (1-2%)\n• Based on ADAPTIVE FUNCTIONING (not IQ): conceptual, social, practical domains\n• Vineland-3 or ABAS-3 scores with domain breakdowns\n• Cognitive assessment scores (with Larry P. caveat for Black students)\n• Functional impact across settings (home, school, community)\n• Prognosis and support needs\n• Recommendations for services\n\nPARENT SHOULD HAVE:\n• Copy of complete evaluation report\n• Written summary of severity level and what it means for daily life\n• List of recommended services\n• Questions for follow-up with RC service coordinator\n\nTIMELINE: At evaluation completion.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: DSM-5 severity is based on ADAPTIVE FUNCTIONING (not IQ scores alone): MILD (IQ ~50-70, ~85% of ID population): can develop academic skills to ~6th grade level, live independently with support, competitive employment possible with accommodations\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Severity level misunderstood as \'ceiling\' for growth. Parents given prognosis without hope. Medical model focuses on deficits rather than strengths and support needs. Severity level drives expectations rather than individualized assessment. Older terminology (mental retardation, EMR/TMR) still used by some professionals — stigmatizing.\n\nRISKS: Severity level misunderstood as \'ceiling\' for growth. Parents given prognosis without hope. Medical model focuses on deficits rather than strengths and support needs. Severity level drives expectations rather than individualized assessment. Older terminology (mental retardation, EMR/TMR) still used by some professionals — stigmatizing.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Diagnosing Provider /\nRegional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nMedical team\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s23','journey-id','step-23','ID Step 2.3: Process Diagnosis — Emotional Support & Next Steps','ID — Step 2.3: Process Diagnosis — Emotional Support & Next Steps\n\nWHAT TO DO: ID diagnosis often triggers profound grief, fear, and uncertainty for families. Key support: (1) Connect with peer families — Family Resource Centers (FRCNCA), UC Davis MIND Institute Family Navigator, Parents Helping Parents (PHP). (2) Understand that diagnosis opens doors to services and supports. (3) Begin learning about dual system (RC + school). (4) Join parent support groups (online and in-person). (5) Learn about person-first language and strengths-based approach. (6) Connect with The Arc (national) and local Arc chapters. Programs: UC Davis MIND Institute — peer support, monthly virtual groups, parent coaching, Padres Para Padres (Spanish). FRCNCA — statewide network of family resource centers.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: ID diagnosis often triggers profound grief, fear, and uncertainty for families.\nSTEP 2: Key support: (1) Connect with peer families — Family Resource Centers (FRCNCA), UC Davis MIND Institute Family Navigator, Parents Helping Parents (PHP).\nSTEP 3: (2) Understand that diagnosis opens doors to services and supports.\nSTEP 4: (3) Begin learning about dual system (RC + school).\nSTEP 5: (4) Join parent support groups (online and in-person).\n\nCONTACT: UC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE FAMILY NAVIGATOR: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer support after diagnosis, monthly virtual groups, Padres Para Padres (Spanish-language), caregiver communities.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — parent-to-parent support, local Family Resource Centers throughout CA.\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS (PHP): php.com — (408) 727-5775 — one-on-one consultations, support groups, webinars.\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — local chapters provide peer support and advocacy.\nUCP (United Cerebral Palsy): ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community, support for multi-disability families.\nNAMI CALIFORNIA: namica.org — family support groups for parents navigating disability diagnosis.\nYOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Connect to vendored family support services.\n\nDOCUMENTS: EMOTIONAL SUPPORT DOCUMENTS:\n• List of peer support resources provided by RC or FRCNCA\n• UC Davis MIND Institute Family Navigator program enrollment\n• PHP consultation records\n• Local Arc chapter information\n• Support group schedule and contacts\n\nNEXT STEPS DOCUMENTS:\n• RC eligibility determination letter\n• IPP meeting scheduling confirmation\n• Service coordinator contact information\n• Your priorities list for IPP development\n• Questions to bring to IPP meeting\n• School district evaluation request (if age 3+)\n\nTIMELINE: Immediately upon diagnosis — don\'t delay connection to support.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Family isolated — no peer connection. Cultural stigma prevents seeking support. Non-English-speaking families lack accessible resources. Medical professionals deliver diagnosis without connecting to support. Parents given only medical/clinical framing without strengths/community perspective.\n\nRISKS: Family isolated — no peer connection. Cultural stigma prevents seeking support. Non-English-speaking families lack accessible resources. Medical professionals deliver diagnosis without connecting to support. Parents given only medical/clinical framing without strengths/community perspective.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Family Resource Centers\nUC Davis MIND Institute\nParents Helping Parents\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nThe Arc\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s31','journey-id','step-31','ID Step 3.1: Early Start IFSP — ID-Specific Services','ID — Step 3.1: Early Start IFSP — ID-Specific Services\n\nWHAT TO DO: For children under 3 with ID: Regional Center Early Start provides family-centered intervention. IFSP services typically include: speech-language therapy, occupational therapy, physical therapy (especially for motor delays), developmental specialist, parent training/coaching, behavioral support if needed, assistive technology/AAC. Services in natural environments (home, daycare). For ID with known etiology (Down syndrome, genetic conditions): medical management and monitoring also critical. Frequency should match severity — more severe ID needs more intensive early intervention. Hanen \'More Than Words\' program often used for children with limited communication.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: For children under 3 with ID: Regional Center Early Start provides family-centered intervention.\nSTEP 2: IFSP services typically include: speech-language therapy, occupational therapy, physical therapy (especially for motor delays), developmental specialist, parent training/coaching, behavioral support if needed, assistive technology/AAC.\nSTEP 3: Services in natural environments (home, daycare).\nSTEP 4: For ID with known etiology (Down syndrome, genetic conditions): medical management and monitoring also critical.\nSTEP 5: Frequency should match severity — more severe ID needs more intensive early intervention.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR REGIONAL CENTER: dds.ca.gov/rc/listing — Early Start intake for ages 0-3.\nCA DDS EARLY START: dds.ca.gov/services/early-start — program information.\nRC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Primary contact for IFSP development and service authorization.\nVENDORED PROVIDERS: RC authorizes early intervention providers — SLP, OT, PT, developmental specialist, parent training.\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support during Early Start.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — if services are delayed or inadequate.\nOCRA: (800) 390-7032 — free advocacy for IFSP disputes.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IFSP DOCUMENTS:\n• IFSP document (Individualized Family Service Plan)\n• Service authorizations for each provider (SLP, OT, PT, developmental specialist, parent training)\n• Provider contact information for all services\n• Service schedule (days, times, locations)\n• IFSP goals with measurable outcomes\n• 6-month review schedule\n• Annual IFSP re-evaluation plan\n\nPARENT CREATES:\n• Service tracking log (dates, attendance, notes from each session)\n• Progress observations journal\n• Questions for next IFSP review\n• Video recordings showing progress\n\nTIMELINE: 45 days from referral to IFSP. Services begin immediately after IFSP.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Service intensity insufficient for child\'s needs. Therapy focused on deficit remediation rather than functional participation. Parent coaching not provided — parent becomes passive observer of therapy. Transition to school at age 3 not planned early enough. Medical management not coordinated with developmental services.\n\nRISKS: Service intensity insufficient for child\'s needs. Therapy focused on deficit remediation rather than functional participation. Parent coaching not provided — parent becomes passive observer of therapy. Transition to school at age 3 not planned early enough. Medical management not coordinated with developmental services.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\n(Early Start)\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nOT\nPT\nDev Specialist\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s32','journey-id','step-32','ID Step 3.2: Transition from Early Start to School District + Ongoing RC (Age 3)','ID — Step 3.2: Transition from Early Start to School District + Ongoing RC (Age 3)\n\nWHAT TO DO: At age 3, DUAL SYSTEM begins: child transitions to school district IEP AND continues Regional Center services. This is DIFFERENT from autism (where some children exit RC if mild) — ID almost always continues with RC. School district evaluation and IEP must be in place by 3rd birthday. RC continues IPP (Individual Program Plan) with different but complementary services. Key: school provides EDUCATIONAL services (classroom instruction, school-based therapies). RC provides COMMUNITY/HOME services (respite, after-school programs, parent training, behavioral support, community inclusion). Parent must coordinate between two systems.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 3, DUAL SYSTEM begins: child transitions to school district IEP AND continues Regional Center services.\nSTEP 2: This is DIFFERENT from autism (where some children exit RC if mild) — ID almost always continues with RC.\nSTEP 3: School district evaluation and IEP must be in place by 3rd birthday.\nSTEP 4: RC continues IPP (Individual Program Plan) with different but complementary services.\nSTEP 5: Key: school provides EDUCATIONAL services (classroom instruction, school-based therapies).\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: ID = \'intellectual disability\' under IDEA — 34 CFR §300.8(c)(6)\nIMPORTANT CA LAW: Larry P. v. Riles — IQ tests CANNOT be used to place Black students in ID category\nCA DEPT OF EDUCATION: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — free legal advocacy (priority for ID families)\nSERR MANUAL: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — comprehensive rights guide\n\nDOCUMENTS: Transition meeting (RC + school district). School evaluation consent. IFSP records. RC IPP continuation.\n\nTIMELINE: Transition conference: 90+ days before 3rd birthday. IEP in place by 3rd birthday.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: DUAL SYSTEM CONFUSION: Parents don\'t understand RC continues after school starts — they think school \'replaces\' RC. Services duplicated or gaps where each system thinks the other covers it. RC service coordinator and school case manager don\'t communicate. IPP goals and IEP goals not aligned. School provides less therapy than Early Start — parents feel \'cliff.\'\n\nRISKS: ★ DUAL SYSTEM CONFUSION: Parents don\'t understand RC continues after school starts — they think school \'replaces\' RC. Services duplicated or gaps where each system thinks the other covers it. RC service coordinator and school case manager don\'t communicate. IPP goals and IEP goals not aligned. School provides less therapy than Early Start — parents feel \'cliff.\'\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center →\nSchool District + RC\nOTHER AGENCIES: SLP\nOT\nPT\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s41','journey-id','step-41','ID Step 4.1: School District Evaluation for ID Eligibility','ID — Step 4.1: School District Evaluation for ID Eligibility\n\nWHAT TO DO: Under IDEA, ID is defined as \'significantly subaverage general intellectual functioning, existing concurrently with deficits in adaptive behavior and manifested during the developmental period that adversely affects a child\'s educational performance\' (34 CFR §300.8(c)(6)). California Code of Regulations (5 CCR §3030). School evaluation includes: IQ testing, adaptive behavior assessment, academic achievement testing, speech/language evaluation, motor assessment, social-emotional assessment, observation. CALIFORNIA-SPECIFIC: Larry P. v. Riles (1979/1986) — IQ tests CANNOT be used to place Black students in ID category or substantially equivalent placements. Alternative assessments required.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Under IDEA, ID is defined as \'significantly subaverage general intellectual functioning, existing concurrently with deficits in adaptive behavior and manifested during the developmental period that adversely affects a child\'s educational performance\' (34 CFR §300.\nSTEP 2: California Code of Regulations (5 CCR §3030).\nSTEP 3: School evaluation includes: IQ testing, adaptive behavior assessment, academic achievement testing, speech/language evaluation, motor assessment, social-emotional assessment, observation.\nSTEP 4: CALIFORNIA-SPECIFIC: Larry P.\nSTEP 5: Riles (1979/1986) — IQ tests CANNOT be used to place Black students in ID category or substantially equivalent placements.\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL DISTRICT SPECIAL EDUCATION: Submit written evaluation request to SpEd Director.\n★ LARRY P. COMPLIANCE: For Black students — school district CANNOT use IQ tests to identify or place in ID category. Must use alternative assessments. This is CA-specific law (Larry P. v. Riles, 1979/1986).\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — free IEP advocacy.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — Larry P. compliance, evaluation rights.\nCDE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file if district uses prohibited testing.\nOAH: (916) 263-0880 — mediation/due process for evaluation disputes.\n\nDOCUMENTS: PARENT CREATES:\n• Written evaluation request letter (hand-deliver AND email, keep date-stamped copy)\n• Parent Input Form (detailed — describe cognitive, adaptive, academic functioning)\n• Larry P. compliance note if child is Black/African American\n\nDISTRICT PROVIDES:\n• Assessment plan within 15 calendar days\n• Evaluation report: cognitive assessment (alternative for Black students), adaptive behavior, academic achievement, related assessments\n• Eligibility determination under IDEA 34 CFR §300.8(c)(6)\n• Parent rights notification\n\nSHARE WITH SCHOOL:\n• All RC evaluation reports\n• RC IPP (shows services already in place)\n• Medical records and genetic testing results\n• Your observations journal and videos\n\nTIMELINE: 15 days to present assessment plan. 60 days from consent to completed evaluation.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Riles (1979/1986) — IQ tests CANNOT be used to place Black students in ID category or substantially equivalent placements\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Larry P. COMPLIANCE: School district uses IQ test for Black student — ILLEGAL in California for ID placement. Alternative assessments for Black students may be less well-standardized. Adaptive behavior assessment incomplete. Child tested in non-native language. Evaluation focuses on deficits only — no strengths documented. Mild ID may not be identified if child compensates well in structured testing.\n\nRISKS: ★ Larry P. COMPLIANCE: School district uses IQ test for Black student — ILLEGAL in California for ID placement. Alternative assessments for Black students may be less well-standardized. Adaptive behavior assessment incomplete. Child tested in non-native language. Evaluation focuses on deficits only — no strengths documented. Mild ID may not be identified if child compensates well in structured testing.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\n(School Psychologist)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nRegional Center\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s42','journey-id','step-42','ID Step 4.2: IEP Development — ID-Specific Placement & Services','ID — Step 4.2: IEP Development — ID-Specific Placement & Services\n\nWHAT TO DO: IEP for ID must address: (1) PLACEMENT on the continuum — from general education with supports (LRE principle) through resource specialist, special day class (SDC), to separate school. LRE = Least Restrictive Environment. Child must be educated with non-disabled peers to maximum extent appropriate. (2) SERVICES: specialized academic instruction (modified curriculum), speech-language therapy, OT, PT, behavioral support, adaptive PE, assistive technology/AAC, 1:1 aide if needed. (3) GOALS: functional academics, communication, self-care/adaptive skills, social skills, community skills, pre-vocational skills. (4) MODIFICATIONS (not just accommodations): modified curriculum, alternative assessments (California Alternate Assessment for state testing). Extended School Year (ESY) — many students with ID qualify because of regression risk.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: IEP for ID must address: (1) PLACEMENT on the continuum — from general education with supports (LRE principle) through resource specialist, special day class (SDC), to separate school.\nSTEP 2: LRE = Least Restrictive Environment.\nSTEP 3: Child must be educated with non-disabled peers to maximum extent appropriate.\nSTEP 4: (2) SERVICES: specialized academic instruction (modified curriculum), speech-language therapy, OT, PT, behavioral support, adaptive PE, assistive technology/AAC, 1:1 aide if needed.\nSTEP 5: (3) GOALS: functional academics, communication, self-care/adaptive skills, social skills, community skills, pre-vocational skills.\n\nCONTACT: IEP TEAM: You, SpEd teacher, gen ed teacher, school psychologist, administrator, related services (SLP, OT, PT as applicable).\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — free IEP advocacy.\nINCLUSION ADVOCATES:\n• TASH: tash.org — inclusion advocacy, research, policy\n• Inclusion Collaborative (Santa Clara Co): inclusion.scusd.edu\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — LRE (Least Restrictive Environment) advocacy. IDEA\'s strong preference for education with non-disabled peers.\nTASK: taskca.org — parent training on IEP development.\nSERR MANUAL: serr.disabilityrightsca.org — comprehensive rights reference.\nCDE ALTERNATE ASSESSMENT: caaspp.cde.ca.gov — California Alternate Assessment info for students with significant cognitive disabilities.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IEP DOCUMENT FOR ID MUST INCLUDE:\n• PLAAFP across all domains (academic, functional, communication, motor, social)\n• Annual goals: academic AND functional/adaptive\n• SDI (Specially Designed Instruction) with methodology\n• Related services: SLP, OT, PT, behavioral, adapted PE\n• Accommodations and modifications\n• ★ LRE (Least Restrictive Environment): IDEA\'s strong preference for inclusion with non-disabled peers\n• ESY (Extended School Year): ID students often qualify due to regression risk\n• CA Alternate Assessment participation (if significant cognitive disability)\n• AT consideration\n• Transition plan (by age 16)\n\nPARENT BRINGS:\n• RC evaluation reports and IPP\n• Parent Concerns Letter\n• Inclusion research and advocacy resources\n• Private evaluation (if obtained)\n• Work samples and progress\n\nTIMELINE: 30 days from completed evaluation to IEP meeting.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: (4) MODIFICATIONS (not just accommodations): modified curriculum, alternative assessments (California Alternate Assessment for state testing)\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: PLACEMENT BATTLES: Child automatically placed in most restrictive setting (separate school) without considering LRE. \'Modified curriculum\' used to justify segregated placement. General education teachers untrained for inclusive practices. District claims inclusion is \'too expensive.\' Parents not informed of full placement continuum. IDEA\'s strong preference for inclusion not honored. Paraprofessional support used as substitute for qualified teacher instruction. ESY denied despite regression evidence.\n\nRISKS: ★ PLACEMENT BATTLES: Child automatically placed in most restrictive setting (separate school) without considering LRE. \'Modified curriculum\' used to justify segregated placement. General education teachers untrained for inclusive practices. District claims inclusion is \'too expensive.\' Parents not informed of full placement continuum. IDEA\'s strong preference for inclusion not honored. Paraprofessional support used as substitute for qualified teacher instruction. ESY denied despite regression evidence.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Local School District\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nParent\nAdvocate\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s43','journey-id','step-43','ID Step 4.3: IEP Dispute Resolution — ID-Specific Issues','ID — Step 4.3: IEP Dispute Resolution — ID-Specific Issues\n\nWHAT TO DO: Common ID-specific disputes: (1) Overly restrictive placement. (2) Failure to provide inclusion supports. (3) Inadequate behavioral support. (4) ESY denied. (5) Transition services inadequate. (6) Larry P. violations. Remedies: IEP meeting request → CDE state complaint (60 days) → mediation → due process (45 days). Disability Rights California (DRC) provides free advocacy for ID families. The Arc provides advocacy resources and local chapter support. Key: ID families more frequently face placement disputes than families of children with ADHD or SLD.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Common ID-specific disputes: (1) Overly restrictive placement.\nSTEP 2: (2) Failure to provide inclusion supports.\nSTEP 3: (3) Inadequate behavioral support.\nSTEP 4: (5) Transition services inadequate.\nSTEP 5: Remedies: IEP meeting request → CDE state complaint (60 days) → mediation → due process (45 days).\n\nCONTACT: DRC (Disability Rights California): (800) 776-5746 — free legal advocacy for SpEd disputes.\nCDE COMPLAINT: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp — file compliance complaint (free, 60-day resolution).\nOAH (Office of Administrative Hearings): (916) 263-0880 — mediation (free, voluntary) and due process hearing.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — free advocacy support.\nDREDF: dredf.org — Disability Rights Education & Defense Fund, Berkeley-based.\nOCRA: (800) 390-7032 — if dispute involves both RC and school.\n2-YEAR STATUTE OF LIMITATIONS: File within 2 years of the action you\'re disputing.\n\nDOCUMENTS: DISPUTE DOCUMENTS:\n• Written record of disagreement with district decision\n• Prior Written Notice from district (they must provide when refusing parent request)\n• CDE Compliance Complaint form: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/cmplntproc.asp\n• Mediation request through OAH: oah.ca.gov\n• Due process complaint (if needed): oah.ca.gov\n\nCOMMON ID-SPECIFIC DISPUTES:\n• Segregated placement vs inclusion — document LRE research\n• Larry P. violation — document prohibited IQ testing\n• ESY denial — document regression evidence\n• Insufficient related services — document needs\n\nKEEP:\n• All correspondence with district\n• Timeline of dispute\n• 2-YEAR statute of limitations — file within 2 years\n\nTIMELINE: CDE complaint: 60 days. Due process: 45 days.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Family doesn\'t know about DRC free services. Attorney fees prohibitive. District \'stays put\' in segregated placement during dispute. Family intimidated by process. Non-English-speaking families face additional barriers. Larry P. violations not reported.\n\nRISKS: Family doesn\'t know about DRC free services. Attorney fees prohibitive. District \'stays put\' in segregated placement during dispute. Family intimidated by process. Non-English-speaking families face additional barriers. Larry P. violations not reported.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District / CDE / OAH\nOTHER AGENCIES: DRC\nThe Arc\nSpecial Ed Attorney\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s51','journey-id','step-51','ID Step 5.1: IPP Development — ID-Specific Services','ID — Step 5.1: IPP Development — ID-Specific Services\n\nWHAT TO DO: Regional Center IPP (Individual Program Plan) is the LIFELONG service plan for individuals with ID. IPP services may include: respite care (relief for families), behavioral support services, day programs/after-school programs, social/recreational activities, community integration support, independent living skills training, supported employment, residential services (as adult), transportation, assistive technology, parent training, crisis intervention. IPP is reviewed at least annually. Services are individualized — no \'menu\' of standard services. POS (Purchase of Service) codes fund specific services. Family must actively participate in IPP development. CA DDS budget: $18.7B (FY 2025-26, largest in history).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Regional Center IPP (Individual Program Plan) is the LIFELONG service plan for individuals with ID.\nSTEP 2: IPP services may include: respite care (relief for families), behavioral support services, day programs/after-school programs, social/recreational activities, community integration support, independent living skills training, supported employment, residential services (as adult), transportation, assistive technology, parent training, crisis intervention.\nSTEP 3: IPP is reviewed at least annually.\nSTEP 4: Services are individualized — no \'menu\' of standard services.\nSTEP 5: POS (Purchase of Service) codes fund specific services.\n\nCONTACT: YOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Primary contact for IPP development. IPP is LIFELONG service plan — reviewed annually.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — IPP rights, service denial appeals.\nOCRA: (800) 390-7032 — free advocacy for IPP disputes.\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — local chapter can help families understand service options.\nCA DDS SELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: dds.ca.gov/initiatives/sdp — participant-directed budget option. Available statewide.\n★ POS (Purchase of Services) SPENDING DATA: Check your RC\'s POS data at dds.ca.gov/rc/purchase-of-service-data — document disparities if services seem insufficient.\nDDS OMBUDSMAN: (877) 658-9731 — if RC is unresponsive.\n\nDOCUMENTS: IPP DOCUMENT INCLUDES:\n• Life goals across all domains: health, safety, education, employment, recreation, social, residential\n• Specific services authorized: respite, behavioral support, day program, transportation, specialized equipment, home modifications\n• Service frequency and provider information\n• Annual review date\n• Emergency contact plan\n\nPARENT BRINGS TO IPP:\n• Your priorities list for each life domain\n• Current IEP (to coordinate school + RC goals)\n• Medical records and provider list\n• Daily routine and support needs assessment\n\n★ POS EQUITY CHECK:\n• Check your RC\'s POS spending data: dds.ca.gov/rc/purchase-of-service-data\n• Compare your family\'s services to RC averages\n• Document any spending disparities for advocacy\n\nTIMELINE: IPP within 60 days of eligibility. Annual review required.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: RC SERVICE GAPS: Service coordinator caseload too high (100+ clients) — limited advocacy capacity. POS spending disparities by race/ethnicity well-documented. Services denied as \'not necessary\' without adequate justification. Family not informed of available services. Generic IPP not individualized to child\'s needs. Wait lists for behavioral support, respite, SLS. RC says \'school is responsible\' for things RC should provide (and vice versa).\n\nRISKS: ★ RC SERVICE GAPS: Service coordinator caseload too high (100+ clients) — limited advocacy capacity. POS spending disparities by race/ethnicity well-documented. Services denied as \'not necessary\' without adequate justification. Family not informed of available services. Generic IPP not individualized to child\'s needs. Wait lists for behavioral support, respite, SLS. RC says \'school is responsible\' for things RC should provide (and vice versa).\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\n(Service Coordinator)\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nService providers\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s52','journey-id','step-52','ID Step 5.2: Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.','ID — Step 5.2: Apply for Medi-Cal, SSI, IHSS, CalABLE\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n\nWHAT TO DO: BENEFITS PACKAGE for ID: (1) MEDI-CAL: HCBS waiver, 45-day determination, covers medical + therapy. ID with RC eligibility = automatic Medi-Cal eligibility in many cases. (2) SSI: Supplemental Security Income for children with disabilities. ID is one of the highest-approval-rate conditions for SSI. Function report critical — describe daily challenges in detail. (3) IHSS: In-Home Supportive Services — personal care, domestic services, protective supervision. Many children with moderate-severe ID qualify for protective supervision. (4) CalABLE: No minimum age. $19K/year tax-advantaged savings. SSI $100K threshold. For ID, CalABLE is essential for long-term financial planning since ID is lifelong.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: BENEFITS PACKAGE for ID: (1) MEDI-CAL: HCBS waiver, 45-day determination, covers medical + therapy.\nSTEP 2: ID with RC eligibility = automatic Medi-Cal eligibility in many cases.\nSTEP 3: (2) SSI: Supplemental Security Income for children with disabilities.\nSTEP 4: ID is one of the highest-approval-rate conditions for SSI.\nSTEP 5: Function report critical — describe daily challenges in detail.\n\nCONTACT: SSA (Social Security Administration): ssa.gov — (800) 772-1213 — SSI application. ID has high approval rate.\nMEDI-CAL: Contact your county human services agency or apply at coveredca.com. HCBS waiver through RC.\nIHSS: Contact your county IHSS office. CA DSS: cdss.ca.gov/in-home-supportive-services — IHSS for ID includes protective supervision.\nCALABLE: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings without losing SSI/Medi-Cal.\nDRC BENEFITS COUNSELING: (800) 776-5746 — help understanding benefit interactions.\nYOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Helps with Medi-Cal linkage, HCBS waiver enrollment.\nSPECIAL NEEDS TRUST: specialneedsalliance.org — find attorney for SNT if savings exceed CalABLE limits.\n\nDOCUMENTS: SSI APPLICATION:\n• Apply online at ssa.gov or in person at local SSA office\n• Child SSI Function Report (SSA-3375-BK)\n• All medical/evaluation records documenting ID\n• School records (IEP, evaluations)\n• ID has HIGH SSI approval rate\n\nIHSS APPLICATION:\n• Apply through county IHSS office\n• Doctor\'s verification of need\n• ★ Request PROTECTIVE SUPERVISION if child at risk due to cognitive disability\n• IHSS assessment will determine authorized hours\n\nCALABLE:\n• Enroll at calable.ca.gov\n• Proof of disability onset before age 26\n• $19K/year contribution limit, $100K SSI-safe\n\nMEDI-CAL:\n• Automatic with SSI in CA\n• HCBS waiver through RC\n• Annual renewal required\n\nTIMELINE: Medi-Cal: 45 days. SSI: 3-6 months. IHSS: 30-60 days. CalABLE: immediate.\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: SSI denied despite qualifying ID diagnosis — appeal is critical (high overturn rate). IHSS protective supervision denied — requires strong documentation. Medi-Cal HCBS waiver not offered. CalABLE not opened early. Benefits coordination complex — SSI and IHSS amounts interact. Self-direction options for IHSS not explained.\n\nRISKS: SSI denied despite qualifying ID diagnosis — appeal is critical (high overturn rate). IHSS protective supervision denied — requires strong documentation. Medi-Cal HCBS waiver not offered. CalABLE not opened early. Benefits coordination complex — SSI and IHSS amounts interact. Self-direction options for IHSS not explained.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SSA (SSI)\nDSS (IHSS)\nMedi-Cal\nCalABLE\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nParent\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s61','journey-id','step-61','ID Step 6.1: Coordinate Medical & Therapeutic Care','ID — Step 6.1: Coordinate Medical & Therapeutic Care\n\nWHAT TO DO: Many children with ID have complex medical needs alongside developmental needs. Common co-occurring medical conditions: seizure disorders/epilepsy (~30% of ID), hearing and vision impairments, cardiac conditions (especially Down syndrome), feeding/swallowing difficulties, sleep disorders, dental issues, obesity. Therapeutic services: SLP (communication/AAC/feeding), OT (fine motor, sensory, self-care), PT (gross motor, mobility), behavioral support (ABA may be appropriate depending on co-occurring autism), psychology/psychiatry (mental health — ID + mental health co-occurs 3-4x more than general population).\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Many children with ID have complex medical needs alongside developmental needs.\nSTEP 2: Common co-occurring medical conditions: seizure disorders/epilepsy (~30% of ID), hearing and vision impairments, cardiac conditions (especially Down syndrome), feeding/swallowing difficulties, sleep disorders, dental issues, obesity.\nSTEP 3: Therapeutic services: SLP (communication/AAC/feeding), OT (fine motor, sensory, self-care), PT (gross motor, mobility), behavioral support (ABA may be appropriate depending on co-occurring autism), psychology/psychiatry (mental health — ID + mental health co-occurs 3-4x more than general population).\n\nCONTACT: PEDIATRICIAN / PRIMARY CARE: Coordinate with specialists.\nSPECIALISTS BY CO-OCCURRING CONDITION:\n• Neurology (epilepsy ~30% of ID): request referral from PCP\n• Cardiology (especially Down syndrome): contact through PCP\n• Gastroenterology (feeding/swallowing): request referral\n• Psychiatry (mental health 3-4x higher): county behavioral health or private\nCA CHILDREN\'S SERVICES (CCS): dhcs.ca.gov/services/ccs — specialized medical services for eligible children with qualifying conditions.\nCOUNTY BEHAVIORAL HEALTH: Each CA county has children\'s behavioral health. Access through Medi-Cal managed care plan.\nREGIONAL CENTER: Funds behavioral services, respite, specialized therapies through IPP.\n\nDOCUMENTS: MEDICAL COORDINATION DOCUMENTS:\n• Master provider list (PCP, specialists, therapists, RC providers, school providers)\n• Medication log (if applicable)\n• Specialist reports: neurology (epilepsy), cardiology (Down syndrome), GI (feeding), psychiatry\n• Therapy progress reports from all providers\n• Medical appointment calendar\n• ★ Mental health screening documentation — psychiatric conditions co-occur 3-4x more often in ID but are frequently attributed to ID rather than diagnosed separately (\'diagnostic overshadowing\')\n• CCS (California Children\'s Services) enrollment if eligible\n• Insurance authorizations and renewal dates\n• Emergency medical plan\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — medical care is lifelong for many ID-associated conditions.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Medical needs overshadow developmental needs (or vice versa). No medical home coordination. Specialists don\'t communicate with each other or with RC/school. Insurance denies therapies. Mental health needs unaddressed — behavior attributed to ID rather than co-occurring depression/anxiety. Polypharmacy without adequate monitoring.\n\nRISKS: Medical needs overshadow developmental needs (or vice versa). No medical home coordination. Specialists don\'t communicate with each other or with RC/school. Insurance denies therapies. Mental health needs unaddressed — behavior attributed to ID rather than co-occurring depression/anxiety. Polypharmacy without adequate monitoring.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Pediatrician / Medical Home\nSpecialists\nOTHER AGENCIES: RC\nSchool\nInsurance/Medi-Cal\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s62','journey-id','step-62','ID Step 6.2: Build Adaptive Skills & Community Inclusion','ID — Step 6.2: Build Adaptive Skills & Community Inclusion\n\nWHAT TO DO: Core focus for ID families: building functional independence through adaptive skill development. Daily living skills: self-care (hygiene, dressing, toileting), meal preparation, household tasks, money management, time management, safety skills. Community skills: transportation, shopping, restaurant, recreation, social interaction. Self-advocacy: understanding own needs, communicating preferences, making choices. KEY PRINCIPLE: Presume competence — assume the individual CAN learn, given appropriate support and instruction. Community inclusion: Special Olympics, adaptive recreation, inclusive community programs, faith community inclusion. Self-Determination movement: individuals with ID have the right to direct their own lives.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Core focus for ID families: building functional independence through adaptive skill development.\nSTEP 2: Daily living skills: self-care (hygiene, dressing, toileting), meal preparation, household tasks, money management, time management, safety skills.\nSTEP 3: Community skills: transportation, shopping, restaurant, recreation, social interaction.\nSTEP 4: Self-advocacy: understanding own needs, communicating preferences, making choices.\nSTEP 5: KEY PRINCIPLE: Presume competence — assume the individual CAN learn, given appropriate support and instruction.\n\nCONTACT: SPECIAL OLYMPICS CA: sosc.org (Southern CA), sonc.org (Northern CA) — sports and social inclusion.\nYOUR LOCAL PARKS & RECREATION: Many CA cities offer adaptive recreation programs.\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — local chapters offer social programs, recreation, community inclusion.\nREGIONAL CENTER: Funds day programs, social skills groups, community integration services.\nPEOPLE FIRST OF CA: peoplefirstofcalifornia.org — self-advocacy organization.\nBEST BUDDIES CA: bestbuddies.org/california — peer friendships and inclusion programs.\nCA STATE COUNCIL ON DEVELOPMENTAL DISABILITIES (SCDD): scdd.ca.gov — advocacy and community inclusion.\n\nDOCUMENTS: ADAPTIVE SKILLS DOCUMENTS:\n• Adaptive behavior assessment (Vineland-3, ABAS-3) — baseline and updates\n• Daily living skills checklist and progress tracking\n• Community skills development plan\n• Self-advocacy skills curriculum\n• Special Olympics registration and participation records\n• Adaptive recreation program enrollment\n• Best Buddies or social inclusion program participation\n• Respite care authorization and provider info\n\nIEP FUNCTIONAL GOALS:\n• Goals addressing daily living skills\n• Community-based instruction (CBI) documentation\n• Transition assessment results (functional, vocational)\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — skill building is lifelong with evolving goals.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Overprotection prevents skill development. Opportunities for community inclusion limited. Social isolation, especially in adolescence. Community programs not accessible or welcoming. Skills taught in isolation (school) don\'t transfer to community. Peer relationships limited to disability-specific settings.\n\nRISKS: Overprotection prevents skill development. Opportunities for community inclusion limited. Social isolation, especially in adolescence. Community programs not accessible or welcoming. Skills taught in isolation (school) don\'t transfer to community. Peer relationships limited to disability-specific settings.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Parents\nRC providers\nSchool\nCommunity programs\nOTHER AGENCIES: The Arc\nSpecial Olympics\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s71','journey-id','step-71','ID Step 7.1: Begin Transition Planning — ITP Required','ID — Step 7.1: Begin Transition Planning — ITP Required\n\nWHAT TO DO: Transition planning for ID is MORE COMPLEX than any other disability category because it involves both school district AND Regional Center adult services. By age 14-16: ITP (Individual Transition Plan) within IEP. Key areas: (1) Post-secondary education/training (community college disability services, adult education, certificate programs). (2) Employment (supported employment, customized employment, competitive integrated employment — CIE). (3) Independent living (supported living, independent living, residential care). (4) Community participation. (5) Self-advocacy and self-determination. Connect to DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation) by age 16. Connect to RC adult services planning by age 16-17.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Transition planning for ID is MORE COMPLEX than any other disability category because it involves both school district AND Regional Center adult services.\nSTEP 2: By age 14-16: ITP (Individual Transition Plan) within IEP.\nSTEP 3: Key areas: (1) Post-secondary education/training (community college disability services, adult education, certificate programs).\nSTEP 4: (2) Employment (supported employment, customized employment, competitive integrated employment — CIE).\nSTEP 5: (3) Independent living (supported living, independent living, residential care).\n\nCONTACT: SCHOOL TRANSITION COORDINATOR: Part of IEP team starting at age 14-16.\nCA DOR (Dept of Rehabilitation): dor.ca.gov — vocational rehabilitation. Refer through IEP by age 16. DOR works with school to develop employment goals.\nREGIONAL CENTER: Transition-age services (16-22). Day programs, supported employment, independent living.\nWORKABILITY I: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/sr/wrkabltyi.asp — CA school-based employment program for SpEd students.\nPROJECT SEARCH: projectsearch.us — internship-to-employment program for IDD.\nFAMILY EMPOWERMENT CENTERS: cde.ca.gov/sp/se/qa/fecprgm.asp — transition planning advocacy.\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — Achieve with Us employment program.\n\nDOCUMENTS: TRANSITION DOCUMENTS:\n• ITP (Individual Transition Plan) in IEP — required by age 16 (start at 14)\n• Transition assessments: vocational, functional, independent living\n• Post-secondary goals: education, employment, independent living\n• DOR referral documentation (by age 16)\n• WorkAbility I program enrollment (if available at school)\n• Project SEARCH application (if available in your area)\n\nCOORDINATE ACROSS SYSTEMS:\n• School IEP with ITP\n• RC IPP with transition goals\n• DOR Individualized Plan for Employment (IPE)\n• SSA adult redetermination prep (starts at 18)\n• ★ THIS IS THE MOST COMPLEX TRANSITION — 4 systems simultaneously\n\nTIMELINE: ITP required by age 16 (begin earlier). DOR connection by 16. RC adult planning by 17.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: TRANSITION CLIFF: School services end at 22 or diploma — adult services don\'t seamlessly replace them. RC adult services have waitlists. DOR vocational services limited. Supported employment underutilized (sheltered workshops still common despite evidence for CIE). Conservatorship pursued when less restrictive alternatives (SDM) would suffice. SSI transition from child to adult criteria at 18 — many lose benefits. Housing crisis for adults with ID.\n\nRISKS: ★ TRANSITION CLIFF: School services end at 22 or diploma — adult services don\'t seamlessly replace them. RC adult services have waitlists. DOR vocational services limited. Supported employment underutilized (sheltered workshops still common despite evidence for CIE). Conservatorship pursued when less restrictive alternatives (SDM) would suffice. SSI transition from child to adult criteria at 18 — many lose benefits. Housing crisis for adults with ID.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: School District\nRegional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: DOR\nSSA\nIHSS\nCalABLE\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s72','journey-id','step-72','ID Step 7.2: Conservatorship / Alternatives at Age 18','ID — Step 7.2: Conservatorship / Alternatives at Age 18\n\nWHAT TO DO: At age 18, child becomes legal adult regardless of cognitive ability. Options: (1) FULL CONSERVATORSHIP: most restrictive — another person makes all decisions. Court process, attorney required, costly, removes nearly all rights. Should be LAST resort. (2) LIMITED CONSERVATORSHIP: most common for ID — conservator has authority in specific areas (residence, medical, education, social) but individual retains other rights. Preferred over full conservatorship. (3) SUPPORTED DECISION-MAKING (SDM): emerging alternative — individual retains all legal rights but designates trusted supporters to help with decisions. Growing movement. (4) POWER OF ATTORNEY: if individual can understand and consent. Start planning 12-18 months before 18th birthday.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: At age 18, child becomes legal adult regardless of cognitive ability.\nSTEP 2: Options: (1) FULL CONSERVATORSHIP: most restrictive — another person makes all decisions.\nSTEP 3: Court process, attorney required, costly, removes nearly all rights.\nSTEP 4: Should be LAST resort.\nSTEP 5: (2) LIMITED CONSERVATORSHIP: most common for ID — conservator has authority in specific areas (residence, medical, education, social) but individual retains other rights.\n\nCONTACT: ★ START PLANNING 12-18 MONTHS BEFORE 18th BIRTHDAY:\nPROBATE COURT: File conservatorship petition in your county Superior Court. Limited conservatorship is most common for ID (7 specific powers).\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — alternatives to conservatorship guidance. DRC advocates for least-restrictive options.\nSUPPORTED DECISION-MAKING (SDM): CA AB 1663 (2023) codified SDM as alternative. supporteddecisions.org — national resources.\nLEGAL AID: Find your county\'s legal aid organization for conservatorship help. lawhelpcalifornia.org\nSPECIAL NEEDS TRUST ATTORNEY: specialneedsalliance.org — conservatorship often established alongside SNT.\nYOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Can help connect to legal resources and explain RC\'s role at age 18.\nSCDD: scdd.ca.gov — policy guidance on conservatorship alternative\n\nDOCUMENTS: CONSERVATORSHIP DOCUMENTS:\n• Petition for Limited Conservatorship (file in county Superior Court — Probate Division)\n• RC letter supporting conservatorship (or alternatives)\n• Medical/psychological reports documenting need\n• Investigation report by court investigator\n• Court-appointed attorney for conservatee\n• Letters of conservatorship (if granted)\n• Annual accounting requirements\n\nALTERNATIVES TO CONSERVATORSHIP:\n• Supported Decision-Making Agreement (CA AB 1663): supporteddecisions.org — template agreements\n• Power of Attorney (if individual can consent)\n• Representative Payee for SSI (through SSA)\n• HIPAA authorization for medical decisions\n• Advance healthcare directive\n\n★ START 12-18 MONTHS BEFORE 18th BIRTHDAY\n\nTIMELINE: Begin planning at 16-17. File 6-12 months before 18th birthday if conservatorship needed.\n\nAVOID: DO NOT: Options: (1) FULL CONSERVATORSHIP: most restrictive — another person makes all decisions\n\nAVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Conservatorship pursued by default without considering SDM or limited conservatorship. Full conservatorship used when limited would suffice. Court process overwhelming and expensive ($3,000-5,000+). Individual\'s preferences not considered. RC doesn\'t inform families about SDM alternative. Conservatorship restricts voting rights in some cases.\n\nRISKS: ★ Conservatorship pursued by default without considering SDM or limited conservatorship. Full conservatorship used when limited would suffice. Court process overwhelming and expensive ($3,000-5,000+). Individual\'s preferences not considered. RC doesn\'t inform families about SDM alternative. Conservatorship restricts voting rights in some cases.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Attorney / Court\nRegional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: Parent\nDRC\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s73','journey-id','step-73','ID Step 7.3: Adult Services Planning (RC IPP, Employment, Housing)','ID — Step 7.3: Adult Services Planning (RC IPP, Employment, Housing)\n\nWHAT TO DO: After school exit (22 or diploma): Regional Center becomes primary service system. Adult IPP should address: (1) DAY SERVICES: day program, supported employment, community-based activities. (2) EMPLOYMENT: CIE (Competitive Integrated Employment) is the GOLD STANDARD — supported employment with job coach, customized employment, self-employment. DOR provides vocational rehabilitation. (3) RESIDENTIAL: family home with supports, supported living services (SLS), independent living, group homes, specialized residential. (4) RECREATION/SOCIAL: adaptive recreation, social groups, community inclusion programs. (5) HEALTH: continued medical management, mental health support. RC budget for adult services is largest portion of $18.7B DDS budget.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: After school exit (22 or diploma): Regional Center becomes primary service system.\nSTEP 2: Adult IPP should address: (1) DAY SERVICES: day program, supported employment, community-based activities.\nSTEP 3: (2) EMPLOYMENT: CIE (Competitive Integrated Employment) is the GOLD STANDARD — supported employment with job coach, customized employment, self-employment.\nSTEP 4: DOR provides vocational rehabilitation.\nSTEP 5: (3) RESIDENTIAL: family home with supports, supported living services (SLS), independent living, group homes, specialized residential.\n\nCONTACT: REGIONAL CENTER: IPP continues through adult life. Annual review required.\nCA DOR: dor.ca.gov — Competitive Integrated Employment (CIE) services.\nCA DDS EMPLOYMENT FIRST POLICY: dds.ca.gov/initiatives/employment-first — CIE as preferred outcome.\nHOUSING OPTIONS:\n• CA HCD: hcd.ca.gov — housing resources\n• HUD Section 8/Housing Choice Voucher: contact your local housing authority\n• RC-funded supported living: through IPP\nTHE ARC: thearc.org — Achieve with Us employment, local chapter community programs.\nSCDD: scdd.ca.gov — community living and employment advocacy.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — housing rights, employment rights, IPP advocacy.\n\nDOCUMENTS: ADULT SERVICES DOCUMENTS:\n• RC IPP (annual review required)\n• DOR IPE (Individualized Plan for Employment)\n• CIE (Competitive Integrated Employment) goal documentation\n• Supported Employment provider information\n• Housing applications (Section 8 waitlist — apply YEARS in advance)\n• Supported living services authorization through RC\n• Day program enrollment (if applicable)\n• Self-Determination Program budget (if enrolled)\n\nBENEFITS COORDINATION:\n• SSI adult redetermination (age 18)\n• IHSS reassessment for adult services\n• Medi-Cal continuation\n• CalABLE/SNT coordination plan\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — annual IPP review. DOR services until employed. Housing: multi-year waitlists.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: HOUSING CRISIS: Affordable accessible housing waitlists are YEARS long. Sheltered workshops still exist despite federal push for CIE. Day programs are \'custodial\' rather than skill-building. RC service coordinator overwhelmed — insufficient advocacy. Family aging out (parent caregivers aging). Self-determination program underutilized. Racial disparities in adult service access persistent.\n\nRISKS: ★ HOUSING CRISIS: Affordable accessible housing waitlists are YEARS long. Sheltered workshops still exist despite federal push for CIE. Day programs are \'custodial\' rather than skill-building. RC service coordinator overwhelmed — insufficient advocacy. Family aging out (parent caregivers aging). Self-determination program underutilized. Racial disparities in adult service access persistent.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: Regional Center\nDOR\nOTHER AGENCIES: SSA\nIHSS\nMedi-Cal\nHousing authority\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s81','journey-id','step-81','ID Step 8.1: Ongoing Benefits Management & Monitoring','ID — Step 8.1: Ongoing Benefits Management & Monitoring\n\nWHAT TO DO: Lifelong benefits coordination: SSI CDR (Continuing Disability Review) every 1-7 years. IHSS annual reassessment. Medi-Cal annual renewal. CalABLE contributions and spending tracking. SNT (Special Needs Trust) if assets exceed SSI/Medi-Cal limits. SSI and IHSS amounts adjust with living situation changes. Report changes to SSA within 10 days (overpayment risk). Benefits coordination for working adults with ID — PASS (Plan to Achieve Self-Support), IRWE (Impairment-Related Work Expenses), 1619(b) for Medi-Cal retention.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Lifelong benefits coordination: SSI CDR (Continuing Disability Review) every 1-7 years.\nSTEP 2: IHSS annual reassessment.\nSTEP 3: Medi-Cal annual renewal.\nSTEP 4: CalABLE contributions and spending tracking.\nSTEP 5: SNT (Special Needs Trust) if assets exceed SSI/Medi-Cal limits.\n\nCONTACT: SSA: ssa.gov — (800) 772-1213 — SSI CDR (Continuing Disability Review) every 1-7 years. Report changes.\nIHSS: Your county IHSS office — annual reassessment. CA DSS: cdss.ca.gov/in-home-supportive-services\nMEDI-CAL: Annual renewal through your county human services agency.\nCALABLE: calable.ca.gov — monitor contribution limits ($19K/year, $100K SSI-safe threshold).\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — benefits counseling, appeal denied benefits.\nHEALTH CONSUMER ALLIANCE: healthconsumer.org — help with Medi-Cal issues.\nYOUR RC SERVICE COORDINATOR: Annual IPP review, service authorization renewals.\n\nDOCUMENTS: BENEFITS TRACKING DOCUMENTS:\n• SSI CDR (Continuing Disability Review) — every 1-7 years depending on category\n• IHSS annual reassessment\n• Medi-Cal annual renewal\n• CalABLE contribution and balance tracking ($19K/year limit, $100K SSI-safe)\n• SNT annual accounting (if applicable)\n• RC IPP annual review\n• Insurance authorization renewals\n\n★ MASTER DEADLINE CALENDAR:\n• SSI CDR date\n• IHSS reassessment date\n• Medi-Cal renewal date\n• CalABLE contribution tracker\n• IPP annual review date\n• IEP annual review date (if still in school)\n• Conservatorship annual accounting date\n\nTIMELINE: SSI CDR: every 1-7 years. IHSS: annual. Medi-Cal: annual. Ongoing monitoring.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Benefits overpayment due to unreported changes. CDR results in loss of benefits (requires appeal). IHSS hours reduced at reassessment. CalABLE/SNT coordination errors. Working adults lose benefits unexpectedly. Complex benefits rules overwhelm families.\n\nRISKS: Benefits overpayment due to unreported changes. CDR results in loss of benefits (requires appeal). IHSS hours reduced at reassessment. CalABLE/SNT coordination errors. Working adults lose benefits unexpectedly. Complex benefits rules overwhelm families.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: SSA / IHSS / Medi-Cal / CalABLE\nCalABLE DETAILS: calable.ca.gov — tax-advantaged savings account (up to $100K without affecting SSI/Medi-Cal). Eligible if disability onset before age 26. Funds usable for housing, education, health, employment, assistive technology, transportation, and more.\nOTHER AGENCIES: Regional Center\nFinancial planner\nSNT trustee\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);
  e.push(['jrn-id-s82','journey-id','step-82','ID Step 8.2: Long-Term Advocacy & Community Engagement','ID — Step 8.2: Long-Term Advocacy & Community Engagement\n\nWHAT TO DO: Lifelong advocacy needs for individuals with ID: (1) The Arc: largest national IDD advocacy organization — local chapters, policy advocacy, community inclusion programs, Achieve with Us employment network. (2) Self-advocacy: People First movement, self-advocacy groups. (3) Voting rights: most individuals with ID CAN vote (conservatorship may affect this — know your rights). (4) Community inclusion: friendships, recreation, faith community, civic participation. (5) Health advocacy: preventive care, mental health access, healthy aging (life expectancy for ID has increased dramatically but healthcare disparities persist). (6) Policy advocacy: Lanterman Act protection, DDS budget, HCBS settings rule, Employment First policy.\n\nHOW TO ACT: STEP 1: Lifelong advocacy needs for individuals with ID: (1) The Arc: largest national IDD advocacy organization — local chapters, policy advocacy, community inclusion programs, Achieve with Us employment network.\nSTEP 2: (2) Self-advocacy: People First movement, self-advocacy groups.\nSTEP 3: (3) Voting rights: most individuals with ID CAN vote (conservatorship may affect this — know your rights).\nSTEP 4: (4) Community inclusion: friendships, recreation, faith community, civic participation.\nSTEP 5: (5) Health advocacy: preventive care, mental health access, healthy aging (life expectancy for ID has increased dramatically but healthcare disparities persist).\n\nCONTACT: THE ARC: thearc.org — policy advocacy, local chapters, community programs.\nPEOPLE FIRST OF CA: peoplefirstofcalifornia.org — self-advocacy movement.\nSCDD (State Council on Developmental Disabilities): scdd.ca.gov — policy advocacy, community inclusion.\nASAN (Autistic Self Advocacy Network): autisticadvocacy.org — neurodiversity and disability rights.\nDRC: (800) 776-5746 — systemic advocacy, voting rights, community integration.\nCA DDS: dds.ca.gov — Lanterman Act protection, DDS budget advocacy.\nNATIONAL COUNCIL ON DISABILITY: ncd.gov — federal disability policy.\n\nDOCUMENTS: ADVOCACY DOCUMENTS:\n• Voter registration (individuals with ID have the RIGHT to vote in CA)\n• Self-advocacy plan and goals\n• People First membership\n• The Arc membership and local chapter participation\n• SCDD public comment and testimony records\n\nPOLICY TRACKING:\n• Lanterman Act — CA\'s foundational disability rights law\n• CA DDS budget (FY 2025-26: $18.7B, largest in history)\n• HCBS Settings Rule compliance\n• Employment First policy implementation\n• Conservatorship reform legislation\n\nHEALTHY AGING:\n• Medical monitoring plan (ID-specific aging concerns)\n• Down syndrome Alzheimer\'s screening (age 40+)\n• Updated IPP reflecting changing needs\n\nTIMELINE: Ongoing — lifelong.\n\nAVOID: AVOID THESE COMMON PITFALLS: Isolation increases as person ages. Self-advocacy opportunities not offered. Voting rights restricted without basis. Health care providers lack training on ID. Aging with ID presents unique medical challenges. Policy changes affect services without family awareness.\n\nRISKS: Isolation increases as person ages. Self-advocacy opportunities not offered. Voting rights restricted without basis. Health care providers lack training on ID. Aging with ID presents unique medical challenges. Policy changes affect services without family awareness.\n\nRESOURCES: THE ARC: thearc.org — advocacy tools, policy updates, community inclusion, local chapters\nFRCNCA: frcnca.org — peer support, advocacy training, language-accessible\nUC DAVIS MIND INSTITUTE: health.ucdavis.edu/mindinstitute — peer groups, parent coaching, Spanish-language support\nPARENTS HELPING PARENTS: php.com — consultations, webinars, support groups\nDRC PUBLICATIONS: disabilityrightsca.org — RC rights, conservatorship, SSI guides (free, multilingual)\nUCP: ucp.org — My Child Without Limits community\nSELF-DETERMINATION PROGRAM: CA self-determination for RC clients\nCA PTI NETWORK: parentcenterhub.org\nBOOKS: \'The Complete Guide to Special Education\' (Wilmshurst/Brue)\n\nPRIMARY AGENCY: The Arc\nSelf-advocacy organizations\nRegional Center\nOTHER AGENCIES: DRC\nCommunity organizations\n','Entity Matrix v9.4','TRUE',now]);

